<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICACUP-AMERICAONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENALTY SINKS AMERICAONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ After losing a major battle with the
gales of Hauraki Gulf Friday, Paul Cayard brought AmericaOne back
in street-fighting form Saturday, going to the wire against Italy's
Luna Rossa.
</P>
<P>
   But with 250 yards to the finish, an extremely controversial
penalty call gave Luna Rossa a win, taking the Italian team to 3-1
in the best-of-nine competition.
</P>
<P>
   With the spinnakers billowing in a 16-knot breeze down the last
leg, Luna Rossa to the left and AmericaOne to the right, Cayard
gybed just ahead of the Prada team and was penalized for failing to
keep clear of an overlapped boat.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's tactician Torben Grael called for the penalty flag, and
after conferring, the two jury boats agreed that AmericaOne was
guilty of a foul. With no time left to do a penalty turn, Luna
Rossa won the race by a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a BS call,'' said Cayard. ``He came from behind me. He
didn't have an overlap.'' Later, Cayard said, ``I'm not sure what
the call was. I thought we sailed clear ahead, but the ump took the
race away from us. I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the umpires were firm on their ruling that Cayard had gybed
too close and below proper course. As the silver boat crossed the
line behind AmericaOne, the committee boat threw up the large
yellow flag signaling a win for Prada and the 600-boat spectator
fleet erupted in horn-blowing mayhem. It was one of the greatest
America's Cup races in memory.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's loss to Prada in gale winds, Cayard's dark gray
boat from San Francisco limped home broken and beaten, having
withdrawn from Race 3 with a badly damaged mast, sails and gear
broken, one man in the hospital, and one with a bruised back.
</P>
<P>
   So few expected Cayard's street fight that allowed AmericaOne to
take control of the race early, and for the next five legs. First
off the start line, AmericaOne locked up on a long left-hand drag
race that proved little speed difference between the two boats.
Positioned better, with starboard rights, AmericaOne beat Luna
Rossa around the mark by 8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But downwind on Leg 2, as Italian skipper Francesco de Angelis
forced his bow in on the windward side of AmericaOne, Cayard
responded with a luffing move. But it didn't pay off until
AmericaOne suffered another split spinnaker _ the eighth one of 44
races since October.
</P>
<P>
   With the spinnaker billowing like a huge lime-green pennant
flag, Cayard now could spin his bow at Prada with a nasty luff. In
fact, freed from the encumbrance of the spinnaker, Cayard was able
to turn Prada so far upwind, it lost control of its own spinnaker,
crash-gybed, and ended heading back toward the upwind mark.
</P>
<P>
   As they controlled the mayhem on board, the Italian boat spun
back to the leeward mark, but now trailed AmericaOne by 39 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the next two legs, Grael and de Angelis probed
the lead of AmericaOne, and made a gain as AmericaOne lost its jib
sheet halfway up Leg 3.
</P>
<P>
   But Cayard and tactician John Kostecki managed to play the
steady west wind to maintain the cardinal match-rule _ staying
between the trailing boat and the next mark. In and out of a heavy
rain squall, the two boats thrashed through the seas, but when the
sun suddenly swelled back over the gulf, AmericaOne was still five
lengths ahead, and appeared to be cruising to a win that would even
the score at two wins.
</P>
<P>
   But just after the fifth mark, as they started the run for the
finish three miles away, AmericaOne made what now seems the fatal
mistake. Prada instituted a gybing duel early in the leg, then set
up to the left on starboard from AmericaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than gybe a final time with Prada, AmericaOne allowed de
Angelis to steer away and get some separation for a possible
passing lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he thought the race was over,'' said Grael. ``We were
just lucky to have it (the separation) and once and we were very
happy to win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the earlier luffing match, Grael said: ``For a boat without a
spinnaker to luff a boat with a full spinnaker going 10 knots . . .
it's just uncivilized.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Leg 6 developed, Cayard's problems led to the Italian
payback. AmericaOne's headsail was not right for the lightening
conditions, and as Cayard and Kostecki tried to decide whether to
make a gybe peel, it was clear that Prada was closing the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Getting near the finish, Cayard drove at Prada to try and gybe
in front and force de Angelis and Grael to gybe away to the left
again.
</P>
<P>
   But the gap had closed so much by that point, AmericaOne's gybe,
made beyond the bow line of Luna Rossa, was judged gybing too
close, or failing to stay clear of an overlapped boat.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard rode back in on a quiet boat. With four races to win in
the next five, Cayard pointed out that he has sailed with his back
to the wall before _ most notably when he was down, 3-1, in the
1992 challenger finals and beat New Zealand at the helm of Italy's
Il Moro.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do now,'' said Cayard, ``is go out and win some
races.''
</P>
<P>
   To our readers: Because New Zealand is 18 hours ahead of US East
Coast time, all action takes place a day ahead (i.e. a Sunday noon
race there is taking place Saturday evening here). To avoid
confusion, all time references in America's Cup stories will
reflect when the events took place according to Eastern Standard
Time.
</P>
</TEXT>
