<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN WALKS A TIGHTROPE IN N.H. PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER AND KRIS MAYES 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   break primary, John McCain is in the delicate position of
needing to attract many of the state's 275,000 independent voters
without alienating the core GOP conservatives who could be critical
to his later success.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tricky dance step.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's standing as a ``reform candidate'' has appeal for
voters of all parties, and that's fine in New Hampshire, where
undeclared primary voters will be permitted to cast either
Republican or Democratic ballots Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the McCain campaign believes its candidate's popularity
outside the Republican Party would make him the most electable of
the five GOP presidential contenders in November.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain risks jeopardizing his conservative credentials if he
appears to move too far to the center _ on abortion, for example _
for the sake of winning over New Hampshire's independents.
</P>
<P>
   From New Hampshire, McCain moves to conservative South Carolina,
where he will campaign nearly non-stop until that state's Feb. 19
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be treading a fine line,'' said GOP consultant
Lyn Nofziger, who was an aide to Ronald Reagan when he was
president. ``If he does well in New Hampshire, he doesn't want to
go down to South Carolina and look like he's flip-flopping on the
issues. And you can bet the (George W.) Bush and (Steve) Forbes
people will be nailing him on any flip-flops down there.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign insists it's neither abandoning party
principles nor gearing its New Hampshire strategy just toward the
``undeclareds,'' who make up a whopping 37 percent of the state's
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't cede conservative territory to anybody,'' said John
Weaver, McCain's national political director. ``We'll do very well
among Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   It's shaping up as a tight race in New Hampshire, targeted by
McCain long ago as his ``Ground Zero.'' He skipped campaigning in
the Iowa caucuses and instead has wagered almost everything on New
Hampshire, South Carolina and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is 9 points up in some statewide polls, McCain
officials won't venture beyond predicting a close one-two finish
with Bush, the Texas governor who leads in the national polls and
in fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, with starting at zero and Bush having $75 million,
anything that comes close, whether it's 1 point down or 1 point up,
is a victory for us,'' McCain's New Hampshire director, Mike
Dennehy, said. ``It just proves that he's not the inevitable
nominee that he said he was going to be. He has the entire
Republican establishment on his side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a success story. Is the success story a win?'' said
Weaver, the political director. ``That will be up to the pundits.
But the fact that we start with 3 percent, with no organization
driving a van around the state _ yeah, I would consider that a
success story.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of McCain's backers say they don't identify with either
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am never going to be a Republican; I am never going to be a
Democrat,'' said Steve Barba, 53, of tiny Dixville Notch, which is
home to 29 voters in the northern part of the state. Its residents
traditionally gather at the old Balsams resort and cast the
primary's first votes, at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Barba selected McCain partly because he believes his leadership
transcends party membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view, I was looking for a leader, a person
willing to stand up and move in a direction that he could bring
followers to him. I have that assessment of both McCain and
(Democratic candidate Bill) Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain is pleased to have Barba's support _ he ac
tively courted the 29 Dixville voters _ he is also eager to wave
the Republican flag, lest he be perceived as somehow disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a proud conservative Republican. I have a 17-year record
of conservatism,'' McCain told a recent gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Some anti-abortion activists questioned McCain's conservative
credentials when he said in August that he would not support ``in
the short term, or even the long term,'' the repeal of ``Roe vs.
Wade,'' the 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion. Then
he said last week that it would be a family decision if his teenage
daughter got pregnant and wanted an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has a Senate record in opposition to abortion,
partial-birth abortion and federal funding of abortion. He has said
the attacks on him are in retaliation for his proposal to reform
the campaign-finance system.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee, among other interest
groups, believes McCain's proposed overhaul would stifle political
speech.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's call to limit the influence of special-interest groups
is a major reason for his appeal to independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one New Hampshire pollster believes the Arizonan's
independent support is shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Recent tracking polls by pollster Dick Bennett's American
Research Group indicate that independents, who were once planning
to enter the GOP race, may now be eyeing the Democratic primary
instead.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bennett, about 7 percent of New Hampshire voters
are independent, socially moderate women who were once looking to
vote for McCain in order to defeat Bush but who now may want to
weigh in in behalf of Bradley against Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were with McCain because they thought it would do the
most good; there is some softening there,'' Bennett said. ``A lot
now depends on what Bradley does.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's support among older Republican women, a key group of
largely undecided voters, may also be dwindling, according to
Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the weaknesses of the McCain campaign has been that it
hasn't targeted older Republican women,'' Bennett said. ``The
veterans' appeal doesn't translate to women. They are more
party-loyal and think Bush can win, and they don't see anything
wrong with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is still a lot of voter movement, the final days
of the primary campaign have been remarkably docile, according to
those who faced off in 1996. Steve Forbes, who carpet-bombed the
state with negative ads four years ago, has largely held his fire
this year. And the skirmishing between McCain and Bush that began
several weeks ago over taxes has died down as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different environment this year,'' said Bill Dal Col,
Forbes' campaign manager during both elections. ``There are
different candidates and different issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As with the other candidates, McCain's strategy finally will
rest on organization.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign plans to post volunteers at every polling site to
check in identified McCain supporters. If one does not show up at a
poll by midafternoon, the voter will get a reminder call from the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the other campaigns have the organization we
have here,'' Dennehy said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
