<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING STRAIGHT TO THE SOURCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have it on very good authority the Rams are going to run away
with Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   My celestial source said so.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Tammy and she's a kindred spirit of Georgia
Frontiere, the St. Louis Rams owner who is such a firm believer in
the stars she once had her players' astronomical charts done.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy is an astrologer and tarot card reader who confessed to
knowing nothing about football. When you're clairvoyant you don't
need to have heard of Jevon Kearse.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, Tennessee's otherworldly rookie left defensive end,
turned Rams right tackle Fred Miller into Don Knotts in the
regular-season meeting between the two teams. Trying to contain
Kearse made Miller so edgy, so spasmodic, he was flagged for six
false starts in the Rams' 24-21 loss in Week 7.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was through with Miller, Kearse had two sacks, a
forced fumble and an honorary membership in the Rams' backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, it's going to be Miller time.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Miller that Tammy needed to know, she learned
from his birthdate, Feb. 6, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``My god, there is a lot of psychic energy around this man,''
she purred after a pregnant pause. ``It's so strong, it's like this
inner knowing that taps into his confidence, his rhythm, his
chutzpah, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's containment of Kearse will give Rams quarterback Kurt
Warner enough time to pick apart a Titans secondary that is
suspect, what with Marcus Robertson sidelined with a broken ankle
and Blaine Bishop enamored of hitting people instead of tackling
them.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, the NFL's top-rated passer and hands-down best story,
will get the ball early and often to Isaac Bruce, Az-Zahir Hakim
and Torry Holt.
</P>
<P>
   With their deep post patterns the Rams receivers will turn the
Super Bowl into the most-watched track meet in Atlanta since the
1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Without knowing Warner's position or personal saga, only his
birthdate (June 22, 1971), Tammy said, ``He most certainly is going
to be a star (today). When I look at his energy field, it's like
the Fourth of July with all the fireworks going off in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope she wasn't having a flashback to the Centennial Park
bombing during the 1996 Olympics. Richard Jewell, who was suspected
of being behind the attack, eventually was vindicated, just as Rams
placekicker Jeff Wilkins will be today.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oct. 31 meeting between the teams, Wilkins got spooked
and missed a field goal with 22 seconds left that would have tied
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Daniel Day Lewis has one person's left foot drawn so
many crowds. Wilkins has been encircled the past few days by
reporters wondering if that missed field goal and the two
medium-ranged field goals he has missed in the postseason were the
result of the chronic tendinitis he has in his left kneecap or a
temporary constricting in his throat.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth-year veteran out of Youngstown State will answer his
critics today. Redemption will be Super for Wilkins, who was born
on April 19, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel a lot of sunshine hitting him,'' Tammy said. ``I
feel tremendous energy surrounding him.''
</P>
<P>
   At $3.99 per minute, this telephone call was sapping my savings,
if not my energy. It was time to let Tammy go, but before I did, I
wanted to know what today holds for the Rams' amateur psychic,
Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   In the grandiloquent tradition of Joe Namath and Ray Buchanan,
the second-year receiver and punt returner out of San Diego State
boldly predicted a Rams victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just how I feel,'' Hakim said in the ensuing days,
staunchly sticking to his statement.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for Hakim, he has the stars aligned behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I feel around him is a bulldog, literally,''
Tammy said of the Gemini, born June 3, 1977. ``He has tremendous
physical strength (today). He's like a bulldog; he'll pull anything
that gets into his path with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammy paused. ``I'm going to tell you,'' she said, ``just with
the energy I feel around him, I really feel his team is going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   So Frontiere need not bother rubbing the uniforms of her players
with crystals today for good luck, as she has done before. The
force field is with her Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I'm picking up from their energy field I would say
it's not going to be a real close game,'' Tammy concluded with such
breathless conviction I was tempted to make my next telephone call
to a bookie. ``I don't know how they keep score in football, but I
see this team getting out front and staying out front.''
</P>
<P>
   Who am I to counteract cosmic karma? Rams 30, Titans 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
