<SLUG> BC-LEPCLASS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING 1 WORD AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KARINA BLAND  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thursday, the children &UR; couldn't say the English words for
hardly any of the 20 objects their teacher pulled from a bag _
butterfly, whistle, boat, frog, key.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, they missed only two: X-ray and lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are learning so fast,'' says Ana Maria Quilantan Hawley, a
bilingual first-grade &UR; teacher at Frank School in Guadalupe. ``I'm
very proud of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of migrant workers, &UR; Hawley was about 11 when her
family settled &UR; in Idaho. She couldn't read in English.
</P>
<P>
   All these years later, she feels the sting &UR; of a teacher asking,
``Why are you so stupid?''
</P>
<P>
   So, when little Tanya Acosta, who has been here from Mexico
since November, shakes her head at one of Hawley's questions,
Hawley tells the girl they will work on it later, just the two of
them.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher for 22 years, Hawley has taught bilingual classes for
all but four.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the school year, all 12 of &UR; her students who read
in English were below grade level. Now, all but one are above.
</P>
<P>
   They pull books from a shelf marked ````Libros predilectos'''' _
Hawley's ``favorite books.''
</P>
<P>
   Her other nine students read only in Spanish _ one at the
third-grade level. Roberto Valenzuela and Yadira Paredez have been
here for only two weeks. Yet, even they know the words for the
things in the bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grueso'' is ``thick'' in English. ``Kazoo'' is the same.
</P>
<P>
   Bilingual classes at Frank end in fourth grade. That's all right
for the first-graders in Hawley's class _ they'll likely be reading
and writing English four years from now. But the cut-off is a
problem for their older siblings who came to America as &UR; third- and
fourth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley tells each new child that it is hard to learn English but
she will help. She tells them not only to listen to what she says _
first in English, then in Spanish _ but to watch the other children
and do as they do.
</P>
<P>
   She puts kids who speak only Spanish next to children who speak
both and doesn't &UR; chide them for whispered explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are they learning a whole new language, but about a
whole new world. She takes them outside to show them ``lawn,'' a
patch of green in their books. ``Pasto.'' Grass. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
