<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALL-OF-FAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL OF FAME'S HEART GOES TO SAN FRANCISCO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Pro Football Hall of Fame Class of 2000 is colored
red and gold.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco 49ers have three of the five honorees
announced yesterday. First-year candidates Joe Montana and Ronnie
Lott and seniors selectee Dave Wilcox will be inducted on the steps
of the Hall of Fame on July 29.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney and Los Angeles/Oakland
Raiders defensive lineman Howie Long give the Hall of Fame, in
Canton, Ohio, an enrollment of 204.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Swann, a receiver on four Pittsburgh Super Bowl champions,
and defensive end Jack Youngblood of the Los Angeles Rams, finished
in the final six, but did not get the 80 percent approval required
for election.
</P>
<P>
   Montana was one of the easiest selections ever for the selection
committee of 38 writers and broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   In his four Super Bowl victories, Montana threw 122 passes
without an interception. He finished his career as the fourth
passer in history to top 40,000 yards. His 3,409 completions ranked
third all-time, and his career passer rating of 92.3 ranks second
all-time behind former 49ers teammate Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   He directed 31 fourth-quarter comebacks, including the 92-yard,
game-winning drive in Super Bowl XXIII against Cincinnati, and
``The Catch,'' that Dwight Clark caught to beat the Cowboys in the
NFC Championship Game on Jan. 10, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``My uncle lived in Canton,'' Montana said. ``I drove by the
Hall of Fame I can't tell you how many countless times. ... And it
was the furthest thing from my mind, maybe because it was an ending
point. With a tremendous honor also comes a little dirt on the
grave that it's truly over. There's no going back now, Ronnie.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott was an eight-time All-Pro at cornerback, strong safety and
free safety. He holds the NFL postseason record with nine
interceptions, and he had 100-plus tackles five times in a 14-year
career that also included stints with the Los Angeles Raiders and
the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in there \Rto the Hall of Fame\S, it's like you
want to get on your knees and bow to some of the people,'' said
Lott, who twice shed tears. ``\RHall of Famer Ray\S Nitschke said
to me one time, `You know, you could play with me.' That's what the
Hall of Fame is about.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lott and Montana were automatics, Wilcox had to wait 21
years before being honored as the old-timer candidate. Although he
earned seven Pro Bowl invitations in 11 seasons with the 49ers,
Wilcox was bypassed in his 20 years of eligibility as a modern era
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' said Wilcox, who played from 1964-74. ``We
played in an era back when the Hall of Fame was just starting. The
21 years, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Long's first season of eligibility was last year, when he was a
finalist. This year he was rewarded for his 84 career sacks, eight
Pro Bowls and three All-Pro selections in his 13 seasons with the
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to put into words what goes through your mind when
they say your name,'' Long said. ``Last year I knew what it was
like when they don't say your name. It's a tremendous
disappointment and leaves a pretty hollow feeling. You feel kind of
complete now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney's family has owned the Steelers since the team was
founded. His father, Art, is already in the Hall of Fame, and they
join Tim Mara and Wellington Mara of the New York Giants as the
only father-son honorees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite surprised,'' Rooney said. ``I didn't think I'd make
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Harry Carson, tight end Dave Casper, defensive end
Carl Eller, wide receiver James Lofton, guard Mike Munchak,
offensive tackle Ron Yary and coach Marv Levy did not make the list
of finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Players must be retired five years to be eligible for the Hall
of Fame. Coaches become eligible upon retirement, and active
administrators can be considered. Old-timer nominees must have
completed 70 percent of their careers by 1975 and automatically
advance to the final seven candidates.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
