<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-OPENER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHL PATROLS TRAFFIC, WINS IRL OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Indy Racing League veteran Robbie Buhl
says there is no such thing as ``strategy'' when racing in a pack
in the final laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to see what's presented there,'' Buhl said at the
Walt Disney World Speedway yesterday afternoon, ``and be in
position to take advantage of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The stuff of Buhl's victory in the season-opening Delphi Indy
200 proved to be some late-race traffic _ backmarkers, as they are
called _ who also just happened to be rookies. Locked in a
single-file freight train with fellow veterans Buddy Lazier and
Eddie Cheever Jr., Buhl played off the inexperience of rookies Sam
Hornish Jr. and Doug Didero to move from third and into first in
the span of eight frenetic laps.
</P>
<P>
   Buhl's final move _ past the frustrated Cheever on Lap 199 of
the scheduled 200 _ gave the IRL's newest owner/driver his second
series victory and first since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all three of us were running there, we were all fairly
equal,'' said Buhl, referring to himself, Lazier and Cheever. ``And
what was going to shake things up was traffic. Sure enough, that's
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhl, Cheever and Lazier had been in each other's mirrors since
Lap 150 around the tight, 1-mile trioval. Lazier led Cheever by
0.630-seconds after 190 laps, with Buhl in third, when Hornish
slowed Lazier's momentum heading into Turn 1 at over 153 mph. That
set up Cheever for a pass on Lazier on the inside of Turn 2 on Lap
191. Buhl also capitalized a lap later, when he motored his Team
Purex Dreyer &AMP; Reinbold Racing G Force/Aurora around Lazier in Turn
1 and into second place.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever, a two-time winner of this event and the defending
champion, led Buhl by 0.477-seconds when the two approached traffic
at the conclusion of Lap 197. Cheever held the point until he
reeled in the car of Didero, whom Cheever charged with blocking him
high and low, allowing Buhl to take the lead on the final lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy got hung up a little bit, and both Eddie and I got by
him,'' said Buhl, who started 22nd in the 26-car field. ``Then
Eddie and I were running fairly equal. I was a little bit better in
Turn 1 than him, but I couldn't do anything with him. So, it was a
matter of waiting for traffic. He got bogged down, and we got a
great shot by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reigning IRL champion Greg Ray of Plano was relegated to a
17th-place finish _ 20 laps off the winning pace _ after the
sequential-shift gearbox in his Dallara/Aurora failed during a pit
stop. And two-time Indy 500 champion Al Unser Jr.'s IRL debut
produced a 25th-place finish after his Aurora engine blew after 64
laps.
</P>
<P>
   Lazier, winless in the IRL since 1997, said he deserved ``a
piece of the racetrack'' heading to the finish with the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the field has spotters and knows the leaders are
coming,'' said Lazier, who like Cheever was attempting to give the
American-made Riley &AMP; Scott chassis its first IRL victory. ``I
mean, I just about ripped the front of my car off on this guy
\RHornish\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever, who in addition to campaigning a Riley &AMP; Scott chassis
also was attempting to give the Nissan Infiniti Indy V-8 its first
series victory, blamed himself for trusting a rookie to move it on
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two laps to go I went down to get around the blue car
\Rof Didero\S, and he moved down,'' Cheever said. ``I tried to go
on the outside. His car drifted up, pushing me into the marbles.''
</P>
<P>
   And into a third-place finish. Buhl's margin of victory over
Lazier was 3.165 seconds in a race that produced eight caution
flags for 65 laps, and plenty of postrace whining.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
