<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' BEST DEFENSE IS AN IMPROVING DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If someone had told the Stars a month or so ago
that defenseman Shawn Chambers' knee injury might cause him to miss
the entire season, the screams probably could've been heard in
space.
</P>
<P>
   Their fifth, sixth and seventh defensemen were that suspect.
</P>
<P>
   So the silence said a lot when Chambers said a couple of days
ago that he might not return this season. The silence said those
defensemen have improved a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for someone to emerge from that group, and I
think all of the guys have emerged quite a bit,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the Stars don't need Chambers, who had surgery
Oct. 12 to remove and repair cartilage in his right knee, but the
panic level has been significantly decreased.
</P>
<P>
   The last month or so has seen the addition of defenseman Kevin
Dean, a Chambers-like player from New Jersey's system, and marked
improvement from defensemen Jamie Pushor, Brad Lukowich and Richard
Jackman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all thought that we had to get the job done or else
they'd get someone else to do it,'' Lukowich said. ``Just from
then, saying we weren't getting the job done, to now, we've all
come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, the biggest improvement has come from Pushor.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled early. He started playing less. He started
struggling more. Finally, he was struggling so much that Hitchcock
talked to him and benched him for a couple of games.
</P>
<P>
   The Pushor who came back was better than the Pushor who left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the first 20, even 30, games,'' Pushor said. ``I just
had to struggle to find my niche. We talked about it with the
coaches, and I was just trying to do what they want me to do out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   What the coaches wanted from Pushor, Lukowich, Jackman and now
Dean is not to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably, the best way to describe it is when you bring in so
many new players on defense through necessity, what you want to do
is have them play the game error free as much as possible,''
Hitchcock said. ``And I think as the season moved along, all four
guys have started to eliminate mistakes in their game and gotten
better and better in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, Hitchcock said, can be found in the little
details.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the pucks that get dumped into the Stars' zone are
getting pushed out a lot faster. Whether it's Pushor or Sergei
Zubov, Lukowich or Richard Matvichuk, the pucks are being handled
with a lot more composure. They come in. They go out. They're
passed to the right places. The plays are made with confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've started to, I guess you can say, fit in a little bit more
and understand our game a little bit more,'' Pushor said. ``There
has been a little more opportunity to play a little more, and there
have been some games where I have definitely started to play better
than others.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars have better been able to absorb the loss of
captain Derian Hatcher and Chambers. The extra minutes Hitchcock
has been able to entrust Lukowich and Pushor with have taken
pressure off Zubov, Darryl Sydor and Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the bulk of the responsibility still falls to that trio but
the other four have been taking on more responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like at the end of the game, when you don't notice
them, things have gone really well,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Silence, indeed, is golden.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
