<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-T     01-30 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS, NEAL HAVE BECOME DESTINY'S DARLINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before the Music City Miracle, Tennessee Titans
fullback Lorenzo Neal was an unknown. Just like his team.
</P>
<P>
   Then, destiny dropped into Neal's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two days later, the Titans find themselves playing for
the Super Bowl championship. Fate is a funny thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that happened, it felt like we had lost,'' Neal said.
``Guys had their heads down, crying, and then, new life. We tasted
defeat in that second, so we know what it feels like to lose in the
playoffs. I think that's what keeps us going.''
</P>
<P>
   With Buffalo leading 16-15 with 16 seconds remaining in an AFC
wild-card playoff game, Bills kicker Steve Christie popped the
kickoff to Neal, who began one of the greatest plays in NFL
history. As everyone knows by now, Neal pitched the ball to tight
end Frank Wycheck, who threw a lateral to Kevin Dyson, who went 75
yards for the game-winning score.
</P>
<P>
   Their 13 seconds of fame will last a lot longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm known more for that play than probably anything in my
whole career,'' Neal said. ``It's real cool. They're comparing it
to the Immaculate Reception by Franco Harris, and it is exciting.
But honestly, I'll trade it all for a Super Bowl win.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal left Fresno State as the school's second-leading career
rusher with 2,405 yards. He ran right into the NFL without
stopping, gaining a league-leading 175 yards on 21 carries in seven
quarters of his rookie season with the New Orleans Saints. But a
shattered left ankle in the third quarter of the second game
changed the course of his career.
</P>
<P>
   In the six seasons since _ three with the Saints, one with the
New York Jets, one with the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and one with the
Titans _ Neal has gained 207 yards on 73 carries. That's a great
rushing day for Titans running back Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, hard road, but it's all worth it now,'' Neal
said. ``I guess I wouldn't savor it as much as if I just went my
first year. I know this opportunity doesn't happen often.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans know that as well as any team in the NFL. It has
taken them 35 years, three cities, six stadiums, a name change and
many heartbreaks to reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, which has played in four stadiums the past four
seasons, has no business being here. But in three postseason games,
the Titans received a miracle, a requiem via instant replay and a
third matchup against a team that can't beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Some things can't be explained. Some things just happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans were meant to be here. They are a team of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, one wild play is the difference in us being in this
game,'' George said. ``If that wouldn't have happened, we wouldn't
be here right now. I guess it is destined for us to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Is anyone willing to bet against fate today?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
