<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0898 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN--BRYANT-HNS &LR;      01-30 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BRYANT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Mature beyond his years, Lakers' Bryant developing uniquely
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Kobe's here.
</P>
<P>
   And, like other wildly popular first-name-only players before
him, no last name is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, all that's really needed to identify Los Angeles Lakers
guard Kobe Bryant, who visits Compaq Center for today's matinee
game against the Rockets, is the given name that was borrowed from
a cattle-raising area of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe.
</P>
<P>
   Just that name is all that's needed to stir images of graceful
athleticism, on-a-leash ball-handling and eye-popping dunks that
define Bryant's high-voltage game. Image after image flash by,
somewhat ironic given the ``Image Is Nothing'' tag line on his
Sprite commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to Bryant's cool, self-assured manner and his polite,
personable way with people and it's a safe bet to assume he one day
will achieve the level of popularity enjoyed by Michael _ and you
know which Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows which Michael, a point that was made by former
Lakers coach Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let me put it this way,'' Harris said. ``When he broke
into the league, he was Michael Jordan. Then after a while, it was
MJ. Then it was Michael. Then he became Mike. Pretty soon, all
you'll need to say is `M,' and people will still know who you're
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant isn't there, but he has reached the point where he, too,
is on a first-name basis with the rest of the basketball world.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Wilt, Oscar and Julius. And just like Magic and
Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Among those first-name-brand greats, Bryant seems to be the most
like Jordan _ at least a lot of people would like him to be. He has
the charisma, the photogenic looks and the game _ you have to have
the game _ that make comparisons to Jordan inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   And his marketing portfolio _ Adidas, Sprite, Spalding, Mattel
and Nintendo so far _ might one day rival Jordan's as well. Give
him time, though, since he's only 21 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dedicated and he's competitive,'' said new Lakers coach
Phil Jackson. ``He reminds me a lot of Michael Jordan, and there's
not too many players who have ever done that.''
</P>
<P>
   See?
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who honed his fatherly basketball-guru chops on Jordan
during his nine-year stint with the Bulls, is trying to put a
damper on much of the hype surrounding Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a 21-year-old kid who's carrying the weight of the NBA on
his shoulders on some level, or the hopes of the NBA in his own
mind,'' Jackson said. ``And I'd like to see him really enjoy the
space he has and the potential that he has to grow to reach that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tentacles are out there, but he hasn't really developed
the roots _ and that's going to come. That's going to be the
interesting part of us watching his game. So, hopefully, he'll let
that happen and not try and force it, but let that kind of happen
and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   There's the rub in Bryant's game.
</P>
<P>
   His motto is, ``Time is precious,'' so sitting back and waiting
for something to happen, even allowing a play to develop, seems to
go against Bryant's nature.
</P>
<P>
   But that's understandable. After all, Bryant, the son of former
NBA player Joe Bryant, went from resident stud at Lower Merion
(Pa.) High School, where he was named National High School Player
of the Year by USA Today and Gatorade, to the NBA without interning
on the college level.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson is working to temper Bryant's impatience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's great _ way more mature than I could ever imagine a
21-year-old kid could be,'' Jackson said. ``A lot of times, Kobe
will take his own lead out there and I understand that. Sometimes
you don't want to misuse your own judgment as a player. And I
understand that; he's got to be able to read on his own and that's
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are times Bryant appears to force things simply
because he believes he can pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say we've experienced times where he's amazed us and
we've been proud of him,'' said teammate Rick Fox. ``(But) you get
frustrated. You wouldn't give your 10-year-old the keys to drive
the whole bus to school. So it's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Like two weeks ago, when Bryant went solo and lost his dribble
to the Cavaliers' Bob Sura in the fourth quarter, leading to a
Cleveland score at the other end. Jackson called timeout and began
ripping into Bryant before the seat of his shorts could even make
contact with the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Look, I try to make a play sometimes, and I know it
doesn't come out or doesn't happen the right way sometimes, but I'm
out there, trying my heart out.''' Bryant said. ``And (Jackson)
said that it's cool, to just put it behind you _ just move on to
the next play, buckle down and win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant wasn't happy about the vocal flogging, but understands
Jackson uses him as his verbal cat-scratch post. Why? Because
Jackson knows Bryant can take it without the danger of a psychic
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care,'' Bryant said. ``I've had coaches who
because of their personality like getting up in your face and stuff
like that. That's fine by me. I played with a coach my first two or
three years (Harris) who didn't say a word. It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson usually employs more low-key ways of putting Bryant in
his place. During practices, Jackson will often wave Bryant off the
court at critical times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be like game point, and he'll take me out of the dang
practice,'' Bryant said. ``Just because. Just because he knows I
hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his age, it would be easy to dismiss such a response as
childish impertinence. Bryant, then 18, was taken by Charlotte with
the 13th pick in the 1996 draft, and a draft-day deal sent him to
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later the Lakers signed free-agent Shaquille O'Neal
to a blockbuster $120 million deal, and suddenly the Lakers, who
were in the process of rebuilding after the Showtime heyday of the
1980s, had their Kareem and Magic _ again, first names only _ of
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaq and Kobe haven't always gotten along, mainly because of
their contrasting personalities. O'Neal's staggering physical
dimensions are dwarfed by his enormous personality, always looking
for fun no matter where the team is playing. But Bryant prefers his
hotel room, writing poetry or nourishing his growing musical
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go hang out just to be hanging out,'' Bryant
said. ``That's a waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is another sign of Bryant's relative inexperience.
Sometimes hanging out with teammates just for the sake of hanging
out is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's moving toward the intimidation factor,'' Fox said
early this year. ``Maybe he has a game plan in his mind he's
putting to work. I just think that it's going to be a long 20 years
in this league if he continues to isolate and not reach out or let
people in.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a point Jerry West, the Lakers' executive vice president
of basketball operations, intends to impress on the precocious
star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really broached that, but I think it's something
that's really, really important for him to understand,'' West said.
``I feel it's important for people to understand the dynamics of a
locker room. I've always felt, be who you are, be yourself. But I
do think you have to embrace your teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as he embraces the game. Not content to simply let his
talent slide him through the league, Bryant constantly works to
hammer out the dings in his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that people wouldn't believe is how hard he
works,'' said former teammate Derek Harper. ``The kid is gifted and
obviously he's very, very talented as a young basketball player.
But the reason he'll be great one day is because of his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He simply works harder than anybody I know. He's the first guy
there (to practice), the last guy to leave a lot of times. He
studies the game and takes it very, very seriously, and that, for a
young player, was a little bit surprising for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need him to be a really super player if we're going to win
a championship,'' Jackson said. ``And it might not happen in one
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson then caught himself and smiled, recalling Bryant's
famous impatience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might take two months.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
