<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SANTAC     01-30 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SANTACLARA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE WINS EIGHTH CONSECUTIVE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
ATTN: Brown 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ The alarm clock went off with precisely fifteen
minutes and thirty-nine seconds left to play.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Pepperdine rose out of bed and went to work. The
alarm didn't come in the form of a nagging buzzer, nor was it
soothing music. Rather, it was a jump shot by Darrell Teat to give
Santa Clara a nine-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   At stake were the Waves' seven-game winning streak, first place
in the West Coast Conference and their perfect record in the WCC.
</P>
<P>
   But off to work Pepperdine went, starting with Craig Lewis'
3-pointer to ignite 10-0 run that Tommie Prince, capped off with a
tough 3-pointer with the shot clock winding down and a hand in his
face.
</P>
<P>
   In less then three mintues the Waves had awakened from their
slumber, seized the lead and taken command of the game, which they
went on to win 67-59 before 1,872 at Firestone Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes for Pepperdine (16-5, 6-0), which extended its
winning streak to eight games and remained in first place heading
into a critical showdown next Thursday at Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play particularly well tonight but I thought we
gutted out a victory,'' Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff said.
``Some games are going to be where you shoot really well and play
really well, and other games you might struggle. But if you can
find a way to win when you don't play very well, then I think
you've got a pretty special team.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly these Waves are showing the characteristics of being a
special team, piecing together wins on off-nights, while playing on
the road and in games when they were pushed to the limit the night
before. Pepperdine rallied Friday night to beat San Francisco while
Santa Clara breezed to an easy win over Loyola Marymont. That might
explain why the Broncos (12-9, 3-3), who got 16 points each from
Brian Jones and Teat, seemed fresher in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Waves settled down in the second, thanks to a better
effort defensively and on the glass _ they forced 10 turnovers and
outrebounded the Broncos by nine in the half _ and the play of
Tezale Archie (18 points, five assists), Armstrong (11 points) and
Kelvin Gibbs (nine points, eight rebounds.)
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Waves outscored Santa Clara 24-7 to take a
57-49 lead. The Broncos never got closer then four points after
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got into the flow and we started to execute the
plays,'' Armstrong said. ``It just came down to where we were all
feeling it at the same time and we started hitting big shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Friday night against San Francisco, the Waves trailed
by one at halftime, 33-32. Unlike the previous night, the problem
wasn't just turnovers. This time it was defensive lapses and cold
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine let Santa Clara's Jones roam free on the perimeter,
and the junior guard from Carson took advantage with 13 points
while connecting on 3 of 6 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos shot just 43 percent from the field, but they were 5
of 12 on 3-pointers and committed just four turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves' frigid shooting compounded the problem. They were a
miserable 36 percent from the field, although they heated up late
in the half, getting 3-pointers from Archie, Armstrong and Gibbs to
keep it close.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine shook off the Broncos' quick start to open the
second, rallying back from a 42-33 hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that we have an experienced team, that we can be down
but still have the character to come back and win the ball game,''
Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Armstrong doesn't want to keep testing that character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're going to try and work on the first half.''
Armstrong said. ``We've got the second half down. We just have to
work on the first half.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
