<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA ROUTED   BY OREGON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Ancient and creaky, McArthur stands across the
street from a cemetary. Its gray concrete walls rise higher than
Oregon pine. There are two levels of green and yellow balcony seats
that deflect noise onto the court. There is not an inch of excess
space; it's a most unforgiving place.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has had its share of Mac Court meltdowns. In 1995, Jim
Harrick lost his cool and was ejected in the final minutes of a
close game. In 1997, the Bruins broke down in the final minutes of
a 16-point defeat . Even mild-mannered players like Tyus Edney and
Bob Myers have exchanged words with the league's rudest students.
</P>
<P>
   But there has never been anything like this _ a collapse so
complete, so sudden that it left the Bruins shaken and sullen. With
one exception, the lockerroom was quieter than it's been all
season.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the final score. (Oregon won 73-58.) These are the
numbers that matter:
</P>
<P>
   - Leading 40-39 midway through the second half, the Bruins were
outscored 18-0.
</P>
<P>
   -During that stretch, UCLA went scoreless for 6:37. That's a
third of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dominated us in every phase,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin
said.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't talking about Duke or Kentucky or Stanford or
Arizona. This was Oregon, a well-coached team with a roster full of
junior college transfers and second-tier recruits. Yet the Ducks
overwhelmed UCLA in a manner usually saved for teams with lottery
picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half,'' Oregon forward A.D. Smith said, ``I
think we won most of the individual battles.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance so disgusted UCLA senior Sean Farnham that he
scolded his teammates in a tirade not heard since Ed O'Bannon
blasted the Bruins at halftime of the 1994 first-round loss to
Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going down like this!'' Farnham screamed, pounding his
right fist against the lockerroom wall. ``I'm not going to the
NIT!''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, calm and throughful, Farnham elaborated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point where we needed a win, we needed a sweep,''
he said. ``We had it in our grasp, and we let it slip away. It's
disappointing because we had a breakthrough in the second half at
Oregon State , and we played well for 15 minutes tonight, and we
couldn't sustain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't execute our offense. We had a lot of turnovers. Ther
e were a lot of similarities to the Arizona game, and that's
frustrating .''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, it seems, is UCLA lacks the fundamentals and the
structure to execute its offense for 40 minutes against elite
defenses. It does not have the patience and the discipline to stay
calm when opponents surge.
</P>
<P>
   The better the foe, the smaller the margin for error, yet the
Bruins play the same way against everyone. They can overcome
mistakes against Arizona State and Oregon State, but not against
Arizona and Oregon and Stanford. Those teams too good; they pounce
on every mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, UCLA opened the second half with five consecutive
turnovers, enabling Oregon to snatch a 35-31 lead. Although the
Bruins stayed close for several minutes, the Ducks had found their
groove. Each basket boosted their confidence and energized the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Mac Court engulfed the Bruins. They began passing and
shooting a split-second quick. Billy Knight and Ray Young missed
ill-timed jumpers. Dan Gadzuric mishandled a pass. Young shot a
3-pointer off the side of the backboard, then clanked a leaner. The
ball movement and patience they showed in the first half vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mental,'' point guard Earl Watson said. ``We lacked
concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Smith walked by the UCLA lockerro om as Farnham
berated his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Someone suggested that a scolding might be just what the Bruins
need. Smith just smiled and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes more than that, guys,'' he said. ``It takes a lot
more than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
