r s BC-BKC-USC-LADN     01-30 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC SETS RECORD IN WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. -- The way USC was shooting Saturday night, its
motto seemed to be ``three-peat after me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans put on an incredible shooting display against Oregon
State, hitting a Pacific-10 Conference record 20 3-pointers in an
82-69 victory over the Beavers at Gill Coliseum before 6,099.
</P>
<P>
   USC smashed its school record for 3-pointers (15) early in the
second half and broke the Pacific-10 Conference record of 18 when
Nate Hair hit a 3- pointer with 8:32 remaining. Washington State
set the old record against Seattle-Pacific in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in the 3-pointer but tonight they made me
believe in the 3-point shot,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``It was
just one of those nights. Guys got really good looks and didn't
force anything. We know we have guys that can shoot the
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were nearly unconscious in the second half. They hit
their first 11 shots and nine of those were 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Every Trojan starter hit at least three 3-pointers, and they did
it with out a single substitution until 57.2 seconds were left in
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, USC finished 20 of 29 on 3-point shots. For good
measure, Orego n State was 10 for 24.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Granville led USC with 21 points, and five 3-pointers.
David Bluthenthal (five 3-pointers) and Jeff Trepagnier (three
3-pointers) each had 17.
</P>
<P>
   Hair scored a career-high 14 points and made 4 of 5 of his
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   USC's first miss of the second half didn't occur until Granville
missed a 3-pointer with 9:42 left. By that time, the Oregon State
fans were chanting ``miss, miss, miss'' each time the Trojans had
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Trojans (13-6, 6-1) remained in a tie for
first-place in the Pacific-10 Conference with Arizona, Stanford and
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more importantly, the Trojans are putting some room
between themselves and the next tier of conference teams in their
drive to earn an NCAA Tournament bid. The next closest teams
(Arizona State, UCLA) are currently three games behind USC.
</P>
<P>
   But inside Gill Coliseum, all anyone was thinking about was the
shooting display put on by the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   USC hit its first eight 3-point attempts of the second half and
made 18 of their first 23 attempts to open a 70-44 advantage with
11:48 left when Bluthenthal hit his fourth 3-pointer of the game.
Forward Brian Scalabrine converted his first three 3-pointers of
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   USC led 39-32 at halftime solely because of their outside
shooting. USC made 9 of 14 3-point shots, and Granville made four
3-pointers and had 12 points in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Hair, inserted into the starting lineup in place of center
Kostas Charissis, scored eight points and made two 3-pointers in he
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier also rebounded from a poor performance at Oregon with
11 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   It was somewhat ironic that the Trojans led by seven,
considering their leading scorer, Scalabrine, scored just two
points in the first half. Bluthenthal, another of the Trojans'
mainstays, had just six.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State stayed within striking distance with its own hot
shooting. The Beavers hit 5 of 11 3-pointers in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State (2-5, 10-8) remained winless at home in Pac-10 play
with an 0-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Trojans return home this week and host California on
Thursday night at 7 at the Sports Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
