<HEADER>
A0904 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     01-30 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS HAVE A SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Titans were forced to hold interviews this week in an
underheated tent outside their Atlanta hotel - while the Rams and
reporters following them enjoyed the comforts of a hotel ballroom -
Tennessee players saw it as evidence NFL officials were playing
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another example of us being considered a second-rate team,'' a
Titans defensive lineman complained, presumably through chattering
teeth, to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like somebody has been playing the
we-don't-get-no-respect card in the motivation game that precedes
Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, before Tennessee faced Jacksonville for the AFC
championship, the Titans were shown a videotape of some of the
opposing players performing a song and dance to be shown at a
charity event, with lyrics suggesting the Jaguars were already on
their way to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like somebody has been playing the
we-don't-get-no-respect card for a while now.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody is Jeff Fisher, the Titans' 41-year-old head coach, a
product of USC and, before that, Taft High in Woodland Hills. The
man whose ingenuity - and whose staff of assistants - holds
Tennessee's hope for an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, applauded for his motivational skills, obviously has
been trying to evoke the emotion that's available only to
underdogs, that feeling that it's them against the world and the
world hasn't noticed.
</P>
<P>
   On paper - the tissue paper upon expectations have been written
this season - the Titans have good reason to feel like the
second-rate team in the Georgia Dome today, whether or not they've
been treated like B-list guests all week in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams are the flashier team, the better
rags-to-riches story. The Rams, not the Titans, are the natural
choice if there were to be a darling of the league and media.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams outranked the Titans on offense (rushing and passing)
and defense (against the rush and the pass) during the regular
season. To find a Titans statistical edge, you have to look at
categories like ``gross punting average.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams met little resistance on their rise to the top of the
NFC until the conference title game against the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers. The Titans needed a once-in-a-lifetime finish just to
get past the Buffalo Bills in the wild-card playoff.
</P>
<P>
   And there's this item, which blows the circuits of everybody who
thinks the comparisons above are out of whack because of the Rams'
weak regular-season schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Rams' and Titans' performances against common
opponents, in the cases where even the venue was the same, home or
road. The Rams did better than the Titans in !ital!all six!off! of
those games - by at least 13 points in each case.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Titans overcome all of that? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the Titans played most of those common opponents
early in the season, and they're a better team now, having exceeded
the oddsmakers' expectations seven weeks in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Also: The Titans' stock in trade is their ability to rise up
against the NFL's best teams. They're 6-0 against Indianapolis,
Buffalo (both in the playoffs), Jacksonville (twice in the regular
season, once in the playoffs) and St. Louis (in their midseason
meeting).
</P>
<P>
   That 24-21 victory over the Rams, which should give the Titans
confidence today, was no more convincing than the score indicates.
It was played in Nashville, on a grass field, not artificial turf
like the Georgia Dome's. It was played after a Titans bye week. And
although that was Titans quarterback Steve McNair's first game back
from a back injury, that might have been an advantage for them,
because the Rams had practiced for Neil O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   But that game might provide enough of a blueprint for Fisher. He
figured out Jacksonville, handing the Jaguars all three of their
defeats, holding them to three of their six sub-20-point games.
</P>
<P>
   Can he do it to the Rams? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the Titans can win:
</P>
<P>
   By getting the lead early, as they did against the Rams on Oct.
31, blunting 1,300-yard ballcarrier Marshall Faulk's impact.
</P>
<P>
   By holding onto the ball, defying a Rams defense that scored
eight touchdowns this season.
</P>
<P>
   By putting pressure on Rams quarterback Kurt Warner, whom they
sacked six times in the earlier meeting, and who seemed flustered
by the Tampa Bay pressure.
</P>
<P>
   By counting on McNair to run away from the Rams' pass rushers,
confounding them with his improvisation.
</P>
<P>
   By coming up with a big play - from McNair? from Eddie George?
from the kickoff-return team? - to score the pivotal points.
</P>
<P>
   Doing all of that won't be easy. But Fisher has shown this year
that he can figure out how, and lead the Titans out of the cold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 0159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
