<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-USC-WRITETHRU-LAD     01-30 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC SETS RECORD IN WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. -- The way USC was shooting Saturday night, its
motto seemed to be ``three-peat after me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Granville made a 3-pointer. Brian Scalabrine hit two
straight. David Bluthenthal got one. Scalabrine sank two more. Then
Bluthenthal again. Jeff Trepagnier added another. Finally, Nate
Hair capped it off.
</P>
<P>
   And this was just to start the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just shake your head and say, `It's one of those games,'
'' Hair said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans put on an incredible shooting display against Oregon
State, hitting a Pacific-10 Conference record 20 3-pointers in an
82-69 victory over the Beavers at Gill Coliseum before 6,099.
</P>
<P>
   USC smashed its school record for 3-pointers (15) early in the
second half and broke the Pac-10 record of 18 when Hair hit a
3-pointer with 8:32 remaining. Washington State set the old record
against Seattle-Pacific in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in the 3-pointer but tonight they made me
believe in the 3-point shot,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``Guys
got really good looks and didn't force anything. We know we have
guys that can shoot the basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby just didn't know they could shoot like this. Overall, USC
converted 20 of 29 3-pointers, and hit its first nine in the second
half. The Trojans made their first 11 field-goals of the second
half to break the game open.
</P>
<P>
   They led 39-32 at halftime, and by the time Hair hit the
Trojans' ninth straight 3-pointer, USC had a 67-44 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is within five or six points, and all of a sudden I
look up and we're up 16 or more,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Every Trojan starter hit at least three 3-pointers, and none
made less than 50 percent of their attempts. And the Trojans almost
did it without a single substitution. Bibby put in his first
replacements with 57.2 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   USC (13-6, 6-1) realized it was on a roll during its 9 for 9
streak when Scalabrine leaned forward and tried to draw a foul by
throwing up an awkward shot that found its way into the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something funny going on when Brian hit his
3-pointer,'' Bluthenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Granville led USC with 21 points, five 3-pointers and 11
assists. David Bluthenthal (five 3-pointers) and Jeff Trepagnier
(three 3-pointers) each had 17.
</P>
<P>
   Hair scored a career-high 14 points and made 4 of 5 of his
3-pointers along with seven assists. Scalabrine made three shots
from 3-point range and finished with 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Gill Coliseum, fans were beginning to wonder if the
Trojans would miss after they hit those first 11 shots after
halftime. USC's first miscue of the second half didn't occur until
Granville missed a 3-pointer with 9:42 left.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Oregon State fans were chanting ``miss, miss,
miss'' each time the Trojans had the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best extra-pass movement we've had since
we've been playing,'' Bibby said. ``I was just hoping we wouldn't
miss tonight .''
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Trojans moved into a four-way tie for
first-place in the Pac-10 with Arizona, Stanford and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps just as important, USC is putting some distance between
itself and the next tier of conference teams in its drive to earn
an NCAA Tournament bid. The next closest teams (Arizona State,
UCLA) are currently three games behind USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important because it's a road win and we needed a split
up here,' ' Bibby said. ``We're fighting for first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State (10-8, 2-5) has lost all five home games in Pac-10
play, and the game was not nearly as close as the score indicated.
USC led 80-54 before being outscored 15-2 over the final 4:37.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if any of you have seen anything like that but I
haven't, '' Oregon State coach Eddie Payne said. ``I've been at
this for about 25 ye ars and I've never seen a performance like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Trojans return home this week and host California on
Thursday night at 7 at the Sports Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
