<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI RULES IN AUSTRALIA 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ The Cold War is well over, but Andre Agassi kept it
hot for a Russian named Kafelnikov for almost 2 1/2 hours Saturday
in his continuing campaign to rule the world.
</P>
<P>
   Victory in the Australian Open assured Agassi of hanging onto
No. 1, in which he girded himself at the close of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It was Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the slim and limber sweet-swinging
25-year-old from the shore of the Black Sea, who came to town
wearing the crown of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But he left bare-headed, with his mood matching the black
stripes on his shirt and shorts, deposed by Agassi in four sets,
3-6, 6-3, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi completed the American double that Lindsay Davenport
launched Friday with her championship. They are the first
home-grown Yanks to win the Australian since Californians Don Budge
and Dodo Bundy in 1938. The last two US citizens to do it were
Chris Evert and Johan Kriek in 1982. The South African-born Kriek
had been recently naturalized.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Agassi and Kafelnikov went at each other
ferociously in a battle of wills and deep groundstrokes to see who
would bend first.
</P>
<P>
   It was Agassi, the champion of this island once before, in 1995,
who was dented quickly. In 14 minutes, he found himself in the
rear, 0-4, as Kafelnikov was out-Agassi-ing Agassi, allowing balls
to barely bounce before he crushed them, sending the American
scurrying from corner to corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yevgeny had to come out fast and he did,'' Agassi said. ``I
felt there was much more of a chance for me to run away with the
match than for him to. But it quickly turned into a physical match
and I liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering, Agassi stormed back to 3-4, but Kafelnikov wouldn't
let him go any further and slugged away dead even with the American
through seven games of the second. There, Kafelnikov began to
falter while Agassi, magnificent all the way, maintained his blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov double-faulted twice to open the eighth game, and his
second serves thwacking into the net seemed to signal his demise,
although he fought gamely to the end in trying to retain the
throne.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi finally sealed his fate with three aces in the
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi sensed blood with Kafelnikov's serving sins, and was all
over him. Before the Russian could recover his stability, he had
been flattened in a seven-game procession that gave Agassi the set
and a 4-0 lead in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov, the 6-foot-3-inch blond, resisted mightily as Agassi
drew even by serving out the second, 6-3, through three deuces. He
nailed it shut with his heaviest serve of the afternoon to that
point, a 112 miles per hour service winner.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi wanted a hot day and was disappointed by the 70-degree
temperature, which was moderate for a Melbourne summer that has
been unusually chilly and kept most of the crowd of 15,000
sweatered up in Rod Laver Arena.
</P>
<P>
   So, Agassi supplied his own heat, burning up the court with his
sneakers and racket, running so swiftly and banging so
relentlessly, with few mistakes, that Kafelnikov was trying to play
catch-up from deep in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's hitting his stride right now,'' Agassi's coach,
Brad Gilbert, said. ``Ultimately he wants to keep improving. There
are a lot more titles for him to win. He has three or four more
good years left in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, winning his sixth major and second straight (following
the US Open), arrived in Melbourne at No. 1, Kafelnikov No. 2 _
those rankings based on a system discarded this year. Under the new
formula, the rankings run from week to week, as a race, and the
12-month cumulative method was abandoned. Thus Agassi and
Kafelnikov were playing for first place in the young season. Agassi
gave himself a shot by eliminating No. 3 Pete Sampras in a five-set
wowzer Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov said, ``I'm amazed at how Andre recovered from losing
the first set and kept raising his level. My legs began to tire at
the end of the third, and he realized it, and raised his level
again. I had been controlling the match, but his belief in himself
is incredible. He just kept competing harder and took over
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching, lunging, battering, leaping, Agassi reinforced his
late-blooming greatness by taking away all but the optimum shots of
his foe and belting them back with added muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got another gear I can always shift into,'' said Agassi,
who made but 35 errors to Kafelnikov's 61. ``And if that's not
enough, the other guy deserves to win. I wanted to keep executing
because Yevgeny's a guy who is too good and can come back. But I
was sure I had the other gear ready if he did.''
</P>
<P>
   With no time to bask in success, Agassi flies to Africa Monday
to spearhead the US Davis Cup first-round effort against the
Zimbabwean Black brothers Wayne and Byron, who defeated Australia
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's just another A to Z voyage in the life of the world ruler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
