r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     01-30 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS END LOSING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Look out NBA. Eric Murdock is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the sentiment the Clippers' journeyman hinted
at Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock had season highs with 16 points, 11 rebounds and 7
assists to help end a 10-game losing streak and boost the Clippers
over the visiting New Jersey Nets, 98-93, before 13,769 at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm healthy, I play pretty good,'' said Murdock, who's
had an array of minor leg problems. ``It's been frustrating for me
because I haven't been healthy all year. This is the best I've felt
since training camp, to be honest with you. Hopefully, I can
continue to get my legs stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Alhough the Clippers' point guard had his best night of the
season, New Jersey's Stephon Marbury had a chance to tie it with a
3-pointer at 95 in the last 16 seconds. Guarded by Lamar Odom,
Marbury turned the ball over to Tyrone Nesby, who dunked to end the
game after a fast break with Odom.
</P>
<P>
   It only could have been a more fitting exclamation point if
Murdock were involved. Murdock's task was especially hard because
his counter point guard was Marbury, who was coming off a
career-high 42 points Thursday at Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Murdock) did an outstanding job for us, offensively and
defensively,'' Clippers coach Chris Ford said. ``He ran the offense
just as we needed him to. If we continue to stick to the offensive
plan, we will continue to have good chances to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind Murdock, who is on his seventh NBA team in nine seasons,
the Clippers weren't just a one-man show. Maurice Taylor scored a
team-high 23 points and had eight rebounds. Odom had 21 points and
10 rebounds, and Derek Anderson had 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   For the Nets (17-27), Kerry Kittles had a game-high 24 points,
and Marbury had 23 points and seven assists. Keith Van Horn had an
off night by shooting 5 of 18 for 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (11-32) took the lead, 82-81, with 4:45 left on a
free throw by Taylor and never relinquished it. The Nets stayed
closed and tied it twice in the following minutes, but the Clippers
finally sealed the victory when Marbury turned over the ball.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the third quarter, Odom nearly led the Clippers
far past the Nets. Odom scored the Clippers' first 10 points in the
quarter and had 12 points and eight rebounds in the third quarter.
With 4:40 left in the third, Taylor scored off a pass from Odom to
give the Clippers' their biggest lead, 61-53.
</P>
<P>
   However, Marbury had four points and an assist in a 9-0 run to
reclaim the lead for New Jersey. By the end of the third quarter,
the Clippers bounced back to lead, 69-66.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers led, 43-42, at the half, after Murdock had his
strongest half this season. The game became a triple-double watch
as Murdock had 11 points, 6 rebounds and 6 assists in the first
half. Starting in just his fourth consecutive game over Troy
Hudson, Murdock also had a season high with 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the stats,'' said Murdock, who added he wasn't
aware of his proximity to the triple-double.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock and his fellow Clippers were relieved to stop their
10-game funk. However, the players downplayed the dubious streak's
importance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not about streaks,'' Anderson said. ''It's about playing
together. More or less, we finally came together for four quarters.
We weren't turning the ball over as much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
