<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TORSO-KILL-AZR &LR;      01-30 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORSO-KILL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIFE DENIES KILLING HUSBAND, ADMITS DUMPING TORSO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JIM WALSH AND CHRISTINA LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Scottsdale beauty salon owner told police she put her
husband's torso into her blue Jaguar and dumped it into a trash bin
four days after finding him dead because she feared she would be
accused of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, one day after being arrested at her upscale salon, a
shaken Valerie Pape, 47, was led into a Mesa court wrapped in a
blue blanket.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked the petite blonde if she was responsible
for killing Ira Pomerantz, 60, her husband of five years, she said,
``No, I am not.''
</P>
<P>
   Pape, described as a ``gentle soul,'' was estranged from her
husband, the former owner of two East Valley bars. The two had a
stormy relationship that drew police to their Scottsdale home a
half-dozen times and caused her to seek an order of protection.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, neighbors said, had been jealous of a male friend
of his wife who dwelled in the couple's home and was part owner of
the Valerie Pape Beauty Gallery at 4200 N. Marshall Way in downtown
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Pape said she found her husband's clothed body lying face up in
a pool of blood in the kitchen of her Scottsdale home Monday
morning. A gun lay nearby. Her husband had been fatally shot in the
back with a medium- to large-caliber gun, police said.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted cleaning up the blood. She hid the weapon under the
rear seat of her car, she said. And she admitted tossing her
husband's legless, armless naked torso behind the Bashas' at
McDowell and Power roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she did not tell us how the body was dismembered,'' Mesa
Detective Butch Gates wrote in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear what she did with the body for four days.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Earle Lloyd, a Mesa police spokesman, said he believed Pape
may have needed help with the slaying because she is petite.
</P>
<P>
   Court records reveal Pomerantz's body was cut apart with an
electric cutting tool. Police have searched her $372,000 home and
her beauty parlor. They have not reported whether they found the
missing body parts. Police seized both the weapon and the car
Jaguar itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She claimed that she did not report this to police because she
thought she would be blamed,'' the court records said.
</P>
<P>
   Some friends and neighbors Saturday recalled the couple's
wedding reception in the back yard of their 2,918-square foot home.
The pair had met in New York, where Pape was caring for Pomerantz's
father, friends said. They moved to the Scottsdale residence in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Bua, whose bakery adjoins the beauty salon, sold Pape her
wedding cake. Bua also was a frequent client in the salon that
charges $48 for a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard her say an unkind thing about anybody,'' Bua
said. ``She's very gentle.''
</P>
<P>
   Pape was described as sweet, happy, athletic and meticulous in
her appearance. She jogged through the neighborhood almost every
morning and frequently hiked Camelback Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   She has a teenage daughter who was born in France but lives in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very sensitive, very sweet,'' one woman said. ``She
has a gentle soul. She wouldn't hurt a fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Vega, manager of nearby Bronco Billy's Night Club in
Chandler, described Pomerantz as ``a good old man, very friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pomerantz had a drinking problem, said Vega and Lynn Waters,
35, a waitress who once worked in one of Pomerantz's bars, Rhythm
and Cues at 140 W. Warner Road in Chandler. Both said he would pass
out while his bar was still open.
</P>
<P>
   His record includes a 1998 arrest for drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not a good businessman,'' Waters said. ``He didn't pay
his employees, he cheated his patrons, he watered down the booze
and served after hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Vega said Pomerantz got into trouble with state liquor
authorities because he served underage customers at Rhythm and
Cues.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Pomerantz gave Pape money from the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Pomerantz was wounded below the waist in the Vietnam War,
according to neighbor Lynn Hartman, 58. He had a daughter; it could
not be determined whether he had more children.
</P>
<P>
   According to bankruptcy and other records, Pomerantz appeared to
be a troubled businessman. He lost to bankruptcy both the
well-known Norton's Country Corner Western bar at Gilbert and
Chandler roads and his Rhythm and Cues bar.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said that several years ago, Michel Sauvage, a friend
of Pape's from France, moved in with the couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed a place to stay, and he was their house guest,''
Hartman said. ``Ira set up her hair salon, and gave him a piece of
it so he could stay in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hartman said Pomerantz told him that Pomerantz had become
suspicious of Sauvage's relationship with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started to smell a rat,'' Hartman said. ``He was really
distraught, but he said his two big Dobermans were his salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a whole big soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Sauvage works in the salon, and was listed as the real estate
agent on the ``for sale'' sign on the couple's home. Pape named
Sauvage as a friend in police reports.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sauvage was at work at the salon, answering phones. He
would not comment on the case. He has been questioned and released.
</P>
<P>
   Pape and Pomerantz fought constantly. Police would not release
reports from their visits to the home, but said they included
burglary, aggravated assault and a violation of an order of
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a deliveryman told Mesa police that he had spotted
Pape driving to the dumpster behind Bashas' in her 1997 Jaguar.
Another witness identified her from a composite drawing, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Pape on Friday at the posh parlor. She made her
initial appearance on suspicion of first-degree murder in West Mesa
Justice Court on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours before her court hearing, police and lab
technicians combed the couple's elegant McCormick Ranch home and
remained throughout the day. They sought body parts and evidence
that the slaying took place in the home.
</P>
<P>
   The salon, in downtown Scottsdale's arts and shopping district
west of Scottsdale Road, the city's main drag, was open. Customers
trailed in, and a woman employee sat on a bench, smoking a
cigarette and cradling her head in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   Pape is ``pretty shell-shocked,'' said James Belanger, her
attorney. ``She doesn't even understand what goes on in the
American legal system.''
</P>
<P>
   In court, Judge Clayton Hamblen ordered her held without bail
and set a Feb. 4 hearing date at which she would be expected to
enter a plea. &QL; 
Reporters Alexa Haussler and Carol Sowers contributed to this
article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
