<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-NH-GOP-HNS &LR;      01-30 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN CHALLENGES BUSH'S EXPERIENCE AS TEXAN RALLIES FAMILY  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDHAM, N.H. _ Arizona Sen. John McCain, pressing his
differences over Texas Gov. George W. Bush three days before New
Hampshire's Republican presidential primary, declared Saturday that
he does not need ``on-the-job training'' to lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   McCain touted his populist campaign at three question-and-answer
sessions as Bush canvassed southern New Hampshire with his famous
family in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush and former first lady Barbara Bush
joined their 52-year-old son on the campaign trail, as did former
Cabinet officer Elizabeth Dole, who dropped her own quest for the
Republican presidential nomination last fall and endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boy, this son of ours is not going to let you down,'' the
former president told more than 1,000 cheering, placard-waving
supporters gathered for a country music concert staged by the Bush
campaign at an indoor tennis complex in Milford.
</P>
<P>
   The former president, who lost his re-election bid in 1992 to
then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, told the crowd his son is ``going
to go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor spoke for barely one minute to the crowd,
including families who had been waiting for up to two hours to hear
the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel something in the air; we're on our way because of
you,'' Bush said as he introduced his parents. Following brief
remarks by his mother and father, Bush added: ``Thank you all for
coming. Work hard. Knock on those doors. Shake those hands. And
we're going to love Tuesday night.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire primary, the first of the 2000 campaign, is
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brief remarks left at least one member of the audience
perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well that was anti-climactic,'' complained Ron Pieterse, 40, a
dump truck driver from Peterborough who attended the rally with his
five-year-old daughter Sabina. ``I came to learn something. I guess
I'll have to go on the Internet to find out his positions on things
I care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Pieterse said he planned to vote for Bush on Tuesday because of
his enduring loyalty to the former president. ``I've got that
bumper sticker, `Don't blame me, I voted for Bush,''' Pieterse said
as he walked to his car with his daughter, who was holding her doll
Sophie.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign issued a statement that cited the benefits of
his proposed tax cut. Bush said his plan would help ``those who
live on the outskirts of poverty'' as well as ``knock down the
tollbooth to the middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said McCain's more modest tax cut included a provision to
tax the benefits paid employees by their companies. Bush said in
the statement: ``That's going to hurt working people.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who spoke to voters in Windham several hours earlier,
cited Bush's use of his legendary family during the final weekend
of the hard-fought New Hampshire campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The celebrities that I'm interested in are the people in this
room and the people of New Hampshire,'' McCain told several hundred
people packed into the auditorium at a junior high school in
Windham, home of the ``Windham Wildcats.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added, at his 109th town hall meeting n the campaign:
``You are the celebrities that are important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Three public opinion surveys released on Saturday showed McCain
leading Bush. The margin ranged from one percentage point in a
CNN-USA Today survey, 36 percent to 35 percent, to eight percentage
points in a University of New Hampshire-WMUR-Fox survey that showed
McCain leading Bush 41 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   John Zogby, a pollster based in Utica, N.Y., said the Republican
race could be ``very tight,'' adding: ``Bush may have the superior
organization to get out the vote and that could be critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Both McCain and Bush appealed for supporters to help turn out
the vote in a GOP field that includes three other candidates who
have not won elective office before _ magazine publisher Steve
Forbes, talk show host Alan Keyes, and former Reagan administration
official Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   McCain devoted 25 minutes of remarks to his audience in Windham
to highlighting differences with Bush over the size of their
proposed tax cuts, action to close corporate tax loopholes, the
breadth of their backgrounds, steps to protect the fiscal soundness
of Social Security and proposals to overhaul the way campaigns are
financed.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Bush was relying too heavily on support from the
wealthy to wage his campaign _ which has raised some $74 million _
while he was fighting to ``get big money out of Washington and give
the government back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added: ``Governor Bush is out there raising money. I'm
going to be out there raising hell.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain emphasized that he would not wage a negative campaign
against Bush, who is a ``good man.'' But the senator sought to
emphasize his experience over Bush, who first won elective office
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the life experiences; I have the legislative
experiences; I have knowledge of the grass roots issues,'' said
McCain, 63. ``I want you to know that I am fully prepared to be
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizonan served 22 years in the Navy, including five years
as a prisoner of North Vietnam, and has served 17 years in the
House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need any on-the-job training. I am fully prepared to
handle these responsibilities,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Johnson, 32, a farmer whose family owns one of the last
two farms in Windham, near the Massachusetts state line, said he
initially planned to vote for Bush but now intends to vote for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Bush talks in sound bites. He doesn't seem to think on
his feet. McCain gives you a straight answer. For me, that is the
No. 1 absolute minimum requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
