<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``WORD COURT'' &QL; 
By Barbara Wallraff (Harcourt, $24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wallraff, who was born and raised in Tucson, now lives in
Massachusetts, where she is a senior editor at ``The Atlantic
Monthly.'' In addition to reading nearly every word that goes into
nearly every issue of the magazine, she writes ``The Atlantic's''
``Word Court'' column, a clearinghouse, of sorts, for questions
about grammar, punctuation, word usage and the general health of
the English language. Her new book is based primarily on
reader-submitted questions, which she answers with an appealing mix
of common sense, research, wit and an occasional foray into
improvisation (although she would not emphasize this _ most of her
``rulings'' are based on solid advice from her dictionaries). She
also includes a ``Grammarian's Dozen,'' in which she addresses
recurring troubles such as the split infinitive or a preposition
left at the end of a clause. This is an engaging book for people
who love language and want to see it treated, if not with
reverence, at least with a little common courtesy.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
``MY GOODNESS'' &QL; 
By Joe Queenan (Hyperion, $21.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The word ``curmudgeon'' has been used to describe Joe Queenan
(``Red Lobster, White Trash''), but we think it is too kind. More
appropriate, perhaps, would be ``curmudgeon with fangs,'' or
``curmudgeon with occasional bouts of virulent malice.'' Either
way, he's a funny guy, except, we are sorry to say, in this book,
where he makes a tedious show of stifling his mean streak and
embracing goodness. He tries to make his newfound virtue
entertaining, but we'll bare our own fangs and say we didn't laugh
much. Far funnier is the paperback ``Confessions of a Cineplex
Heckler'' (Hyperion, $12.95), a collection of previously published
essays in which Queenan, among other exploits, shouts comments in a
dark movie theater just to see how other patrons will react, or
jumps fully clothed into the Atlantic to prove that Leonardo
DiCaprio could not have lived as long or talked as much as he did
at the end of ``Titanic.''Queenan might be hostile, but which book
do you want to read? &QL; 
 &QL; 
``ON THE REZ'' &QL; 
By Ian Frazier (FSG, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's something edgy _ dangerous, even _ about the premise of
this book: A middle-age, middle-class White man with a ponytail and
no particular leg to stand on writes about Indians, specifically
the Oglala Sioux of the Pine Ridge Reservation in South Dakota.
Indeed, Frazier begins by announcing his affinity for things
Indian, by confessing his admiration for historic Indian leaders
and wishing something ``Indian'' for himself, something traditional
``but harder to pin down.'' It's enough to make you squirm, were it
not for the immediate, disarming quality of Frazier's voice. By the
third page, you know you are not in for worshipful romance, but for
a story _ many stories _ told in a scattered but engaging way,
devoid of judgment or condescension, attentive to virtues but
unflinching in the face of trouble, all of it lifted by Frazier's
descriptive style (in winter, he says, cottonwood trees look ``as
if they had decided never to grow leaves again and were tormented
by the decision''). &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE TOP 10 OF EVERYTHING 2000'' &QL; 
By Russell Ash (DK, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   Every year, we swear we will not do this, every year we resolve
to banish Russell Ash from our thoughts, and every year we find
ourselves sitting for an irrational amount of time with his new
book of trivia clutched in our hot little hands. This time, we
learned that the pope who served the shortest term was Urban VII
(12 days in 1590). That the first American singer to have a No. 1
hit single in the United Kingdom was Al Martino. That the longest
word in the English language is the name of an enzyme and has no
less than 1,909 letters (this sounded familiar, giving rise to the
suspicion that Ash is cribbing from his earlier books, but we
refuse to go back and check). That the world's greatest population
of pigs can be found, thankfully, in China. That the country with
the highest life expectancy for males and females is Japan (the
United States is not in the Top 10). None of this information has
staying power, of course. By the time you read it, we will have
moved on. See you next year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1603EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHAOS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     01-30 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAOS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHAOS THEORY': APPEALING COMPANIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review. Boldface word in
2nd-to-last graf should be italicized.) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are a long way from the Hardy Boys mysteries in Gary Krist's
new thriller, ``Chaos Theory,'' about political corruption in the
city government of Washington. Still, an appealing atmosphere of
adolescent companionability lingers on, as Jason Rourke and Dennis
Monroe, juniors at Robert F. Kennedy High School, try to unravel
why their attempt to buy a couple of joints in the Northeast
section of the city has gone so terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jason and Dennis are both bright and mildly troubled. Jason
still feels the aftereffects of the suicide of his mother, who
suffered from clinical depression. He lives uneasily with his
father, Graham, who feels guilty about overprotecting him. Dennis
is considered an ``Afro-Saxon'' by the other blacks in his class,
``a brother hanging with the white kids'' like Jason, ``playing at
being white.'' Yet ``he understood that copping ghetto attitude was
a loser's game _ something that would get him absolutely nowhere in
this world.''
</P>
<P>
   So it seems plausible enough that after suffering a classmate's
``sedate, alcohol-free birthday celebration'' that included a
prayer of thanksgiving, they decide to cut out and buy some grass.
The problem is that when they do, their dealer starts shouting
about being betrayed, pulls a gun on them, sticks it in the window
of their car and tells them to get out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jason grabs the man's wrist and tells Dennis to drive
away. The dealer, after being dragged along the street and firing a
harmless shot into the car, collides with the back of a parked car
and falls to the ground. The next day Jason and Dennis read the
newspaper headline ``Undercover cop slain in brutal Northeast
attack.'' The article explains that Detective Ramon Harcourt was
found dead with two gunshot wounds in him, lying near a weapon that
had been discharged three times.
</P>
<P>
   But later, when the newspaper runs a photo of Harcourt, Jason
and Dennis realize he isn't the man who attacked them. And of
course they soon become the focus of a threatening police
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Krist _ whose previous books include two noted collections of
stories, ``The Garden State'' and ``Bone by Bone,'' and a novel,
``Bad Chemistry'' _ does several things well while untangling this
mystery. He gives us striking snapshots of Washington scenery:
``Across a quiet stretch of the Tidal Basin, the Jefferson Memorial
floated: a big white jellyfish, the pillars hanging down like
tentacles. He could just make out the statue of the president
inside, about to be swallowed.''
</P>
<P>
   He paints a complex picture of what Jason's father refers to as
``the great racial divide'' that ``no D.C. resident could ever
forget, living in a center of white power that just happened to
have a population that was over 60 percent black.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, what lies behind Jason's and Dennis' problems is
a good deal easier to figure out and considerably less shocking
than Krist counts on it being. So his plot can't bear the weight of
an analysis that sees Washington as a city emasculated because it
can't ``tax the real estate of its major tenant or the income of
its commuting workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the hard money to run the city still had to come as a
handout from the federal government,'' the analysis continues,
``paternalism was practically built into District affairs.'' But in
truth the corruption that Jason and Dennis get caught up in could
occur in any metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to the truth is the remark of one of the story's
villains: ``They're all talking about accountability now _
openness, order. Responsible, accountable government. But you ask
any businessman, he'll tell you about accountability. Why do you
think they're all running to Russia and Eastern Europe nowadays?
It's the chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chaos is just another word for opportunity,'' the villain
continues. ``The weak person's crisis...is the strong person's
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is the Hardy Boys element of companionship that makes
``Chaos Theory'' appealing: Jason and Dennis reaching across the
racial divide to help each other out of a pickle, as Graham Rourke
continues his musings about race in Washington: ``Could people like
Graham and the Monroes ever hope to harmonize their interests, or
even remotely  &UR; understand &LR;  each other's interests? It was a big,
unanswerable question, relevant in every American city but
especially in the District of Columbia ... Would it take new dogs _
puppies like Jason and Dennis, maybe _ to learn this new trick?''
</P>
<P>
   Krist's novel, while somewhat flawed as a thriller, holds out
the pleasant hope that puppies like Jason and Dennis will learn
this new trick.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `CHAOS THEORY'
</P>
<P>
   By Gary Krist.
</P>
<P>
   347 pages. Random House. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
