</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NIXON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NIXON'S CHINA GAME': THE STEALTH CAMPAIGN TO OPEN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Program notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a dollop of Eric Ambler, add a whiff of the Marx Brothers,
stir wildly, and you have ``Nixon's China Game,'' Monday night's
zesty account of the huggermugger surrounding President Richard
Nixon's celebrated ``opening to China.'' The supersecrecy that kept
Secretary of State William Rogers in the dark and put Henry
Kissinger in disguise are laid out by an international cast of
players who served the Nixonian geopolitical strategy to transform
relations between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday nights' ``American Experience'' on PBS, which combines
newsreels and interviews, the former president stars as diplomatic
tactician: daring, devious and remarkably farsighted. When
intelligence operatives detected a breach between China and the
Soviet Union early in his presidency, Nixon, the impeccable
anti-communist, put into effect a plan to repair relations with
China as a way of putting pressure on the Soviets, and vice versa.
It had to be done in secret, lest Republican right-wingers get wind
of the plot and cry, ``Soft on Communism!''
</P>
<P>
   So began an international feeling-out process that included a
fashion show at the Yugoslav Embassy in Warsaw, where, a member of
the Chinese delegation reports, the U.S. ambassador ran after the
Chinese, shouting: ``I saw President Nixon in Washington! He wants
to establish relations with China!'' When State Department
officials expressed reservations about the initiative, Nixon cut
them out of the loop.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Yahya Khan, the Pakistani leader, served as middleman
between Nixon and Zhou Enlai, China's prime minister. As relations
showed signs of warming, Kissinger, the national security adviser,
was given the job of arranging a presidential visit to China, code
named Marco Polo. The emissary, in a big black raincoat, a big
black hat and dark glasses, was spirited into China's once
forbidden city.
</P>
<P>
   The asides add flavor to the hour. A Pakistani official couldn't
find his car keys. Kissinger forgot to take an extra shirt, which
gave one of his assistants, Winston Lord, a chance to crack,
``Before you even sit down and talk with them, you've lost your
shirt!''
</P>
<P>
   One immediate effect of the Chinese-American enterprise, it is
reported here, was to goad the Kremlin into proceeding with stalled
arms talks. As Nixon said, ``So the Russian game made the Chinese
game work, and the Chinese game made the Russian game work.''
</P>
<P>
   In the election year of 1972 Nixon gathered several score
television journalists to come along on his momentous trip. As
Stanley Karnow, one close observer who contributes to the hour,
notes, ``This was going to be a television show.''
</P>
<P>
   The ever touchy subject of Taiwan brought what Nixon called
``some very spirited discussions between Rogers and Kissinger.''
Finally Zhou himself helped to smooth matters, and at the closing
banquet the president is described as getting happily tipsy from
all the toasts.
</P>
<P>
   The program is an entertaining peek behind the negotiation wall,
illuminating an episode whose ramifications continue to be felt in
the current complicated relations with the Chinese. By the 1980s,
the narrator reminds us, a new Nixonian slogan appeared in Beijing:
``To get rich is glorious!''
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE: NIXON'S CHINA GAME'
</P>
<P>
   Channel 13, New York, at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A Brook Lapping Productions film in association with ``The
American Experience.'' For Brook Lapping: Norma Percy and Brian
Lapping, executive producers; Mark Anderson, series producer and
director; Victoria Price, editor. For ``The American Experience'':
William Lattanzi, producer and writer; Michael Whalen, music; David
Ogden Stiers, narrator. ``The American Experience'' is produced by
WGBH/Boston. Margaret Drain, executive producer; Mark Samels,
senior producer; David McCullough, series host.
</P>
</TEXT>
