<P>
   NH-GOP (Hudson, N.H.) _ Texas Gov. George Bush tries to corral
the stubborn insurgency of Arizona Sen. John McCain by disparaging
his Republican challenger's modest tax cut plan as the kind of
scheme offered by the Clinton-Gore administration. But McCain
continues his attacks on Bush. He demands that the Texas governor
persuade New York authorities to let him on the March 7 primary
ballot in that state. And McCain insists that he will be a stronger
GOP candidate against Vice President Al Gore because he alone has
rejected the questionable fund-raising practices used by the
Clinton-Gore re-election campaign in 1996. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   TEXANS-INVADE (Nashua, N.H.) _ If it's a presidential year and
if it's the New Hampshire primary, chances are there is at least
one Texan on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it is Texas Gov. George W. Bush seeking the
Republican presidential nomination. In past years it was Lyndon B.
Johnson, a Democrat; John Connally, a one-time Democratic governor
who became a Republican; Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, a Democrat; Republican
Sen. Phil Gramm; and the cantankerous Reform Party candidate Ross
Perot. By GARY MARTIN.
