<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      01-30 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER SAVORS REPUTATION FOR RELENTLESSNESS  
 HELEN GURLEY BROWN COMES CLEAN  
 TIT FOR TAT IN PARK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Spelling of Dorthy is CQ.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In more than three decades as a reporter, Leonard Levitt became
known for questioning everything and everyone. Prosecutors. Police
commissioners. Editors. He has chased facts, chewed facts, shaken
facts until they are as bedraggled as his rain hat, whose brim has
all but parted company with the hat itself.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt, who is 57, began looking into the police investigation
of the 1975 murder of Martha Moxley, a 15-year-old Greenwich,
Conn., girl, as a freelancer in 1983. Levitt said he undertook the
project at the request of Ken Brief, then editor of both The
Greenwich Time and The Stamford Advocate, which are sibling papers
owned by Times Mirror Co. He submitted a draft of an article in
1984, and several drafts subsequently, but year after year it
remained unpublished.
</P>
<P>
   But Levitt, who later joined another Times Mirror paper,
Newsday, as a police reporter and columnist, kept in touch with
Martha's mother, Dorthy, telling her the article would be printed
someday.
</P>
<P>
   When the Moxley case came back into the news in 1991, Levitt was
quoted in The New York Post about the article that had never run.
Within days, The Time and The Advocate both published the piece _
seven years after Levitt's first draft.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what made the difference. Brief, now a professor
at Columbia Journalism School, declined comment. Steven L.
Isenberg, the former publisher of the newspaper, said the draft he
had reviewed in the mid-1980s had legal and journalistic
shortcomings; he did not know what happened afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were legitimate questions,'' said Kevin Donovan, who
began collaborating with Levitt months after the project began.
``It was a sensitive story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rewritten,'' Donovan added, ``but the heart of the
story did not really change.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the story involved the police behavior toward
Thomas and Michael Skakel, two teen-age neighbors of Ms. Moxley's.
The story detailed the failure of the police to search the Skakel
house, though the golf club used in the murder matched other clubs
found in a bag in the Skakel home.
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Skakel, now 39, was arrested in connection with Ms.
Moxley's death this month, men with bigger names _ like the former
detective Mark Fuhrman _ were widely interviewed. But none of them
had gnawed at the case as relentlessly as Levitt. Nobody gnaws at
police commissioners like him either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will go through brick walls,'' said Don Forst, a former
Newsday editor who is now editor of The Village Voice.
</P>
<P>
   John Miller, a former deputy police commissioner for public
information, said: ``Whatever he covered, he immediately alienated
the mainstream sources, the leadership, and thus ingratiated
himself with the disenfranchised and the unhappy. They are much
better sources.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt says straightforwardly, ``I'm a great reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   His detractors agree he is relentless, but say he lacks
proportion. Marilyn Mode, Miller's successor, said, ``He is a very
petty little man.'' Referring to a recent item in Levitt's Newsday
column, she added, ``For the record, my dog has not bitten
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Lennie Levitt has.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   First `Cosmopolitan Girl' Reveals a Secret
</P>
<P>
   Helen Gurley Brown, the 76-year-old former editor in chief of
Cosmopolitan magazine, has come clean in her new memoir, ``I'm Wild
Again: Snippets from My Life and a Few Brazen Thoughts'' (St.
Martin's Press). In a chapter titled ``The Year of Being Kept (But
Not Very Well),'' she reveals for the first time that she had a
financial arrangement when she was 24 with an older, married man
who, in exchange for rent and a nominal secretarial job, had a
sexual relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   According to her book, the unnamed paramour _ a movie studio
executive _ limped, was totally bald and old (he was 43).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said she decided to write about the arrangement
because her readers think of her as a confidante and this was a
piece of her life she had not yet disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any shame about it, really,'' Ms. Brown said in
an interview. ``It was the right thing at the time. I was trying to
get enough money together to send to my mother and my sister, who
had polio. This was just something I never wrote about before. I
was just doing the best I could do for 24.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown wrote that she was never ``guilt crazy'' about the
arrangement, rather she was ``using this golden opportunity to
stash enough money to take care of Mother and Mary and me the rest
of our lives.'' She described the situation as ``freedom from
hunger and want, bye-bye pinchies and scrimpies, farewell fiscal
fright.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said that although she would not even characterize the
relationship as an affair (``an affair is sexier,'' she wrote), the
man was not utterly revolting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, he wasn't that awful,'' Ms. Brown said. ``He wasn't a
gargoyle. And believe me, I have never, ever in my grown-up life
believed that you only go to bed with men that you are in love
with.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Show Business Dailies Brawl at Sundance
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The competition between Daily Variety and The
Hollywood Reporter moved last week to the slopes of Park City,
Utah, site of the Sundance festival.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, The Hollywood Reporter, which is owned by the
Billboard Publications unit of VNU, published an article about the
arrest of Daily Variety's national columnist, Dan Cox, at a party
at Park City's Snow Park Lodge. According to the newspaper, about
1,000 people showed up at the party on Tuesday night, given by the
Creative Artists Agency. But only 300 were invited.
</P>
<P>
   When the police arrived to turn people away, turmoil ensued. Cox
was the only one arrested. He was booked for disorderly conduct and
released on bail a short time later, The Hollywood Reporter said.
``The crowd control at Sundance is ridiculous,'' Cox was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Then came tit for tat.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Friday, Daily Variety, which is owned by the
Cahners division of Reed Elsevier, reported that The Hollywood
Reporter's chief film critic, Kirk Honeycutt, and the actress
Courtney Love ``squared off'' Wednesday night at the Lakota
restaurant in Park City, at the height of the film festival's
activities. The newspaper reported that Honeycutt's wife, Mira,
tried to take a picture of Ms. Love, who apparently lost her temper
and threw the camera on the ground. Honeycutt ``butted in and,
insiders say, clenched his fist in preparation to hit the
actress,'' Variety said. Later, Honeycutt and Ms. Love made up.
</P>
<P>
   The Variety article was written by two reporters. One was
Charles Lyons. The other was Dan Cox. Cox did not respond to a
phone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Honeycutt said the Variety account was ``mostly fiction'' and
that he had not threatened to punch Ms. Love. ``It's a reflection
of the editorial integrity of Daily Variety that they permitted a
reporter, Dan Cox, who clearly had an ax to grind, to report and
write that story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BERNARD WEINRAUB
</P>
