<HEADER>
A1058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELECTRONIC-TAX31-COX     01-30 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-TAX31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electronic filing may prove to be a quick, easy solution to
what's taxing you
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Under the best of circumstances, filing income
tax returns is an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the worst circumstances _ you owe lots of money, your tax
situation is complicated, you don't have all the forms and records
you need, etc. _ filing your taxes can be a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Using computer technology to file your taxes can cut down on
some of the headaches and can even get you your refund a little
faster than paper filing. But unless your tax situation is among
the simplest, you'll probably pay a bit extra for the convenience
of electronic filing.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic filing covers five methods of submitting income tax
forms to the government without filling in the traditional paper
income tax return.
</P>
<P>
   The methods are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Professional tax preparation services who specialize in
filling out tax forms for people who can't or don't want to fill
out their forms on their own. These services will file the returns
they complete electronically for a fee. Or you can fill out your
forms yourself and take them to a tax preparation service for
electronic filing, but the fees are quite high. You'll probably pay
two to four times as much to have a tax service file your return
electronically than you would pay an online service.
</P>
<P>
   _ Volunteer tax preparation services. Senior citizen service
providers and some social service agencies provide tax assistance
to certain groups, typically the elderly and the poor. The services
are usually free or carry only a nominal fee. Not every community
has volunteer tax preparers, and not all services are the same. So
you may have to call a couple senior citizen centers and other
agencies to see what might be available close to you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Telefile, a free service provided by the Internal Revenue
Service that lets unmarried taxpayers of moderate income file using
a touch-tone phone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Home-based electronic filing using software programs. You buy
a software program, enter tax information to complete a return,
then pay the software provider to transmit your return.
</P>
<P>
   _ Online tax preparation services. You skip the step of buying
software and log on to a tax preparation site on the Internet. You
pay to complete your return using the online system, and you may
pay a separate fee to have the service provider forward your return
to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Carolee Pfefferman, acting public affairs officer for the
Internal Revenue Service office in Cincinnati, said the government
expects the number of people filing electronically to increase
every year as taxpayers become more comfortable and proficient with
electronic filing systems.
</P>
<P>
   Pfefferman said the IRS expects 23.7 million taxpayers to file
electronically through professional tax services, up from 21.2
million who used the option last year. The number using Telefile is
expected to rise from 5.7 million last year to 5.9 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The largest percentage increase, however, is expected in online
filings. About 2.4 million taxpayers filed federal returns online
using software or Web-based tax services. The IRS expects 4 million
such filings this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pfefferman said the government welcomes electronic filing and is
encouraging the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you file electronically, the chance for human error is
greatly reduced,'' she said. ``There's less chance for math errors
on the part of the filers, and less chance of error on the part of
IRS employees copying information from tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax returns are processed faster with fewer errors, and
refunds go out more quickly. Everybody benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   TAX SOFTWARE FOR 2000
</P>
<P>
   If you bought an income tax preparation software product for
your tax return last year, you won't be able to use it again for
this year's return.
</P>
<P>
   An article in this section last year erroneously implied that
income tax programs could be updated from year to year. Tax
programs can be updated when tax laws for the year they cover
change, but they aren't updated to cover subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax laws and tax tables change too much from year to year
to keep using the same programs,'' said Colleen Ferrin,
spokesperson for Intuit Inc., the leading producer of tax software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has entered the tax preparation software arena this
year with TaxSaver Federal and TaxSaver Federal Deluxe.
</P>
<P>
   Local software retailers are displaying the new Microsoft
programs alongside Quicken TurboTax and Quicken TurboTax Deluxe
from Intuit Inc. and Kiplinger TaxCut and Kiplinger TaxCut Deluxe
from Block Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Based on information on the packages and the company Web sites,
the software programs are fairly similar.
</P>
<P>
   The basic tax programs lead users through the tax preparation
process by asking questions. The taxpayer uses the computer
keyboard to enter figures, names and addresses, and uses the mouse
to pick answers from multiple choice lists.
</P>
<P>
   When the questions are answered, the programs calculate the
taxes and produce a return for the taxpayer to check.
</P>
<P>
   After verifying the accuracy of the return, the taxpayer can
either print out a return and mail it or link to the company's Web
site to electronically file the return.
</P>
<P>
   The deluxe versions of the three companies software work about
the same but they include onscreen videos of tax experts and other
extra features.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the costs of the programs can be complicated. Most of
the basic programs have a list price of around $20, and the deluxe
packages sell for $30 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   But almost all the packages offer significant rebates, and you
can get several of the tax preparation products for free if you buy
other financial management products from the same company.
</P>
<P>
   Also you have to calculate the costs of electronic filing and
the costs of state forms.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the programs include rebates for the fee for filing your
first electronic return. After that software companies typically
charge around $10 per return.
</P>
<P>
   None of the basic tax preparation packages include programs to
file your Ohio income taxes, so you'll have to buy a separate
program for your state taxes. But you may get a state program free
if you buy one of the deluxe packages.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE SERVICES FOR TAX RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   If you are comfortable working with businesses online, you might
want to consider using a Web-based tax service instead of buying a
software package.
</P>
<P>
   The number of companies offering online services has increased
from last year, they are more experienced so their services should
be more reliable and easy to use, and competition is holding the
price of services down.
</P>
<P>
   Typically the fee for filling out and filing a federal income
tax return online runs about $10 to $15.
</P>
<P>
   Online services work much like the tax preparation software
programs you buy for your home computer. In fact, the leading
software producers run Web sites using essentially the same
programs they sell to home users.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you have a slow Internet connection, the process of
filling out tax forms online can be especially tedious.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not possible to link directly to IRS computers to
file your taxes online. For security reasons, the IRS requires
taxpayers to work through intermediary companies or agencies, and
generally the companies demand payment for the service.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS responds to online filings with a confirmation notice
within 48 hours. If you sign up to have your refund deposited
directly to your bank account, you can have a refund in less than
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To complete an online filing, you'll have to send the IRS a
signed Form 8453-OL along with your W2 forms.
</P>
<P>
   If you filed online last year, you might receive a special
electronic code number from the IRS this year. The code numbers are
being distributed to 11 million taxpayers as part of a pilot
project, and if you receive one you'll be able to use it to sign
your return electronically and skip mailing Form 8453-OL.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to start getting information about your
electronic filing options is at the IRS Web site at
www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/elecsvs/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   From there you can link to the information page for individual
taxpayers. There you'll find listings for about 15 companies
offering tax filing services online.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES
</P>
<P>
   _ The Digital Daily at www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/cover.html is
the Internal Revenue Service's main taxpayer information site, and
it's quite complete. You can get answers to frequently asked
questions, download tax forms, find tips and statistics, and link
to commercial sites for online filing and tax software.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. Tax Code On-Line at www.fourmilab.to/uscode/ is basically
a site that links chapter by chapter to the entire tax code. Much
of it is in dense legal language that's hard to understand.
</P>
<P>
   The prices of tax preparation software packages can vary as much
as $20 between stores, so it pays to shop around a bit. Also, just
about every package comes with some sort of rebate offer. If you
read the offers carefully, you may be able to get the tax software
for free if you're willing to buy other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The following prices were offered by the software manufacturers
online:
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger TaxCut, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger TaxCut Deluxe, $39.95
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger TaxCut Allstate, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   _ Microsoft TaxSaver, $19.95
</P>
<P>
   _ Microsoft TaxSaver Deluxe, $44.95
</P>
<P>
   _ Quicken TurboTax, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   _ Quicken TurboTax Deluxe, $49.95
</P>
<P>
   _ Quicken TurboTax State, $27.95
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
