<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millions in funds pumps life into Bradley campaign
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Democrat Bill Bradley hasn't been getting
much good news lately. First, he disclosed more episodes of an
irregular heartbeat, a non-life threatening condition that
nonetheless raised questions about his health.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was trounced in the Iowa caucuses. Here in New
Hampshire, he has been greeted by a steady stream of polls showing
him trailing Vice President Al Gore, although the gap is narrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst the bad news, however, Bradley produced one bit of
information last week that gave his flagging campaign plenty to
cheer about: Whatever tomorrow's outcome, Bradley will leave the
Granite State with almost $20 million to spend on his insurgent bid
to win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign claims the amount is slightly more than what
Gore will have in the bank, meaning that Bradley will have the
resources to take his campaign into the March 7 primaries, and
possibly beyond. The next two rounds of primaries will decide more
than two-thirds of all the delegates that go to the Democratic
nominating convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both financially and organizationally, we are prepared to go
and go hard beyond New Hampshire,'' said Eric Hauser, Bradley's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But time will be short. Because of the front-loaded primary
schedule, Bradley will effectively have five weeks to make the case
that he can beat Gore and win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire holds only 1 percent of the delegates sent to the
Democratic convention, but the state's influence over how voters
elsewhere perceive the candidates far outweighs its modest delegate
count.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley competed in Iowa, a state he knew he could not win, to
prove that he could run a credible campaign. He has staked millions
of dollars and more than a year of campaigning in New Hampshire to
prove he is worthy of a win.
</P>
<P>
   A loss here will badly damage his prospects, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a two candidate race,'' said Emory political scientist
Merle Black. ``There is a winner and a loser. Making it close in
New Hampshire may give him a little incentive to keep going. But he
really needs a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has succeeded in attracting voters who are disenchanted
with the negative tone of politics in America, Black said, but he
needs to convince traditional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley's real problem is that he has to give Democratic
primary voters a reason not to vote for the vice president of the
United States in an administration that is very popular among
Democratic voters,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   After months of shying away from direct contrasts with Gore,
Bradley has now taken the offensive. On Sunday, he raised questions
about Gore's role in a 1996 fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple in
California. Gore has denied that he knew it was a fund-raiser, even
though the woman organizing the event was a longtime financial
contributor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is more explanation that is needed ... about his
participation,'' Bradley told voters in Concord, N.H. Bradley
asserted voters would reject a campaign that wasn't forthcoming
about the fund-rasing scandals, which he called ``a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also has sought to raise questions about Gore's
commitment to abortion rights and gun control, a strategy that his
aides say he will continue into the next phase of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's health, however, could continue to be an issue for
him. He said Sunday on ABC's ``This Week with Sam Donaldson and
Cokie Roberts'' that he would consider using the 25th Amendment to
temporarily transfer power to his vice president if he had to be
anesthetized for atrial fibrillation. Bradley suffers from an
irregular heartbeat and he must be anesthetized for three or four
minutes if an electric shock is required to return his heart
rhythms to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably appropriate,'' Bradley said in response to a
question about invoking the 25th Amendment. ``I would make the call
at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if Bradley wins New Hampshire and has a financial edge,
he still faces long odds against a well-organized campaign of a
sitting Vice President who enjoys the support of labor unions and
other Democratic constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday, several states loom large for Bradley: New York,
Connecticut, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri, Ohio and, of
course, California.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's strongest base of support is in his home state of
Missouri and the Northeast, where he is well-known both as a former
New Jersey senator and a New York Knick.
</P>
<P>
   He is counting on his long-standing ties to the Northeast to
help him in the Northeastern primary states. Bradley has scheduled
his biggest campaign event following the New Hampshire primary in
New York City on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is also planning to devote significant time and
resources in California, which has the largest number of Democratic
delegates. Bradley is less well-known than Gore in California and
he has almost no support from the state's Democratic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign, however, claims that grass-roots organizing
in the Golden State is going well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign has always been built around the idea of letting
Democrats across this country have a say,'' said Doug Berman,
Bradley's campaign chairman. ``Iowa and New Hampshire are the
opening part of it _ and an important part of it _ but there is
always a national event. That's what we've been preparing for.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
