<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia flag issue demands a leader to act with courage
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Feb. 13, 1956, a loaf of bread cost 15 cents and
the Loew's Theater in Atlanta welcomed a packed house to see
``Forever Darling,'' starring Lucille Ball and Desi Arnaz.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Gold Dome, Gov. Marvin Griffin signed into law a bill
changing the historic 1879 Georgia flag to one that embarrasses as
the world spotlight shines on my hometown again, this time for
Super Bowl 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The strains of ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' will float from the
Georgia Dome toward the Capitol, where the flag, with its
Confederate battle emblem, flutters in an icy wind.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what televised panorama will reach which corners of a
shrinking multiracial globe. Who knows how many will say, after
all, this is the home of Braves player John Rocker, whose racial
slurs confirmed that the stereotypical redneck Southerner lives on.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer a matter of whether Georgia will eliminate the
emblem placed on the flag. It is simply a matter of when a leader
will muster the courage and support to do it. For Gov. Roy Barnes,
it soon will be a question of whether to spend some of his ready
political capital on it.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper clips of the highly charged 1956 legislative session
magnify the motivation for the flag change. It was the angry
backlash of a segregationist Legislature rebelling against the 1954
U.S. Supreme Court decision mandating an end to public school
segregation. Winning near-unanimous legislative approval along with
the flag bill was a state resolution declaring the school
desegregation ruling ``null and void.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other bills aimed at strengthening enforcement of state
segregation laws sailed through: One declared that no person could
occupy a vacant seat on a bus next to a female passenger without
her permission; another demanded that any peace officer who refused
to enforce segregation laws would lose his state pension.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular myth, there was no great oratory about
preserving history in the changing of the flag. Rep. Denmark
Groover of Bibb County, Ga., the Democratic floor leader, declared
that replacing ``the meaningless stripes with something that has
deep meaning for all true Southerners'' would somehow hold on to a
bit of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Poring over the old newspapers, I was reminded of the first
press conference I covered as a college journalism intern in 1960 _
one staged by a bunch of die-hard segregationists known as
Georgians Unwilling to Surrender, or GUTS.
</P>
<P>
   I searched the editorial pages in vain for criticism of the flag
change. But the only opinion pieces in either The Atlanta Journal
or the Constitution relating to racial issues the week of the flag
bill complimented Democratic presidential candidate Adlai Stevenson
(whom I'd always thought of as a liberal) for calling for the
banishment of the segregation issue from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   At the national and state level, politicians still are calling
the flag matter a nonissue. Barnes, a Democrat who can attribute
his election two years ago to blacks and women, says the flag issue
isn't part of his agenda. But Barnes, who already has outsmarted
his adversaries to the point of making them anxious to join him on
controversial transportation, health care and education reforms, is
storing up plenty of political capital.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has had to apologize for voting against the Martin Luther
King Jr. holiday when he was a state legislator. And though the
Rev. Jesse Jackson called off his planned Atlanta demonstration,
the governor surely knows the day is near when he will have to
decide whether to risk his political popularity on the flag issue.
</P>
<P>
   I hope he makes the right decision. He is determined to elevate
Georgia's outdated governmental and educational institutions to the
level of her economic success. But the flag issue goes to something
far less tangible and more lasting: the soul of a state and its
</P>
<P>
   people.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
