<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN31-COX     01-30 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Psychology, political correctness square off in search for
reason
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _Women who dress to look sexy need to know that they
could trigger an attack by men who are natural-born rapists.
</P>
<P>
   Women who argue that rape is about power reject this notion.
</P>
<P>
   Men who don't want to be considered potential rapists also spurn
this view, which is vended in the current issue of The Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't leave many people to defend the article in the
scientific journal that contains excerpts from a book that will be
released in April by the MIT Press titled ``A Natural History of
Rape: Biological Bases of Sexual Coercion'' by Dr. Craig T. Palmer
of the University of Colorado and Dr. Randy Thornhill of the
University of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are experts in the science of evolutionary psychology,
not political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   They say current beliefs about rape are based on ``empirically
erroneous, even mythological, ideas about human development,
behavior and psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   Rape prevention programs need to take the natural evolutionary
drive of males to commit rape into account. Women should be told to
watch how they dress. Men should be told that just because women
are friendly or wear tight blouses does not mean they are asking
for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who just awoke from a 35-year coma might wonder what all
the fuss is about. Before the mid-1960s, rape generally was
considered a sex crime, not a crime motivated by power or violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a long time to pull back from what is politically
correct and do an analysis on it,'' Thornhill was quoted in a New
York Times article.
</P>
<P>
   Thornhill and his co-author report that lectures on their
findings have been picketed and their scientific articles rejected
due to their findings that men have evolved to be promiscuous with
young women likely to bear children. Women have evolved to be to
more selective.
</P>
<P>
   Rape, the scientists propose, evolved as a mating technique for
males who were not as adept or lucky in love as other males.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists also note that rape is not unusual in nonhuman
species. They give as examples insects, fish, birds and even
nonhuman primates.
</P>
<P>
   These scientific conclusions find considerable opposition in the
scientific community as well as the general public, according to
the New York Times article.
</P>
<P>
   An unrelated scientific study by Dr. Keith McBurnett of the
University of Chicago reports that mean, violent and disruptive
boys can be identified by analyzing their saliva.
</P>
<P>
   McBurnett's four-year study found that consistently disruptive
boys have low levels of the stress hormone cortisol in their
saliva.
</P>
<P>
   Boys who started fights, used weapons, were cruel or forced
sexual acts were tested. Some boys rated as meanest were tested.
</P>
<P>
   There was a correlation between low levels of cortisol and
disruptive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   McBurnett said children with persistent conduct disorders may
have a genetic predisposition that causes them to produce hormones
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Women don't want to think that the way they dress or act
encourages their own rape. Men don't want to believe that they are
potential rapists. Perhaps the truth lies somewhere between culture
and evolution, or nature and nurture.
</P>
<P>
   The mapping of the complete human genome is not far off. Genetic
and evolutionary influences on the human condition are being
discovered in rapid succession.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the day is not far off when instant saliva tests can
accurately predict the likelihood of all sorts of behavior and
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   What we do with that information will be the political
correctness battleground of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-TEXANS-INVADE-HNS &LR;      01-30 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXANS-INVADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS CANDIDATES OFTEN FIND COOL RECEPTION IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GARY MARTIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ If it's a presidential year and if it's the New
Hampshire primary, chances are there is a Texan on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it is Texas Gov. George W. Bush seeking the
Republican presidential nomination. In past years it was Lyndon B.
Johnson, a Democrat; John Connally, a Democratic governor who
became a Republican presidential hopeful; Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, a
Democrat; George Bush, the father of the current candidate;
Republican Sen. Phil Gramm; and the cantankerous Reform Party
candidate Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Not all have found success in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are bright colors,'' said Clark Hubbard, a political
science professor at the University of New Hampshire. ``We like our
colors more muted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be something to the notion that the political style
in Texas doesn't play well up here: the image of Texans and the
self-promotion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hardscrabble New Englanders, while brimming with pioneer spirit,
like their politics more low-key than the colorful Texans who have
crossed the countryside here.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a larger-than-life figure, was on the ballot but stayed
out of New Hampshire in 1960, won easily here as a sitting
president in 1964, and was humiliated in 1968 when he won by only a
handful of votes. Johnson announced a short time later he would not
seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Connally spent $10 million and won one delegate in 1980 before
he dropped out of the race. He finished near the bottom in New
Hampshire, crushed by Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's poll numbers were so low he dropped out of the
presidential race just days before the New Hampshire primary in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Bennett, an independent pollster in New Hampshire, said in
1996 that the bragging by Texans about their prowess at raising
money irritates New England voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connally, literally, put out press releases about all the
money he had, all the copy machines he bought,'' he said. ``That
may impress people in Texas, but it doesn't here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett also criticized Gramm's heavy Southern accent and the
fact that in 1996 he repeatedly referred to his mother in a bid for
folksiness. Gramm's ``talk-funny business about momma'' did not
play well with New England voters, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Yankees, and we are more reserved about things like
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, of course, has sent more patrician candidates to the
Northeast, but they didn't fare very well, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen in 1976 and George Bush, who has roots in the Northeast,
came in 1980, 1988 and 1992. Bentsen lost to Jimmy Carter in the
Democratic primary; Bush fell to Ronald Reagan in 1980. Bush,
claiming Houston as his residence, served as Reagan's vice
president for eight years before winning the presidency himself in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   The less than successful record of Texans in New Hampshire
suggests a regional bias, but Hubbard said that isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much regionalism as a clash of political
cultures,'' Hubbard dryly noted, with reference to the bravado of
Connally, Gramm and other presidential casualties from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ager, 40, an engineer from Merrimac, said the Lone Star
State has been well represented in presidential politics here
because ``Texas is a big state. It has a big pool to draw from.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ager said personality, not the state, is what makes or
breaks candidates in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has more charisma than his father or Gramm. When Gramm
said he was an economics professor, you said, `Yeah, you are an
economics professor,''' Ager said of the senator's professorial
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bush walks into a room, he has a lot of bearing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hutchenson of Londonderry, though, said she is put off by
the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's money doesn't impress us,'' she said. ``He was born
with a lot of money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OLDMASTERS-MARKET-2TA     01-30 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDMASTERS-MARKET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTION SHIFTS TO NEW YORK FROM LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five museums _ the Metropolitan Museum, the National
Gallery of Art in Washington, the J. Paul Getty Museum, the St.
Louis Art Museum and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art _ bought
old master paintings at Christie's on Thursday. On Friday, an
anonymous donor bought a rare Rembrandt drawing for the Morgan
Library at Christie's sale of old master drawings. And two U.S.
museums were buyers at Sotheby's sale of old master paintings on
Friday: the National Gallery and an institution that wished to
remain anonymous. At both auction houses museums were willing to
pay record prices for works that would fill gaps in their
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's paintings sale brought in $47.4 million, while
Christie's paintings sale totaled $39.2 million. Bidding in the
salesrooms for the most popular works was fiercely competitive,
with dealers from all over the world raising their paddles and
telephone bidders aggressively trying to buy something, no matter
what the price. Experts from both auction houses said there were
more new buyers in these sales than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old masters have been undervalued for a long time,'' said
George Wachter, director of Sotheby's old master paintings
department worldwide. ``If you go to an Impressionist sale,
$400,000 will get you a mediocre Renoir. But at an old masters
sale, buyers can get something A-1 for under $500,000, and that's
something people are finally beginning to realize.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently London was the center of the old master universe.
It was where the most serious scholars lived and where the best
dealers could be found. Europe of course has always been a fertile
field for the finest works of art. The stately homes of titled
families in Britain and on the Continent are still treasure troves.
</P>
<P>
   But now Sotheby's and Christie's in Manhattan are taking
advantage of a significant increase in Americans buying old masters
and the intricate web of import taxes crippling dealers living in
European Union countries. Many top London dealers are opening
spaces in New York in order to capitalize on its flourishing
market. Some experts wonder whether New York will eclipse London in
a few years as the center of the old master market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans have shot themselves in the foot with the
complex taxes,'' said Johnny van Haeften, one of London's leading
old master dealers. For example, he said, collectors and dealers
who live in a country like Switzerland, which is not part of the
European Union, would rather sell a work of art in New York, which
has no import tax, than send it to London, where they would incur a
5 percent import tax levied on works of art brought into European
Union countries.
</P>
<P>
   Van Haeften added that the improved quality of the auctions in
New York had more to do with Sotheby's and Christie's recent
expansions in the city than with tastes and taxes. He pointed out
that it was only natural that the two auction houses would make the
old master market in New York as profitable as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Kennedy, who ran the old master paintings department at
Christie's in Manhattan for 16 years and is now president of
Dickinson Roundell, an East Side gallery, said that the strength of
the New York market had more to do with marketing than anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auction houses are trying to cultivate more buyers by
making their sales good,'' he said. ``The Impressionist market has
become so much stronger in New York than London because the best
things are sold here, and it seems Sotheby's and Christie's are
trying to do the same for old masters.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, in an effort to make the sales more successful,
the auction houses moved the date of their January sales later in
the month, in part to take advantage of Wall Street collectors with
year-end bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while experts for the two auction houses are promoting
New York's improved status, they gamely defend London's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is definitely flourishing, but that doesn't mean
London isn't,'' said Anthony Crichton-Stuart, head of Christie's
old master paintings department in New York. ``More things are
coming here for sale because the perception is that New York is a
richer market. But good things are still being sold in London,
especially in the July sales.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years the New York auctions have sold works by
artists like Rubens, Rembrandt, El Greco, Guardi and Velazquez at
record prices, which encourages sellers to keep consigning works
there. Young Wall Street traders are now putting their money into
old masters rather than the contemporary art they favored during
the '80s boom years. Experts ascribe the shift partly to changing
tastes and partly to fear. For some collectors who remember how the
contemporary art market took a nose dive in the early '90s, old
masters seem like a sounder investment. Even seasoned collectors
who were once loyal buyers of Impressionist and modern art are
beginning to get their feet wet buying the occasional Sweerts or
Canaletto, auction house experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a massive amount of money in this country,''
Crichton-Stuart said. ``But it's not just collectors who are buying
old masters. American museums with large acquisitions budgets are
active buyers both here and abroad. And that's something that
doesn't happen in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Met bought Ludovico Carracci's ``Pieta,'' a
sprawling image of Jesus that stretches the full width of the
painting. While it was estimated to sell for $300,000 to $500,000,
the museum paid $5.2 million, a record price for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been looking for a major early Baroque painting,'' said
Philippe de Montebello, director of the Met, after the sale at
Christie's. ``It's probably the most important picture of that
period that's been available.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was difficult for museums to buy at auction because
the timing was not always right, and it was hard to predict how
much a painting would actually sell for. ``We buy if the right
thing comes along and we can manage the price,'' he said, noting
that the painting cost 10 times the high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery bought a Baroque painting for a record
price as well. It purchased Domenichino's ``Rebuke of Adam and
Eve'' for $3.3 million at Sotheby's on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been slowly building our Baroque holdings,'' said Earl
A. Powell III, the museum's director. ``And this is a major
building block.'' It is also not the only purchase the National
Gallery made last week. At Christie's on Thursday it bought
Boilly's ``L'Escamoteur sur les Boulevards,'' an 1806 scene of
Parisians watching a card trick, for $662,500.
</P>
<P>
   The J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles, which has been a big
buyer at auction for years now, bought Tiepolo's ``Alexander and
Campaspe in the Studio of Apelles'' at Christie's for $2.2 million,
another record price. An anonymous donor spent $3.7 million to buy
a rare Rembrandt drawing. ``We wanted it badly,'' said Charles E.
Pierce Jr., director of the Morgan. ``It's an extraordinary drawing
from the 1640s, and very few are available.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say American museums don't go abroad to buy when
the right painting comes along. In London in July at the fabled
sale of art looted by the Nazis from the Austrian branch of the
Rothschild family, the prize painting _ a three-quarter-length
portrait by Frans Hals of an Amsterdam merchant named Tieleman
Roosterman _ was bought by the Cleveland Museum of Art for a record
price of $12.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years the Getty Museum has purchased
important old masters by artists like Poussin, Fra Bartolommeo,
Fragonard and Correggio. Smaller museums, like the Sterling and
Francine Clark Art Institute in Williamstown, Mass., and the J.B.
Speed Art Museum in Louisville, Ky., have also bought a number of
Old Masters.
</P>
<P>
   And while American museums, like avid collectors, will buy
wherever the goods are to be found, many institutions find it
easier to buy art in this country rather than risk the hassle of
applying for an export license and being turned down. Last October
when the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth was set to buy
Botticelli's ``Virgin Adoring the Christ Child'' for $24 million
from the Earl of Wemyss' home in Scotland, the export license was
denied when, at the last minute, the National Galleries of Scotland
were able to match the Kimbell's price.
</P>
<P>
   The dealers representing the Wemyss Heirloom Trust were the
Simon C. Dickinson Group, a London company with two galleries:
Simon Dickinson in London and Dickinson Roundell in New York. Both
handle old masters as well as Impressionist, modern and
contemporary art and both are run by former experts from
Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the faster growth of the market in Manhattan than in
London, the company recently moved into three floors of a town
house on East 66th Street, which it is currently renovating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is not slower in London, it's more expensive,'' said
David Ker, a director of the Simon C. Dickinson Group. ``The bite
of the VAT is just beginning to be felt,'' he said, referring to
value-added tax.
</P>
<P>
   Ker said his company had many good works of art to sell from
European collections because it had a presence in New York. ``There
are Europeans who like the discretion of selling in New York,'' he
added. ``The market here is more discreet. If something sells,
whether it ends up going to Australia or France nobody knows,
whereas London is a small town. Everybody knows everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Hall, who headed the New York branch of Colnaghi until
1996, and Richard Knight, who ran Colnaghi in London, formed a
partnership of their own with galleries in New York and London four
years ago. Like the Simon C. Dickinson Group, Hall &AMP; Knight has
just expanded its space on the Upper East Side. ``Americans still
like to go to Paris to buy French furniture, but collectors of old
masters find it's more convenient to buy paintings here,'' Hall
said. ``Clients interested in a painting can easily take it home to
see how it looks in their living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers, in both New York and in London, who specialize in
other areas have moved into old masters to meet the growing demand.
Lowell Libson, who runs Spink-Leger, a New Bond Street gallery, has
started dealing in old master drawings even though he built his
reputation selling mainly 18th- and 19th-century British works on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was a way of removing British art from its gloomy
sideline, by showing works by, say, Gainsborough, in context with
Fragonard,'' he said. But now, as more American collectors come to
him for old master drawings, he finds himself spending more time in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   One of the attractions for both dealers and the experts at the
auction houses is trying to lure big buyers who have made a name in
other collecting areas into the old masters field. Last year
Stephen A. Wynn, chairman of Mirage Resorts, bought the two most
expensive paintings in Sotheby's January sale in New York, a
Rembrandt and a Rubens. Both are hanging in Wynn's minimuseum at
Bellagio, his $1.6 billion hotel and casino complex in Las Vegas.
Experts say that Paul Allen, co-founder of Microsoft, who has had
eyes mostly for classic Impressionist paintings, is now buying
Canalettos.
</P>
<P>
   Value aside, tastes and fashion are also a draw. It was once
only the pretty old masters, flower paintings or landscapes, that
appealed to American buyers, while Europeans would embrace the more
difficult religious subjects. More recently buyers here are asking
for Baroque paintings, Wachter of Sotheby's said, pointing to
``Adam and Eve Lamenting the Death of Abel,'' by Philippe de
Champaigne. The painting, which depicts a blood-splattered Abel,
might be described as a difficult subject, yet Wachter said he had
lots of interested takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they learn,'' he said, ``the more sophisticated they
are getting.'' The work sold to a telephone bidder for $266,500,
not quite twice its high estimate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
