u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      01-30 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An intensifying disturbance moving through Maine will circulate
chilly but drier air into the middle Atlantic region and much of
southern New England on blustery winds from the west. Along the
coast, sunshine will return by midday and the wind will gust at
over 30 mph. Inland, an abundance of low clouds will cover the
region from the foothills of the Appalachians westward. Snow
showers will be most common in the higher elevations and along the
west slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Bright but cool weather is expected across the South as high
pressure glides east from Arkansas. A cold front moving southward
through Florida will be preceded by clouds and showers. The return
flow of moist air into south Texas will cause low clouds and
drizzle. A veil of high clouds will stream into the southern Plains
ahead of a new disturbance over the Four Corners.
</P>
<P>
   Light to moderate snow will fall in southern Utah and northern
Arizona, with snow showers developing across western Colorado and
New Mexico. The deserts of the Southwest will be mainly sunny,
though cooler. High pressure in Wyoming will lead to pleasant
conditions in the northern Rockies, though valley fog will persist
in some sections of Idaho and western Montana.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful storm will approach the Northwest, with gales and
heavy rain developing on the coast and wet snow spreading through
the Cascades. Showers should reach northern California later. The
Central Valley fog will linger into the afternoon in many sections.
The Pacific coast will turn cooler.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: January Flip
</P>
<P>
   It took until the last couple of days of the month, but the
average temperature for January 2000 has slipped a bit below the
30-year normal for the first month in both Boston and New York.
This is a remarkable turnabout, since after the first week of the
new year both cities were averaging nearly 15 degrees above normal.
The weather pattern made a switch between Jan. 12 and 14 as
jet-stream winds from the northwest began to dominate. Frequent
surges of polar air have kept readings generally below seasonal
levels for over two weeks. There is no sign of a significant change
in the week ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-OLDMASTERS-MARKET-A     01-30 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-OLDMASTERS-MARKET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTION SHIFTS TO NEW YORK FROM LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five museums _ the Metropolitan Museum, the National
Gallery of Art in Washington, the J. Paul Getty Museum, the St.
