old master paintings department in New York. ``More things are
coming here for sale because the perception is that New York is a
richer market. But good things are still being sold in London,
especially in the July sales.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years the New York auctions have sold works by
artists like Rubens, Rembrandt, El Greco, Guardi and Velazquez at
record prices, which encourages sellers to keep consigning works
there. Young Wall Street traders are now putting their money into
old masters rather than the contemporary art they favored during
the '80s boom years. Experts ascribe the shift partly to changing
tastes and partly to fear. For some collectors who remember how the
contemporary art market took a nose dive in the early '90s, old
masters seem like a sounder investment. Even seasoned collectors
who were once loyal buyers of Impressionist and modern art are
beginning to get their feet wet buying the occasional Sweerts or
Canaletto, auction house experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a massive amount of money in this country,''
Crichton-Stuart said. ``But it's not just collectors who are buying
old masters. American museums with large acquisitions budgets are
active buyers both here and abroad. And that's something that
doesn't happen in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Met bought Ludovico Carracci's ``Pieta,'' a
sprawling image of Jesus that stretches the full width of the
painting. While it was estimated to sell for $300,000 to $500,000,
the museum paid $5.2 million, a record price for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been looking for a major early Baroque painting,'' said
Philippe de Montebello, director of the Met, after the sale at
Christie's. ``It's probably the most important picture of that
period that's been available.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was difficult for museums to buy at auction because
the timing was not always right, and it was hard to predict how
much a painting would actually sell for. ``We buy if the right
thing comes along and we can manage the price,'' he said, noting
that the painting cost 10 times the high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery bought a Baroque painting for a record
price as well. It purchased Domenichino's ``Rebuke of Adam and
Eve'' for $3.3 million at Sotheby's on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been slowly building our Baroque holdings,'' said Earl
A. Powell III, the museum's director. ``And this is a major
building block.'' It is also not the only purchase the National
Gallery made last week. At Christie's on Thursday it bought
Boilly's ``L'Escamoteur sur les Boulevards,'' an 1806 scene of
Parisians watching a card trick, for $662,500.
</P>
<P>
   The J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles, which has been a big
buyer at auction for years now, bought Tiepolo's ``Alexander and
Campaspe in the Studio of Apelles'' at Christie's for $2.2 million,
another record price. An anonymous donor spent $3.7 million to buy
a rare Rembrandt drawing. ``We wanted it badly,'' said Charles E.
Pierce Jr., director of the Morgan. ``It's an extraordinary drawing
from the 1640s, and very few are available.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say American museums don't go abroad to buy when
the right painting comes along. In London in July at the fabled
sale of art looted by the Nazis from the Austrian branch of the
Rothschild family, the prize painting _ a three-quarter-length
portrait by Frans Hals of an Amsterdam merchant named Tieleman
Roosterman _ was bought by the Cleveland Museum of Art for a record
price of $12.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years the Getty Museum has purchased
important old masters by artists like Poussin, Fra Bartolommeo,
Fragonard and Correggio. Smaller museums, like the Sterling and
Francine Clark Art Institute in Williamstown, Mass., and the J.B.
Speed Art Museum in Louisville, Ky., have also bought a number of
Old Masters.
</P>
<P>
   And while American museums, like avid collectors, will buy
wherever the goods are to be found, many institutions find it
easier to buy art in this country rather than risk the hassle of
applying for an export license and being turned down. Last October
when the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth was set to buy
Botticelli's ``Virgin Adoring the Christ Child'' for $24 million
from the Earl of Wemyss' home in Scotland, the export license was
denied when, at the last minute, the National Galleries of Scotland
were able to match the Kimbell's price.
</P>
<P>
   The dealers representing the Wemyss Heirloom Trust were the
Simon C. Dickinson Group, a London company with two galleries:
Simon Dickinson in London and Dickinson Roundell in New York. Both
handle old masters as well as Impressionist, modern and
contemporary art and both are run by former experts from
Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the faster growth of the market in Manhattan than in
London, the company recently moved into three floors of a town
house on East 66th Street, which it is currently renovating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is not slower in London, it's more expensive,'' said
David Ker, a director of the Simon C. Dickinson Group. ``The bite
of the VAT is just beginning to be felt,'' he said, referring to
value-added tax.
</P>
<P>
   Ker said his company had many good works of art to sell from
European collections because it had a presence in New York. ``There
are Europeans who like the discretion of selling in New York,'' he
added. ``The market here is more discreet. If something sells,
whether it ends up going to Australia or France nobody knows,
whereas London is a small town. Everybody knows everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Hall, who headed the New York branch of Colnaghi until
1996, and Richard Knight, who ran Colnaghi in London, formed a
partnership of their own with galleries in New York and London four
years ago. Like the Simon C. Dickinson Group, Hall &AMP; Knight has
just expanded its space on the Upper East Side. ``Americans still
like to go to Paris to buy French furniture, but collectors of old
masters find it's more convenient to buy paintings here,'' Hall
said. ``Clients interested in a painting can easily take it home to
see how it looks in their living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers, in both New York and in London, who specialize in
other areas have moved into old masters to meet the growing demand.
Lowell Libson, who runs Spink-Leger, a New Bond Street gallery, has
started dealing in old master drawings even though he built his
reputation selling mainly 18th- and 19th-century British works on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was a way of removing British art from its gloomy
sideline, by showing works by, say, Gainsborough, in context with
Fragonard,'' he said. But now, as more American collectors come to
him for old master drawings, he finds himself spending more time in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   One of the attractions for both dealers and the experts at the
auction houses is trying to lure big buyers who have made a name in
other collecting areas into the old masters field. Last year
Stephen A. Wynn, chairman of Mirage Resorts, bought the two most
expensive paintings in Sotheby's January sale in New York, a
Rembrandt and a Rubens. Both are hanging in Wynn's minimuseum at
Bellagio, his $1.6 billion hotel and casino complex in Las Vegas.
Experts say that Paul Allen, co-founder of Microsoft, who has had
eyes mostly for classic Impressionist paintings, is now buying
Canalettos.
</P>
<P>
   Value aside, tastes and fashion are also a draw. It was once
only the pretty old masters, flower paintings or landscapes, that
appealed to American buyers, while Europeans would embrace the more
difficult religious subjects. More recently buyers here are asking
for Baroque paintings, Wachter of Sotheby's said, pointing to
``Adam and Eve Lamenting the Death of Abel,'' by Philippe de
Champaigne. The painting, which depicts a blood-splattered Abel,
might be described as a difficult subject, yet Wachter said he had
lots of interested takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they learn,'' he said, ``the more sophisticated they
are getting.'' The work sold to a telephone bidder for $266,500,
not quite twice its high estimate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
