<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CHILDREN-REVIEW-NY     01-30 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHILDREN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHILDREN IN WAR': CHILDREN CAUGHT IN THE WARS ADULTS WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Program notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(js) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first scene says it all. In Sarajevo, a
7-year-old boy is shot by a sniper. He lies dead in the street, a
huge pool of blood beside his head. He is one of an estimated
15,000 children, the narrator says, killed in the civil war in his
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   For viewers of a certain age, it will be impossible to watch the
HBO documentary ``Children in War'' Monday night without
visualizing the 1960s poster that said, ``War is unhealthy for
children and other living things,'' illustrated with a childlike
drawing of a flower. It was a sentiment meant to overwhelm with its
obviousness, which may be the thinking behind this film as well.
</P>
<P>
   Alan and Susan Raymond, who wrote, directed, produced,
photographed and narrated the two-hour documentary, visited and
interviewed children in four very different war zones: Bosnia,
Israel, Rwanda and Northern Ireland. The results are sometimes
poignant, occasionally chilling and often predictably parrotlike.
</P>
<P>
   When a teen-age girl in Northern Ireland is asked if her father,
who is in prison, is a terrorist, she answers, ``Yes, he has been
accused of being a terrorist, although, as the saying goes, one
man's terrorist is another man's freedom fighter.'' When a
Palestinian boy in a classroom is asked whether he believes the
tactics of Hamas, the militant Palestinian group, are right, he
replies, ``We support Hamas and all its actions.'' He adds, ``The
Jews do much more to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The film hopes, it is assumed, to convey the voices of children,
but it's clear that these are the opinions of their parents and
other elders. If the young people have reflected on these views, if
they have observed their situations and come to those conclusions
independently, there's no sign of it here. If the Raymonds ever did
ask, ``What do your parents tell you about this?'' or ``Is this how
you feel or how your parents and teachers feel?'' they haven't
included the exchanges in the finished documentary.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the sentiments the children appear to have
heard at home are more positive. Some children speak of resignation
and of hoping that others are spared suffering. ``God forbid that
they have to live what we've gone through in Bosnia,'' says a
12-year-old boy with only one arm. It's both heartening and
heartbreaking to hear him say of the attack that took his left arm:
``What can you do? A shell doesn't have eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of those interviewed are adolescents, presumably
chosen because they would be more articulate than their younger
siblings. But the youngest victims are some of the most eloquent. A
5-year-old Rwandan girl, with the scars of huge gashes in her head,
tells of running with her mother and her father from the attackers,
watching her parents being killed and being attacked herself.
``They cut me with a machete and killed me,'' she says. Why did
these people do these things? ``They did it for nothing.'' Some
300,000 children, the film reports, were victims of the Rwandan
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   At times ``Children in War'' inadvertently presents the trauma
as nothing that a little art therapy couldn't fix. (Numerous
children's drawings of tanks and explosions and bodies are shown.)
At other times, the film makes the horror fresh. An Israeli street
scene shows piles of plastic garbage bags on the sidewalk. They are
filled, we are told, with body parts of bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
   The unanswerable question the film brings to mind is which is
worse, boys and girls who have never experienced the innocence of
childhood because they have grown up in the middle of armed
conflict (as in Israel and Northern Ireland), or those whose
childhoods were snatched away suddenly when war broke out (Bosnia
and Rwanda)? The choice is between children with hard eyes or with
dead eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``War,'' says a 12-year-old girl in a Bosnian refugee camp, who
speaks calmly but has the air of someone permanently startled,
``Whoever hasn't experienced it doesn't know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CHILDREN IN WAR: A CALL FOR PEACE THAT A CIVILIZED WORLD CANNOT
IGNORE'
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Monday night at 10
</P>
<P>
   A film by Alan and Susan Raymond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
