<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN-9     01-30 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE IS THE NEXT STOP ON THE AGASSI EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ ``Five shots, can you believe I had to
get five shots?'' Brad Gilbert said of the medical requirements
shortly before he and the new Australian Open champion Andre Agassi
boarded a plane that was headed in the direction of Harare,
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   No, the next stop on Team Agassi's ever-more successful world
tour will bear little resemblance to those that preceded it. After
winning his sixth Grand Slam singles title on Sunday in Rod Laver
Arena with its eye-catching retractable roof, Agassi will be
playing his next match under a potentially leaky roof in the City
Sports Centre, a ramshackle arena with wooden bleachers that is
full of drafts and history and located just a short drive from
central Harare up a rough road.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Zimbabwe and its two key players, Wayne and Byron
Black, hosted a Davis Cup match, the financially strapped electric
company cut power to part of the city: the part that included the
arena. That meant that the lights went out in the midst of Wayne's
singles match against Chile's Marcelo Rios. While Zimbabwean tennis
officials hustled off to plead for power, the arena remained dark
for approximately an hour, and by the time the lights were finally
switched back on, most of the spectators had already headed home.
</P>
<P>
   But the lights are expected to remain in working order when
Agassi comes to town along with his new Davis Cup captain John
McEnroe and the rest of the American team. But not with Pete
Sampras, who withdrew because of a torn hip flexor sustained early
in his five-set semifinal loss to Agassi in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to it,'' said Agassi on Sunday of
his return to Davis Cup after a self-imposed one-year absence.
``It's unfortunate that Pete is not going to be able to make it,
because it certainly made all of our jobs a lot tougher, but I
think we can rise above.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi has been excelling professionally since May, and he has
now won three of the last four Grand Slam events: his only loss
coming against Sampras in the Wimbledon final. ``There's not
anything in my career that compares with these last eight months,''
Agassi said, after defeating Yevgeny Kafelnikov on Sunday, 3-6,
6-3, 6-2, 6-4. ``Winning in Paris alone has given me more than I
could ever ask for or dreamt of, let alone the U.S. Open and here.
It's been a crazy life.''
</P>
<P>
   More unusual still because it is now shared with Steffi Graf,
who won 22 Grand Slam singles titles of her own before retiring
shortly after winning the French Open and losing in the Wimbledon
final. Graf was in the stands for each of Agassi's matches in
Melbourne, sitting between coach Gilbert and Agassi's powerfully
built trainer Gil Reyes. She was there again on Sunday, her face
impassive throughout much of the match but her leg nervously
jiggling as Agassi relentlessly, inexorably overcame yet another
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nerve-wracking, no question about it,'' Graf said afterward.
``It's difficult to watch but also very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Agassi understandably prefers to keep his
private life exactly that. ``Certain things are sacred,'' he said.
``Our relationship is for us, not for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no question that Graf, the most successful
attacking baseliner in the history of the women's game, could find
much more to relate to in Agassi's backcourt duel against
Kafelnikov than she could in the fast-twitch fourth round against
Mark Philippoussis or the semifinal against Sampras when long
rallies were far from the rule.
</P>
<P>
   And that is perhaps the most impressive aspect of Agassi's run
to a second Australian Open title _ he beat players with widely
varying styles. He beat players who happened to be the most
dangerous in the draw, including local hero Philippoussis and
Sampras, whose big serves were theoretically big advantages on a
Rebound Ace court that was much quicker than usual: so quick that
tournament director Paul McNamee said it will be slowed down next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Sampras' injury removed some of the satisfaction from
his victory, Agassi quickly answered no. ``For me it's about doing
what I need to do when I'm out there,'' he said. ``He came up with
200 kilometer second serves in the breaker. As far as I'm
concerned, hurt or not, he was brutal to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been even harder to stop Agassi, who has now won 27 of
his last 28 matches in the Grand Slam events. ``Only Steffi, Rod
Laver twice and Don Budge can say they reached the 28-0 mark, so
he's in pretty good company there,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in his post-match news conference what it would mean to
him to complete the Grand Slam by winning all four majors in the
same calendar year, Agassi said: ``The same thing as winning the
lottery would mean to everybody in here. I couldn't even comprehend
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed a highly unlikely prospect: ``I'm not even thinking
about that at all,'' he said. But what he is interested in is
sustaining the fitness and white-hot concentration that have
transformed him from a gifted yet unpredictable wild card into a
lean and hungry trophy hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you if I fall off the face of the earth again,
I'm not coming back,'' said Agassi, who was ranked 141st and
playing Challenger Tour events late in 1997. ``But I'll take it as
long as it's there for me, and as long as it's in the plan of my
life for sure.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Reyes said: ``I used to see the frustration in his eyes when I'd
see him on court, and now his eyes look like laser beams out there:
fixed on the point at hand and then the next point.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he ever been this focused during a Grand Slam event? ``I was
pretty focused at the Open, too,'' Agassi said referring the U.S.
Open late last summer. ``With Pat Rafter and Pete gone, I had just
to keep the course. I had to stay focused there, too, but yeah
there wasn't a point I let go here.''
</P>
<P>
   And precious few he celebrated, as he jerked his glance away
from his winners like others jerk away from their mistakes. ``The
question you've got to ask yourself and answer is how do I make
this the most difficult on my opponent, because he's struggling as
much as you are,'' Agassi said. ``He's having to beat you, too, and
the only way to do that is to think about the next point. It's
quite a profound simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Made all the simpler when one is not gasping for air or feeling
pain in one's legs. In previous years, Agassi has relaxed in the
off-season. This year, he chose to train at home in Las Vegas
without skipping a day, including Christmas Eve when he and Reyes
headed to the hill near his house that they call ``Magic Mountain''
for sprints of approximately 320 yards from the bottom to the top.
``Up there with no TV cameras and no bright lights,'' Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi said: ``We had to maximize the time that we had, and you
don't have a lot. A month is not a lot of time to recover and
prepare. I wasn't worried about how long a year it was as far as
how much tennis I had played. I was more concerned about getting
myself to a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Reyes, Agassi is in the best shape of his life at
age 29 and can lift the entire stack of weights on a leg machine
and bench press nearly 300 pounds. According to Gilbert, Agassi has
never had a better understanding of the game's intricacies, and
Gilbert believes he can reasonably expect to play for three more
years. Yet as Gilbert, Reyes, Agassi and even Graf also understand,
the question is whether someone who already has reached the summit
can keep summoning the desire to climb higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knows he needs to,'' Gilbert said. ``He can't slack
off. He does not serve like Pete. He can't hit an ace any time. He
has to work his butt off. If he's a little bit vulnerable everybody
knows it because people pay more attention to Andre than any other
player, man or woman.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, it will be the Zimbabweans turn to pay attention, and
if Agassi can keep the focus with the drums beating and perhaps
even the roof leaking, they will also be in for a treat, if not
necessarily a celebration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1739EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
