<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VODAFONE-VIVENDI-NYT     01-30 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-VIVENDI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VODAFONE SETS BROAD ALLIANCE WITH VIVENDI OF FRANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Vodafone AirTouch PLC of Britain announced Sunday that
it had agreed to an alliance with Vivendi SA of France.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the other benefits to Vodafone, the most immediate
effect is to derail a plan by Mannesmann AG, a German company that
had planned to link with Vivendi in hopes of thwarting Vodafone's
$156 billion hostile bid to acquire Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone, a major mobile phone company, and Vivendi, a
broad-based company that owns a 44 percent stake in the French
mobile phone carrier Cegetel, said the two companies would develop
a ``portal'' or entranceway to the Internet accessible by
computers, mobile phones and cable or satellite television. They
said the alliance might also include the two companies' wireless
and fixed-line telephone networks. The alliance is contingent upon
Vodafone's success in acquiring Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gent, chief executive of Vodafone, and Jean-Marie Messier,
chairman of Vivendi, announced their alliance Sunday afternoon in
Paris, where they described their plans for a Web portal. The new
offering would be called MAP, for multiaccess portal. The companies
said they might list MAP on the stock exchange as a separate
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most compelling alliance of the Internet age in
Europe and beyond,'' Messier said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Vodafone would sell Vivendi an additional
7.5 percent stake in Cegetel if Vodafone acquired Mannesmann. Now,
Mannesmann has a 15 percent stake in Cegetel. Gent did not specify
the financial terms, but said that the Cegetel stake would be sold
``at a fair price.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's announcement was a setback for Mannesmann, which had
held talks with Vivendi about a complex merger, one that could have
provided a compelling argument against a Vodafone takeover of
Mannesmann. Klaus Esser, Mannesmann's chief executive, had been
outspoken about his desire to create a closer relationship with
Vivendi. Esser also counts Messier as one of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Esser responded to the Vodafone-Vivendi alliance by issuing a
statement Sunday. ``Vodafone's sell-off of Mannesmann's premium
assets continues,'' he said, referring to the planned sale of the
Cegetel stake. ``This would destroy Mannesmann's superior growth
prospects and destroy the opportunity for greater value for our
shareholders.'' Under British regulations, Vodafone would have to
sell Mannesmann's British wireless company, Orange PLC, if the
Vodafone takeover succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann, an industrial company that in recent years has made
communications its mainstay business, was most interested in
Vivendi's stake in Cegetel, a holding company that owns the French
mobile phone company SFR and Cegetel 7, a struggling competitor to
France Telecom in fixed-line communications.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mannesmann already owns wireless networks in three of
Europe's biggest markets _ Germany, Italy and Britain _ control of
Cegetel in France would have given it an unrivaled position in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks said Vivendi had decided against a
deal with Mannesmann, which was discussed at a board meeting on
Saturday in Paris, because of the German company's uncertain
future. The executives explained that Vivendi was betting that
Vodafone would win its battle for Mannesmann and that the French
company would be able to benefit from access to the combined
company.
</P>
<P>
   Gent heralded the deal as another reason shareholders should
back Vodafone's offer for Mannesmann. ``Everyone was focusing on
Mannesmann doing a deal with Vivendi, but I think they liked our
approach in terms of partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi, which was formerly known as Compagnie Generale des
Eaux, is a complex operation. It owns water utilities and
water-treatment companies around Europe and in the United States,
as well as several electric utility companies. It also owns stakes
in scores of media companies, including 49 percent of Canal Plus
SA, Europe's biggest pay-television company; 25 percent of B-Sky-B,
the British satellite television company controlled by the News
Corp., and all of Havas SA, the French advertising and publishing
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
