<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DILLER-MEDIA-MARKETPL     01-30 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DILLER-MEDIA-MARKETPLACE-ART-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: DILLER'S DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than two decades, Barry Diller has been among the most
respected _ and feared _ figures in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   To admirers like Joe Roth, who resigned earlier this month as
the head of Disney's movie studios, Diller is ``the smartest, most
astute businessman I've ever worked with.''
</P>
<P>
   To critics, who generally won't speak by name, Diller's temper
and unwillingness to share power have kept him from building a
first-tier media company. In Hollywood, stories of Diller's
behavior are legendary, including the time a decade ago when he
threw a videotape so hard that he put a hole in a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Diller's career has come to a crossroads. Diller, who will
turn 58 on Wednesday, is no longer the whiz kid who took control of
the Paramount film studio 26 years ago, or the can't-miss
programmer who in the late 1980s built the Fox network into a
challenger to television's traditional Big Three. The company he
now controls, USA Networks, ranks far behind top old-media players
like Disney in clout, size and profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new crop of moguls dominates the media industry,
including Sumner M. Redstone of Viacom, Mel Karmazin of CBS and,
more recently, Stephen M. Case and Robert W. Pittman of America
Online. If Diller is ever to seize the crown of power and
recognition that friends say he wants, he must somehow figure out a
way to close the gap between USA and its bigger cousins. Otherwise
he runs the risk of being remembered as the Dan Marino of the media
business, a great player who was unable to win the biggest prize in
his chosen game.
</P>
<P>
   Diller's quandary has sharpened the last four months, as America
Online has agreed to buy Time Warner and Viacom to merge with CBS.
Together, those deals create a new scale for media companies. The
combined AOL Time Warner will have annual revenue of more than $30
billion, while Viacom-CBS will have annual revenue of around $25
billion. In comparison, USA will have revenue this year of less
than $4 billion, according to analyst's projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be enormously difficult for him to get
the brass ring, if the brass ring is that very small circle of
those largest and most powerful companies,'' said Michael Fuchs,
the former head of HBO and Warner Music and a friend of Diller.
``And in the last couple months, in the light of what's happened,
he's gotten relatively smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   But Diller's friends warn not to bet against him. And in an
interview on Friday, Diller rejected the notion that he will feel
successful only if USA reaches the media industry's first tier. He
said he aims to build a company that is a profitable hybrid of old
and new media.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a wrestling show on his flagship USA Networks might
direct a viewer who wants to buy tickets to a local wrestling match
to www.ticketmaster.com, a Web site that is part-owned by USA.
After buying the tickets, the fan would then be offered a wrestling
T-shirt from the Home Shopping Network, another USA company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company is both old media and new media, supported by
advertising revenue, subscription revenue and pure commerce
revenue,'' Diller said. ``Now you could say that we won't pull it
off. We believe that if we do pull it off, we will have created a
great company.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Howard Stringer, chairman of Sony Corp. of America, said of
Diller: ``I'm sure Barry would like a larger opportunity, but it's
a pretty good business he's got. His search is for the right
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Diller's relative silence recently is notable, given some
of his past efforts at making deals. In 1993 and 1994, he was
thwarted in separate efforts to buy Paramount and merge with CBS.
His bold attempt last year to recast himself as an Internet
visionary by taking over Lycos, a Web portal company, failed after
a major Lycos shareholder came out against the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Lycos merger blew up, Diller has contented himself
with much smaller Internet acquisitions. Most recently, he traded
his Internet Shopping Network and $40 million in cash for a 75
percent stake in Styleclick.com, a company that had all of $768,546
in revenues in its September quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a $140 billion merger out there, and Barry buys an
Internet company for $40 million. It's a slightly different
scale,'' Fuchs said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a testament to Diller's reputation, even that
relatively minor deal drew substantial attention in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, revenues and profits do not necessarily equal power
in the media industry. Both in Hollywood and on Wall Street,
control of prime assets like a major film studio or a broadcast
network is perceived as incredibly valuable, though their profits
are relatively meager.
</P>
<P>
   But the assets Diller controls do not exactly make up in
prestige what they lack in size or profitability. In addition to
USA and Home Shopping cable channels, his company owns Ticketmaster
and a television production company. It also owns a chain of
little-watched local television stations viewed as likely
candidates to be sold or merged with ABC under relaxed station
ownership rules regulators issued last year. Its Internet assets
include 43 million shares of Ticketmaster Online-City Search, which
provides online ticketing and local guides, and the Hotel
Reservations Network.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, investors have given Diller the benefit of the
doubt. Most Wall Street analysts rate USA Networks a buy, and his
company's stock has risen fivefold the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry's up to something,'' said the mutual fund manager Mario
Gabelli, whose funds owned more than 3 million USA shares as of
Sept. 30. ``You've got electronic commerce and entertainment,
you've got a wonderful array of portals.''
</P>
<P>
   Other investors appear to be hoping that Diller will sell USA to
a larger media company, or even an Internet company like Yahoo.
Mark Greenberg, portfolio manager of the $575 million Invesco
Leisure fund, which owns 60,000 USA shares, said Diller could
easily find a buyer if he wanted to sell. But any buyer will have
to tread lightly, since Diller has repeatedly said he would never
again work for anyone else. Further complicating any combination is
the fact that Seagram controls close to half of USA and has veto
power over any major deal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   USA's soaring stock valuation has left the company expensive
compared with other big media companies, leaving Diller little room
for error.
</P>
<P>
   USA has not yet reported its fourth-quarter results, but for all
of 1999, analysts expect the company to report about $3.2 billion
in revenues and $550 million in cash flow. In 2000, with the aid of
several small acquisitions, the company is expected to post about
$3.8 billion in revenues and less than $700 million in cash flow.
(Cash flow is operating profit before interest, taxes, and
depreciation and amortization costs. Media industry analysts often
focus on cash flow rather than bottom-line profit, which few media
companies except Disney have much of.)
</P>
<P>
   With about 370 million shares outstanding, USA's total market
value is close to $19 billion. So assuming the company's total cash
flow meets estimates this year, USA is currently trading at about
28 times its 2000 cash flow and five times revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, Walt Disney trades at about 17 times estimated
2000 cash flow and 3.5 times revenues, while the combined
Viacom-CBS would trade at 23 times estimated cash flow and five
times revenues. Yet Disney and Viacom-CBS have brands, reach to
consumers and influence with advertisers that USA can only dream
of. Even if USA's money-losing Internet businesses are factored out
and valued separately, a step most analysts take, the company
remains expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The high valuation leaves some in Hollywood and on Wall Street
puzzled. USA Networks ``has been a very good market performer
relative to its actual results,'' said Harold Vogel, an independent
media analyst and author of ``Entertainment Industry Economics: A
Guide for Financial Analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogel said USA's stock has such strong returns mainly because of
Diller's reputation. ``He is very good at presenting himself as a
visionary, and he has done some very important things in the past
that validate that view on Wall Street,'' Vogel said. But Vogel
added that he was not sure what to make of Diller's current
strategy. ``Recently, it hasn't come together, it hasn't come
together as well as he would have liked.''
</P>
<P>
   But the PaineWebber media analyst Chris Dixon, who rates USA a
buy, said that ``anybody who's looking at cash flow or earnings
today doesn't get it.'' Dixon said that USA's combination of
television and Internet assets would make it a leader as the two
media converge.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Diller disputed the notion that USA is overly
expensive. ``I think the fact that this company is highly valued
has something to do with people's faith in the management, but I
don't think that's a major reason,'' Diller said. ``The businesses
that we are in have promise, and the strategy as articulated makes
some sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
