<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHNS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A ST. JOHN'S, DISCORD AND CONFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ First he apologized for his late arrival at a
postgame news conference. Then, Mike Jarvis played concerned
pastor, perplexed by his distracted flock. St. John's had just been
bounced around by a Notre Dame team far less talented than his own.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that the sermon he gave his team after a 73-60
defeat _ the Red Storm's third loss in its last four games _ lasted
a little longer than usual. With a rueful smile, he quipped that
there had been a ``double collection.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit a high, gentle note by reminding his team, as well as
observers, that about 250 other college teams would love to be 13-5
and ranked in the top 25. He dropped a low, vengeful note when he
scolded that his bunch had launched a greedy 29 3-pointers and
turned its back on the Red Storm's attacking style.
</P>
<P>
   He called that long range attack fool's gold. Like fools, Jarvis
intimated, his players grabbed for the easy score and paid for it.
The St. John's coach is too patient to panic and too calculating to
show up his team publicly. But he made it clear that the Red Storm
received a Come-to-Jarvis talk.
</P>
<P>
   He made it plain that Monday night's game with undefeated and
fourth-ranked Syracuse (17-0) in the Carrier Dome is as good a time
as any for the Red Storm to renew its faith in its system and in
each other. He told them he performed his best when things are at
their worst.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is time for his players to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses was in the desert for 40 years,'' Jarvis intoned in one
last evangelical flourish. ``We've only been in there for a couple
of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing a few games in January is not that big a deal. Neither
are the occasional on-court mental lapses that allowed Ohio State
to dash off an 11-0 run in the final 2 minutes 49 seconds of one
recent defeat. Or the Red Storm's stubborn insistence last Saturday
to try to outgun rather than outrun a plodding Fighting Irish team
_ despite the fact St. John's is one of the poorest
3-point-shooting teams in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   What is worrisome, however, is the increasingly dissatisfied
tone of the players in the locker room after the losses. In both
instances, players have complained about whistles that were or were
not blown. The senior Lavor Postell, one of the team's most
clearheaded leaders, announced his intention to call a players-only
meeting after Saturday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   In another corner, Erick Barkley said calling a meeting is fine
but what is really needed is for his teammates to remember their
roles. In a nutshell: the shooters should shoot and the passers
should pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should do what they do best,'' said Barkley, a
grimace darkening his face. ``What they do in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore runs the floor for the Red Storm. He is a splendid
talent and a zealous competitor who worked hard in the off-season
to improve his jump shot. Barkley had been magnificent so far this
season, but he is also louder, more demonstrative and often
disapproving of his teammates during the game. At one point against
the Irish, he screamed ``No!'' as Chudney Gray attempted to launch
a shot over Troy Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Gray suffered an 0-for-7 shooting night; but the
senior's defensive effort and rebounding, as well as nine points a
game, have been vital _ especially since he essentially is the Red
Storm's only bench player.
</P>
<P>
   When Barkley was asked if he was perhaps trying to do too much _
especially after a 6-of-16 shooting performance (a team-high for
attempts) with 11 3-point tries (also a team-high) countered by
just one assist, he dismissed the question disdainfully. ``They are
starting to play me differently,'' he said. ``They are keeping me
from the basket and forcing me to kick it out. Guys got to step up
and make those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse offers no such discord or confusion about how they fit
together. Three seniors _ Jason Hart, Ryan Blackwell and Etan
Thomas _ have led the Orangemen to their best start in school
history. The defensive-minded Hart leads the Big East in assists
(6.8 a game). Blackwell unobtrusively patrols the blocks, and
scores and rebounds (8.2 a game), and Thomas is the best
shot-blocking center in a league full of them. He leads the Big
East with 4.1 blocks a game, and he scores 14.9 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis and his players find comfort in the fact that they had a
similar rough stretch at this time last season _ three tough losses
to Duke, Connecticut and Miami _ which they learned from to reach
the South Regional finals of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament. Syracuse Coach Jim Boeheim and Hart are
motivated by a first-round loss to Oklahoma in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   When Syracuse walloped UConn last Monday, Boeheim urged his
players to take part in a fans-to-the-floor celebration at the
Carrier Dome. The Syracuse coach wanted his team _ virtually the
same underachieving group from last season _ to understand that
they had just taken a big step toward their national-title
aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   But Jarvis has a different team this season, one without the
budding National Basketball Association star Ron Artest or the
sturdy Tyrone Grant and a rotation that often went nine deep. The
St. John's coach has acknowledged that this edition is not as
talented, but rightfully believes it is a serious threat come
tournament time.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that, however, each member must take responsibility
for these recent defeats and recognize they are significant
setbacks to their title dreams. No whistles. No finger pointing.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm need not worry about wandering in the desert for
40 years, but they quite possibly could get lost through March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
