<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MANNESMANN-VODAFONE-A     01-30 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANNESMANN-VODAFONE-ART-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN VOTE ON VODAFONE BID SHOULD BE A SQUEAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Klaus Esser, the chairman of the German industrial power
Mannesmann, has built his career by amassing control. The next
seven days will determine if he loses it.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of an election-style campaign that may
determine who will dominate Europe's booming market for wireless
communications, Esser is desperately trying to persuade
shareholders to vote down a hostile takeover bid by Vodafone
AirTouch of Britain. Mannesmann shareholders have until next Monday
to decide whether to accept or reject Vodafone's offer of about 290
euros, or nearly $282.50, for each share of their stock.
</P>
<P>
   It is the biggest hostile takeover ever attempted, and it has
electrified Germany, a country where hostile bids have been rare
and successful ones almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Esser suffered a potential major defeat Sunday when Vodafone
announced a major alliance on Internet projects with Vivendi, one
of France's most important media and communications companies.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is contingent on the success of Vodafone's bid, but it
is devastating to Mannesmann because Vivendi's chief, Jean-Marie
Messier, has been a longtime ally. Indeed, Esser had sought to
devise his own merger with Vivendi.
</P>
<P>
   With a current value of about $155 billion, the hostile bid is
inflated by investors' delirious expectations about wireless
stocks. And it has sent Esser barnstorming for support, from
Duesseldorf to New York, with the same core message: ``It is easy
to see how this would benefit Vodafone shareholders. But it offers
nothing to Mannesmann shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mannesmann's share price of 260 euros still trails
Vodafone's offer of more than 300 euros, it has soared 78 percent
since rumors of a Vodafone offer began in early November. Esser,
who has raised his estimate of the ``true'' value of Mannesmann
twice since the fight began, says the offer is still too low.
</P>
<P>
   But Vodafone's chief executive, Chris Gent, has waged his own
charm offensive. Knowing that resistance to his offer is strongest
in Germany, he spent much of last week visiting investors there and
exchanging potshots with Esser.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have taken out numerous advertisements in German
newspapers, sometimes in response to each other. After one
Mannesmann ad featured a baby and the headline ``He has made big
plans,'' Vodafone countered with one showing a breast-feeding baby
and the headline ``Whoever wants to get big needs a good mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Esser's chances of victory are only even at best, according to
analysts, who say that about 60 percent of Mannesmann shares are
held by foreign investors, and many of them appear ready to sell.
</P>
<P>
   All this has left Europeans, especially Germans, gaping in
disbelief. The value of European mergers hit a record pace in 1999,
exceeding that of U.S. mergers for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, German companies were among the biggest foreign buyers,
as when Deutsche Bank bought Bankers Trust and Mannesmann itself
bought the British cellular carrier Orange for about $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many Germans, including Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, attack
the Vodafone bid as an ``Anglo-Saxon'' assault on their country's
tradition of a ``consensus'' economy.
</P>
<P>
   The shock has been all the greater because of the target:
Mannesmann, which a decade ago was a maker of steel tubes and auto
parts, transformed itself into a fast-growing communications
company that had seemed to be doing almost everything right.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what may surprise most, given the uproar, is the extent to
which Mannesmann and German leaders have been willing to play by
Anglo-Saxon free-market rules. The clash has shaped up largely as a
struggle between two expansionist corporations with a common goal:
creation of a pan-European communications giant that controls
networks across the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude may explain why the Germans have not tried to
challenge Vodafone's right to mount a hostile bid. There is no push
to restrict foreign takeovers. And, in a departure, neither the
government nor Germany's patrician financial institutions have
tried to protect Mannesmann by buying a friendly stake in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generates very emotional reactions among the people who
are affected, but it isn't a rational reaction,'' said Hans Georg
Crone-Erdmann, director of the Association of Chambers of Commerce
in Mannesmann's home state, North-Rhine Westphalia. ``When you see
which banks, insurers and chemical companies are merging across
national boundaries, then you know that these kinds of takeovers
are natural.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine two more different personalities
leading the campaigns. Gent, a gregarious and irreverent
51-year-old, is a magician at using the Vodafone stock as currency
for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Esser, a methodical and phlegmatic 52-year-old lawyer who
studied business at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
achieved his successes by taking a handful of shrewd, calculated
chances.
</P>
<P>
   But both have strong ambitions to expand their companies _
ambitions that were set on a collision course early last year.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone already owned Britain's second-largest wireless phone
network and several stakes in wireless carriers around the world.
Mannesmann's crown jewel, meanwhile, was its controlling stake in
D-2, Germany's largest wireless carrier.
</P>
<P>
   And to think that when Mannesmann first applied for a wireless
license in 1989, the move seemed little more than a side bet.
``Most of the management was either skeptical or hostile,'' said
Peter Mihatch, who persuaded Mannesmann's chairman at the time,
Werner Dieter, to take the plunge and then ran the mobile-phone
unit until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, though, it was clear that Europe's digital
wireless telephones _ linked throughout the European Union by a
common technical standard called GSM _ would become a huge
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Esser, who was financial director of a Mannesmann engineering
unit at the time, played almost no role in Mannesmann's original
move into mobile phones. By the time he was elevated to chief
financial officer in 1994, though, he was convinced Mannesmann's
future lay in communications, rather than in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, Esser, who became chief executive last
May, orchestrated the sales of many older businesses and began
branching into new areas. He bought a 15 percent stake in Cegetel,
a French consortium led by Vivendi, that owned France's
second-largest mobile network. In 1997, Mannesmann expanded its
stake in Omnitel, the Italian mobile carrier owned by Olivetti, to
22 percent. And it started building fixed-line networks to compete
against Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   It was in January 1999 that Esser began to regard Gent as a
threat. That was when Gent reached a deal to buy the big U.S.
wireless carrier AirTouch Communications for about $65 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Esser had no interest in the U.S. market. But AirTouch worried
him, because it owned 35 percent of the D-2 network and was a
partner in most other Mannesmann telecommunications ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had always had a close partnership with AirTouch,'' he said
recently. ``We both had a lot of respect for each other and would
never have considered a hostile takeover.''
</P>
<P>
   In a fax to Gent on Jan. 7, 1999, Esser warned that an AirTouch
deal would create a ``conflict'' and that Gent ought to consult
with Mannesmann before proceeding. Gent did meet with Esser in
London eight days later _ the same day AirTouch agreed to
Vodafone's takeover.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, both executives saw opportunities to collaborate.
Mannesmann wanted access to the British market, while Gent sought
to expand his grip on the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, though, both were wary about ceding control. Esser
said that Vodafone rebuffed his suggestions about Mannesmann taking
a ``meaningful stake'' in its British operation. And he grew
suspicious when, later in January, The Financial Times published a
gossip item that Vodafone was interested in buying Mannesmann _
though people close to Gent say he had no firm plans at the time.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Esser was busy shoring up his own position around
Europe. In a coup last summer, he acquired control of the Omnitel
cellular network in Italy by supporting Olivetti's successful
takeover bid against Italy's dominant telephone company, Telecom
Italia.
</P>
<P>
   In that deal, Mannesmann agreed to buy Olivetti's stake in
Omnitel and a fledgling fixed-line phone service for $7.8 billion.
That cleared a regulatory path for Olivetti to win control of
Telecom Italia, which had its own mobile telephone business.
Suddenly, Mannesmann controlled wireless networks in Europe's two
biggest markets, Germany and Italy, in addition to a small stake in
the French wireless network SFR.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened, Esser began a frontal assault on Vodafone in
Britain. ``We always made it clear that entering the United Kingdom
was one of our highest priorities,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Flying to Hong Kong in October, Esser hammered out a deal with
the Hong Kong holding company Hutchison Whampoa, the biggest
shareholder in Orange PLC, Britain's third-largest wireless
carrier. In October he said Mannesmann would acquire Orange for $33
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gent was outraged. He said he learned of the deal by reading
about it in a newspaper on Oct. 20 _ the day before he was
scheduled to meet Esser in Berlin to discuss further
``cooperation.'' Late that night, Esser called Gent to confirm the
news and to cancel the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Gent hired Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. to analyze a
possible run at Mannesmann. On Nov. 14, Gent announced Vodafone's
hostile takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two-and-a-half months later, people at both companies say
it is possible, though unlikely, that the two will reach a friendly
deal before next Monday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Gent's main argument for a merger is that the combined company
would instantly form the world's dominant wireless carrier,
generating huge savings and having far more muscle to roll out new
technologies for high-speed data communications.
</P>
<P>
   Esser's counterargument is that Mannesmann already controls the
basis of a European platform. He dismisses the value of Vodafone's
American properties, noting that Vodafone cut a deal last year with
Bell Atlantic Corp. that left it with only a 45 percent stake in
those systems.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann also says that, unlike Vodafone, it has a growing
array of fixed-line fiber optic networks able to offer a full line
of high-speed data and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone says it can prevail simply by winning more than 50
percent of Mannesmann shares. Esser argues that Vodafone could be
blocked on key issues, which under British regulations might
include the forced sale of Orange, unless Vodafone buys out all
minority shareholders _ an expensive process that would require
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that U.S. institutional investors, which own about
20 percent of Mannesmann shares, appear overwhelmingly ready to
accept Vodafone's offer. ``The bottom line is that this would be a
global company on the first day,'' said Jo Oliver, an analyst at
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, German individual investors, who hold an estimated 10
percent of the company's shares, seem to support Mannesmann
overwhelmingly. German financial institutions, which own about 30
percent, are keeping quiet but are believed in most cases to lean
toward Mannesmann. The company can also count on support from
Hutchison Whampoa, which owns 10 percent of its stock, a result of
the Orange deal.
</P>
<P>
   In short, many analysts see the contest as too close to call.
But not all analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recently, our official view was that it was a 50-50
race,'' said Frank Rothauge, senior telecommunications analyst at
Sal. Oppenheimer &AMP; Co. in Frankfurt. ``But I now believe that
Mannesmann has a slightly better chance than Vodafone.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothauge said European institutions were concerned that shares
of a new Mannesmann would not remain part of the key European or
German benchmark indexes, since British companies _ outside
Europe's single-currency zone _ are not included. That could cause
investment funds based on those indexes to sell the stock.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, the companies have not ruled out a
last-minute deal. But before that could happen, Esser or Gent would
have to make a decision neither has ever made before: to give up
control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
