   (lh) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Monday, Jan. 31. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHER-DEBATE (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ The school voucher
debate is playing out all across the country with increasing
intensity these days as more than 25 legislatures are considering
bills that would create some type of system in which public dollars
would be used for private and parochial schools By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE (Baltimore) _ A $2.5 million federally
financed study at the University of Maryland represents a new wave
in academic medicine: the application of rigorous, Western
scientific methods to test alternative therapies, from ginkgo
biloba to shark cartilage to a mystical Chinese healing art known
as qi gong. Just five years ago, many academics would not have gone
near such studies, for fear they would become a laughingstock. And
while alternative therapies remain hugely controversial,
multimillion dollar clinical trials are getting under way this year
at some of the nation's most prestigious university hospitals. By
Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SUPER-BOWL (Atlanta) _ Game story; Titans vs. Rams. Kickoff
at 6:25 p.m. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DYNASTY (Washington) _ They were on the same platform on
Saturday, George Bush and George W. Bush, father and son, former
president and would-be president, plus the family matriarch,
Barbara Bush, and three of George W.'s four siblings, seeking votes
in the New Hampshire primary. But you will incur the Bushes' wrath
if you compare their family to that other well-known American
political clan, the Kennedys. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NH-CAMPAIGN-RDP (Dateline TK) _ Bradley is expected to take on
Gore over campaign finance. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-HOLOCAUST (Yantarniy, Russia) _ The slaughter of 7,000
Jews, mostly young women, in Kaliningrad four days after the
liberation of Auschwitz in 1945 may have been the last, and one of
the most forgotten, episodes of the Nazi campaign of genocide. That
is, until today. By Michael Wines.
</P>
