<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-CAPTIONS-MEDIA-ART     01-30 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CAPTIONS-MEDIA-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART (AND BUSINESS) OF READING TELEVISION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By THOMAS W. HOLCOMB Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The argument in the control room was subtle, but not trivial.
Did the actor on the video screen grunt? Or did he clear his
throat? Or did he grunt in the process of clearing his throat?
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we trying to get across here?'' asked Chris Kallet, a
training supervisor at VITAC of Canonsburg, Pa., 20 miles southwest
of Pittsburgh, one of the top three television captioning companies
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A trainee answered, ``More or less, he's just getting a little
emphatic about having just won a bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hutchins, a VITAC executive, stood to the side and watched
as the captioners replayed over and over a few frames of the video.
``This may never come up again,'' Hutchins explained. ``You can't
make a rule out of it and say when somebody goes, `Uhmmmm,' here's
what you write. But what you can say is, `What did we get as
hearing people?'''
</P>
<P>
   So goes the work of the nation's captioners. They are a busy
breed these days. Once used only to help the deaf and those with
partial hearing loss, captions are increasingly ubiquitous, with
advertisers and television networks recognizing their value. More
and more, they are appearing on screens in places like sports bars,
health clubs and offices, where the audio would be distracting or
difficult to hear. They are also being used to help teach the
English language.
</P>
<P>
   Captioning got a jump-start a few years ago when the Federal
Communications Commission, seeking to help those with hearing loss,
set a schedule mandating that captioning be phased in for most
television programming by 2006. But the major broadcasters and some
cable companies are well ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   So there is plenty of work for companies like VITAC and
captioners like VITAC's Marla M. Lahr, who must combine the
quickness and ear of a stenographer with the nerves of an
air-traffic controller.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of captioning. One is offline captioning,
done by fast typists who work on taped programs, using standard PC
keyboards and professional video editing software.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lahr, initially trained as a court reporter, does ``real
time captioning'' for live programming. This requires the speed
made possible by a 22-key stenography machine and the skills to
break a stream of speech into the basic sounds of language, like
the ``buh om buh'' that make up the the word ``bomb'').
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lahr has one shot to get it right and must maintain a pace
that keeps the transcript no more than an echo away from the
action. Though a script is often delivered beforehand _ the same
one that prompts the on-air talent, like a news anchor _ the actual
dialogue often deviates, and there are always unscripted segments.
Ms. Lahr has to recognize what is new, transcribe it and send it
instead of the scripted material.
</P>
<P>
   VITAC has to make significant changes in technique before court
reporters can go on the air as captioners. ``There's a certain
pathology to the process that we recognize,'' Hutchins said. ``A
young lady will come in here, pretty good court reporter, very
confident about her abilities, excited that she's going to get into
captioning, and she will begin the training process very fired up,
excited. Generally we know that in two to four weeks that she is
going to be walking around with stooped shoulders, totally
dejected, feeling like, `I'll never get this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A court reporter _ responsible for a more limited vocabulary and
in most cases unconcerned with context _ can concentrate on speed
and clean up the transcript later. Real-time captioners, on the
other hand, must be aware of context _ should they use ``there'' or
``their''? _ and may have to write on subjects ranging from war to
baseball and are constantly making decisions about what they are
sending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Izmit the name of a town or a person, or something else?''
Hutchins asked an imagined captioner. ``Is Izmit the name of a
seismic registry system? If you don't have a clue, you don't even
know where to begin looking for the answers as to how to make that
caption more accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   The people at VITAC talk a lot about making captions accurate.
Twenty years ago, the emphasis was on getting captions into the
video signal. The first captioning agency, the Caption Center, was
established in 1971 at WGBH, the Boston public station.
</P>
<P>
   It began by providing open captioned (visible by all who tuned
in) rebroadcasts of ``The French Chef'' with Julia Child and the
ABC News programs. The center, now part of a larger body, the
CPB/WGBH National Center for Accessible Media, worked with ABC, the
FCC, advocacy groups and technology providers to develop the
current system of closed captioning. In 1979, the FCC formed the
National Captioning Institute as a nonprofit provider of
closed-captioning programming.
</P>
<P>
   Newer, for-profit companies like VITAC, which is announcing a
merger Monday with the court reporting company LegaLink, Media
Captioning Services of Carlsbad, Calif., and others have since
entered the market. They compete with the Caption Center and the
National Captioning Institute for the federal grants and
advertising dollars that pay for captioning.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Feinberg, director of marketing services for the captioning
institute, said the first closed-captioned programming was
broadcast by three stations on March 16, 1980: the Sunday night
movie on ABC, ``The Wonderful World of Disney'' on NBC and
``Masterpiece Theater'' on PBS. Only viewers with decoders, which
had just become available, could view the captions. A decade later,
federal law mandated that closed-captioning decoders be built into
most televisions produced for the American market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Although the amount of captioned programming has grown immensely
the last two decades and the technology involved has advanced, the
human talent needed for the job has remained a constant.
</P>
<P>
   A real-time captioner has to keep cool under all circumstances,
from tragedy to comedy. At the 1988 Republican National Convention,
Hutchins recalled, an anchor asked a nearby delegate what he
thought of George Bush's choice of a running mate, Dan Quayle. The
delegate answered that where he came from ``we shoot quail.'' The
whole captioning team was in stitches, including Marty Block, now
an officer at VITAC, who was doing the captions and managed to hold
on even though he could barely control his fingers for a few
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The other extreme is captioning tragedies. Concentrating on such
live coverage as the deaths of Diana, Princess of Wales, and John
F. Kennedy Jr. was difficult for the captioners at VITAC, Hutchins
said, because the emotional elements were distracting.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Thursday evening, Ms. Lahr took a turn captioning
CNN's Headline News at the 5 p.m. return from a commercial break.
</P>
<P>
   She tapped a pedal with her right foot to send the script, as
she heard it, one line at a time, and she read ahead in the preview
screen to determine when she would need to transcribe. Even as she
tapped the pedal, her fingers danced, in coordinated motions,
pulsing the air over her steno keys. They need to descend a nearly
imperceptible amount to take over the writing. Her transitions are
seamless.
</P>
<P>
   It was a virtuoso performance, the stress of which was belied by
her dry brow. The only hint at what it took to accomplish was her
comment during a commercial break: ``Whew, only three more
half-hours left.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
