<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT &LR;      01-30 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS NOT ON THE AGENDA (YET) AS TYSON PONDERS HIS FUTURE  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, England _ A few minutes after he had dispatched
Julius Francis with a technical knockout in the second round, Mike
Tyson returned to the center of the same ring here at the MEN Arena
for a press conference. It was the perfect setting, because he
looks very much at ease there.
</P>
<P>
   There was no snarling, no gloating. There was no overwhelming
appearance of joy, either. It seemed like just another day at the
office for Tyson, who knocked Francis down five times before
referee Roy Francis stopped the bout at 1 minute 3 seconds of the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed all in black, Tyson mopped sweat from his brow
occasionally as he dissected his victory over the hapless British
heavyweight champion. He thanked the British fans for their
hospitality and held out the possibility that he will fight here
again. Tyson shed little light on his future other than to say that
he would like to fight within six weeks, and possibly in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But before anybody pronounces him the Tyson of old, Tyson
himself knows the difference. ``I've got a ways to go,'' he said.
``I'm trying to get better and cultivate my skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Francis (21-8) was completely overwhelmed by Tyson
(47-3), the former undisputed heavyweight champion got hit a lot.
He was moving his head and making himself a difficult target to
track, but at one point Francis nailed Tyson with a stiff jab that
seem to keep him at bay momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me, but I'm still here,'' Tyson said. ``We're in the
hurt business. If you're not prepared to get hit, you shouldn't
step in the ring. I really didn't know what to expect from him. I
was in a real determined mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis lacked the skills and the means to keep Tyson off him
and eventually Tyson's work to the body (Francis was dropped by two
body shots) did Francis in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried, man,'' Francis said. ``He's a good puncher. Everybody
knows he's a great boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expected Francis, 35, to do any better than he did. And
he did come to fight. He did not run away from Tyson and make it a
horrible match. But he was not even in the same class with Tyson
who is struggling to get his confidence back. When asked whether he
needed to step up to a higher level of opponent or fight more
consistently to get his confidence back Tyson said, ``Yeah, all of
those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has a March 25 date to return to the ring. The opponent
will either be Shannon Briggs or Lou Savarese, who retired after
getting battered by Michael Grant in June. The sites being
discussed are the Meadowlands, Paris, Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's advisers let go a huge sigh of relief that this fight
did not dissolve into something bizarre. It was Tyson's cleanest
fight in his last three bouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mood and spirits are better than they have been in a very
long time,'' said Jay Larkin, senior vice president of sports and
event programming at Showtime, which broadcasts Tyson's bouts. ``I
will tell you that getting his head in the right place is as
important as the amount of time he spends in the gym preparing for
a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson and his advisors are at a crossroads. If his skills have
diminished to the level that he cannot handle top level competition
then they would risk his financial future by matching him against
someone who could beat him. But they must be careful to find
opponents the buying public will accept.
</P>
<P>
   They have some options: There are Zeljko Mavrovic and Vitali
Klitskcho, the World Boxing Organization heavyweight champion. They
can continue to have him fight in Europe and other foreign
countries where people will come out to see him simply because he
is Mike Tyson, the celebrity boxer, regardless of who he fights. Or
they can gradually step up the competition over the next two fights
and try to prepare Tyson for an eventual heavyweight championship
bout against Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are no guarantees that Lewis will have the
undisputed heavyweight championship by the time Tyson is ready to
fight him. Lewis will meet Michael Grant in April at Madison Square
Garden and no one is sure how that bout will end.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, Tyson and Lewis are not on a collision
course, because each man has an exclusive contract with rival cable
networks. Tyson is signed with Showtime and Lewis is signed with
Home Box Office.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said it is ridiculous for anyone to be talking about
Tyson and Lewis fighting. He mentioned the fact that HBO would
never allow Lewis to fight on a rival network, although Showtime
fighters (Evander Holyfield and Felix Trinidad) have fought on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they would allow Lennox to fight on Showtime, I'd love to
do the fight,'' Larkin said. ``But look at the history. Have you
ever seen that door open the other way? And it never will. The only
way it will happen is if Lennox goes to them and says make the
fight. Mike Tyson doesn't need Lennox Lewis. Lennox Lewis needs
Mike Tyson.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMNN-NY     01-30 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMNN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A SUPER ATTRACTION WITHOUT THE DYNASTIES HERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VESCEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the nice things about Super Bowl XXXIV was that
neither the St. Louis Rams nor the Tennessee Titans carried the
heavy weight of entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   The players seemed genuinely grateful to be part of the Super
Bowl, knowing that it might only come around once, and none of them
brought an attitude of ``been here, done that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the blessing of parity, of which the National Football
League can never get enough. The concept of parity comes off as a
goofy stereotype until Commissioner Paul Tagliabue starts talking
about how the league shares its network television money to level
the playing field for well-run organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Then along come the Rams and the Titans, two teams that made the
right choices of players and coaches in the short run, which is
really all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had never appeared in a Super Bowl, going back to the
Houston Oilers franchise that began in 1960. The Rams had made
their only appearance in a previous life in Los Angeles back in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   A number of franchises have given off the definite impression
that they belonged in the Super Bowl just about every year _ even
though their identities shifted over the years, from Dallas to San
Francisco, from Buffalo to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the biggest thing was how I always perceived teams who
made it to the Super Bowl,'' said Bruce Matthews of the Titans, in
his first Super Bowl after 17 years. ``I always thought they were
head and shoulders above other teams, or if I was ever going to be
on a Super Bowl team there would be no doubt in my mind that we
were going to make the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Matthews played on a transplanted team with an
excellent 13-3 won-lost record that survived the extra week of the
wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each week our confidence grew, and I don't think until the
clock ran out in Jacksonville that I ever perceived ourselves as a
Super Bowl team,'' Matthews said. ``I think that's a quality in our
team that has helped us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a bunch of hungry guys who haven't really accomplished
anything as far as a team goes in this league. We want to taste
that success. We're sick and tired of hearing, `You can't do this
and you can't do that,' and basically watching other teams in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time two franchises were in the Super Bowl for the
first time was in 1986, when the Chicago Bears and the New England
Patriots met. Leading up to that game, the Bears acted as if they
were good enough to blow away the Patriots, which is exactly what
they did, by a 46-10 score.
</P>
<P>
   This year both teams believed they were good. The Rams were
favored by roughly 7 points, and the Titans smarted a bit about
that, noting that they had already beaten the Rams, 24-21, this
season, and didn't that count for something?
</P>
<P>
   Both teams gave off the old sports cliche of just being happy to
be here.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Proehl, who caught the pass for the Rams' only touchdown
in the conference title game, said: ``I've been to every one since
I've been in the league. I come just because I'm a fan of the game.
It's just fun to come down and see a lot of the guys you play
against.'' Now he was getting paid to attend the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream about it growing up playing football in the streets
with your friends,'' said Frank Wychek, the Tennessee receiver who
tossed the lateral for the game-winning touchdown in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when I'm in my hotel room, I just think about what
is really happening this week. You have to stop and pinch yourself
because these things don't happen to guys like me.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm enjoying every second of it. Just to play in the
game and set foot on the field is enough for me, but to do
something special in a game of this magnitude is just icing on the
cake.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of excitement even came from the two coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fisher of the Titans, who earned a ring with Chicago
although injured in the Bears' Super Bowl season, never lost his
poise in public this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil of the Rams had coached the Philadelphia Eagles in
the 1981 Super Bowl, and then left the business, citing the dreaded
``coach's burnout.'' He returned to coach the Rams three years ago
and has been generally upbeat in this sudden rush to the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil did turn crabby when both teams were advised against
trying to get to the Georgia Dome for a practice last Saturday
because of the icy roads.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the nasty weather that produced an introverted
feeling of waiting for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no golf, no going around in shorts,'' noted Neil
O'Donnell, the Titans' backup quarterback, who played for
Pittsburgh in the 1996 game in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was a focus, a looking forward to the game
itself. If this was to be their Super Bowl experience, they were
going to enjoy it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
