u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-BENCH-NYT     01-30 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-BENCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' COACH FACES FINE OR SUSPENSION FOR THROWING BENCH ON ICE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ALEX YANNIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After losing only once in 15 games, the Devils lost twice in two
nights over the weekend. One of their players was badly cut, and
Coach Robbie Ftorek may be fined or suspended for tossing a bench
onto the ice in the 3-1 loss on the road to the Detroit Red Wings
on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek threw the bench because he was so incensed at the
officials for not calling a penalty against the Red Wings when Jay
Pandolfo was crashed into the end boards by Mathieu Dandenault. The
cuts to Pandolfo's forehead and face were so severe that he
required 84 stitches, mostly over his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never lost consciousness, but I knew I hit my head hard,''
Pandolfo said. ``I got the cut on my forehead for crashing against
the boards, but the rest is because someone's skate caught me.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was falling on the ice behind Martin Brodeur's goal
from the check by Dandenault, Sergei Brylin of the Devils fell
backward over Pandolfo. Brylin's skate opened up the most dangerous
cut over Pandolfo's left eye.
</P>
<P>
   Pandolfo is almost certain to be placed on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hockey League may take action against Ftorek as
early as Monday. One mitigating element for Ftorek is that he did
not toss the bench toward an official but threw it on the ice in a
moment of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek would not say whether he expected to be suspended for the
incident, but Ron Ego, the supervisor of officials at the game,
said a suspension for Ftorek was rather unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Devils interviewed about the incident put blame on
Ftorek for losing his cool in the game between the league's two
conference leaders. For a game of such significance, especially
since it was the teams' only meeting in the regular season, it
seemed peculiar that the league did not assign two referees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Robbie; he's a fiery guy,'' defenseman Lyle
Odelein said. ``He was frustrated, we all were, that a player got
hurt like that and nobody did anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik, who is usually the most outspoken of all the
Devils, was visibly upset that there was no call on the play
involving Pandolfo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a democracy, but don't get me going,'' Holik
said. ``Don't get me to say anything. There is an unwritten rule
that players are not allowed to talk about officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek threw the bench to the delight of the sellout crowd
immediately after Kirk Maltby scored the third goal for the Red
Wings. It came with 6 minutes 44 seconds left in the period in the
same sequence during which Pandolfo got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The moment drew more laughs from the crowd when it was announced
that the Devils were assessed a bench minor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
