<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
San Francisco Chronicle copywright 200
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COFFEE AND ONE OF THOSE DANISH, PLEASE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Steve Horwitz &LR;  forwards a Wall Street Journal account of the
international sperm industry, in which Danish sperm bank executive
 &UR; Ole Schou &LR;  proclaims, ``We think we can be the McDonald's of
sperm.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmark is ``Europe's sperm king,'' says the Journal, because
the sperm quality is considered high, because blue eyes are in
demand and because Danish law permits 25 live births from each
donor.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In other international business notes about exports from
the land of  &UR; Hans Christian Andersen &LR;  and  &UR; Victor Borge &LR; ,  &UR; Bennett &LR; 
 &UR; Woll &LR;  says the label on his Trader Joe's Capers says the buds are
picked on the shores of the Mediterranean. It also says the capers
are products of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh2,10p10  &LR; Flash
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rt,10p10  &LR;  -  &UR; Miuccia Prada &LR; , whose yacht is representing Italy
in the America's Cup races, told the Telegraph of London that she
considers herself a socialist, ``except where money is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   - LuxuryFinder.com, a Web site being created by former National
Law Journal publisher  &UR; James Finkelstein &LR; , will have tips on
``jetiquette,'' manners for flying on private jets, reports the
Providence Sunday Journal.  &UR; Angela Weber &LR;  suggests a site for the
rest of us, on ``the etiquette of flying coach.''
</P>
<P>
   - Flipping through the business listings of the Pacific Bell
phone book,  &UR; Lyn Gray &LR;  came upon page 69, ``Demented-Devilboy,''
which seems, without telling a story, to tell a racy story. Can
other readers find stories in the headings?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Libby Gelman-Waxner &LR;  writes in Premiere magazine that TV
stars don't easily become movie stars. ``TV stardom is nothing to
be ashamed of; it's like microwave popcorn or Pop-Tarts, handy and
almost as tasty as the real thing. Being in movies tends to expose
most TV stars; you can see their tinkly little brains working way
too hard, trying to remember what an emotion is, while their souls
are desperately figuring out what to wear on `Leno.' ''
</P>
<P>
   - Nature is expensive, says the Washington Monthly: Backpacker
magazine surveys found that its average reader makes $89,500 a year
and spent $4,500 on backpacking equipment in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   - Every man named Smith listed in the Manchester, N.H., phone
book was invited by George magazine to a screening last night of
``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,'' after which viewers were to be
polled as to which candidate ``best reflects the values'' of the
 &UR; Jimmy Stewart &LR;  candidate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM YALE SCHOLARS &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;   &LR; Researchers at the Gender Communications Laboratory at Yale
University, whose studies are financed by a grant from Physique, a
new Procter &AMP; Gamble hair care line, have determined that both men
and women are influenced by ``bad hair days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more fascinating,'' said psychology and women's and
gender studies Professor  &UR; Marianne LaFrance &LR; , ``is our finding that
individuals perceive their capabilities to be significantly lower
than others when experiencing bad hair.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEGAL LOVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rt,10p10  &UR; Uncle Zeb &LR; , the advice columnist for the UC Berkeley
law student-run Web site Boalt.org, &LR;   &LR; offers legal scholars answers
to all kinds of questions:
</P>
<P>
   ``Zeb,'' begins one query, ``what if someone was severely
allergic to peanuts and vomited at the slightest smell of them? Do
you think that person could ever travel by plane?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a total mindblower,'' writes Zeb. ``How could one go
through life without peanuts? ... But sure, you could fly United.
They are giving out these weenie little pretzels the size of dimes
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   (United Airlines confirms that it has abandoned peanuts in
response to complaints from passengers deathly allergic to them.
Spokesman  &UR; Matt Triaca &LR;  says of the alternative snacks, pretzels
and (by Personals' personal vacation experience) cracker-like
objects impregnated with cheese molecules, for example, ``Our
customers love them.'')
</P>
<P>
   And Uncle Zeb, reveals California Lawyer, is  &UR; Robert Berring &LR; ,
director of the Boalt Law School Library.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; ``In my humble opinion, lovemaking to Henry was secondary
compared to what he could do for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   - Manhattan socialite  &UR; Jan Cushing Amory &LR; , who revealed in a New
York Observer story about the sex lives of women over 50 that she'd
had a fling with  &UR; Henry Kissinger &LR; , whose Washington girlfriend
Nancy was not yet his wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
