<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      01-30 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vodafone-Vivendi Alliance Derails Mannesmann Plan
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone AirTouch of Britain announced that it had agreed to an
alliance with Vivendi of France. Whatever the other benefits to
Vodafone, the most immediate effect is to derail a plan by
Mannesmann, a Germany company that had planned to link with Vivendi
in hopes of thwarting Vodafone's $155 billion hostile takeover bid
for Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone, a major mobile phone company, and Vivendi, which owns
a 44 percent stake in the French mobile phone company Cegetel, said
they would develop an Internet portal accessible via computers,
mobile phones and cable television. The alliance is contingent upon
Vodafone's succeeding in its bid for Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   New NatWest Bids Are Likely
</P>
<P>
   Royal Bank of Scotland and the Bank of Scotland are preparing to
increase their bids for National Westminster Bank, as the British
takeover battle nears its peak, people familiar with the plans
said. Royal Bank will have to pay at least another $3.2 billion to
top the $38.7 billion that Bank of Scotland is offering for
NatWest, Britain's third-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   A Cosmopolitan Confession
</P>
<P>
   Helen Gurley Brown, the 76-year-old former editor in chief of
Cosmopolitan magazine, has come clean in her new memoir, ``I'm Wild
Again: Snippets from My Life and a Few Brazen Thoughts.'' In one
chapter, Ms. Brown reveals for the first time that she had a
financial arrangement when she was 24 with an older married man
who, in exchange for rent and a nominal secretarial job, had a
sexual relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   Rules May Slow Investment in China
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government announced several new regulations last
week governing the release of material on the Internet that could
hobble several start-up companies that had hoped to go public this
year to capitalize on the growth of online usage in China.
</P>
<P>
   TV Captions for a Wider Audience
</P>
<P>
   Television captions, once used only to help the deaf and hard of
hearing, are becoming increasingly common, with advertisers and
television networks recognizing their value. They often appear on
screens in places like sports bars, health clubs and offices, where
the audio would be distracting or difficult to hear. Captioning got
a jump-start a few years ago when the Federal Communications
Commission set a schedule mandating that captioning be phased in
for most television programming by 2006. But the major broadcasters
and some cable companies are ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Digital Lighting in the Home
</P>
<P>
   A Boston-based company, Color Kinetics, hopes to equip ordinary
houses with digital lighting. The technology is based on
light-emitting diodes _ or LEDs, tiny little lights that have been
used as indicators on electronic circuits and stereos. Essentially,
the inventors have bunched many diodes together for a new type of
color lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Creating Smells Online
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Firestein, a biology professor and a leading expert in
the neurobiology of olfaction _ the science of smelling _ is
helping DigiScents, a privately held company, bring smells to
computer games, Web pages and even movies. The company is creating
a digital language for recording, re-creating and transmitting
fragrances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
