<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A NEW SUNRISE FOR THE ORIGINAL T.D. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every Super Bowl has an X-factor; a play, a player or
a happening that emerges from the shadows to alter the course of
the glitter-drenched championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Miami, the X-factor turned out to be an
off-the-field escapade involving Eugene Robinson, the Atlanta
Falcons' veteran safety and team leader, who was arrested for
soliciting a prostitute for $40 the night before the Super Bowl. A
year earlier it was Terrell Davis, who had a breakout game in a
breakout season. In Super Bowl XXXI there was Desmond Howard's punt
return.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV had a number of potential X-factors. There were
well-known X's like Rams quarterback Kurt Warner and running back
Marshall Faulk, Tennessee quarterback Steve McNair and running back
Eddie George. There were lesser known X-factors like London
Fletcher, the Rams 5-foot-11-inch linebacker, and Rams wide
receiver Ricky Proehl.
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony Dorsett was the X-factor waiting to happen. Dorsett,
26, is the Titans free safety who was suddenly thrust from his
special-teams role when he was forced to start for Marcus
Robertson, the Titans veteran free safety, who broke his laft ankle
in last Sunday's conference championship game. Dorsett's father is
Tony Dorsett, the Hall of Fame running back for the Dallas Cowboys
who played in two Super Bowls. The father-son angle became a
compelling story line this week with the young Hawk, as he is
called, asked to look at his celebrity father through a child's
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night into early Sunday morning, Tony Dorsett put
aside the paternal feelings and looked at his son the way the Rams
would look at him: Like the hunter looks at the deer, like the lion
looks at the zebra.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at his son as prey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was game-planning the Titans,'' Dorsett said, ``and I got
a young guy stepping in there, starting for the first time in the
biggest game of the year, I'd test him. I'd test him early, and I
might test him often until he gave me reason to say, `OK, he's
going to hold this down. We might be shooting some blanks thinking
that we're going to win this game going in that direction.' If he
steps up to the plate, that's fine; if he doesn't then they're
going to come at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett leaned forward in his chair. ``They want to see if he's
going to be out of position,'' he added, ``if he's done his
homework throughout the course of the week. They want to see if
he's going to be the weak link.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond discussing specifics of the game, Dorsett said he wanted
to make sure his son savored the moment. Throughout the week, Tony
Dorsett has tried to put the day, the game, the moment in
perspective for Anthony _ from the feeling of running out of the
tunnel to hearing the national anthem just before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dorsett played in Super Bowl XII in 1978 when Dallas
defeated Denver, 27-10; he played in Super Bowl XIII when Dallas
lost to Pittsburgh, 35-31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Anthony, think about this: I don't know who's
going to be introduced, offense or defense, but if they introduce
that defense, they're introducing you to the world,''' Dorsett
said. ``You got a big stage, a big platform to perform in. The
feeling that you're going to have is unexplainable, it is the best
feeling you're going to ever have, being introduced for a football
game, in your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may come back, but you won't experience it like you're
going to experience it the first time. You ain't going to be able
to wait for that ball to be kicked off.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett and Dorsett look alike, wear the same number (33) on
their jersey. They are linked by blood and history but are
separated by age and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dorsett was a hardened, seasoned veteran. A heralded
All-American at the University of Pittsburgh, Dorsett barreled into
the Cowboys organization as the second player chosen in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had leverage that he didn't have at this stage of the
game,'' Dorsett said. ``One thing I knew with the Cowboys was that
they needed me as much as I needed them. That was always my
mentality. I wasn't afraid. I wasn't the kind of guy who said, `I
need to be making more,' but was afraid to go ask for more, or
afraid to challenge them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett, the Cowboys' all-time leading rusher with 12,036 yards
and No. 2 on the National Football League's all-time rushing list
with 12,739, was traded to Denver in 1988 after 11 seasons with
Dallas. He tore up his knee and retired in 1989. He wanted to
return to the Cowboys but the team signed Emmitt Smith instead.
</P>
<P>
   Most athletes do not get a second crack at the system. Now, Tony
Dorsett warns his son and his nephew, Ty Law, who is a cornerback
for the New England Patriots, not to get so blinded by the money
and the glitz that they lose track of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're becoming more aware of the business aspect of
what's at stake,'' Dorsett said. ``I'm sitting down with Anthony
and one of his teammates the other day, the kid asks, `What do you
think about what happened in Denver? It just came out that Terrell
Davis is going to have to come back next year and fight for his
job. Have to win his job back from a rookie.' I said, `That just
goes to show you where you're at: When you get some leverage, you
have to take advantage of it because you're just a number to them.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some numbers are more significant than others; no other
Dallas Cowboy player will wear Dorsett's No. 33. There is also the
magic of being able to play in two Super Bowls and have a son
become a central figure in a third.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Tony Dorsett said that win, lose or draw Sunday, he
would say he watched his son play in the game of both their lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
