<SLUG> BC-NH-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUSH LIKENS McCAIN TAX PLAN TO CLINTON-GORE  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.Y. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush on Sunday challenged
the tax-cut plan of Republican rival John McCain, criticizing it as
a knockoff of the Clinton-Gore administration as he seeks to eke
out a victory in the hard-fought New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, acknowledging a ``healthy debate'' between the rivals for
the Republican presidential nomination over tax reduction, said his
$483 billion tax cut was far more distinctive than the $250 billion
tax break being offered by McCain, the senior senator from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important for our party to nominate somebody
running for president who'll have a tax cut plan that stands in
stark contrast to the Clinton and Gore people _ not somebody who
sounds exactly like them,'' Bush told a packed campaign rally at a
high school in this southern New Hampshire community.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the GOP would need to ``draw clear distinctions'' over
taxes with the Democratic candidate so that ``the American people
will have a choice'' in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, McCain pressed his grass-roots crusade. He staged
his 114th question-and-answer session before more than 1,000 people
crowded into the three-story town hall in Peterborough, where he
had faced barely 40 people at the first such event last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator demanded that Bush telephone New York Gov.
George Pataki to clear the way for McCain to get on the statewide
ballot in New York's March 7 primary. And McCain insisted that he
would be a stronger challenger to the front-running Democrat, Vice
President Al Gore, because he alone favors overhauling campaign
financing practices that contributed to questionable donations to
the Clinton-Gore re-election drive in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced I can beat Al Gore like a drum,'' McCain said in
a nationally televised interview on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who leads in national polls, is no guaranteed winner in
Tuesday's primary. Surveys released on Sunday showed at least
one-third of likely voters still have not decided how they will
vote. Bush and McCain remain locked in a statistical dead heat,
with Bush pulling even with McCain with support from previously
undecided Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain are competing in a GOP primary with three other
candidates who have never been elected to public office _ magazine
publisher Steve Forbes, talk show host Alan Keyes and former Reagan
administration official Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave his campaign audience on Sunday a real stem-winder
after speaking briefly on Saturday at a campaign rally in Milford,
where his parents, former President George Bush and Barbara Bush,
joined him on the New Hampshire campaign trail for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor touted his family, plans for tax cuts,
strengthening the armed forces, bolstering education and extending
the American dream to people left behind amid prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed a ``positive and hopeful'' campaign against his
``worthwhile opponent'' in the days ahead. But the two-term Texas
governor drew contrasts with McCain, without ever naming his
63-year-old rival, a former Navy pilot who has served in the House
and Senate for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 53, appealed directly for voters' support both at the
outset and at the conclusion of his remarks. ``Today I am here to
ask for your vote,'' Bush said. ``I want your vote come Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   His appeal for support in remarks to more than 500 people packed
into a standing room-only rally was not enough to persuade Kathy
Cooper, 42, an engineer living in Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he said just didn't do it for me,'' said Cooper, who said
she is a registered Republican torn between voting for Bush or
magazine publisher Steve Forbes. ``There was no chemistry there. By
Tuesday, I'll have to decide whether to vote my heart and support
Forbes _ or vote my brain and go with the man who looks like he'll
win the Republican nomination anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Cloutier, a woman in her 60s working part time to register
new voters in Hudson, said she expects a close race between Bush
and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a Bush supporter,'' Cloutier said with some
hesitation two days before voting. McCain ``might take it,''
though,'' Cloutier said, recalling that President Bush had an
uneven record in New Hampshire. ``George lost here too,'' Cloutier
remembered. ``Do you think history will repeat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Bush lost the New Hampshire primary to Ronald Reagan
in 1980. Bush lost the contest again in 1988, to Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas, but recovered to win the GOP nomination and the presidency.
Bush won the GOP primary here in 1992. But the 37 percent showing
by challenger Patrick Buchanan was seen as a setback that critics
said weakened Bush and helped enable then-Arkansas Gov. Bill
Clinton to defeat him in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain defended his $250 billion tax cut proposal in his
televised interview, saying that his more modest tax cut was
designed to reserve most of the federal budget surplus to bolster
middle-class entitlement programs, including Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   McCain echoed his subtle criticism of Bush in his television
appearance, saying that there is only one Republican in the race in
New Hampshire who is ``fully prepared'' to be president.'' McCain
added: ``These are all good people that are running, but I believe
I'm the person who can lead the country in this new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush countered, saying that his executive experience as a
governor of the nation's third most populous state would make for a
better president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not of the Washington scene. I'm not a committee
chairman,'' Bush said in a thinly veiled reference to McCain, who
is chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
