<P>
   SCI-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE (Baltimore) _ A $2.5 million federally
financed study at the University of Maryland represents a new wave
in academic medicine: the application of rigorous, Western
scientific methods to test alternative therapies, from ginkgo
biloba to shark cartilage to a mystical Chinese healing art known
as qi gong. Just five years ago, many academics would not have gone
near such studies, for fear they would become a laughingstock. And
while alternative therapies remain hugely controversial,
multimillion dollar clinical trials are getting under way this year
at some of the nation's most prestigious university hospitals. By
Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
