<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-AUSTRIA-MAVERICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIAN RIGHTIST'S RISE STIRS PASSION LEFT AND RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(mk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT GERLITZEN, Austria _ To many average Austrians, Joerg
Haider is that southern governor with the odd blend of liberal
spending plans and anti-immigrant sentiments that they might
quietly agree with but that they know look bad to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   To his local fans here, he is their maverick man shaking up the
fat cats in Vienna who for decades handed out jobs based on
political connections rather than brains or talent.
</P>
<P>
   To foreigners, he is that xenophobic Austrian who once said
several pro-Nazi things.
</P>
<P>
   For the 14 years of Haider's seemingly irresistible rise in the
politics of tranquil, prosperous Austria, these differences were
mostly a tempest in a schnapps cup. Now that his party looks set to
join Austria's government, Israel has threatened to break
diplomatic relations, and France, Germany, Belgium, Sweden, Italy _
in fact all of Austria's 14 partners in the European Union _ are
seriously alarmed and pondering retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the winners in the national elections in October, the
Social Democrats, have failed to form a government after three
months of bickering with their traditional partner, the
business-oriented People's Party, Haider is taking a crack at it.
</P>
<P>
   If he and the People's Party can find common ground, they will
have a 104-vote majority in the 183-seat Parliament, and squeeze
the Social Democrats out of power for the first time in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is up in arms, warning Austria's president, Thomas
Klestil, against allowing Haider's party into power and threatening
unspecified consequences. Simon Wiesenthal, the Nazi hunter based
in Vienna, warns of a ripple effect across Europe and of a drastic
decrease in the tourism and trade on which Austria depends for its
evident well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Haider favors shutting the door to new immigrants and preventing
the expansion of the European Union, which he says would mean a
flood of impoverished east Europeans into Austria, the union's
easternmost member.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's allies do not see this as anything to do with Nazism,
and seem deaf to accusations of racism. Haider's parents were
Nazis, of course, and he made some hasty remarks years ago about
Third Reich labor policies and the steadfastness of World War II
veterans, they say, but they were blown out of proportion and,
anyway, he apologized.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Haider was asked whether he was angry about the
foreign criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not angry, amused,'' he said. ``We're a small country, and a
small party inside it, and all the powerful leaders of the world
are afraid of our success fighting the rigid system in Austria.''
</P>
