<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-KINGS-NYT &LR;      01-30 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT THE KINGS AT THEIR OWN PLAYGROUND GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks fixed their attention on Sacramento's
pop-culture hit as he strutted onto the Madison Square Garden floor
with his power of illusion and sleight-of-hand to all but pull
quarters from behind their ears.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Williams had the talent to use the Knicks as props for his
show. In a dizzying second, the fancy future of the league that is
embodied by the Williams-inspired Kings could have left the
buttoned-down Knicks looking as antiquated as a wagon wheel. But
completely out of character, the Knicks crossed the chalk line the
Kings drew on the asphalt and stepped into the lighter side of this
playground game Sunday afternoon. All of a sudden, the conservative
Charlie Ward was lofting a stream of alley-oop passes to a variety
of teammates, including one lob to a wide-eyed Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   Camby leaped, reached and emphatically put down a dunk. Before
he came to earth, he swung on the rim and drew a technical foul for
his theatrics. For once, a Knick got a technical for overzealous
fun instead of out-of-control fuming.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Coach Jeff Van Gundy was willing to let his
spirited players go free as long as they remembered one staple:
defense. The Knicks clamped down on the Kings in an overpowering
second quarter and built a stunning 24-point lead late in the
third. Soon, an exasperated Williams was ejected and a hot Chris
Webber got bogged down in foul trouble. Although they experienced
their habitual fourth-quarter meltdown, the Knicks muddled through
the anticlimactic end for a 120-111 victory after taking the Kings'
dare to play for style points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of West Coast basketball,'' said Latrell
Sprewell who dunked and drove and played unrestrained on his way to
matching his season high of 32 points. ``I felt at home. It was
fun. It's more of a playground style of basketball, and I think we
all enjoy that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks faced down the league's highest-scoring,
snazziest-passing team with their highest point total in two years.
But unlike the Kings, the Knicks had limits on the circus plays
they were willing to pull. On a breakaway in the third quarter,
Williams tossed a pass off the glass for Webber to turn into a
highlight dunk. Webber flubbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd tried that?'' Sprewell said. ``Jeff would have had a
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks had not played defense, Van Gundy would have been
much more upset. The Knicks gave up 61 percent shooting in the
first quarter. Then the Knicks began to get back in transition and
hover around the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, in the second quarter the Knicks did not allow a
fast-break point and held the Kings to 33 percent shooting. With a
14-2 run and a 66-foot heave by Camby at the buzzer, the Knicks
led, 66-51, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a grade-school shot,'' said Camby, who leaped up over
the scorer's table and bounded into the locker room at the half.
``I'd never done that before. That was lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   But luck had nothing to do with hard, aggressive defense. While
the Knicks continued to bang and shadow their men, the Kings gave
Allan Houston (28 points), Kurt Thomas (13 points) and Sprewell
precious open space. In a jump-shooting zone, the Knicks went on a
20-10 run to take a 24-point lead with 1 minute 31 seconds left in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This nationally televised debacle was getting to Williams. The
kid from rural West Virginia _ a second-year player who had never
been to New York _ came unraveled under the bright lights of the
Garden with 11:15 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After Hue Hollins called him for traveling, Williams flung the
ball in frustration high into the air and behind the Knicks' bench.
Hollins slapped him for a technical foul. Nine seconds later,
Williams was guarding Ward, mumbling to himself and shaking his
head. What seemed harmless enough irritated Hollins, who tossed
Williams out of the game. Some Knick fans even booed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say anything,'' said Williams, who finished with an
unspectacular 2-for-9 effort from the floor, 5 points, 12 assists
and 7 turnovers. ``I don't know what happened. Your guess is as
good mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Williams would have heated up. Perhaps Webber, who scored
19 of his 26 points in the first 20 minutes, would have gathered
some steam if he had been beside Williams. As it was, Coach Rick
Adelman had taken all of his starters out with the Knicks up by 22
points and 9:18 left. The Kings' second group preyed on a sudden
slump in the Knicks' aim _ 31 percent shooting in the fourth
quarter _ and took off on a 20-6 run. But after two missed jumpers
by Darrick Martin, and some timely free throws from a Knick team
that set a club record by hitting all 24 of its attempts, the
Knicks escaped disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in New York, when you beat a very good team, are you
asked about the fourth quarter,'' Van Gundy said. ``Let's not talk
about those first three quarters, let's get right to the
negativity. But you are right, it wasn't as good a finish as we
would have liked. We don't have the killer instinct, yet, with our
best players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' best side came out Sunday against an elite team. Not
only did they play well defensively when they had to, they opened
up their game and let the fun come out. They threw six alley-oop
passes just in the first half, Sprewell came up with a couple of
nifty driving dunks in the second, and Houston was automatic from
the perimeter all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize that they are going to make some
spectacular plays,'' Houston said. ``It's fun to play them. We
weren't as concerned about making it spectacular _ although we had
fun, too _ but we knew we still had to work and get the win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
