<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1150 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AUSTRIA-MAVERICK-ART-     01-30 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-MAVERICK-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIAN RIGHTIST'S RISE STIRS PASSION LEFT AND RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT GERLITZEN, Austria _ To many Austrians, Joerg Haider is
that southern governor with the odd blend of liberal spending plans
and anti-immigrant sentiments they might quietly agree with but
know look bad to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   To his local fans, he is their maverick man shaking up the fat
cats in Vienna who for decades handed out jobs based on political
connections rather than brains or talent.
</P>
<P>
   To foreigners, he is that xenophobic Austrian who once said
several pro-Nazi things.
</P>
<P>
   For the 14 years of Haider's seemingly irresistible rise in the
politics of tranquil, prosperous Austria, these differences were
mostly a tempest in a schnapps cup. Now that his party looks set to
join Austria's government, Israel has threatened to break
diplomatic relations and France, Germany, Belgium, Sweden, Italy _
in fact all of Austria's 14 partners in the European Union _ are
seriously alarmed and pondering retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Haider and his supporters are openly offended by the idea that
fellow Europeans would issue threats over an election result not to
their liking. But Saturday, they had other things to do at his 50th
birthday party, an all-day affair that moved from hut to hut on
this magnificent alp, with beery crowds of well-wishers at each
stop.
</P>
<P>
   The day culminated at the last chairlift in a trick-skiing
display, fireworks and the gift of a snowboard _ made, the emcee
proudly told Haider, right here in Carinthia, the southern Austrian
province that borders Italy and Slovenia. Carinthia is inordinately
proud of its tanned, athletic native son, who led his party to
second place in the national elections in October.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the winners, the Social Democrats who have been in
power continuously since 1970, have failed to form a government
after three months of bickering with their traditional partner, the
business-oriented People's Party, Haider is taking a crack at it.
</P>
<P>
   If he and the People's Party can find common ground, they will
have a 104-vote majority in the 183-seat Parliament, and squeeze
the Social Democrats out of power for the first time in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is up in arms, warning Austria's president, Thomas
Klestil, against allowing Haider's party into power and threatening
unspecified consequences. Simon Wiesenthal, the Nazi hunter based
in Vienna, warns of a ripple effect across Europe and of a drastic
decrease in the tourism and trade on which Austria depends for its
evident well-being.
</P>
<P>
   But Carinthia can hardly wait. At every stop on Haider's route _
followed by an entourage of skiing politicians, skiing spokesmen
and skiing cameramen (plus a few hapless hacks in street shoes who
had to stumble off the lifts and chase him on foot) _ was a table
with blue bottles of Bear Beer, made in nearby Villach. Blue is the
Freedom Party's color, and each had a happy bear named Joerg in
blue overalls on it.
</P>
<P>
   Next to them were free samples of a new Villach schnapps named
Stand Up, Little Man. It is a sexual double-entendre, but the
little man was also wearing a bow tie. That is the unmistakable
symbol of Wolfgang Schuessel, leader of the People's Party, who
invariably wears one in public.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel, currently foreign minister, is now negotiating with
Haider over who will hold what roles in a joint government.
</P>
<P>
   He is also trying to reassure the world that Haider will not be
a problem. ``I am the guarantor of Austria's stability,'' he has
boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schuessel's convinced he'll tame Haider, but I'm convinced he
won't be able to,'' said Christa Zochling, author of a biography of
Haider. ``Schuessel thinks he's quick, intelligent and smooth, and
he is, but not enough. He won't tame him.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This question of who is taming whom in this political dating
game is giving editorial cartoonists a field day. The front page of
the mass-circulation tabloid Kronen Zeitung has a drawing of
Schuessel in his briefs spraying on deodorant (his toilet kit has
little bow ties on it) while Haider waits in bed in a wig and blue
underwear. The caption is ``Fatal Attraction,'' a reference to the
movie where a man thinks he is seducing a woman and then sees her
nearly destroy his family.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly magazine News has Haider on the cover dangling
Schuessel as a marionette.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The subtext to the ``taming problem'' is this: Haider favors
shutting the door to new immigrants and preventing the expansion of
the European Union, which he says would mean a flood of
impoverished East Europeans into Austria, the union's easternmost
member.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's allies, and his ever-growing circle of voters, do not
see this as anything to do with Nazism, and seem deaf to
accusations of racism; they have simply voted out what they regard
as a cozy, corrupt bunch of politicians and replaced them with a
man who seems to offer a dynamic alternative. His parents were
Nazis, of course, and he made some hasty remarks years ago about
Third Reich labor policies and the steadfastness of World War II
veterans, they say, but the remarks were blown out of proportion
and, anyway, in November, he apologized.
</P>
<P>
   To Haider and his allies, the foreign criticism smells of panic
by Social Democratic governments around Europe that see one of
their own being shoved out of power, and a right-wing party
entering government at a moment when traditional conservatives are
riven by scandal in France and Germany, raising the specter that
right-wing parties there will emulate Haider's success.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Labor government is complaining because it hates to see
its leftist allies shoved out in Austria, contends Peter
Sichrovsky, a prominent Jewish member of Haider's party who wrote
``Born Guilty,'' a book of interviews with children of Nazis. ``But
they're speaking as Jews because they know it's more powerful that
way,'' he said. ``You'll notice Sharon's party is being very
careful.'' Ariel Sharon is the leader of the right-wing Likud bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Haider has even become a factor in the New York Senate race,
with Hillary Rodham Clinton releasing a letter asking people to
``express their concern'' that the Austrian might enter government
after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani appeared on the same dais as Haider at
a Martin Luther King Jr. Day dinner. Giuliani's spokeswoman said
the mayor did not know that Haider would be there.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At one of his ski stops Saturday, Haider was asked whether he
was angry about the foreign criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not angry, amused,'' he said. ``We're a small country, and a
small party inside it, and all the powerful leaders of the world
are afraid of our success fighting the rigid system in Austria.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he might visit foreign leaders to reassure them, he
quickly answered: ``No. I refuse to make a tour to explain myself.
We'll convince them by doing and not by speaking.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Haider has made tours in the past _ to Israel, to New
York, to Washington to visit the Holocaust Museum and eat dinner
with the Congress on Racial Equality. But Hans Rauscher, a
political analyst for the daily Der Standard, says, ``He gets his
photo taken with a rabbi from some fake Jewish group, but he's not
connected where it counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider's supporters deny that he is even really a right-winger.
``Le Pen hates us,'' Sichrovsky said of Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader
of the right-wing National Front in France. ``I wanted to throw Le
Pen out of the European Parliament for calling the Holocaust a
minor issue.''
</P>
<P>
   And Georg Hoffman-Ostenhof, an analyst for the weekly news
magazine Profil, delves into psyche-probing to explain his worries
about Haider: ``I'd never say he's a Nazi, but he has the Nazi
views of his father in his background, and they inform him.''
Haider has called Churchill a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   He despises the Social Democrat-Christian Democrat split as a
Democratic/Republican or Labor/Tory political form imposed on
Austria by the Allies, Hoffman-Ostenhof said, adding: ``In 30 years
in politics, he makes pro-Nazi remarks every five years. It's not
by chance. It's inside him.''
</P>
<P>
   Haider's fans consistently reject such analyses. They are not
Nazis, not anti-Semites and not racists, they contend; they just
find Austria's immigration laws absurdly liberal and threatening to
their high wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``When foreigners come to Austria, they can say they have five
children in the old country and get money for them, even if it's
not true,'' said Sandro Vecellio, 26, the owner of Mad Mexx bar,
who was skiing with his bartenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an Austrian, you need lots of papers to make a business,
but a foreigner only needs the papers he needs in his own
country,'' he said. ``Someone from another country can get
unemployment insurance here without having worked here. This
shouldn't be, and Haider's against that.''
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth Sickl, hostess at one stop on Haider's birthday trail,
says she would never be part of a party that did not share her
``humanist values.'' She joined Haider's party, she said, because
she was a teacher and could not get a principal's job without
joining one of the two governing parties. Since coming to power in
Carinthia, she said, Haider has introduced a merit system fair
enough to promote Social Democrats and even Slovenian nationalists
in the civil service.
</P>
<P>
   Squeezing past them on her way out for some air was Claudia
Kohlweg, 24, one of the skiing bears who accompanied Haider from
stop to stop. Obviously, she was a merit selection, because few
people can ski with their head inside a big fur fishbowl. As it
happens, a cuddly brown bear is both Haider's party symbol and
Mount Gerlitzen's mascot. But, this ski teacher was asked, was she
a Haider voter?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she confessed, a little tentatively. ``My boss told me
to do this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-CONGO-NYT &LR;      01-30 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CONGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. FACES BIG CHALLENGE IN ANY CONGO PEACEKEEPING MISSION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an unusual meeting of African leaders and the Security
Council ended last week, there was general agreement that the
United Nations will have to be given a major role in bringing peace
to Congo. But when, and in what form, are still open questions that
are expected to dominate council discussions in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, Secretary-General Kofi Annan, a former director of
U.N. peacekeeping, recommended that the Security Council, which has
already authorized sending 500 cease-fire monitors to Congo, add
5,537 troops. This would include infantry as well as medical,
communications, mine-clearance and air and water transportation
experts for a nearly roadless region. The start-up cost is
estimated at $41 million.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Annan said that 960,000 Congolese have been
displaced by the war and that they and another 300,000 refugees
from other wars in the region are dangerously short of food.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and U.N. officials say they see in Congo's complicated
war a challenge like no other that the organization has faced since
the Balkans disintegrated into ethnic warfare after the collapse of
European communism.
</P>
<P>
   Within the United Nations, even the word Congo has tragic
resonance. Secretary-General Dag Hammarskjold died on a Congo peace
mission in 1961 when his plane crashed in what is now Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the American representative, called the
unusual meeting of African presidents and ministers as January's
council president. He has been telling U.N. officials and members
of Congress that the Congo operation may be the United Nations'
last chance to prove it can get peacekeeping right. That was the
message he delivered directly to the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee on its recent field trip to New York.
</P>
<P>
   But other diplomats say that this assertion masks another
problem. Unless the United States allows the Security Council and
the U.N. peacekeeping department to mount a credible operation in
Congo, they say, the organization will be in danger of repeating
its experience in Somalia and Rwanda, two regional conflicts that
it proved unable to bring under control. .
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Rwanda, where a genocidal war in 1994 first
disrupted the region and drew Congo into the fighting, the United
States prevented the Security Council from acting for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke says that he is determined that this will not happen
again. But he also accepts that he has two huge tasks ahead. The
Clinton administration has agreed to give Congress 15 days notice
of Security Council resolutions creating U.N. peacekeeping
operations, for which the United States is billed more than 30
percent of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   So Holbrooke will have to persuade reluctant members of Congress
that skimping on Congo will lead to disaster. Congress already has
a law on the books saying that the United States will limit its
payments to 25 percent, and often balks at that.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Holbrooke has been urging African leaders, on
a trip there in December and in the Security Council in January, to
take more responsibility for the region. Without political will in
Africa, he tells them, nothing the United Nations tries can
possibly work. A few Africans left New York last week saying they
felt ``bullied.''
</P>
<P>
   Last July, African nations involved in the Congo war joined the
government of President Laurent Kabila in Lusaka, Zambia, where
they agreed on a peace accord. A month later they were all back at
war. By the fall, they were clamoring for international help, a
message delivered most bluntly last week by President Robert Mugabe
of Zimbabwe. He supports Kabila's government in its war with rebels
who are, in turn, backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   In Security Council speeches last week, and in a statement of
purpose that followed the meetings, African leaders coupled their
calls for U.N. peacekeepers with new pledges to put their Lusaka
agreement into practice. Britain's representative, Sir Jeremy
Greenstock, welcomed African commitments to peace. But reflecting
the skepticism of many at the United Nations, he noted that the
world had been pleading with Africans for action for some time, but
``frankly, they weren't listening.''
</P>
<P>
   The deep divisions between Congo and its neighbors, evident even
in public speeches last week, were reportedly even more pronounced
in closed-door meetings among the African leaders, Annan and
American and other officials and diplomats. One Western official
said that by the end of the council deliberations Wednesday there
was ``blood on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Considerable attention was focused last week on Kabila, who made
his first trip to the United States and apparently went home less
convinced of American support for his enemies, Rwanda and Uganda.
Kabila's American public relations aides were elated with his trip
and say that he plans to return in May, hoping to talk with
American companies about more investment in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats and American officials see hope in economic
pressures. All the nations involved in the Congo war are now
feeling the costs of that involvement and are looking for a way to
withdraw without a loss of dignity, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The political will to take that step, the secretary-general's
report says, is not only what matters most but is also the basic
condition for peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
