<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT GETS DEFENSIVE IN SECOND HALF TO THWART SETON HALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Upset by St. John's two weeks ago and
decisively beaten by Syracuse last Monday, sixth-ranked Connecticut
seemed vulnerable Sunday afternoon as it prepared to face a Seton
Hall team that had won 10 of its last 11 games. That one of Seton's
Hall victories by the Pirates came over St. John's, two days after
the Redmen had beaten the Huskies at home, appeared to enhance
Seton Hall's chances even further.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of the first half at the Hartford Civic Center, it
appeared that UConn was indeed vulnerable. Seton Hall outplayed the
Huskies, mainly on the strength of the perimeter shooting of Darius
Lane, who connected on all five 3-point shots he took, and five
blocked shots by the 6-foot-11-inch freshman center, Samel
Dalembert, who had seven over all. But then a 3-point basket by
Albert Mouring put Connecticut ahead 25-24 with 8 minutes 35
seconds left in the half. UConn led at intermission, 36-32, and
never relinquished the lead en route to a 66-56 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, we did a terrific job, especially in the second
half,'' Jim Calhoun, the Connecticut coach, said.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Amaker, the third-year coach of Seton Hall (13-4 over all
and 5-2 in the Big East), agreed. ``They turned it up a notch
defensively in the second half,'' said Amaker, a defense-oriented
coach. ``And they defensed Lane much better in that half.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane is the Pirates' leading scorer, but the Huskies limited the
6-4 sophomore from Brooklyn Center, Minn. to only five shots in the
second half. He made only one of them, another 3-pointer with 6:02
left in the game, that enabled him to finish with a game-high 21
points. By then UConn (15-4, 4-3) had taken a 15-point lead, its
biggest of the game, before a crowd of 16,294.
</P>
<P>
   At least Lane scored. Connecticut effectively shut down Seton
Hall's second and third leading scorers, seniors Shaheen Holloway
and Rimas Kaukenas. Holloway, who had averaged 13.3 points through
the Pirates' first 16 games, made only four of 12 shots, but none
of six from 3-point range, to finish with 8 points, four in each
half. Kaukenas had an even worse time, getting off only six shots
and making just one, a layup with 4:45 remaining in the game. That
gave him 2 points, 10 below his average.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Lane's success from 3-point range, Seton Hall _ which
had made 33 of 69 3-pointers (47.8 percent) in its last three games
_ lost its touch from the perimeter. Unable to work themselves
free, the Pirate shooters connected on only two of 11 3-point
attempts over the final 20 minutes to finish at eight for 22 on
perimeter shots.
</P>
<P>
   Besides intensifying its defensive pressure, Connecticut also
became more of an offensive force in the second half, making 45
percent of its shots.The point guard Khalid El-Amin made five of 13
from the field, including two 3-pointers, and all four of his free
throws to finish with 16 points. Jake Voskuhl, the 6-11 UConn
center, who scored a career-high 18 points in the loss to Syracuse
and whose effectiveness in the post has improved markedly in the
last two weeks, hit on four of five shots and all three free throws
to finish with 11 points. He also had with six rebounds, all on the
defensive end, and four blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Though Connecticut shot 42.3 percent as against 37.5 by Seton
Hall, the Huskies actually made only one more basket. But they went
to the free-throw line far more often, where they made 19 of 24
free throws compared with six of only 10 by Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their strength and experience were big factors,'' Amaker said.
``And they're very strong and very physical. They're a very good
basketball team, while we need to be quicker and faster and
stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
