<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1163 &Cx1f; kan-z
s a BC-BC-PRIESTS1-TWOTAKES-     01-30 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-PRIESTS1-TWOTAKES-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST1: DAY ONE OF PRIESTS SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Eds.: This is a retransmission.)
Hundreds of Roman Catholic priests across the United States have
died of AIDS-related illnesses, and hundreds more are living with
HIV, the virus that causes the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The actual number of AIDS deaths is difficult to determine. But
it appears priests are dying of AIDS at a rate at least four times
that of the general U.S. population, according to estimates from
medical experts and priests and an analysis of health statistics by
The Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri and Kansas alone, at least 16 priests and two
religious-order brothers have died of AIDS since early 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths are of such concern to the church that most dioceses
and religious orders now require applicants for the priesthood to
take an HIV-antibody test before their ordination.
</P>
<P>
   For the nation's 60 million Catholics, served by 46,000 priests,
the AIDS issue goes straight to the heart of church doctrine _ a
doctrine that teaches compassion and forgiveness but also considers
homosexual relations a sin and opposes the modern practice of
``safe sex.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide confidential survey of 3,000 priests by The
Star, two-thirds of the more than 800 responding lauded the church
for being caring and compassionate to priests with AIDS. Often, the
church covers medical costs, gives them a place to live and cares
for them until they die.
</P>
<P>
   Most priests, however, said the church failed to offer an early
and effective sexual education that might have prevented infection
in the first place. Two-thirds said sexuality either was not
addressed at all or was not discussed adequately in the seminary.
Three of four said the church needed to offer more education about
sexual issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexuality still needs to be talked about and dealt with,''
said the Rev. Dennis Rausch, a priest with AIDS who runs an AIDS
ministry program for Catholic Charities in the Archdiocese of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to get into the seminary here for the last
several years to do an awareness course for the guys, so when they
come out, they at least have some knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Other findings of the survey, which had a margin of error of 3.5
percentage points, include:
</P>
<P>
   Six of 10 Roman Catholic priests in the United States know at
least one priest who died of an AIDS-related illness, and one-third
know a priest currently living with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of those responding _ about 1 in 114 _ said they either
have HIV or AIDS or might have but haven't been tested. That would
translate into about 400 priests nationwide, an estimate supported
by members of the National Catholic AIDS Network. In the general
U.S. population, according to figures from the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, between 1 in 300 and 1 in 420 people are
infected.
</P>
<P>
   Many priests and behavioral experts argue that the church's
adherence to 12th-century doctrine about the virtues of celibacy
and its teachings on homosexuality have contributed to the spread
of AIDS within the clergy. Unwittingly, the church has kept
fledgling priests _ some of whom were as young as 14 when they
entered seminary in the '60s and '70s _ uneducated about the
reality of a sexual world and its temptations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, by treating homosexual acts as an abomination and the
breaking of celibacy vows as shameful, the church has scared
priests into silence, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this speaks to a failure on the part of the church,''
said Auxiliary Bishop Thomas Gumbleton of the Archdiocese of
Detroit. ``Gay priests and heterosexual priests didn't know how to
handle their sexuality, their sexual drive. And so they would
handle it in ways that were not healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to be celibate and to be gay at the same time, and how to
be celibate and heterosexual at the same time, that's what we were
never really taught how to do. And that was a major failing.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholic cardinals in the United States and high-ranking
church officials in Rome declined requests to discuss the issue or
the newspaper's findings.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican, which has no policy on dealing with priests who
have AIDS, referred questions about the issue to local bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Raymond J. Boland of the Diocese of Kansas City-St.
Joseph in Missouri said the AIDS deaths show that priests are
human.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much as we would regret it, it shows that human nature is
human nature,'' Boland said. ``And all of us are heirs to all of
the misfortunes that can be foisted upon the human race.''
</P>
<P>
   Boland thinks church leaders now are doing a better job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel today that a lot of our men get many opportunities _
the standard of spiritual direction, the standard of formation is
much higher,'' Boland said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the issue of AIDS deaths among priests has
been so sensitive that many of those who later died kept their
illnesses a secret. Some death certificates listed AIDS-related
conditions such as pneumocystis pneumonia but never mentioned the
disease itself. Other certificates were falsified.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church clearly is not alone. Clergy in other
denominations also struggle with sexuality and have died of AIDS.
But the Catholic Church's condemnation of homosexual acts, its
requirement that priests be male and its unique demand of celibacy
make the issue all the more vexing for its followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very strong social implications behind this,''
said Robert Goss, a former Jesuit priest who is now chairman of the
Department of Religious Studies at Webster University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Gays are in the priesthood, and not all of them are celibate, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of those issues are explosive issues that superiors and
bishops don't want to deal with publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss himself left the priesthood after 11 years when he fell in
love with a seminarian who was just shy of ordination. The two
became longtime partners. The former seminarian died of AIDS in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Several church leaders MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1164 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-DYNASTY-ART-2NDT     01-30 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DYNASTY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: their lives.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with college, he added; each of his children
had gone to a different university. It also was the case with
politics; he insisted and George W. confirmed that the former
president had never urged any of his children either to run for
office or not to. A real patriarch, the younger Bush said, lays the
groundwork for his sons but his father never sought to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Still, George W. said he has always suspected that when an old
friend of his father's, former Gov. Allen Shivers of Texas, came to
see him in 1978, just before the congressional race in West Texas,
his father was behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Shivers told me I had no shot at winning,'' Governor
Bush said. ``He said the district wasn't ready for a Republican. I
ran anyway, ran a good campaign, and lost. But whether he sent
Shivers to see me or not, my dad clearly wasn't pulling strings,
trying to get me the seat.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as recently as the impeachment proceedings against
President Clinton, when strong stirrings of a George W. Bush
presidential candidacy began to be heard, his father told several
of his intimates that he was not sure that George W. would end up
running. Jeb Bush, he said at that time, might be a stronger
candidate, in some future election.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite Saturday's appearance, one of fewer than half a dozen he
has made this year, the elder Bush has also avoided trying to
stage-manage his son's presidential campaign. They talk often on
the phone, as often as three or four times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the ball's in his court,'' the former president said. ``I
don't want to be the hovering father here, like Joe Kennedy. When
we talk, it's more `How you doing,' `Don't let them worry you,'
that kind of thing. No pointers, nah. I'm in no position to tell
him to shift this policy or that. I can't tell you the fine points
of his health plan, or Clinton's.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush senior is intensely proud of his children. The day in 1998
when two sons were elected governor, one for the first time, one
for the second, ``was the happiest day of my life,'' he said,
``even happier than my wedding day, even happier than the day I was
elected president.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, George W. has been his father's fiercest defender.
He knows the former president made mistakes in his unsuccessful
re-election bid; in an interview in 1994, he said that ``the big
lesson I learned in 1992 is that you can't rest on your laurels and
hope the voters will elect you out of gratitude.'' His father
should not have allowed Bill Clinton to set the terms of debate, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he still thought his father deserved to win, and was deeply
hurt when he was beaten. Ever since, he has bitterly blamed Ross
Perot, the Texas maverick who ran as the Reform Party candidate,
for costing President Bush a second term.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush has a long memory. He has never forgotten, or
fully forgiven, a remark made to him in his undergraduate days by
William Sloane Coffin Jr., then chaplain at Yale, shortly after his
father lost a Senate race to Ralph W. Yarborough in 1964. Coffin, a
die-hard opponent of the Vietnam War, has since denied it, but Bush
distinctly recalls him saying: ``I know your father. Frankly, he
was beaten by a better man.''
</P>
<P>
   He resented Yale for waiting until 1991 to give his father an
honorary degree and resented even more the fact that Helen Whitney,
a maker of left-leaning documentary films, who is married to Benno
C. Schmidt Jr., then Yale's president, did not attend the reception
for his father.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During the years he spent as an adviser to his father in the
White House, the younger Bush resented anyone on the staff, as he
said at the time, ``who gets confused about who is president and
who works for him.'' The extreme case, in his view, was John
Sununu, the chief of staff, and he played a major role in
persuading Sununu to resign. The younger Bush called himself ``the
enforcer.''
</P>
<P>
   But he can charm as well as browbeat, and last week Sununu, a
former governor of New Hampshire, endorsed him with the comment,
``I have never had a problem with any conversation I have had with
Governor Bush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
