<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PEACECORPS-SENIOR-655     01-30 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACECORPS-SENIOR-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DREAM IS FULFILLED, AFTER 39 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICHOLASVILLE, Ky. _ Last spring, when Wini Yunker stopped
dyeing her hair black and let it grow in gray, her friends finally
began to believe her decades of talk about joining the Peace Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't take all the cosmetic supplies I need for that to
Ukraine,'' Wini explained, looking wistful but venturesome as she
made the rounds to say goodbye to her friends in this bluegrass
town where she was born 65 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I just can't do this any more,'' said Wini, who had
decided she needed to make a fashion statement worthy of her
long-delayed wanderlust. ``It was a big step 'cause I always liked
my hair dark,'' she said. ``But I went and shaved all my hair off.
I looked like Michael Jordan. A man at church saw my shaved head
and said, `That's a real foxy hairstyle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now Wini looks like a silver-locked Peter Pan, ready to fly to
Kiev on Monday after a 39-year wait to join the Peace Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Gertie, of Gertie's Dirty Pie fame at the Nicholasville Cafe,
offered Wini a terse, honest Kentucky goodbye at the cash register
during the busy lunchtime. To avoid tears, Wini seemed to be doing
most of the talking, table-hopping to Sam O'Connell, who was just
out of the hospital. ``Tickled to see you,'' she said in farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to live in a small town,'' Wini said with a gentle
tone of passion as she headed down Main Street to arrange an
absentee ballot at the Jessamine County Courthouse. ``Everybody
knows everybody. People here still stop on the sidewalk out of
respect when a funeral procession passes by.''
</P>
<P>
   On Main Street, Wini looked up at the cupola on the Presbyterian
Church, which, older neighbors still remember, she climbed on a
whim when she was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always doing things like that,'' said her son, Joe, who
at 22 is old enough for Wini to be able to leave the family's
simple working-class frame house on North Second Street to fulfill
her dream of joining the Peace Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had gone to Washington to look for a career like so many
young girls back then,'' Wini said of a spellbinding time when she
was 26 and got an office job a block from the White House. She saw
President John F. Kennedy, who passed by often, waving and smiling,
as the embodiment of a special style of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just dashed when the Peace Corps turned me down,'' she
said of her fling at Kennedy idealism that has far outlasted the
Kennedy days.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, Wini came home and lived a full life. On
Tuesday, she finished a career here at Sargent &AMP; Greenleaf, a lock
company, where she moved up from the clerical pool to chief
assistant to the president.
</P>
<P>
   In this time, she has enjoyed at least two courtships and a
wedding, raised a son who has Wini's amiable way, and got a
divorce. And she studied at night and on weekends for the
bachelor's degree (plus a master's) that she was lacking when her
Peace Corps application was first rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they told me Ukraine, I thought that was Siberia,'' Wini
said, laughing. ``But then I realized Yalta is in Ukraine and I
thought, great,'' she said, showing the instincts of a true
Kentucky Democrat raised to worship the history of President
Franklin D. Roosevelt and his search for world peace at the Yalta
summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been reading up and discovered the Ukrainian people are a
lot like us here,'' said Wini, who will begin her adventure by
living with a Ukrainian family for 12 weeks to learn the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ukrainians are very independent, don't like Russia telling
them what to do,'' she said, packing every bit of experience with
her as she heads off to spend the next two years teaching American
business techniques to Ukrainians.
</P>
<P>
   Older volunteers make up less than 10 percent of the 7,000 Peace
Corps volunteers in 77 countries, but Wini finds nothing special in
her status. ``I can do this,'' she said flatly after all the years
of protecting her dream.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In her final hours here, Wini said goodbye to her five older
sisters, making them promise to stay healthy while she is gone. She
had a final lunch with her best friend, Patsy Gray, who will handle
her finances while she is away. She exulted in a fluent goodbye
with Soon Bok-kin, a young Korean immigrant whom Wini taught
English. And she welcomed Tom Smith from Tennessee for a parting
weekend visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be engaged and we stayed good friends,'' Wini
explained, heading for the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``E.J.,'' she said sadly to the county clerk, Eva McDaniel, a
girlhood friend. She gave E.J. a hug and an unnecessary promise to
keep voting straight Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're one of a kind,'' Eva said as Wini headed off.
</P>
<P>
   Out on Main Street, Wini savored a last look at this place, but
in a paradoxical way. ``I may not come back,'' she suddenly said.
``I may stay. I hear there are these American businesses there who
need people like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Wini Yunker was trying to stay one dream ahead as she
left home. ``If I come back here I think my life will be changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
