<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER OF ISRAELI-BACKED LEBANESE MILITIA KILLED BY BOMB
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Guerrillas fighting to oust Israeli troops from
southern Lebanon killed the second-most-senior officer of the
Israeli-backed militia there Sunday with a bomb that exploded near
his house.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, took
responsibility for killing the officer, Col. Akl Hashem, 47, who
commanded the western brigade of the pro-Israeli militia, known as
the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Hashem, who was also the chief of the group's intelligence
service in his area of command, was considered the likely successor
for the 71-year-old militia commander, Gen. Antoine Lahd.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from southern Lebanon said that Hashem, who had survived
several previous attempts on his life, was killed instantly when a
cluster of explosive charges went off in the yard of his farmhouse
near the village of Dibel in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh of Israel promised a
response to the killing of Hashem, and he accused Syria, which
exercises wide influence in Lebanon, of showing bad faith in
negotiations with Israel by failing to rein in Hezbollah. Talks
between Israel and Syria resumed in December but were suspended
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't conceal the fact that this assassination is a real
blow for us and for the south Lebanese,'' Sneh said. ``That is why
it will not go unpunished.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing jolted the Israelis and threatened to demoralize
further their militia allies, who are already worried about their
future after an expected Israeli pullout from southern Lebanon.
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has promised to bring the Israeli troops
there home by July.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has held a nine-mile-wide swath of territory in southern
Lebanon since 1985, saying it serves as a buffer zone against
guerrilla attacks on northern Israel. About 1,100 Israeli troops
are stationed in the zone, allied with the 2,500-member militia.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials were reported Sunday night to be urging
militia commanders to use restraint and resisting their calls for
retaliation, cautioning against an escalation in fighting that
could spin out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do everything so that those who struck Akl Hashem will
get the punishment they deserve,'' Barak said. ``At the same time I
expect the situation not to deteriorate all along the Lebanese
border. The potential is there, and the harm of a possible
deterioration is clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy exchanges of gunfire and Israeli airstrikes were reported
throughout the day in southern Lebanon, and a Lebanese woman was
seriously wounded. An anti-aircraft shell fired by guerrillas
landed near a kindergarten in the Israeli border community of
Margaliot, but there were no casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syria allows Hezbollah to carry out serious attacks that can
lead to escalation,'' Sneh, the Israeli deputy defense minister,
said. ``That means Syria doesn't care if there's a deterioration,
and this raises grave doubts about the seriousness of their
intentions in the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Sneh, a former commander of the southern Lebanon zone held by
Israel, said that he had known Hashem for more than 20 years and
called him ``one of the strongest and staunchest allies of Israel
in Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese authorities had sentenced the colonel, who defected
from the Lebanese army in 1976, to death for ``dealing with the
enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming responsibility for killing him on Sunday, Hezbollah
said it had slain ``the criminal traitor Akl Hashem.'' In the
Lebanese port city of Tyre and in the town of Nabatiye, Hezbollah
supporters celebrated in a raucous car convoy and handed out candy
to motorists.
</P>
<P>
   In the protracted war of attrition fought between Israel and
Hezbollah in southern Lebanon, both sides have used bombs as a tool
to assassinate key military and political figures, relying on
informers to track their movements. Hezbollah's last major success
was in February of last year, when a roadside bomb killed an
Israeli general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
