<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-WILLIAMS-N     01-30 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JASON WILLIAMS IS HAVING FUN DOING IT HIS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Skedded earlier as BKN-KNICKS-COLUMN)  
(ms) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeff Van Gundy wore an incredulous look when he
returned to the bench for the third quarter Sunday. He rolled his
eyes, shook his head and remarked to no one in particular,
``Throwing it off the backboard?''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' coach was referring to the circus pass Jason
Williams left for a trailing Chris Webber at the end of the first
half, a highly unorthodox play for a team 15 points down.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules of hoop etiquette, Williams is supposed to lay
the ball in, get back on defense, walk to the locker room with his
head down and regroup for the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happened instead: Webber blew the dunk so
spectacularly, Ty Corbin grabbed the long rebound and hit a bomb of
a 3-pointer with 1.2 seconds left. And then Marcus Camby launched a
66-foot prayer at the second-quarter buzzer, as if he was shooting
for a Range Rover. Swish!
</P>
<P>
   It was the most surreal end to a half at Madison Square Garden
anyone could remember, triggered by that mischievous showboat who
plays point guard for the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Desecrating the game can be awful lot of fun sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A behind-the-back pass is as easy for me as a chest pass is
for you,'' said Williams, unfazed that several of those passes
ended up in the Garden's third row Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks beat the Kings, America's church-league team,
120-111. Williams missed seven of nine shots he attempted, threw
more than a half dozen no-look turnovers and got under the skin of
old-school referee Hue Hollins enough that Hollins through him out
in the opening moments of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Before it turned to slop late, the game was a wildly
entertaining matinee. Van Gundy, the purist, prevailed over the
Kings' panache. He earned the right to coach the Eastern Conference
All-Star team next week in Oakland, Calif., where you can already
picture Vince Carter in the doghouse because he failed to block out
his man at the end of a 145-120 East victory.
</P>
<P>
   Williams will probably not be at the center of the NBA universe
next week, but he is already smack in the middle of a growing
generational debate in the hoop community: Should a dynamic
ball-handler with shades of Pete Maravich be constantly hyped if he
only makes 35 of every 100 shots he takes? And if he should, at
what juncture does entertainment supersede winning?
</P>
<P>
   To sell the Post-Michael NBA to viewers, David Stern and Dick
Ebersol need Williams and Webber to perform their open-court magic.
But if that magic only lasts one round of the playoffs, what good
will that do anyone? It is a tough act to balance, playing the game
for fun on instinct while occasionally using your head during a key
possession, so the game does not get away from you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When players start thinking what they're going to do, they're
going to start playing like a robot or something,'' Williams said,
explaining his propensity for flair. ``I just go out and ...
whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams put on some incredible theater in the first quarter,
depositing unreal passes on the fingertips of teammates streaking
to the basket. Over the shoulder. Through the legs. The building
was in awe. Like a pool shark, the more difficult the angle and
placement, the more personal satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   But there were several moments where he just got caught up in
the spectacle of playing at the Garden for the first time during
his first-ever visit to New York, junctures in which looking good
appeared to get in the way of leading his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little pain in my chest when he does it,'' said Pete
Carrill, the Hall of Fame college coach who went West two years ago
to become a Kings assistant.
</P>
<P>
   It is an odd pairing, the Coach of Backdoor U. and the Crossover
Kid, sitting by side by side on the same bench. Carrill would have
never let his coat-and-tie Princeton teams play this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's driving me crazy,'' Carrill said. ``But I
notice the difference, I'll tell you that. That's the way this team
has to play for the time being, until they get to be more mature
and our point guard finds better ways to do what he wants to do and
be more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Former coaches turned announcers like Hubie Brown and Matt
Guokas have taken Williams' game to task on many occasions, to
which Williams pays no mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lot of older people in the crowd and older announcers really
don't like it, and I think they don't like it because they couldn't
do it when they was little or younger,'' Williams said. ``And they
still can't do it. But I bet they're the first in line to see us
come to town. They're talking out of both sides of their mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' No. 55 jersey disappears in stores quicker than any
other NBA item, a coveted product among thousands of young
ballplayers. Meanwhile, grade-school coaches watching those same
young ballplayers yo-yo downcourt openly curse his name.
</P>
<P>
   On it rages, kids and fuddy-duddies arguing over whether or not
a 23-year-old point guard is good, great or detrimental to the
game. There is no neutrality. Just ask Van Gundy as he rolls his
eyes. Or Hollins after he threw him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the refs sometimes see a lot of the things we do
as players,'' Williams said. ``For the first time, they're kind of
amazed.'' Then he added, referring to the summer Rucker League in
New York: ``Maybe they need to get out to the Rucker or
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
