<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-NH-PRIMARY-UPCOUNTRY-     01-30 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-PRIMARY-UPCOUNTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES LOOK TO NORTH COUNTRY FOR MARGIN OF VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HART'S LOCATION, N.H. _ Deep in the icy expanse of the White
Mountains, Bill Bradley stood with his back to a crackling fire in
a remote inn, facing every voter in the hamlet _ all 27.
</P>
<P>
   Time raced toward Tuesday's New Hampshire primary, a test that
could make or break Bradley's quest for the White House. Yet on a
day when other candidates were all but tripping over each other in
the state's populous southern tier, Bradley nestled Saturday over
cookies and coffee with one of the tiniest blocs of voters in the
state's largely ignored, but potentially crucial, North Country.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that there were only three Democrats in the bunch.
There were 12 independents, and any one of them could make the
difference in a race that Bradley considers as tight as a political
contest can be. And Bradley, like a number of other candidates who
have recently spent time up north, are demonstrating that they know
their New Hampshire history.
</P>
<P>
   While the population mass clearly is in the south, the great
stretch of country north of Concord sometimes provides just enough
votes for a margin of victory in a tight race: precisely what the
candidates are looking for. Candidates such as Patrick Buchanan in
1996 and George Bush in 1988 have won primaries here in part
because of their strong showing in the north country.
</P>
<P>
   So, in addition to Bradley's foray, Steve Forbes last week
traveled to Littleton and George W. Bush recently spent
considerable time in the Lakes Region, although it has been awhile
since he went to the White Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The North Country can be crucial in different ways for the two
parties. Some of the most active and conservative Republicans live
throughout the North Country. And Berlin is a sort of Democratic
island in the White Mountains, a working-class city with a
reputation for high voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley stopped in Berlin, a largely Franco-American factory
city and Democratic stronghold that is nearly as close to Montreal
as it is to Manchester. There, a moose mascot danced in the doorway
as Bradley was introduced by a supporter, Roland Beausejour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other candidates say, `To hell with the North Country,
we'll go to Manchester where there are a million people living,' ''
Beausejour said afterward. ``I think it will make a good impact
that Bill Bradley came here.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Bradley made an impromptu stop at a Wal-Mart in Berlin,
he discovered the region's contrarian nature. Shaking the hand of a
female customer, he said, ``I hope you'll vote for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep hoping,'' the customer responded.
</P>
<P>
   A Wal-Mart manager then shooed Bradley and his entourage out of
the store, announcing, ``There is no soliciting on Wal-Mart
property.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, most of the presidential campaign takes place in
what many consider to be the exurbs of Massachusetts, in a region
that runs roughly from Portsmouth to Nashua to Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more than half of the registered voters in this
10-county state live in the two southernmost counties, Rockingham
and Hillsborough, and more than two-thirds of the voters are south
of Concord. So it is in the southern tier, amid the suburbs and
shopping centers and strip malls, that most of the candidates spend
most of their time, hitting the same town halls and restaurants and
VFW halls.
</P>
<P>
   But in the popular imagination, the real New Hampshire lies
northward, in the rustic hamlets and gritty logging towns of the
White Mountains, in the covered-bridge country hard by the Vermont
border, in the lakes region and the vast heavily timbered tracts
``north of the notches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two states here,'' said former Governor Hugh Gregg,
who has watched the state change dramatically over the last several
decades. ``North of Concord is the old New Hampshire. South of
Concord is the new New Hampshire, where the independents have come
in, where we have got the highest density of high-tech workers per
capita in the nation. The south is where the presidential
candidates are concentrating. North is for the `photo ops.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But another former New Hampshire governor, John H. Sununu, told
a St. Anselm's College seminar last week that presidential
candidates ignore the north country at their peril. Sununu said
that the defining moment of former President Bush's 1988 primary
came when he insisted that the campaign go north in the final days.
Sununu said it wound up providing the margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   John Harrigan, who edits three North Country weekly newspapers,
including the Coos County Democrat, said that he has seen fewer
visits by presidential candidates over the years. But Harrigan said
Bradley was wise to go north because many people there are upset
with President Clinton's actions and tag Gore with their
unhappiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley will run away from Gore here,'' Harrigan predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican race, however, is as tight in the north as it is
in the southern part of the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, in an interview, said that he made an extra
effort to go north, believing the region is heavy with veterans and
independent-minded voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent a lot of time there,'' said McCain, who often tells
audiences that he has twice been to Dixville Notch, the home of The
Balsams resort, where a handful of voters cast the first primary
votes. ``But the difference between now and 1996 is that there has
been a real significant economic uptick in the northern part of the
state. In '96, the south was doing well, the north was in trouble.
Now the north is doing better.''
</P>
<P>
   The region is notorious for its bad weather, and every campaign
seems to have a story of canceled trips. But some candidates insist
on making the trip, believing it could make or break their
campaign. In 1976, with a vicious snowstorm was swirling around
Manchester, Jimmy Carter was determined to keep an engagement in
Berlin. A reporter who accompanied Carter asked, ``Is this trip
necessary?'' Carter replied that he had been reading the Bible the
night before and had found a passage that spoke about how the
apostles set ``a straight course unto Coos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the county where Berlin is located, don't you?''
Carter said. ``It's Coos County.'' So Carter flew into the teeth of
the storm and delivered his speech in the Democratic bastion of the
north country _ and won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Curtis Wilkie and staff reporter Michael
Crowley contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
