<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONE AGAIN LOSES AT ITS OWN GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Before the start of the final round of
the Louis Vuitton series to determine the next America's Cup
challenger, and well before the San Francisco-based America One
syndicate found itself down by 3-1 to Italy's surprisingly
hard-nosed Prada Challenge, the U.S. skipper Paul Cayard offered
what has become a prescient analysis of the action to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be some hard races,'' he said. ``Some
heartbreaking races. You might lose a race after leading all the
way around the course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you deal with that,'' he added, ``could make all the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, after having led at every mark of the 18.5-mile course,
Cayard and his team succumbed to Prada in the final excruciating
moments of Race 4 in the five-of-nine final.
</P>
<P>
   There was no racing Monday in observation of Auckland
Anniversary Day. When the series resumes Tuesday, Cayard and his
squad will need to stage a mighty rally to salvage their hopes of
facing Team New Zealand in the America's Cup finals, which begin
Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   When the series began, the conventional wisdom went like this:
with a slight speed deficit in some conditions, Cayard and his more
experience crew would ultimately prevail after rattling the
Italians into submission with an aggressive, take-no-prisoners,
street-fighting style.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to King Cayard's
coronation. America One has enjoyed a slight but pronounced
boat-speed advantage in the gusty conditions in which the last two
races were sailed. But it didn't matter. The Italians were still
victorious in both contests.
</P>
<P>
   In each contest, Prada beat the gunslinger Cayard at his own
game.
</P>
<P>
   In Race 3, a wet, wild affair with blasting winds that peaked at
more than 30 knots, the Italians stayed calm and collected in a
tight downwind crossing that is the sort of close-quarters racing
in which Cayard and his mates usually thrive. Instead, the
Americans panicked and fouled the Italians, the first of several
sail-handling errors that led to an easy Prada victory.
</P>
<P>
   Race 4 was something altogether different, a contest in which
America One gained control in savage fashion on the first downwind
run. Cayard's aggressive tactics sent the Italians spinning out of
control and flailing in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the final downwind run in which the race was
won...and lost. In the closing stretch, having pulled back into
contention on the winds of a strong following breeze, the Italians
again converged on America One in another crossing maneuver that
would decide the affair.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Cayard's crew could not pull off the
maneuver in time. Obliged to stay clear of Prada, Cayard could not
and the on-the-water umpires signaled America One for a foul.
</P>
<P>
   America One crossed the finish line a nose ahead, but still had
to complete its penalty turn.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it did, the race was over. Prada had won.
</P>
<P>
   The deck is now indeed shuffled. The only remaining question now
is, does Cayard hold an ace up his sleeve?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
