<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ITALY-LAW-570&AMP;ADD-NYT     01-30 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-LAW-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIANS ARGUE OVER EFFORTS TO MAKE TRIALS FAIRER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Italy prepared for the year 2000 by passing laws to speed
up its notoriously slow judicial process and to protect the rights
of defendants better.
</P>
<P>
   But so far those milestones seem almost buried by a clamorous
debate over whether justice in Italy is independent or ruled by
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, politicians on the left and the right were
obsessively re-examining cases past, seeking to rewrite two of the
most turbulent chapters of recent Italian history: the terrorism of
the 1970s and 1980s _ a period so violent that it is known as the
``years of lead'' _ and Tangentopoli, or Bribesville, the criminal
investigations into a huge web of corruption and bribery that in
the early 1990s brought down the centrist Christian Democratic
party and its Socialist allies.
</P>
<P>
   Those two very different cases have at least one thing in common
_ critics on each side insist that the investigations were
politically biased. And those sentiments, echoed most heatedly in
Parliament, highlight one of the weaknesses that undermine efforts
at legal reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now a real effort to make changes in the legal
system,'' said Vittorio Grevi, director of the C. Beccaria
Institute of Law and Criminal Procedure in Pavia. ``But the real
problem is that there is such deep distrust of the magistrates who
apply the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The tortuous legal saga of Adriano Sofri and two co-defendants,
radical leftist intellectuals who were convicted in 1990 of
conspiring to kill a police inspector in 1972 and maintained their
innocence throughout eight different trials, is a cause celebre
that has long polarized Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Dario Fo, a Nobel Prize winner, wrote ``Accidental Death of an
Anarchist'' based on one of the elements of the Sofri case. When a
Venice court upheld the convictions last week, there was an
outpouring of anger and distress.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Veltroni, who leads the Democrats of the Left, the party
of Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, said the verdict must be
``respected'' but added, ``The whole truth of that unjustifiable
murder must come out and the guilty be brought to justice,'' a
statement that clearly implied that all the trials and judges'
verdicts so far had not achieved this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence in the justice system has so deteriorated that
people feel they can just dismiss a verdict they don't agree
with,'' said Massimo Pavarini, a law professor at the University of
Bologna.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, however, it is the center-left that usually argues
that magistrates in Italy are impartial enforcers of the law, and
that any attempt to rein in their power is a political assault by
politicians who fear corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of Parliament on Wednesday approved a
parliamentary committee to investigate Tangentopoli, in which
hundreds of businessmen and politicians were charged and convicted,
though only a few served time in prison. It is not yet clear
exactly what is under scrutiny: Italian socialists and center-right
politicians on the committee want to show that the prosecutors were
overly zealous and politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left, including the government of D'Alema, hopes to
show that if anything, the prosecutors did not probe deeply enough.
The government reluctantly agreed to the commission, not because it
believed there was any need to re-examine Tangentopoli, but because
it wanted to woo socialist backing for its fragile center-left
coalition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Political mistrust is so entrenched that few court decisions are
viewed as unassailable. At the funeral of the former Socialist
prime minister, Bettino Craxi, who fled to Tunisia before he was
convicted on corruption charges stemming from Tangentopoli, some of
his supporters hurled insults at government representatives who
attended the service.
</P>
<P>
   But not even his supporters maintain that Craxi, who was
convicted in two separate trials, was innocent. Instead, they
insist that every political party accepted bribes and illegal
contributions, and that Craxi was unfairly singled out.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition leader, Silvio Berlusconi, a former prime
minister and media tycoon, has led the campaign to limit the power
of prosecutors. There are legal experts who agree that prosecutors
in Italy have too much power and that defendants' rights need to be
strengthened. But Berlusconi's motives can hardly be described as
impartial. He has been convicted three times on charges of false
accounting and illegal campaign financing, and is currently
awaiting trial on accusations that he sought to bribe judges.
</P>
<P>
   For all the political squabbling, however, Parliament did manage
to pass two reforms before the end of 1999. One law reduces from
three to one the number of judges who preside over most criminal
trials. It is aimed at speeding up trials that in Italy can drag on
for years.
</P>
<P>
   The other, passed in November, is called ``just trial.'' Most
important, the law obliges witnesses to testify in court and be
cross-examined, as is customary in the United States. (Before,
prosecutors could rely on affidavits signed by informants during
the police investigation, even those that reported hearsay.)
</P>
<P>
   The Italian legal system's dependence on the testimony of
hostile witnesses, most notably on ``pentiti '' _ defendants who
testify in exchange for liberty or shorter sentences _ has long
been under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, such testimony was used in trials in which the
defense could not cross-examine the accusers. And the Italian
witness-protection program allowed several pentiti to continue to
commit crimes while guests of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The acquittal of Giulio Andreotti, the former prime minister
whose two trials on charges that he collaborated with the Mafia
while in office dragged on for years, was one of the most visible
blows to the credibility of pentiti.
</P>
<P>
   In a less noticed but equally telling ruling, a court in Palermo
earlier this month acquitted seven men charged with a 1995 bank
robbery _ and handed their accusers, mobsters turned state's
witnesses, far stiffer sentences than the ones they received from
plea bargaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1194 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MYCIO-WEB-SFCHRON &LR;      01-30 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYCIO-WEB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 McAfee Hopes One Good Launch Leads to Another  &HT;     
 By KELLY ZITO  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hoping to build on the momentum of its spin-off McAfee.com, whose
price tripled in a stock market debut in December, Network
Associates will launch MyCIO.com, a Web site where businesses can
download antivirus and other security software.
<P>
   The site, which went online today under the direction of a new,
100-employee division within Santa Clara's Network Associates, aims
to be a Web-based provider of information technology services. CIO,
in this case, stands for chief Internet officer, rather than the
better-known chief information officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is changing the (information technology)
business,'' said Zach Nelson, president and chief executive of
MyCIO. ``All businesses want to be e-businesses ... and things like
security are mission critical, but no one wants to spend time
building that expertise in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   The move illustrates a continuing shift within the traditional
packaged software industry to move products and services online as
the Internet emerges as a more efficient means of distribution than
brick-and-mortar stores. It also reflects an organizational change
for Network Associates, which sees itself becoming a holding
company of smaller entities built around its core antivirus and
security technology. Network Associates' traditional business model
has been based on consulting and software development.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, MyCIO will offer two products to potential
corporate clients _ VirusScan ASaP and CyberCop ASaP. The first
allows a company to purchase a certain number of ``agents'' which
sit on an employee's desktop. Each time a user signs on, the agent
automatically updates itself with new antivirus cures each day by
dialing into MyCIO. The cost of the service is $3.50 per user per
month and goes down as the number of users increases.
</P>
<P>
   The second is a way for a company to test the vulnerability of
its firewall _ usually the first line of defense against its
Internet-connected systems _ by bombarding it with models of known
hacker attacks. A group of six such scans costs $500.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually MyCIO hopes to expand its offerings to include
so-called ``availability'' applications, which assess and provide
reports on things like why a company's network is slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``(MyCIO) makes a lot of sense from a business strategy point of
view,'' said Erik Suppiger, analyst at Chase H&AMP;Q. ``There are a lot
of organizations out there that are organizationally constrained
when it comes to IT. To the extent (companies) can outsource''
elements of their business that aren't a core competency, ``it's a
great efficiency for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said that if the company meets its goals _ which include
about $20 million in sales in its first year _ Network Associates
hopes to spin MyCIO out into a separate business, and to eventually
take it public.
</P>
<P>
   So far, MyCIO has no signed agreements, but Nelson said he has
gotten calls from DuPont and United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   In early December, Network Associates offered shares of
McAfee.com, which sells a range of consumer-oriented computer
maintenance and antivirus programs, to the public. Originally
priced at $12 per share, the stock soared to close at $44 on
Nasdaq. Since then, it's closed as high as $54.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the tracking stock gave a needed boost to its
parent, which retains 85 percent ownership in McAfee.com Inc.
Network Associates stock dropped more than 60 percent last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
