<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEEVES-URBAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Ask Jeeves, Urban Cool Take the Web to the Street  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Where's do you buy phat clothes in Oaktown?
<P>
   Who's sells the best hip-hop?
</P>
<P>
   What up? What the dealio?
</P>
<P>
   It's Ask Jeeves' new Internet search service that will look for
answers to questions posed in the popular language of the street.
</P>
<P>
   Emeryville's Ask Jeeves Inc., today will announce a deal to
develop an ``urban street language'' database for Urban Cool
Networks Inc., a Web portal aimed at those in the hip, young urban
culture who may not be down with the Net just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Adding street language to the Internet is one way of helping
bridge the Digital Divide that is keeping some urban dwellers away
from the Web, said Jake Miles, founder and CEO of Urban Cool,
located in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are millions of people at lower ends of the economic
scale that aren't on the Internet,'' Miles said. ``Getting them
access, we believe, is just part of the solution. The other part is
that the Internet is not relevant to them. The Internet does not
speak their language.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban Cool, which links to about 6,000 urban business and
consumer sites, has struck a deal to have Ask Jeeves create a
specialized version of natural language search technology to
include common street idioms not found in Webster's dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   That way, a visitor to Urban Cool can find the best, or ``Pretty
Hot and Tight'' clothing in Oakland. And a search for hip-hop style
music or clothing in Atlanta won't come with ways to get
hip-replacement surgery or hops for beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone uses the old term `homey,' it will be able to
recognize that as well,'' Miles said.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Cool, at &LR;  www.urbancool.com &LR; , also plans to install a
network of high-speed Internet kiosks in 25 urban markets and has
announced plans for an initial public offering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-U.N.-CONGO-ART-NYT &LR;      01-30 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-U.N.-CONGO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. FACES BIG CHALLENGE IN ANY CONGO PEACEKEEPING MISSION
</HEADLINE>
   (Adds art note) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When an unusual meeting of African leaders and the Security
Council ended last week, there was general agreement that the
United Nations will have to be given a major role in bringing peace
to Congo. But when, and in what form, are still open questions that
are expected to dominate council discussions in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, Secretary-General Kofi Annan, a former director of
U.N. peacekeeping, recommended that the Security Council, which has
already authorized sending 500 cease-fire monitors to Congo, add
5,537 troops. This would include infantry as well as medical,
communications, mine-clearance and air and water transportation
experts for a nearly roadless region. The start-up cost is
estimated at $41 million.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Annan said that 960,000 Congolese have been
displaced by the war and that they and another 300,000 refugees
from other wars in the region are dangerously short of food.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and U.N. officials say they see in Congo's complicated
war a challenge like no other that the organization has faced since
the Balkans disintegrated into ethnic warfare after the collapse of
European communism.
</P>
<P>
   Within the United Nations, even the word Congo has tragic
resonance. Secretary-General Dag Hammarskjold died on a Congo peace
mission in 1961 when his plane crashed in what is now Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the American representative, called the
unusual meeting of African presidents and ministers as January's
council president. He has been telling U.N. officials and members
of Congress that the Congo operation may be the United Nations'
last chance to prove it can get peacekeeping right. That was the
message he delivered directly to the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee on its recent field trip to New York.
</P>
<P>
   But other diplomats say that this assertion masks another
problem. Unless the United States allows the Security Council and
the U.N. peacekeeping department to mount a credible operation in
Congo, they say, the organization will be in danger of repeating
its experience in Somalia and Rwanda, two regional conflicts that
it proved unable to bring under control. .
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Rwanda, where a genocidal war in 1994 first
disrupted the region and drew Congo into the fighting, the United
States prevented the Security Council from acting for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke says that he is determined that this will not happen
again. But he also accepts that he has two huge tasks ahead. The
Clinton administration has agreed to give Congress 15 days notice
of Security Council resolutions creating U.N. peacekeeping
operations, for which the United States is billed more than 30
percent of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   So Holbrooke will have to persuade reluctant members of Congress
that skimping on Congo will lead to disaster. Congress already has
a law on the books saying that the United States will limit its
payments to 25 percent, and often balks at that.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Holbrooke has been urging African leaders, on
a trip there in December and in the Security Council in January, to
take more responsibility for the region. Without political will in
Africa, he tells them, nothing the United Nations tries can
possibly work. A few Africans left New York last week saying they
felt ``bullied.''
</P>
<P>
   Last July, African nations involved in the Congo war joined the
government of President Laurent Kabila in Lusaka, Zambia, where
they agreed on a peace accord. A month later they were all back at
war. By the fall, they were clamoring for international help, a
message delivered most bluntly last week by President Robert Mugabe
of Zimbabwe. He supports Kabila's government in its war with rebels
who are, in turn, backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   In Security Council speeches last week, and in a statement of
purpose that followed the meetings, African leaders coupled their
calls for U.N. peacekeepers with new pledges to put their Lusaka
agreement into practice. Britain's representative, Sir Jeremy
Greenstock, welcomed African commitments to peace. But reflecting
the skepticism of many at the United Nations, he noted that the
world had been pleading with Africans for action for some time, but
``frankly, they weren't listening.''
</P>
<P>
   The deep divisions between Congo and its neighbors, evident even
in public speeches last week, were reportedly even more pronounced
in closed-door meetings among the African leaders, Annan and
American and other officials and diplomats. One Western official
said that by the end of the council deliberations Wednesday there
was ``blood on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Considerable attention was focused last week on Kabila, who made
his first trip to the United States and apparently went home less
convinced of American support for his enemies, Rwanda and Uganda.
Kabila's American public relations aides were elated with his trip
and say that he plans to return in May, hoping to talk with
American companies about more investment in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats and American officials see hope in economic
pressures. All the nations involved in the Congo war are now
feeling the costs of that involvement and are looking for a way to
withdraw without a loss of dignity, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The political will to take that step, the secretary-general's
report says, is not only what matters most but is also the basic
condition for peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1199 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ANTHRO-TECH-SFCHRON &LR;      01-30 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRO-TECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Designing Products Based on Real Life  &HT;       
 By Peter Kupfer  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jack Whalen surveyed real estate agent Cid Young's home/office in
Moss Beach with the keen eye of a tax assessor. As Young described
her daily routine, Whalen listened attentively, occasionally
jotting down notes or training his digital camera on the blizzard
of papers and Post-it notes scattered around the room.
<P>
   Why, Whalen asked, did Young have three computers? Wouldn't it
be easier, he wondered, to use computerized forms instead of paper
ones? How does she access the Multiple Listing Service that is the
lifeblood of every real estate agent?
</P>
<P>
   Despite appearances, Whalen isn't an IRS auditor. Nor is he a
documentary filmmaker. He's a sociologist from Xerox's legendary
Palo Alto Research Center studying how people who work out of their
homes and on the road access the vital information they need to do
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He's among a growing number of social scientists hired by
technology companies to conduct ethnographic research, a branch of
anthropology that studies human culture. But unlike Margaret Mead
and other academics, the ethnographers who toil in the technology
industry have been hired with the idea that their observations and
insights will lead to the development of new products and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit like a reconnaissance mission,'' said David
Frohlich, a psychologist specializing in conversation analysis at
Hewlett-Packard's research center in Bristol, England. ``You're
mapping out the landscape, constantly foraging for opportunities
for new technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In years past, product development in the technology industry
was largely driven by engineers, who usually designed products
based on their own interests and left the marketing department with
the task of finding consumers to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   But with the accelerating pace of technological innovation,
product cycles are measured in weeks rather than years. Many
companies are finding that it makes better business sense to design
products based on what consumers want rather than what engineers
think they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, you had a bunch of white middle-aged guys
sitting around saying, `This is what I like and this is what my
wife likes, so let's make that,' '' said Marietta Baba, chairwoman
of the Anthropology Department at Wayne State University in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Baba, who has conducted ethnographic studies for automakers and
technology companies, said that the increasing globalization of
markets makes such an ethnocentric approach to product design
impractical. For example, a black cell phone with myriad functions
designed for the U.S. market may hold little attraction in Latin
America, where bright colors and simpler designs are preferred.
</P>
<P>
   The quest for information about consumer behavior has taken
ethnographers to some unlikely places and has sometimes yielded
surprising results.
</P>
<P>
   When Intel sent John Sherry to Alaska to research a salmon
fishery, he discovered that the tender who picked up the day's
catch from the fishermen had duct-taped a notebook computer to the
outside of his cabin. The reason? The tender had to keep a lot of
records and that was the most convenient spot for him to enter the
data. The study, dubbed ``Fish and Chips,'' helped Intel understand
the importance of designing microprocessors capable of withstanding
extreme weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   When Motorola sent anthropologist Jean Canavan to the Caspian
Sea region to investigate business opportunities in the emerging
markets of Azerbaijan, Kazakstan and Uzbekistan, she found that
savvy consumers had learned to read the bar codes on cell phones to
find out where they were manufactured. Those made in the United
States, Canavan discovered, were considered more desirable.
</P>
<P>
   Another Motorola study found that Chinese businessmen working in
rural areas with no telephone service had developed an elaborate
system of using pagers to send coded messages. That discovery led
Motorola to develop a two-way pager for the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of office workers in England, Hewlett-Packard's
Frohlich noticed a recurring theme: Workplace communications almost
always involved documents. ``We realized that something that could
bring together people's conversations and printed documents would
be very useful,'' he said. That finding led to the development of
the DeskSlate, a device that connected to a telephone and allowed
users to view a document and listen to voice mail about that
document at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every field trip leads to a product idea. Intel
sent a team of three ethnographers to observe families in Europe
last summer. The team shadowed their subjects from morning to
night, following them in their homes and workplaces, to
neighborhood cafes and restaurants, through parks and markets. The
researchers took thousands of photographs, hundreds of hours of
audio recordings and reams of notes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings was that life in Europe revolves around the
family to a far greater extent than in the United States. ``In
Europe, business conforms to life,'' said Tony Salvador, an
experimental psychologist at Intel who participated in the study.
``In the United States, life conforms to business.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the research has not resulted in any specific products,
it has given the company a better grasp of an important market.
``Europe is a place we don't understand as well as we should,''
said Christine Riley, who oversees ethnographic research at Intel.
``This was an investment in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the seminal ethnography studies by a technology company
was conducted by Lucy Suchman, a young anthropologist hired by
Xerox PARC in 1979. Suchman made a now-famous film showing office
workers struggling to do a copying job on a Xerox machine. After
viewing the film, Xerox engineers concluded that simplicity was
more important than fancy features. That finding gave rise to the
large green button to make a single, fuss-free copy that is now a
prominent feature on almost every Xerox machine, no matter how
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Another Xerox study discovered that the company's repair
technicians often learned how to fix troublesome machines during
informal exchanges with their colleagues. ``They swapped war
stories at restaurants and bars, and embedded in those stories were
diagnostic clues and procedures,'' said Baba. ``This was a major
 &LR; aha &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Xerox equipped its repair technicians with mobile
phones to facilitate the exchange of information.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Suchman study, almost every major technology company,
and many smaller firms, have integrated ethnographic research into
their product development process.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnographers say their approach has a number of advantages over
traditional market research techniques such as surveys and focus
groups. For one thing, ethnography entails first-hand observations
of what people do in their everyday lives, as opposed to what they
say they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people say and what they do are often very different,''
said Susan Squires, president of the National Association for the
Practice of Anthropology and a founder of GVO, a technology
consultancy in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   One example of this disparity involved a major management
consulting firm that hired Squires' outfit to evaluate the
feasibility of installing video-conferencing technology in its
offices around the world. When Squires interviewed company
executives, they were enthusiastic about the idea and couldn't wait
to get the new technology. But when a prototype of the system was
installed in the offices of several executives, almost every one of
them turned the cameras off in short order because they found them
distracting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a classic mismatch,'' Squires said. Her company
recommended delaying the installation, and the client saved
millions of dollars on unnecessary technology.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of ethnographic research is that it can be
done relatively quickly. Although some studies take months, or even
years, to complete (Hewlett-Packard's Frohlich once spent three
years observing and analyzing the telephone habits of a single
English family), others can be done in a matter of weeks or days.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rapid pace of technological change, you need to find
out what is going on out there, and you need to find out fast,''
said Baba. ``Big surveys can take months. Ethnography is fast.'' A
sound methodology, she said, will translate into valuable insights
in a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnographers commonly have degrees in anthropology, sociology
or psychology, but some technology firms are casting a wider net in
their quest for knowledge about consumer behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Sapient, an Internet consultancy in Cambridge, Mass., and one of
the pioneers in ethnographic research, for example, has a workforce
that includes historians, actors, theologians, literary critics and
even a cookbook author. What this wildly eclectic group has in
common, said Rick Robinson, Sapient's chief experience officer, is
that ``they are all good at observing the relationship between
people and culture and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Moss Beach, Xerox researcher Whalen called it a day
after spending nearly four hours observing Young as she worked in
her office and visited a nearby house she was trying to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the lab, Cid is just another real estate agent,'' Whalen
said. ``But out here, she comes alive. That's the beauty of
ethnography. You can't design products for someone unless you can
see the richness and uniqueness of their world. That's lost in the
laboratory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2048EST &QL; 
