<HEADER>
A1200 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EXCITE-ATHOME-SFCHRON     01-30 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-ATHOME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ExciteAtHome Hopes Security Tool Calms Users  &HT;       
 By Todd Wallack  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
For years, ExciteAtHome executives have earnestly tried to fend off
criticism that their high-speed Internet cable service is wide open
to hackers.
<P>
   Now, the Redwood City company seems to be conceding it is losing
the public relations battle.
</P>
<P>
   In a stark admission that many customers continue to be worried
about intruders, ExciteAtHome today plans to team up with
McAfee.com to sell subscribers a sophisticated computer security
tool, called a firewall, that is normally only used to guard
corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ExciteAtHome executives still insist that the vast
majority of its customers don't need to install a firewall on their
home PC. But company representatives said they hope the McAfee deal
will calm those subscribers who are particularly worried about
intruders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical deal since there is an overwhelming, albeit
incorrect, feeling that broadband (or high-speed service) is less
secure than 56k (traditional modem service),'' said ExciteAtHome
spokeswoman Jacqueline Russo.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome concedes there were major security flaws when cable
modem service first became available a few years ago. Because
Microsoft's Windows operating system makes it easy to share files
with other computers, subscribers sometimes discovered they could
just as easily browse documents stored on their neighbors'
computers. ExciteAtHome's service is delivered over traditional
cable TV lines, which are shared among neighboring homes much like
a telephone party line.
</P>
<P>
   But ExciteAtHome said subscribers can easily solve that problem
by turning off the option to share files. Indeed, ExciteAtHome
technicians try to make sure that is done when setting up new
subscribers. Executives say their newer equipment also helps
prevent the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts say that all high-speed links, including cable
modems and phone companies' digital subscriber lines (DSL), are
attractive targets for hackers because the computers are often
connected to the Net around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   With conventional dial-up access, most customers are only on for
an hour or so at a time _ giving hackers less time to break in and
use the computer. Plus, each time users log on again, they are
normally assigned a different Internet address (called an IP
address), making it harder for the hacker to find them and break in
a second time.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ExciteAtHome subscribers normally keep the same IP
address for months at a time, making them tastier targets. ``Those
of us with cable modems and DSL connections are watching the
systems be scanned for security vulnerabilities several times a
day,'' said Mudge, a Boston hacker and computer security expert
best known for telling a congressional committee that he and his
colleagues could shut down the Internet in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jay Rolls, ExciteAtHome's vice president of network
engineering, concedes ``the exposure is higher'' when a computer is
connected to the Internet around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   But ExciteAtHome executives insist that the average user running
a Mac or PC with Windows doesn't need to install a firewall.
</P>
<P>
   Mike StJohns, a network architect with the company, said only
advanced users are likely to be hit by hackers. That would include
people using their PC to host a Web site, those running Linux
(which is similar to the Unix programs frequently targeted by
hackers invading corporate networks) or those trying to link their
computer to a home network. Also vulnerable are users who download
many files from a variety of Web sites without running antivirus
software. StJohns said users doing more sophisticated tasks also
need more sophisticated security.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome said it won't distribute the firewall product,
called McAfee Personal Firewall. But McAfee paid ExciteAtHome an
undisclosed amount of money to pitch the product to its customers.
McAfee, a unit of Santa Clara's Network Associates, also agreed to
give ExciteAtHome customers a discount and let them try it out free
for 90 days. Russo said prices haven't been set yet.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell spokesman Shawn Dainas said his company, which
offers DSL high-speed links to California customers, is considering
similar security deals. But he couldn't resist using the
announcement to crow about cable modem's past security problems.
``There has always been a concern with cable modems because
neighbors share the network,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp. analyst Jeanette Noyes said it's
awkward for ExciteAtHome to peddle high-power security tools while
insisting the cable service is nearly invincible to hackers. But
she noted that the company has to appeal both to novice users ``who
probably don't need and wouldn't know how to use'' a firewall, as
well as power users who want the service for their home business or
to power a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Noyes said demand for both DSL and cable modem
service hasn't been slowed by security concerns. Between 1 percent
and 2 percent of homes now subscribe to the fast Net service, and
both cable and telephone companies are scrambling to keep up with
orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
