<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED NOTICES FOR THE TOUGHER BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Trent Thompson sees a lot of things in former
Sen. Bill Bradley that he likes, from his down-to-earth style to
his ideas for expansive government. But when Bradley began accusing
Vice President Al Gore of being dishonest last week, it tweaked
Thompson's loyal Democratic sensibilities in an unpleasant way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gore has a lot of integrity,'' said Thompson, a
31-year-old physician. ``I think he's being unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark underscores the problem Bradley faces as he ratchets
up his attacks on Gore's integrity in the final days before New
Hampshire's primary on Tuesday, the first in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It was less than a week ago that Bradley drastically shifted
gears in his insurgent campaign, dropping his reasoned, soft-spoken
responses to Gore's brass-tacks criticisms of him and beginning a
full-throated attack against Gore's character.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had not been honest in this campaign, Bradley and his
surrogates began asserting _ about his record on abortion, about
his proposals for health care and gun control, about his role in
campaign finance abuses by the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The new, get-tough tone cheered many of Bradley's strongest
supporters here, who had grown dispirited by Bradley's falling poll
numbers and by a steady diet of anti-Bradley criticism from the
vice president's camp.
</P>
<P>
   But to many independent voters, many undecided Democrats and
even some of Bradley's supporters, the insurgent's brash new tone
is troubling.
</P>
<P>
   To some Democrats, Bradley seems to be trying to tar the vice
president with President Clinton's ethical problems, which to them
seems unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   To others, Bradley's new attacks are reminiscent of what they
like least about politics: the bickering and negative tit-for-tat.
</P>
<P>
   And to some of his supporters, Bradley's new approach seems to
rub against the grain of what they liked most about him: his gentle
style, his idealism, his anti-politics politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the idea that he's changed his approach,'' said
Steve Harvey, a 51-year-old independent voter who came to see
Bradley speak in a college bar in Durham Sunday. ``I'd like to see
someone who stays above the fray as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Morris, an undecided Democrat, liked Bradley enough to
venture out Sunday night to hear him speak in a packed auditorium
at Phillips Exeter Academy. But he said he had been disappointed by
Bradley's performance in a debate last Wednesday, finding him a
little naive, even annoying, when he began bitterly complaining
about Gore's attacks against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded a bit childish,'' said Morris, 48, a space science
researcher at the University of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he was not impressed by Bradley's assertion that
Gore is not honest. ``The most truthful president in my lifetime
was Jimmy Carter, and it didn't do much for him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's attacks against Gore for 1996 campaign finance abuses
also seemed to upset some Democrats who feel that the Clinton-Gore
campaign's aggressive fund-raising, while questionable, was
necessary to accomplish Democratic goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bothered by what happened in the 1996 campaign,'' said
Thompson. ``But the Clinton administration has done good things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides say the people criticizing him for punching back
at Gore seem to have forgotten that the vice president started the
fight by slashing at Bradley's record and campaign agenda months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   And clearly, Bradley's new assertiveness is playing well among
his staunchest supporters here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fired up finally,'' said Silvie Thierry, 61, who came to
see Bradley speak in Concord Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few months ago, I was worried that he wouldn't be able to
handle the Republicans, that he was too much Mr. Nice Guy. Now I'm
more confident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
