u i BC-JAPAN-HACKERS-1STLD-W     01-30 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-HACKERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB HACKERS IN JAPAN DENOUNCE RAPE OF NANJING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Inserts new graf beginning ``The problem ...'') 
(lb) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Internet hackers posted messages on the Web site of
Japan's postal service Sunday criticizing this country's wartime
role in China in the 1930s, as a series of similar attacks over the
last week began to look like a daily ritual.
</P>
<P>
   At least 11 government agencies here have been attacked by the
hackers. In each incident, they have denounced Japan's involvement
in the so-called Nanjing Massacre, or Rape of Nanking, the
murderous 1937 sacking of that city by Japanese troops.
</P>
<P>
   The security breaches, which have affected the Science and
Technology Agency, the Supreme Court, the Bank of Japan, the
Finance Ministry and the Defense Ministry, among others, have
deeply embarrassed the Japanese government, which has rushed to set
up a task force to catch the intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Perceiving that it lags behind the United States in Internet
technologies, the Japanese government has been pushing use of the
Web for government information and services as a top priority. But
after the recent incidents, many commentators here have said that
Internet security seems to have been something of an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the Japanese government security in
cyberspace is that the government leaders know little about
technology,'' Raisuke Miyawaki, a former chief cabinet spokesman
and now an independent security analyst, told the newspaper Nihon
Keizei Shimbun.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents have also served to keep attention focused on
Japan's wartime role, a source of continuing tension between Japan
and China and other Asian nations that were occupied by Japanese
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions over Japan's wartime atrocities were revived last week
when nationalist groups held a conference in Osaka at which
revisionist historians and others gave speeches denying that there
had been any large-scale massacre at Nanjing and disparaging
Japan's critics.
</P>
<P>
   China criticized Japan bitterly for the conference, warning that
it would oppose Osaka's bid to be the host city for the Olympics
unless the Japanese government took action against similar
conferences in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi has said that it
would be an infringement of free speech to prevent people from
holding conferences on controversial subjects, but it has called
the Nanjing Massacre a regrettable fact of history.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional historical accounts of the December 1937 attack on
Nanjing hold that the Japanese occupiers killed 60,000 to 300,000
people, including thousands of civilians and prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Internet attacks Sunday, a message in English
holding Japan responsible for the Nanjing killings appeared as a
Web page added to the site of the Posts and Telecommunications
Ministry in Naha, the capital of Okinawa province.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, hackers inserted an image of a Japanese flag and a
Chinese message in red characters, including the phrase ``Tokyo
Massacre,'' on the site of the Government Data Research Center in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, a Web site of a nonprofit organization
affiliated with the prime minister's office was attacked with a
similar message.
</P>
<P>
   Another attack erased most of the contents of the Web site
operated by the National Personnel Authority.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the Web site of the Bank of Japan was attacked at
least 1,600 times by hackers, said a bank spokesman, Satoru
Yamadera.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1203 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE-ENZYME-SFCHR     01-30 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-ENZYME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Drug Companies Battle Over Patent for Enzyme Used in DNA Testing  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A pinch of mugwort, a drop of lemon balm, these are the elements of
a witch's brew. But the real sorcery of the modern age is the
manipulation of DNA, and here one of the magic ingredients has been
an enzyme named Taq.
<P>
   Originally found in bacteria living in the hot springs of
Yellowstone, Taq speeds up the widely used process that amplifies
trace amounts of DNA in order to create enough material for
scientific study.
</P>
<P>
   Every time an AIDS patient gets an HIV viral load test, or a
forensics expert studies a DNA sample from a crime scene, a bit of
Taq, or a related enzyme, goes into the test tube along with the
genetic material.
</P>
<P>
   A pinch of Taq only costs 30 cents to 65 cents, but with all the
DNA work being done in commercial and academic labs, not to mention
the genome-mapping programs, those many dime-sized doses add up to
a chemical market worth $200 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   That explains why this innocent enzyme is at the heart of a
7-year-old legal battle between Roche Molecular Systems of Alameda,
which owns the Taq patent, and Promega Corp., a Wisconsin firm
which Roche has accused of selling this chemical without a license.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been argued in the San Francisco court of U.S.
District Judge Vaughn Walker who, any year now, will finally settle
the contractual and patent haggles and decide who owes whom money
as a result.
</P>
<P>
   But this protracted dispute offers a hint of what may be in
store as commercial firms race to file conflicting patents on human
genes and the chemicals used to identify and manipulate them.
</P>
<P>
   The Taq story begins in 1987, when scientists at the now-defunct
Cetus Corp. in Berkeley patented polymerase chain reaction. PCR
turns small amounts of DNA into large amounts of DNA. The process
involves adding an enzyme to DNA, heating the mixture, then cooling
it, again and again, doubling the amount of DNA present with each
heating and cooling cycle.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the subsequent discovery _ and patenting _ of Taq
that made it easy to automate PCR. The first enzymes used during
PCR were degraded by rising temperatures. Someone had to stand
around to add a pinch of enzyme between each cycle during the four
hour process.
</P>
<P>
   Taq could take the heat. After Cetus patented this enzyme in
1989, PCR machines became common. Scientists could throw a dash of
Taq into a test tube with some DNA, put the tube in a PCR machine,
and walk away while the machine went through its cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made PCR faster and more practical for a whole host of
applications,'' said Thomas White, senior vice president of Roche
Molecular. Roche entered the picture in 1991, when it purchased
Cetus's &LR;  patents for PCR and Taq. Roche has licensed these patents
to some 27 vendors who supply the market for DNA test equipment and
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   But Promega, relying on a contract signed with Cetus in 1990,
has refused to bow to Roche's licensing terms, and since 1992 they
each have spent millions to argue their conflicting claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Promega) act as if they're carrying on this crusade,''
said Roche Molecular's President Kathy Ordo &LR; n &LR; ez, making quote
marks in the air. Ordo &LR; n &LR; ez said Roche has used some of the profits
from Taq sales to create new types of DNA tests like one that
measures HIV virus in the bloodstream, which has opened up new
types of treatment. She characterized Promega's conduct as
``piracy,'' which undercuts such advances.
</P>
<P>
   Promega, which says it was selling Taq before Cetus got its
patent, says it was first bullied by Cetus, and now by Roche, and
isn't going to take it anymore. It has used the case to attack the
validity of the Taq patent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think their patent was fraudulently obtained, and so far
the judge seems to agree with us,'' said Promega President Bill
Litton, who was cheered by a preliminary decision in December
invalidating one of Roche's patents.
</P>
<P>
   Roche and Promega were in San Francisco last week as their case
winds slowly through the legal sausage grinder.
</P>
<P>
   More important than the eventual decision on Taq is the warning
this case should send up about the mass of patents being filed on
human genes. At least 10,000 are stacked up in the patent office,
with more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech observers realize that many of these patents will have
conflicting claims. Someone will use this enzyme to identify that
gene, while someone else uses a different chemical, leading to
potential conflicts over primacy of discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these conflicts will land in the lap of some federal
judge, who will then spend years sifting through legal arguments
and expert testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The imminent completion of the human genome map has been
heralded as the next fundamental advance in medical knowledge. And
that it may eventually be. But as the Taq case illustrates, in the
rush to patent genes we could be stirring up a legal cauldron of
double, double, toil and trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Resurrection: &LR;  Fourteen months ago, I wrote about
Neurobiological Technologies Inc., a biotech firm in Richmond that
was trying desperately to raise enough cash to carry on clinical
trials of a pain-killing drug called Memantine.
</P>
<P>
   The drug showed some promise of relieving the unbearable nerve
tinglings associated with extreme forms of diabetes. It was also
being eyed as a possible pain reliever for nervous system disorders
associated with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Now NTI is beginning to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
CEO Paul Freiman recently announced that the company had achieved
positive results for a Phase II clinical trial of Memantine. In
November, it bolstered its short-term cash position with a $4.2
million private placement.
</P>
<P>
   NTI was delisted from Nasdaq in 1997 when the company was at its
lowest point, and now trades as an over-the-counter stock. Its
recent efforts, combined with a resurgent biotech stock sector,
have allowed its shares to surge from $1 in September to $5.38,
although it was off 25 cents on Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging as it sounds, Freiman has a big challenge ahead. He
must find a drug company willing to fund a Phase III study, costing
on the order of $10 million, in return for a license to market a
diabetes pain reliever with a market potential of between $150
million and $300 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone in Washington, D.C., Freiman said he's
confident some company will take the bet _ even though a large
percentage of drug candidates fail in the third and final stage of
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big pharmaceutical companies need drugs, and we have a good
candidate,'' said Freiman, adding that his relatively low-cost
trial ``is tip money for a big company.''
</P>
<P>
   Freiman said he's hopeful of announcing a deal by April, when
NTI presents the full data from its study _ so far it has only
released a summary _ before the American Academy of Neurology. Stay
tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send your biofeedback to Tom Abate by e-mail, abate &LR; sfgate.com, fax
(415) 543-2482, or phone (415) 777-6213. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
