<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1205 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PIRATES-MOVIES-SFCHRO     01-30 1907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRATES-MOVIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE, MUSIC INDUSTRIES TAKE ON DIGITAL DUPES  
  
</HEADLINE>
   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Like the sheriff in an old B-grade Western, Jack Valenti wants to
draw a line in the sand.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The head of the Motion Picture Association of America sees a new
gang of digital outlaws a-ridin' in, bent on pillaging his town _
Hollywood. He doesn't want to allow the same kind of rampant
digital piracy that he says has beset the record industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to file a thousand lawsuits a day, we'll do it,''
said a defiant Valenti. ``It's less expensive than losing control
of all your creative works.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the MPAA and other industry groups have filed several
lawsuits in the past month trying to stop a variety of Web site
operators from spreading the tools that entertainment companies
fear open the door to widespread digital piracy of movies and
music.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other side of the showdown, the so-called outlaws say
they have the law on their side, including the shield of the First
Amendment rights to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   They say the technological advances that let consumers download
digital music, books and eventually top-flight films right from the
Internet to their homes are already bringing a new sheriff to town.
</P>
<P>
   That means the old-guard entertainment industry leaders will
either have to get with the program, or get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about hacking, it's not about copyright infringement,
it's not about piracy,'' said Tom McGuire, vice president of
communication for the Electronic Frontier Foundation of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is evolving at such a fast pace and it is so
empowering to consumers that (consumer-driven technical innovation)
is going to happen. The motion picture business would be better off
embracing what's going on and not villain-izing everybody,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in intellectual property and entertainment say the
motion picture industry's battle against hackers is the latest in a
number of important showdowns over who will control distribution of
traditional consumer entertainment, like music, books and film, in
the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment community is a lot more concerned about
(piracy) because they see their traditional strength _ their
stranglehold on distribution _ evaporating,'' said Eric Doney, a
Marin attorney who has specialized in intellectual property issues
for the software industry since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The MPAA, the DVD Copy Control Association and the Recording
Industry Association of America have been involved in a flurry of
court activity in the past two months that highlight some of the
changing forces at work.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Morgan Hill's DVD Copy Control Association sued 99
hackers and Web site operators for posting the code to a free
software program called De-CSS, which can be used to unlock the
program that scrambles movies recorded on DVDs, or digital
versatile discs.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD association alleged the descrambling code amounted to
theft of its intellectual property, a DVD Content Scrambling
System, or DVD CSS, devised to make it difficult, although not
impossible, to make illegal copies of movies recorded on DVD. The
code was crucial for the DVD industry to convince major film
studios to trust putting their movies in that format.
</P>
<P>
   The De-CSS code was originally posted on the Web in October by
Norwegian teenager Jon Johansen and a group called the Masters of
Reverse Engineering and picked up by thousands of Web sites
worldwide. Norwegian authorities last week raided the 16-year-old
Johansen's home and confiscated his personal computers, some disks
and a mobile phone, according to press reports from Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The De-CSS code, the author of which is still unknown, allows
users of the Linux computer operating system to play back DVDs on
their machines. Linux supporters say they had no choice but to hack
because the DVD industry has only licensed devices that play back
DVDs on machines using Windows or Macintosh operating systems, but
refuse to support alternatives like Linux because the market is
still too small.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown continues, as the DVD Copy Control Association said
its code is available for license to anyone wishing to produce a
Linux DVD player, but no one has applied. The MPAA, meanwhile,
contends that no matter what, the hackers simply broke the law when
they broke the code.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire, whose online civil liberties group has stepped in to
help fight the suits, said the 1998 federal Digital Millennium
Copyright Act, which allows programmers to legally reverse engineer
software to make them more useful, allows the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a single example of anyone doing anything remotely
like piracy here,'' McGuire said.
</P>
<P>
   And he said posting the code on the Web was no different than
writing and posting a good poem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fundamental component of the way open systems
software is created, designed and improved. If this kind of
activity had been made illegal, Linux might not be around today,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   On January 21, Santa Clara County Judge William J. Elfving
issued a preliminary injunction of 21 defendants named in the suit
to stop posting the De-CSS code.
</P>
<P>
   Just a day earlier, a New York judge issued an injunction in a
similar lawsuit the MPAA filed against three Web site operators in
New York and Connecticut who also posted the De-CSS code.
</P>
<P>
   And on the same day, the MPAA joined the four major U.S. TV
broadcast networks and two professional sports leagues in a suit to
block a Canadian Web site, iCraveTV.com, from retransmitting
over-the-air broadcasts of TV shows and movies through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the record industry, which has been struggling for
two years with the widespread digital copying and distribution of
songs on the Internet spurred by the MP3 revolution, got into the
act.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America filed a copyright
infringement suit in New York against MP3.com. The complaint claims
a new service that allows users to instantly hear music from the
San Diego Web site and add their personal music to a playlist for
others was a copyright infringement, a charge MP3.com refutes.
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA also went to court in December to sue a small San Mateo
online company called Napster, which the group claims ``facilitates
music piracy'' by allowing millions of people to share and swap
digital songs with each other over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are already huge for the worldwide recording
industry, which claims counterfeit CDs and illegally downloaded
songs cost them $4.5 billion each year in lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The movie industry doesn't face as immediate a threat from
digital piracy, although it estimates the losses from pirated VHS
movies amount to about $3 billion a year. Valenti said bootleg
copies of first-run films like ``Toy Story II,'' ``Eyes Wide Shut''
and ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace'' were available even before
they were released in theaters. Copies of ``Phantom Menace'' were
on as many as 400 Web sites when the movie first came out last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   For now, there are several barriers to making a DVD copy. For
one thing, a DVD disc holds about 5.2 gigabytes of data, an
impractical amount for most home computer users to copy, and it
would take about 40 hours to download the same data off the
Internet using a 56-Kbps modem.
</P>
<P>
   And the price of a writable DVD disc is still about $50 each,
about twice the cost of buying a prerecorded DVD movie. Consumer
electronic companies Samsung and Panasonic have announced plans to
introduce DVD recorders later this year, but the units will cost at
least $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   But those barriers could fall over time with the increase of
high-speed Internet cable and DSL services and digital satellite
services. The movie industry itself is slowly moving toward the day
when instead of shipping analog film on reels, studios beam
first-run movies digitally to theaters. Experts say this will
inevitably spur some hacker to devise a method of tapping into
those transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti recently told a congressional subcommittee that with
future methods of digital recording and transmission, ``our
ramparts are being breached on all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the outcomes of the current flurry of court
suits will go a long way in shaping consumer entertainment of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But as the recording industry has found with the spread of
MP3-formatted songs, trying to stop every digital bootleg movie or
song on the vast World Wide Web will be virtually impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that they can absolutely control distribution
overstates their solutions,'' said attorney Eric Doney, of Donahue,
Gallagher, Woods &AMP; Wood in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The movie and recording industries instead are taking the path
set by software companies, which fight piracy through a combination
of consumer education and selective enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're educating the public on what is right and what is
wrong,'' Doney said. ``They're combining enforcement as the stick
and the carrot of education, and in general, it's worked.''
</P>
<P>
   And software companies have worked to improve their wares so
that consumers are inclined to buy legitimate software that comes
with support and upgrades, rather than using bootleg copies that
may crash.
</P>
<P>
   Changing consumer perception of copied digital music or movies
may prove more challenging than with software, however. Unlike
copying a VHS tape, the 100th digital copy of a song or movie is
just as good as the original, and there are no support issues.
``They've got to do something to make their original product
something that's not easily matched on the outside'' in pirated
versions, Doney said.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Garon, a professor of entertainment law at the Western State
University College of Law in Fullerton, said the movie industry is
using digital piracy as ``a rallying cry'' that is more show than
substance. But he said the industry needs to start embracing the
technology soon or get left behind in the stampede.
</P>
<P>
   The major record labels are already moving quickly to control
Internet music distribution. The biggest example is the recent
merger agreement between record giant EMI and Time Warner, which
itself is merging with Internet powerhouse America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the majority of the studios recognize where the
industry could head,'' Garon said.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs the studios are waking up. This month,
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer and Blockbuster agreed to develop and test a
way to make MGM's movies available for download into homes via
Blockbuster's Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Lea Porteneuve, MGM's corporate communications director, said
the two companies have not figured how to make digital movie
downloading work, but ``the great hope is that we have something to
show by year's end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the entertainment industry will ever be able
to get their arms around piracy completely,'' Porteneuve said.
``It's the same with films and video and any other forms of
entertainment products; it's always been the subject of piracy.
It's a matter of us doing our best to circumvent that piracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti said he's not opposed to the coming new digital world.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we're going to have films borne by some digital
delivery system, like the Internet or cable or satellite, it has to
be protected from those who would steal it,'' he said. ``That's a
simple declaration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
