<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EGYPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK VISITS EGYPT'S LEADER TO GIVE PEACE EFFORT A PUSH
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel held three
hours of talks here Sunday with President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt in
an effort to re-energize Middle East peace efforts on several
fronts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders gave few details about their discussion, but
Barak said he remained hopeful that the stalled negotiations with
Syria would soon resume and that new talks with the Palestinians,
which began Sunday, would bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiators settled in for what was described by
both sides as serious and intensive talks at an undisclosed
location in Jerusalem aimed at bridging the wide gulf on difficult
issues like refugees, the status of Jerusalem and the contours of a
possible Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had set Feb. 13 as a deadline for achieving at least a
framework agreement on the outstanding issues, with a further aim
of reaching a full-fledged treaty with the Palestinians by
September.
</P>
<P>
   The reopening of talks has been attended by a flurry of
diplomatic activity. In addition to Barak's visit to Egypt,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met with Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, and with Amr Moussa, Egypt's foreign minister,
at the site of the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, commenting in Davos on the sputtering Middle East
negotiations, optimistically compared them to an Alpine walk in
winter. ``It's a lot like walking across the path here and slipping
occasionally, then getting back on track, or moving from summit to
summit through valleys and basically trudging along through snow
and ice and trying to get to an end,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moussa soon left for Moscow, where another offshoot of Middle
East negotiations, a round of multilateral talks between Israel and
Arab countries, is set to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Among the officials attending will be the Saudi foreign
minister, Prince Saud al-Faisal, representing the Arab countries on
the Persian Gulf, and the foreign ministers of Israel, Jordan,
Canada and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions will cover regional issues like water, trade and
security. Syria and Lebanon have boycotted the multilateral talks
since the Madrid peace conference on the Middle East in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   On another diplomatic front, Dennis Ross, President Clinton's
envoy to the Middle East, is expected in Israel on Wednesday. Barak
is also set to meet with Arafat on Thursday or Friday and said in
Cairo that he would go to Jordan next week to meet with King
Abdullah II.
</P>
<P>
   The missing link in the newly intensified peace effort is Syria,
which resumed talks with Israel in December after a break of nearly
four years. After a second round of negotiations in the United
States in mid-January, the talks again broke off.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian officials have said they want Barak to commit Israel to a
full withdrawal from the Golan Heights as the starting point of
talks, before discussions about security arrangements, opening of
normal relations and sharing of water. In remarks to reporters
after his meeting with Mubarak, Barak repeated his position that
talks should proceed without preconditions. But he added, ``We
respect the Syrians, their dignity, their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been criticized at home for taking on too much
at once by trying to negotiate simultaneously with the Syrians and
the Palestinians, the Israeli prime minister said he could handle
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we can, and should, move forward without trying
to play each track against the other,'' he said. ``If we try to do
it, at first it seems to be tempting, but it will end up with loss
of trust on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has long played a role as facilitator, message carrier,
adviser and booster in the often rocky relations between Israel and
other Arab countries. Mubarak said Sunday that he would continue to
act as a kind of consultant to the parties.
</P>
<P>
   He made a surprise visit to Syria last week to meet with
President Hafez Assad and has taken the lead among Arab countries
in pressing Israel to open its nuclear arms program to
international inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's nuclear weapons capacity, long a subject that Israeli
leaders have refused to discuss or even acknowledge, is one of the
topics that the Arab foreign ministers have said they want to talk
about in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak also dismissed suggestions that Barak would be hampered
by the controversy in Israel over allegations of illegal
contributions to his election campaign last year. The controversy,
Mubarak said, is an internal matter for Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
