<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-N.H.-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP     01-30 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.H.-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-ART-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY QUESTIONS BUDDHIST TEMPLE DONATIONS AND GORE COMPLAINS OF
ATTACKS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER with ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley said Sunday that Vice
President Al Gore would lose the general election unless he offered
a better explanation for attending a fund-raiser at a Buddhist
temple four years ago, but minutes later Gore assailed Bradley for
``divisive, manipulative attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The harsh words Sunday were the latest in a series of
back-and-forth attacks between the two Democratic presidential
candidates, who had spent the past few days arguing over who was a
more reliable defender of abortion rights. At a rally Sunday in
Somersworth, Gore said that when his rival attacked him over old
anti-abortion votes he was dividing the abortion rights forces
``for the sake of his own political tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   And about Bradley's campaign finance attack, Gore asked, ``Why
did Senator Bradley raise this issue to divide Democrats, which
only helps Republicans, who are the true impediments to campaign
finance reform?''
</P>
<P>
   Before he spoke, Gore's supporters passed out copies of a
statement by the minority leaders in Congress, Sen. Tom Daschle of
South Dakota and Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge that Senator Bradley's campaign remain focused on the
issues,'' the statement said, ``and that he abandon negative,
personal attacks that do not bring credit to this nomination
contest or to the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   With almost every public poll showing him trailing by a
substantial margin, Bradley escalated his attacks to their toughest
level yet by questioning Gore's electability, an explosive issue
that until now Bradley has left to his followers.
</P>
<P>
   The issue troubles Democrats because of the ammunition it will
provide to the Republicans if the vice president is nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has been pressed by his followers to open up on Gore's
greatest vulnerability, his 1996 appearance at a Buddhist temple
where campaign cash was raised. But he has been reluctant to do so,
instead raising the issue incrementally.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, for example, he said that Gore should ``face up
to his disgraceful behavior.'' He also said that unless the
Democrats cleaned up their own house, the Republicans would do it
for them. He repeated that remark here Sunday, and in an interview
this morning on the ABC News program, ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Bradley cited an article in the latest issue of
Fortune magazine saying that Gore must have known that money was
being raised at a Buddhist temple where he appeared in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said he only learned of the fund raising after the
fact, a statement widely doubted by critics of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago when Bradley was asked in a television interview
what he thought of the 1996 Democratic fund raising, he praised
Gore for saying he had learned lessons from the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley continued: ``In Al's case, the attorney general
investigated it fully and determined that an independent counsel
was not needed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday the senator told several hundred supporters gathered
at Franklin Pierce College, an institution named for the only
native of New Hampshire ever to become president: ``Here is the
latest article in Fortune magazine about Al Gore and the year 1996,
relevant to the fund-raising issue. Quite frankly, I think there is
more explanation that is needed, that this article raises, about
his participation. And I believe that unless that explanation is
forthcoming, that the public will reject a candidacy in the fall
that fails to come to terms with this circumstance in our
Democratic Party in 1996. Just as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore speech, given in a horse barn in Somersworth, had been
planned before Bradley's latest attack over fund raising, but was
adjusted to account for his comment on ``This Week'' and his
stronger remarks in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   At first Gore spoke stiffly from notes, but he got hotter as he
went on and the crowd booed mentions of Bradley's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now clear that Senator Bradley is looking for a different
kind of fight,'' Gore said. ``In the closing day of the New
Hampshire primary, Senator Bradley has suddenly changed. Instead of
the promised character, courage and commitment, we have
manipulative attack after manipulative attack.'' Boos followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley is now stepping down, unfortunately, to the
level of personal vilification, challenging the integrity of those
who disagree with him,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Bradley of inventing differences between them ``where
there are none.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proudly pro-choice and he knows it,'' Gore continued.
``He knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore accused Bradley of running a divisive campaign ``because he
cannot answer real questions from real people about the very real
problems we face.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Then Gore attacked Bradley's health care proposal, saying the
average $150 a month Bradley's health care plan proposed ``leaves
people with disabilities, the elderly in nursing homes, people with
AIDS, the 40 million Americans who depend on Medicaid out in the
cold.''
</P>
<P>
   He complained that Bradley had no program on education. ``He
doesn't rebuild one crumbling school,'' Gore said. ``He doesn't
have one idea to turn around failing schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, ``He cannot defend his own proposals, so he's
committing foul after foul, and I believe that on Tuesday, the
likelihood is that the voters are going to blow the whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   When the speech was over, two Bradley supporters, Sen. Bob
Kerrey of Nebraska and Rep. Jerrold Nadler of New York, turned up
to criticize Gore. Then Gore supporters arrived and started trying
to drown them out, chanting ``stay and fight'' and ``airball.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Bradley has been arguing that because Gore was not telling
the truth in his campaign, he could not be trusted as president, a
reporter asked Kerrey if he considered the vice president
trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey replied, ``I personally think he's trustworthy. Yes. But
I'm just one voter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
