<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAUER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAUER GAINS SOMETHING OTHER THAN VOTES ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Gary Bauer was in his hotel lobby taking
questions from a handful of reporters when Steve Forbes blew by,
trailed by stampeding cameramen and the two guys in pink pig suits
who accompany him everywhere, waving signs that say, ``Cut pork!''
and ``Tax meat!''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly knocking over his fellow candidate's wife, Carol Bauer,
Forbes paused: ``Oh! Sorry,'' he said, patting her back. ``Nice to
see you, Steve,'' she called after him, as he and the crowd charged
on.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing badly in the polls, Bauer had only one reporter
traveling with him Sunday and, without conceding anything, was
already showing a sense of humor about his chances. Asked what he
would do if he lost, he laughed and said: ``What? A blow right to
the solar plexus! Well, in the unlikely event that I don't get the
nomination ...''
</P>
<P>
   But Bauer, the conservative head of the Family Research Council,
would not walk away empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   He has had an enormous amount of face time with the
front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush, who he proudly says has been
cribbing some of his lines on abortion. With jokes, candor and some
unexpected positions _ a focus on racial reconciliation, which he
mentions in nearly every speech, and support for a ban on soft
money _ he has also made a surprising number of friends in the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not enough to put him up there with Sen. John McCain, but
quite a coup nonetheless for one of the country's leading
anti-abortion and anti-gay rights lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Making friends with reporters ``has been one of the nicest parts
of this,'' Bauer said. ``Conservatives too often adopt an
adversarial attitude with the media. And previously there was a
tendency to put me more in a box.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, a campaign aide even fretted about a reporter's decision to
tag along on a Sunday, when the schedule was heavy on church
meetings, ``a stereotype Gary has worked hard to get away from.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also had a humanizing scandalette this fall, when an aide
who later went to work for Forbes made a fuss over the fact that he
sometimes spent time behind closed doors consulting with a much
younger female aide. He responded by turning the matter into a
feminist issue, asking how women who cannot meet privately with
their bosses could ever hope to get ahead.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he rode in the van with three top female aides: the
same young woman whose closed-door advice caused the stir; his
wife, Carol, who was sharing hand lotion with the aide; and his
daughter, Elyse, who an aide noted is as important to the Bauer
campaign as Karenna Gore Schiff is to her father's operation.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bauer mused that his campaign should have used the
slogan ``Beep for Bauer'' on signs instead of letting Bill Bradley
get ``Beep for Bradley,'' she did weigh in: ``That's not that
original,'' she said, with proper daughterly disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggest that women see a softer side in Bauer. He
is the only Republican, in fact, who does better with women than
men.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning speech to a Republican audience, Bauer was
approached by a couple who described themselves as liberal
Democrats but could not stop praising him. ``It makes me proud
there's someone like you in politics,'' said Julie Schoenfeld of
Boulder, Colo., who said she did not agree with Bauer on any of the
issues but admired him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So, after all these years, has Gary Bauer gone mainstream? He
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always mainstream,'' he said. ``You guys just figured it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the exception of McCain, no other candidate seems to
be enjoying himself more. Bauer seems genuinely moved ``that the
son of a janitor can run for president along with the son of a
president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish you could make a living doing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, appearing at a pregnancy counseling center, Bauer held a
baby in front of the center and said it was important to remember
that the work done here, talking young women out of abortions, was
not theoretical. In his soft-spoken way, he also denounced same-sex
marriage, and a girl holding a big Bauer sign yelled, ``That's
cool!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some social conservatives have indicated they like to
see some righteous anger in their candidate, more along the lines
of the perpetually churning Alan Keyes, who bested Bauer in last
week's Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to his hotel at the end of the day, Bauer suggested
that after this campaign, he may be in a rather enviable position
to push his issues, even if conservative voters end up favoring the
louder Keyes and the richer Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going away,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
