<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WIRESERVICES-INTERNET     01-30 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRESERVICES-INTERNET-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A.P. TO DISTRIBUTE ONLINE SITE'S NEWS REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Associated Press, a news service whose journalism
has been a staple of American newspapers for 151 years, plans this
week to begin distributing the work of Cnet News.com, a
four-year-old Internet site, as part of The A.P.'s overall offering
of financial news, according to executives of both news services.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Cnet, which ich specializes in coverage of the
Internet and related industries, is The A.P.'s first with a
nontraditional news organization and provides another validation of
Internet journalism _ a genre sometimes associated with gossip and
scandal-mongering.
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, The Associated Press would take 5 to 10
of Cnet's articles daily, edit them and distribute them on The A.P.
financial news wire, whose 300 clients include most American
newspapers with circulations over 100,000. In exchange, Cnet
News.com (www.news.com) would get access to The A.P.'s online
service, a distillation of its national, international, sports and
entertainment services.
</P>
<P>
   Like the arrangement made a year ago to link CBS News and the
online financial news site MarketWatch.com, The Associated Press'
deal with Cnet represents a major news organization's desire to
compete more aggressively in the new media world. It is a world
well understood by Cnet News.com, which was born to sell itself
online.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a world that the Reuters news service, The A.P.'s
chief rival, has set out to conquer. In 1998, 55 percent of the $63
million revenue that Reuters earned in the Americas came from
online sites like Yahoo, Excite(AT)Home and Walt Disney's Go.com.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Crooke, a spokesman for Reuters, which is owned by the
Reuters Group, said last week that of the 250 online sites that buy
the Reuters service, 20 percent were owned by traditional newspaper
and broadcast companies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for The A.P. said on Friday that the service did
not disclose the number of customers it has on the World Wide Web
or the revenue derived from Web sales.
</P>
<P>
   Internet audiences, analysts say, tend to be eager consumers of
financial news, particularly news about the Internet. The A.P.
executives said that enhancing their financial reporting with the
coverage of Cnet's 45 journalists _who specialize in new products
and deals _ would enhance the content of the Associated Press
members' Web sites. It may also fatten the news service's bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Cnet's first deal with a traditional media
organization: it provides news to the online edition of The New
York Times, for example. But The A.P.'s reach _ it has 1,549 daily
papers among its members, of which about 900 have Web sites _ will
ensure dissemination of Cnet's articles to millions of readers
largely unfamiliar with its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unprecedented that an online-only news
organization would partner with a 150-year-old entity,'' said Jai
Singh, the editor of Cnet News.com, who began his career in the
mid-1970s at a chain of suburban newspapers outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, which is organized as a cooperative, has
made one similar arrangement to use the journalism of a news
organization outside that framework. In 1994, facing pressure from
the then-upstart financial news service of Bloomberg L.P., The A.P.
arranged to repackage substantial material from the Dow Jones wire
as part of The A.P.'s financial news wire _ an arrangement that
continues.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jon Wolman, The Associated Press' managing editor,
the new Cnet deal is ``an evolution'' of the thinking that led to
the Dow Jones deal. ``News presentation is changing and news
services are popping up; Cnet is a great example,'' he said. ``We
want to present our members with a great variety, and we want to
respond to the explosion of interest in Internet and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   That interest in technology and financial news is palpable on
the Internet, with growing audiences viewing news sites like
CNNfn.com, CNBC.com, MarketWatch.com _ in which CBS now has a stake
_ and TheStreet.com, in which The New York Times Co. owns a stake
and with which The Times operates a joint financial news service.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the national and international news that
Reuters and The A.P. provide is now so ubiquitous that its use
affords a Web site little competitive advantage in gaining an
audience. There is greater demand for news that is unique _ often
local news _ and news that is specialized and timely.
</P>
<P>
   While local news has long been an A.P. specialty, the wire
service could not devote anything close to the 45 reporters that
Cnet News.com has covering technology and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While Reuters is part of a diversified company _ media revenue
represented about 5 percent of total revenue in 1998 _ The A.P. is
a cooperative that answers to its members. It is controlled by a
governing board made up of top executives from major newspaper
companies and gets constant feedback from groups like the
Associated Press Managing Editors' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Under this cooperative arrangement, the members of The A.P. _
newspapers or broadcasters _ pay a fee, based on the size of their
audiences or circulations, for a variety of services that include
national, international, sports and entertainment news. Much of the
material is generated by The Associated Press' own corps of 3,500
editorial and technical employees, working from 240 bureaus in
state capitals and other American cities, financial centers and key
international sites.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While The A.P. has rapidly expanded into new areas, investing
millions of dollars in technological improvements and video and
audio news operations, many of its members still retain the same
kind of conservatism that caused their predecessors to balk at
selling the news service to radio broadcasters 70 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of close scrutiny from A.P. members, the service's
executives have tended to be conservative about what news they
distribute, and to whom. Jim Kennedy, The A.P.'s director of
multimedia services, said that when he first proposed the Cnet
arrangement, ``there was some queasiness in The A.P. about it; some
people didn't know who Cnet was.''
</P>
<P>
   Members, Wolman said, are likely to have similar qualms.
``Everyone is going to want to see it to believe it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wick Temple, The Associated Press' vice president and director
of newspaper membership, said that ``some members think A.P. should
serve only traditional customers.'' The biggest concern about
selling news to online competitors, Temple said, is that such
features will help online rivals lure away the high-margin
classified advertising that accounts for one-third to one-half of
the revenue of most newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   When Singh started Cnet News.com in 1996, he said, he came to
The A.P. as a potential customer, looking to buy one of its general
news products. ``I went to A.P. and said, `I would like to get your
service.' They said, `Get lost; we don't provide news to just
anybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   But, Singh added, that kind of skepticism evaporated. ``The
lucky thing for us,'' he said, ``has been that from the get-go we
have been able to prove, on a daily basis, that we do credible
journalism.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
