<HEADLINE>
ON MORNING NEWS CIRCUIT, A DIFFERENT SUPER SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.H., S.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Company was coming and Laurie Luhn could not
believe the mess her colleagues were making of the green room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we pick up all the little trash?'' she asked, sounding a
tad frazzled as she surveyed the cramped chamber that was to hold
Gov. George W. Bush and his entourage before his appearance Sunday
on ``Fox News Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Snow and Paula Zahn, the Fox News personalities, grabbed
some of the empty cups and plates and cleared out. ``Laurie, be
calm,'' Brit Hume said to Ms. Luhn, the segment producer, who was
doing double duty as Fox's emissary to the Bush campaign for the
morning. ``All the trash will be picked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hume, Fox's Washington managing editor and a veteran political
reporter, could be forgiven for affecting a certain blase air. But
in truth, Bush's agreement to appear on ``Fox News Sunday'' on the
weekend before the New Hampshire primary was cause for some
jitters. It was, after all, a minicoup for the three-year-old news
program, perhaps the least well established in the competitive
battleground of Sunday morning punditcasts.
</P>
<P>
   All five of the major Sunday talkfests decamped for New
Hampshire this weekend, eager to stock their shows with
presidential timber. Sen. John McCain signed on with ``Meet the
Press'' on NBC; Bill Bradley assumed the hot seat on ``This Week''
on ABC; McCain and Alan Keyes were guests on ``Late Edition'' on
CNN; and Bush, after appearing on Fox, moved on to ``Face the
Nation'' on CBS. Vice President Al Gore did not appear on any of
the programs.
</P>
<P>
   The ritual grilling of the candidates takes on a kind of tense
pageantry on a pivotal weekend like this one. The questioners and
questioned understand, Hume said, that they are all participating
in something a bit more rarefied than a conversation at a groggy
hour of the morning. ``This is not an interview in the usual sense
_ it's an event,'' Hume said. ``There are certain customs that are
observed on Sunday mornings. You're expected to seek to make news.
There's a certain formality to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hour before the broadcast, the panelists gathered in the
offices of WMUR-TV, Fox's headquarters for the primary, to figure
out what line of inquiry might make Bush blink. ``He's been so
controlled,'' Snow, the program's host, said. ``My strategy is to
loosen him up a bit. I want to try as best as I can to get him off
his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, no one on the panel held out much hope of a scoop.
``You have to figure out a new question, otherwise, he's got these
stock answers,'' observed Morton Kondracke, executive editor of
Roll Call, a Capitol Hill newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Barnes, executive editor of The Weekly Standard, was
positively mopey. ``I'd rather have on Karl Rove than `W.,''' he
said, referring to the governor's chief strategist.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush and his team strolled in minutes later, however,
cynicism retreated. The governor seemed energized and his upbeat
air was infectious. ``Hey, there they are, the big shots!'' Bush
declared. His makeup applied, the candidate lingered in the hallway
outside the green room, clutching an extra large container of
coffee. It was clear that he viewed the interview circuit more as
required basic training than as a chance to mix it up with
inside-the-Beltway types. ``It's part of what candidates have to
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has seemed a bit looser in debates of late; he says he gets
a lot of unsolicited suggestions about how to improve his
television image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a very calculating person,'' he said. ``I haven't had
any coaches. I'm trying not to be theatrical.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the hourlong program was devoted to Bush, who was
pressed on everything from his view on flying the Confederate flag
over the South Carolina Statehouse (it's up to South Carolina, he
said again) to a list of his favorite bands (the Neville Brothers
and Van Morrison). When it was over, the panel judged it one of his
more engaged, persuasive performances.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ms. Zahn said she had figured out why: ``I went over
to him and asked, `You get any sleep last night?' and he said,
`Nine hours.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
