<SLUG> BC-N.H.-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN TURNS UP THE HEAT A NOTCH ON BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, N.H. _ It was almost like a sentimental homecoming as
Sen. John McCain held his 114th and last New Hampshire town hall
meeting Sunday in the building where six months ago he had to give
out free ice cream to draw 40 people.
</P>
<P>
   This time more than 1,000 people packed the Peterborough Town
Hall, cheering, chanting and giving McCain a standing ovation as an
announcer boomed, ``Please welcome the next president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What was supposed to be a coronation, which we thought we got
rid of in 1776, is going to be an election on Tuesday,'' said
former Sen. Warren Rudman of New Hampshire as the audience screamed
its agreement that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was getting a run
for his money. Rudman called on the crowd to ``turn out in droves
and send a message to the world on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's main opponents, Bush and Steve Forbes, also appeared at
enthusiastic rallies with hundreds of supporters. Although Bush
stuck to his standard stump speech, Forbes mounted a blistering
attack on the governor, complaining about what he called the
``wishy-washiness'' of Bush's $483 billion tax-cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Forbes cited comments Bush had made about the tax
proposal in an interview on the television program ``Fox News
Sunday.'' Bush had said he hoped to accomplish the tax cut in his
first term. To that, Forbes said: ``When it comes to taxes, on
certain basic principles, you don't just hope. You've got to have
somebody who's going to fight for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance here Sunday, McCain pulled out all the stops.
He gave his microphone to an anti-tax protester dressed as a shark.
He drew cheers when he pointed out reporters to the audience and
joked that they had ``all agreed to be here afterward to explain
the liberal commie bias of the media to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by a man who wanted to legalize hemp, he taunted,
``Good luck with your crop.'' Questioned about the danger of
dictators like Saddam Hussein, he said, ``I hope that Fidel Castro
has a chance to meet Karl Marx.'' That drew hisses.
</P>
<P>
   He attacked Al Gore for campaign finance abuses of 1996 and
Gore's statement, when it was disclosed that he had used a White
House phone for fund-raising, that there was ``no controlling legal
authority.'' He acted out how he would tell Gore in a debate,
``Well, I'm going to give you a legal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   And he criticized Bush for supporting the current campaign
finance system. ``My friends, Gov. Bush says that campaign finance
reform will hurt our party,'' he said. ``I have throughout my
entire life had one fundamental belief: that what is good for our
country is good for our party.'' The crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   He also continued to raise questions indirectly about Bush's
ability to step into the role of commander in chief. ``I am fully
prepared to lead,'' McCain said. ``I do not need on-the-job
training.''
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's New Hampshire primary crucial to his insurgent
campaign, McCain then journeyed to a packed VFW hall here to call
on the veterans who have rallied to his side to get out the vote
against the party establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started our battle with the privates, the seamen and the
chief petty officers,'' he said. ``They can have the generals and
the admirals.'' He implored, ``I need you again to go on a
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday on ``Face the Nation,'' Bush was asked
about McCain's suggestions that he was not ready to assume the
presidency. Bush first pointed to his experience as governor of
Texas, saying, ``I have been in the position of setting agendas, of
making decisions, of putting an administration together and
bringing Republicans and Democrats together to achieve what's been
right for my state.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``A lot of United States senators are asking the same
question _ Republican senators _ saying, which one of the two, Sen.
McCain or Gov. Bush, should we endorse? Who should we help based
upon their leadership skills? And by far the overwhelming majority
of United States senators who are Republicans are supporting me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
