<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-U.S.-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-NORTH KOREA TALKS SET FOR MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ North Korea has agreed to send a high-level delegation
to the United States in March, opening the way for talks on North
Korea's missile program, the spread of nuclear weapons and
terrorism, the U.S. State Department said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on North Korea was made by the State Department
spokesman, James Rubin, who arrived here Sunday morning with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright for three days of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin described the North Korea visit as an ``important step
forward'' in improving the hostile relations between the two
countries. The agreement came at the end of seven days of meetings
in Berlin between the United States and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration hopes that the visit in March will
lead to a permanent agreement under which North Korea would agree
to permanently stop flight tests of its ballistic missiles, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea agreed late last year not to continue these tests
while talks on improvements in relations between the two
governments continued. At the same time, Washington agreed to take
steps to lift some economic sanctions against North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, North Korea fired an intercontinental ballistic
missile. It appeared to be in the final stages of another launch
last fall when the tentative agreement was reached between
Washington and Pyongyang to halt the launches.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of ballistic missiles from North Korea capable of
hitting the United States has been the prime reason behind the
Clinton administration's proposal for the deployment of a limited
national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is scheduled to meet here on Wednesday with the acting
President, Vladimir Putin, and Washington's plans for national
missile defense are high on the agenda. So far, Moscow has been
resistant to the administration's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by the North Koreans in March would provide the ``best
opportunity'' to make progress on issues that are ``central to
peace and stability in Northeast Asia and the Asia-Pacific
region,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea, which is governed by a harsh communist regime, had
been offered no concessions on its designation by the United States
as a sponsor of terrorism, Rubin said. In order to be removed from
that list, North Korea had to meet ``objective criteria.'' It had
so far not done so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Washington's effort to bring North Korea out of its
isolation, a high-level delegation of U.S. officials led by former
Defense Secretary William Perry visited North Korea last March. The
Clinton administration has been trying for many months to persuade
senior North Korean officials to reciprocate with a visit to
Washington.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the Berlin talks, North Korea's vice foreign minister, Kim
Gye Gwan, officially accepted the invitation, although a definite
agenda for the Washington visit still needs to be decided, Rubin
said. The North Koreans have not yet said who will lead their
delegation, but he would be of similar seniority to Perry, who is
President Clinton's special envoy to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation in Berlin was led by Ambassador Charles
Kartman, and Rubin said the two sides ``exchanged views on issues
of common concern in a constructive, businesslike environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
