<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMP-WORKERS-ART-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPORARY WORKERS SEEKING CODE OF CONDUCT FOR JOB AGENCIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.J., N.Y., Calif., Mass. Wis., S.C.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ Meeting once a month at a rundown union hall
here, a dozen temporary workers are trying to ignite a campaign to
win for the nation's 3 million temps the benefits that most
permanent workers take for granted, like health insurance, sick pay
and paid holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey workers, along with nonprofit groups here and in
half a dozen other states, are drafting a voluntary code of conduct
for temp agencies that they say will improve job conditions for the
soaring population of temporary workers _ a segment of the labor
force that has tripled nationwide in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey temps are planning to make a major push this
March, in league with temps in New York, California, Massachusetts
and elsewhere, to promote their code in the hope that most of the
nation's 7,000 temp agencies, including 600 in New Jersey, will
adopt it.
</P>
<P>
   The code calls on agencies to give their lowest-paid workers a
``living wage'' and to provide health insurance, job training, paid
holidays and other benefits. It also opposes a practice they say is
widespread in the industry: bait-and-switch job advertising, in
which agencies give workers jobs worse than those promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to help temp workers because temping is such a
fast-growing phenomenon and because temp workers face so many
injustices,'' said Barrie Peterson, director of the Bergen County
Employment Action Project, the union-backed nonprofit group that is
heading the New Jersey efforts to develop and promote a code. &UR;  &LR; 
``They are paid 70 percent of what people doing comparable
permanent jobs earn,'' he said. ``They rarely receive health
benefits. And you have a lot of temp workers stuck in the same
assignment for years and years. That's a real abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The code's sponsors voiced confidence that they would be able to
persuade dozens of cities and counties, and perhaps a few state
legislatures, to agree to hire only agencies that subscribe to the
code _ a move that they said would pressure many agencies to sign
on.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at many temp agencies have denounced the code as
unnecessary, saying that agencies already know they have to treat
temps well if they are to attract workers when unemployment is so
low. But even these days, many temps say a code of conduct is the
only leverage they have. Forming a union for temporary workers has
proved as hard as herding butterflies, and picketing of abusive
agencies would open the protesters to being blackballed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergen County Employment Action Project and a South Carolina
advocacy group were the first two organizations to create a code of
conduct, and now they are seeking to work with 35 other nonprofit
groups on a model nationwide code.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to encourage agencies to take a high-road approach,''
Peterson said. ``If we can steer workers and companies to agencies
that agree to treat people better, that will presumably create
pressure on all agencies to move in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   So far the Bergen County Employment Action Project is the only
group in the nation to get temp agencies _ 27 so far _ to sign a
code of conduct, and it has sought to reward those agencies by
steering workers their way. In San Jose, Calif., Working
Partnerships, a nonprofit temp agency as well as a support group
for temps, has obtained 500 signatures to petition the county
supervisors to use only agencies that sign the code.
</P>
<P>
   As Wisconsin pushes many welfare recipients into temp jobs,
9to5, the National Association of Working Women, which is based in
Milwaukee, wants the state to use only agencies that have signed
the code. And the Carolina Alliance for Fair Employment is pressing
South Carolina's state government, which employed more than 10,000
temps in 1999, to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to reward the good agencies and penalize the bad
ones,'' said Charles Taylor, co-director of the Carolina Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Temp workers are a heterogeneous group, including $7-an-hour
janitors, $14-an-hour secretaries and $50-an-hour software
designers with Ph.D.'s. Although many Americans choose to temp
because they like a flexible schedule, many temps say they prefer
the security and benefits of a permanent job.
</P>
<P>
   The American Staffing Association, representing the $60
billion-a-year temp industry, has urged employers not to sign the
new code, contending that it is a union-backed plot to make the
industry look bad, raise its costs and drive temps into unions.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at many agencies assert that they already comply with
most of the code's provisions, like treating workers with respect
and not discriminating by race or sex. They say that other code
provisions, like health insurance and a so-called living wage, are
too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the things these people say agencies should do, we're
already doing,'' said Barry Franzino, president of Career Center
Inc., an agency in Hackensack.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``These are our employees, and we take good care of them,'' he
added. ``The labor market is very tight right now, and that makes
it imperative for us to do everything to make sure our workers are
happy, because if we don't, they'll go work elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, complaints of mistreatment abound _ about an
agency's making it hard for injured temps to get workers'
compensation, about a factory's paying female temps $1.12 an hour
less than male temps, about temps' being charged for safety
equipment for jobs held for just one day, about being barred from
consideration for permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen O'Donnell complained that during her three years of
temping in various administrative jobs in northern New Jersey she
had received no health insurance, no vacations, no paid holidays
and no paid sick days.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Vanderbeek, an engineer downsized out of a longtime job,
said that when fears of lengthy commuting made him refuse a temp
job 60 miles away, his agency threatened to deny him unemployment
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   And Joseph Beattie, who worked 20 years as a corporate credit
manager before downsizing hit, said he was angry that his temp
agency refused to give him leads about permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a caste system,'' Beattie said. ``And we're the goose
that lays the golden egg for these agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lab Support, an agency with an office in Elmwood Park, N.J.,
that specializes in placing scientific personnel, has signed the
New Jersey code, concluding that it is easily acceptable because
the agency already provides vacation pay, paid sick days, a 401(k)
retirement plan and health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Lab Support pays most of the health insurance premiums. By
contrast, many agencies that boast about offering health coverage
require temps to pay far more than half the premiums, often
amounting to $3,000 or more per year, something many temps cannot
afford.
</P>
<P>
   But many agencies are unenthusiastic or hostile toward the code.
Alan Baker, owner of Horizon Personnel in Parsippany, N.J., signed
the New Jersey code, but said he was less happy about the national
model. Unlike the New Jersey one, the national code calls for
paying a living wage and providing transportation when there are no
buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I provide paid holidays, but I don't provide sick days or
health benefits,'' Baker said. ``It would make my administrative
costs go up and would make my clients' costs go sky high.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the living wage is particularly divisive. Some
supporters of the code say that means paying $11 or more an hour,
while many agencies say client companies are unwilling to pay more
than $8 an hour for janitorial or clerical work.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Joerres, chief executive at Manpower Inc., the nation's
largest temp agency, said his company already satisfied most of the
code's provisions, but he still harbored serious reservations about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Agency executives say the campaign will give the industry a
black eye. But Ellen Bravo, co-director of 9to5, said, ``Some
people say they don't want the code calling negative attention to
the industry. It's negative practices, not a code, that call
negative attention to the industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
