<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-CANADIENS-MCCLEAR     01-30 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CANADIENS-MCCLEARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYER HIT BY PUCK IN THROAT SENDS NOTE OF RECOVERY TO CANADIENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Montreal Canadiens forward Trent McCleary was
seconds from death after being hit in the throat by a puck Saturday
afternoon, the team's surgeon said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But now the worst is almost certainly over for McCleary, the
surgeon, David Mulder, said at a hushed news conference Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   McCleary remained in critical condition at Montreal General
Hospital, breathing with the aid of a respirator. But his condition
was no longer life-threatening, Mulder said. McCleary was able to
write an inspirational message to his teammates before their 3-0
victory Sunday afternoon over the Carolina Hurricanes. The news
that McCleary was out of danger was greeted with a loud ovation
from the Molson Center crowd of 19,380.
</P>
<P>
   McCleary's message, delivered by General Manager Rejean Houle to
the Canadiens' dressing room, read: ``Doing great everybody. Here's
$500 on the board for the win. Battle hard. I'll be listening. Go
Habs! Trent. (NU)6.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal Coach Alain Vigneault said the players and coaches
would visit McCleary before they left for Florida on Monday.
Vigneault also said team doctors had briefed the Canadiens on
McCleary's condition before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That took a lot of pressure off of the game,'' Canadiens wing
Benoit Brunet said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, McCleary, a little-used 27-year-old, had gone down
to block the slap shot of Philadelphia Flyers defenseman Chris
Therien during a 2-2 tie at the Molson Center. The puck, which was
shot at the left point from 8 to 10 feet away, hit McCleary
squarely in the throat and fractured his larynx.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to get to his feet and nearly made his way off the
ice on his own. But he could not breathe and his legs gave out just
after he left the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder, who performed an emergency tracheotomy on McCleary
within a half-hour of the accident, said McCleary nearly died on
the way to the operating room. The only player to die from an
injury in an N.H.L. game was the Minnesota North Stars' Bill
Masterton, whose head hit the ice in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how close McCleary had come to dying, Mulder said,
``It's about as close as I think you could come.''
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, McCleary also suffered a collapsed right
lung, which caused his heart to shift to the right side of his
body, Mulder said. ``And that can be just as life-threatening as
the airway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But after observing McCleary's condition through a night in
intensive care, Mulder was optimistic about McCleary's prognosis.
Mulder said McCleary's ability to breathe was the most important
consideration over the next 24 hours, but he thought it was under
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent is still in intensive care,'' Mulder said. ``But in
terms of danger to his life, he went though that last night and his
life is not in danger at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   That represented substantial progress. Mulder and Daniel
Fleiszer, the head trauma surgeon at Montreal General, performed a
tracheotomy, which involved cutting a hole in McCleary's windpipe
and inserting a tube.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder, who said McCleary was conscious until the operation,
described what McCleary went through on the ambulance ride to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like drowning in your own blood,'' said Mulder, who
compared McCleary's injury to what the driver of a car experiences
in a head-on accident when the steering wheel hits him in the
throat.
</P>
<P>
   The tracheotomy was a success, Mulder said, and now it is up to
ear, nose and throat specialists to determine whether McCleary will
have surgery to repair his larynx or whether the doctors will wait
for the extreme swelling to go down in an attempt to let the larynx
heal on its own.
</P>
<P>
   McCleary will remain in the hospital for at least a week, Mulder
said. McCleary, who friends say loves to gab, cannot speak now,
which Mulder said was the thing that most frustrated the Canadiens
player. He will have to undergo voice rehabilitation, which takes a
long time, Mulder said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the resumption of his hockey career, Mulder said: ``It's
too early to predict. At this point, it's not possible to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury was the latest in a series of career-threatening
injuries for McCleary, a journeyman from Swift Current,
Saskatchewan. Five years ago on Super Bowl Sunday, he nearly lost
an eye when he was hit by Boris Mironov's stick in an American
Hockey League game. Earlier this season in an A.H.L. game, McCleary
caught a skate in the eye, severing a tear duct.
</P>
<P>
   McCleary, who was not drafted after playing his junior hockey in
the Western Hockey League, has appeared in parts of four seasons
with Ottawa, Boston and Montreal. In 12 games with the Canadiens
this season, he has one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got all of the shot,'' a shaken Therien said after the game.
``It was like the whole thing, the puck, everything, was in slow
motion. I could hear him breathing. It sounded like something was
stuck in his throat.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury reverberated with players on other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised we don't see that more often,'' Rangers
defenseman Stephane Quintal, a teammate of McCleary's last season
in Montreal, said on Saturday night. ``Thankfully, it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers defenseman Rich Pilon said he had experienced a similar,
though less serious, incident earlier in his career. ``Every time
you go down to block a shot, you're just hoping it gets you in the
right place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' acting captain, Adam Graves, who was cut on the
face when hit by a puck Thursday, said: ``It's a play that happens
20 times a game. It's just scary, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rare light moment at his news conference, Mulder said
surgeons did not have time to do anything but cut open McCleary's
Montreal sweater before the operation began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Trent that this was the first time I ever finished an
operation, looked up and the patient still had his skates on,''
Mulder said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
