<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC'S PREGAME PERFORMANCE IS SHORT, BUT NOT ALWAYS TO THE POINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best analysts always tell you what you can't see. Not
always. Expecting brilliance every time a replay pops up is asking
too much. It can't happen.
</P>
<P>
   But it does not happen often enough with ABC's Boomer Esiason,
an area he must improve upon to reach the level of John Madden,
Phil Simms and Dan Dierdorf. Too often he tells us, in great
detail, precisely what we have just seen.
</P>
<P>
   During Sunday night's Super Bowl, he described a run by
Tennessee quarterback Steve McNair over a replay:
</P>
<P>
   ``They're bringing the blitz, right up the middle,'' he said.
``Nobody's panicking, the offensive line doing its job. Watch Steve
McNair. Poise, poise, poise. He looks downfield, then decides to
take off. Watch him run. He breaks a tackle there, another tackle
there and takes a defensive lineman on.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that is just what we saw.
</P>
<P>
   Or, on a replay of St. Louis offensive lineman Orlando Pace,
Esiason said: ``Pace pushing down a defender. Then, he goes after
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that is what we just saw.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Esiason employed his former quarterbacking skills
to buttress his calls. Watching St. Louis quarterback Kurt Warner
smoothly slice the Titans' defense, he said: ``He goes through his
progressions, he can find his second and third receivers easily.''
Viewers would have been well-served by his use of his experiences
as a Super Bowl quarterback in 1989 to give a better sense of what
first-timers Warner and McNair were experiencing. Esiason is the
only former quarterback ever to analyze a Super Bowl for the ABC
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Al Michaels, as usual, showed he is the best at his craft. He is
three-quarters play-by-play announcer, one-quarter analyst. There's
always something extra, like, ``London Fletcher pushed aside on
that play as if he were made of papier mache.'' Or, adding a light
touch, he said about Warner: ``Here's a guy in the Super Bowl who's
played in two Arena Bowls.'
</P>
<P>
   One of the dangers of having more technical toys at your
disposal is the desire to overuse them. The last few seasons we
have seen football directors cutting to assistant coaches, ad
nauseum, almost without regard to viewers knowing who they are. The
ABC production seemed to isolate the assistants, without isolating
enough players.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, when there wasn't much to say about Mike Martz,
the St.Louis offensive coordinator, Esiason said: ``You've got to
love Mike Martz.'' Perhaps if I were Mrs. Martz the comment would
have been relevant.
</P>
<P>
   What a surprise that the best segment in ABC's four-hour pregame
show was Barbara Walters hosting a special edition of ``The View.''
During six minutes of harmless fun, the Walters crew debated the
significance of football:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all about the butt,'' Meredith Viera said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a bunch of guys jumping around in tights,'' Joy
Behar said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC offered several reasons to sit through the program, which
was shorter by three hours than the full load Fox laid on viewers
last year. But only on occasion did ABC deliver the emotional
impact that it promised.
</P>
<P>
   Like every Super Bowl pregame, there was a lot of filler (did we
really need Emeril Lagasse preparing jambalaya or Chris Berman's
interview with Phil Collins, a halftime performer, who doesn't
understand football, but likes the Super Bowl's ``event and
spectacle''?). But here were some high points:
</P>
<P>
   --Dan and Claire Marino's adoption of an abandoned Chinese girl
_ and her rapid inclusion into a family with four older children _
was a dramatic and moving story, augmented by home video of Claire
Marino's trip to China.
</P>
<P>
   --A profile of Fritz Pollard, a black player-coach in the
National Football League in the 1920s, with an interview by N.F.L.
Films in 1974, illuminated the brilliant life of a little-known
pioneer. But it omitted any details about his post-football life in
finance, journalism and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   --Andrea Kremer's examination of concussions typified her
stellar work. The animation of what happens to the brain during a
concussion was jarring, as was the former Giant linebacker Harry
Carson's admission about extended memory loss from concussions and
the problem it has posed for him in broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   But for everything else, ABC played it safe and probably tried
to do too much. The network focused its too-short player profiles
on usual suspects like McNair and Warner, and the Titans' Jevon
Kearse, and strayed from seeking out unsung or unusual stories. The
strategy is geared to a casual audience that may not know about
Warner's rise from supermarket stock boy to most valuable player,
but it demonstrated a lack of adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously omitted from the program was:
</P>
<P>
   --A sense of the icy, unseasonable weather outside the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   --A feature on the carpetbagging history of Tennessee, a refugee
from Houston and Memphis, and St. Louis, late of Anaheim, Los
Angeles and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The overly busy format of the program did not give Berman and
Steve Young a great amount of time to develop a rapport, or for
Young to flex his nascent analytic muscles. In his usual Sunday
morning ESPN perch, Berman is a ringmaster. In Sunday's format, he
was a subdued supporting player. But as always, in his ABC work,
his hair looked far better than it does on ESPN. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
