<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SHUTTING OUT JOHN MCCAIN, AND NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y., S.C., Fla., Iowa)  (jw) 
 By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why, beyond respecting good government and democracy and all
that, should New Yorkers care whether John McCain can run for
president in their state?
</P>
<P>
   Because politics runs on quid pro quos. On commitments.
Promises. And candidates who don't have to think about New York as
they move out of New Hampshire won't; they can focus on California,
Georgia, Ohio and the other seven states in the Super Tuesday
primaries on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   By locking McCain out of the Republican contest, New York makes
itself pander-proof: why would a candidate bother to woo voters if
he is either out of play or virtually assured of victory because
his party has eliminated the strongest opponent?
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Republican Party's manipulation of New York's
deliberately complicated ballot process _ intended to discourage
insurgents and protect the party's choice _ McCain's name may not
appear on the presidential primary ballot in many New York
districts, while George W. Bush's name will appear everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The party, with the blessing of Gov. George Pataki (a Bush man),
is busy trying to knock the Arizona senator off primary ballots by
raising technical objections to his nominating petitions, and the
McCain camp is fighting back on every legal front. The most
prominent Bush supporter to object to his party's tactics is Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who hasn't got the standing to do more than
complain.
</P>
<P>
   If the courts don't revive McCain, where is the incentive for
the governor of Texas, the presumed front-runner, to promise us
anything? Or, to put it more decorously, to hear about and debate
the city and state's concerns? And if McCain should break through
in New Hampshire tomorrow but remain out of contention here, New
York will fall off the Republican radar screen altogether. (A third
candidate, Steve Forbes, is weak in the polls.)
</P>
<P>
   Urban America gets short shrift from national candidates anyway;
to invite their apathy takes matters to a new level. If there is
any question that candidates would court New York votes if they had
to, look at the goings-on elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, presidential contenders of both major parties fell all
over one another to pledge their allegiance to ethanol subsidies,
even though the corn-rich fuel is costly and inefficient. Only
McCain _ who did not seriously run in Iowa _ denounced the ethanol
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, the Republican candidates, afraid of
offending some white voters, have turned themselves into pretzels
to avoid objecting to the Confederate flag, which flies over the
Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Florida and its strong Cuban-American vote.
Don't be surprised if Elian Gonzalez's fate isn't resolved until
the Florida primary on March 14 is past us.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of politicking may trouble more sensitive readers, but
that's how things work. For New York to pull itself out of play to
keep lawyers busy and gratify the Republican Party establishment is
nothing if not shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
   We know what to do, given the opportunity. Presidential
candidates running in New York have had to focus occasionally on
urban issues in the past. Ronald Reagan and Jimmy Carter famously
visited the burned-out South Bronx (which was rebuilt, not because
of either of them, but their visits put an embarrassing focus on
that emblem of urban neglect).
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Al Gore, Jesse Jackson and others got plenty of
attention _ as well as trouble _ talking about Israel to Jewish
voters. And when Bill Clinton ran for president in 1992, he and his
opponent, Jerry Brown, debated urban problems for 75 minutes at
Gracie Mansion. Imagine.
</P>
<P>
   It is fun to fantasize about what Bush and McCain could be
discussing if they had any reason to show up in New York other than
to raise money or hold news conferences comparing the state's
voting system to Russia's.
</P>
<P>
   They could debate the future of the city's teaching hospitals.
Getting more help for mass transit, for our cultural institutions
and airports. Improving education. Doing more for immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, if Bush wins in New York without a fight, the only debt
collectors would be Pataki and other party factotums. The governor,
besides getting a good time slot for his speech to the Republican
convention, might extract some federal goodies for New York from a
President Bush. But a personal debt is not the same as a public
commitment. You can hold politicians to their public pledges, or
try to.
</P>
<P>
   If they deign not to pander because they don't have to, what can
you do? Watch them raise the flag in South Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
