<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-NOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC NOTEBOOK: Scary hit for Bishop
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tennessee safety Blaine Bishop sprained his neck in a
frightening third-quarter collision Sunday with St. Louis receiver
Ernie Conwell in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop attempted to tackle Conwell head-first after a 14-yard
reception and was motionless on the Georgia Dome floor for almost
15 minutes. Rams quarterback Kurt Warner knelt down beside Bishop
and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop was removed on a stretcher and waved to the cheering
crowd as the medical vehicle reached the tunnel. He did not lose
any feeling in his arms and legs and was conscious. He was sent to
Piedmont Hospital for precautionary X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Before the kickoff, Bishop led the Titans in a rousing pre-game
cheer on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd replaces Thigpen
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee scratched wide receiver Yancey Thigpen before the
game. Thigpen decided before the game he would not be able to play
because of a hairline fracture in his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   He broke the foot in the AFC Championship game last week against
Jacksonville and didn't practice all week. But the two-time Pro
Bowl receiver had hoped that a splint in his right shoe would allow
him to play.
</P>
<P>
   He tested the shoe a couple of hours before kickoff, talked with
Titans coach Jeff Fisher and trainer Steve Watterson and then went
off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen was deactivated for the game, and Isaac Byrd started in
his place.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd caught 14 passes for 261 yards while starting six games
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Super spectators
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee also deactivated seven other players before Sunday's
game: safety Marcus Robertson, linebacker Phil Glover, cornerback
Craige Page, guard Zach Piller, third-string quarterback Kevin
Daft, running back Spencer George and defensive end Mike Frederick.
</P>
<P>
   Vicarious thrill
</P>
<P>
   Former Cleveland and Falcons linebacker Clay Matthews, who holds
the NFL record for most games played without appearing in a Super
Bowl, is getting a vicarious thrill from seeing his brother Bruce
reach Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like I'm going, and I don't have to worry about
playing,'' said Clay, who played in 278 games for the Cleveland
Browns and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm living through Bruce.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Matthews, an offensive lineman for Tennessee, made his
first Super Bowl appearance after 17 years in the NFL. He even had
his number called in the second quarter. Matthews was penalized 5
yards yards for a false start.
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco cools off
</P>
<P>
   When Al Del Greco hooked a 47-yard field goal attempt in the
first quarter, it was uncharacteristic for the veteran kicker from
Auburn. Del Greco had been on a postseason hot streak, having made
seven of his last eight field-goal attempts in the playoffs prior
to the Super Bowl. His second 47-yard attempt early in the second
half was blocked by St. Louis cornerback Todd Lyght.
</P>
<P>
   Titan of a surprise
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's one element of offensive surprise was using backup
tight end Jackie Harris as a primary receiver. Harris caught two
passes for 24 yards in the first half. The Titans usually throw to
starting tight end Frank Wycheck, hero of the last-second kickoff
return (he threw the lateral) that beat Buffalo in the first round
of the playoffs. Wycheck, the team's leading receiver with 69
catches this season, went without a reception through the first two
quarters but caught a 13-yard pass on the first play of the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Challenging history
</P>
<P>
   Behind 9-0 at the half, Tenneesse became the 10th Super Bowl
team to go scoreless in the first 30 minutes. The other nine teams
lost the game. The Titans were optimistic: In three playoff games
they had overcome first-half deficits against Buffalo (one point),
Indianapolis (three points) and Jacksonville (seven points).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
