<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-NFCNOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC NOTES: Starting status off, then on for Bush
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ St. Louis safety Devon Bush didn't get a super start
to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At one point this week, the former Falcon was expected to start
at free safety in place of Keith Lyle, who has missed eight games
with a bruised nerve in his left shoulder and neck area.
</P>
<P>
   But Lyle, who is a Pro Bowl second alternate despite the injury,
convinced Rams coach Dick Vermeil that he would be able to start.
After one series, however, Bush and Lyle switched places and Lyle
played only in obvious passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who signed with the Rams as a free agent before this
season after four years with the Falcons, knew the scenario could
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be cool with me (if Lyle starts),'' Bush said
earlier this week. ``It's his position, and I'm just playing it
while he's hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle was the only last-minute change in St. Louis' starting
lineup. Vermeil put four players on the inactive list to the meet
the mandated 45-man roster for the Super Bowl: third-string
quarterback Joe Germaine, safety Ron Carpenter, guard Cameron
Spikes and wide receiver Chris Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   More bark than bite
</P>
<P>
   For the second week in a row, the high-flying St. Louis offense
_ ranked No. 1 in the NFL _ sputtered at critical times in the
first half. The Rams racked up 294 yards offense over the first two
quarters, but managed only three field goals and went to the locker
room with a nine-point advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in last week's NFC Championship against the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers, the Rams had no problem moving the ball _ until they
entered the red zone. St. Louis got inside the Tennessee 20-yard
line five times in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable misses
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis kicker Jeff Wilkins has been a hot topic throughout
the playoffs. Vermeil considered putting him on the inactive list
after the kicker was bothered with tendinitis in his left knee
before the NFC Championship. Wilkins misfired on one of four
field-goal attempts against Tampa Bay last week. He missed one in
the first half Sunday, shanking a 34-yarder wide right.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams also had another botched attempt on their first series
of the game. Holder Mike Horan fumbled the snap, recovered the ball
and was tackled by cornerback Donald Mitchell for no gain. Horan,
the oldest player to play in a Super Bowl (he turns 41 Tuesday),
remained the Rams' holder despite the blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky this time
</P>
<P>
   History repeated itself for the second week in a row for Rams
quarterback Kurt Warner. Just like against Tampa Bay, Warner's
first pass of the game was tipped up in the air by a defender. Last
week, it was caught for an interception by Steve White to set up a
Tampa Bay field goal. Sunday, Tennessee's Jevon Kearse tipped a
Warner toss and it ended up in the hands of St. Louis right tackle
Fred Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to be a millionaire? An early bet on the Rams to win
the Super Bowl would have given you a shot. The preseason odds were
200-1 against the Rams making it to Sunday's game and winning. . .
. Vermeil wasn't the Rams' No. 1 choice when they hired a new head
coach in 1997. He was the fifth pick, right behind Jim Mora.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
