A1235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-TVCOLUMN31-     01-30 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-TVCOLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABC's call was short on visuals
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There were some givens about ABC's telecast going into
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures would look good. Play-by-play announcer Al Michaels
would be articulate and informative, and Boomer Esaison would be a
fine listen with his blend of candor and humor.
</P>
<P>
   All of those elements were there Sunday night, but it had the
feel of that old beer slogan commercial: Taste great, less filling.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Esiason pointed out there was a lot of
miscommunication in the Rams secondary with backup Anthony Dorsett
calling signals. While the analysis was strong, there was nothing
to support it. No illustrations were offered. No replays.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason was noticeably better at reacting to plays than
explaining why they happened. But it was a strength that was much
needed during that somber time when Titans safety Blaine Bishop was
injured, a situation Esiason and Michaels handled with admirable
sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, it was taste great, less filling. Reporter
Lesley Visser noted Rams quarterback Kurt Warner went over by
Bishop, knelt down and prayed, but if there was a picture of that
moment, it was too fleeting to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kurt Warner's wife, Brenda, received plenty of notice.
Although the shots of wives have become cliches, her husband's
rags-to-riches story is such a great one, and her reactions were so
expressive, it was obvious director Craig Janoff felt she had
become a centerpiece of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   On one possession by the Titans in the first half, it seemed the
only shots away from the ball were of Warner's wife. The search for
a similar centerpiece for the Oilers was not as rewarding until
late in the third quarter, when an emphasis was placed on Titans
coach Jeff Fisher, complemented by a terrific shot of Steve
McNair's wife, Mechelle, in a prayerful pose when Tennessee was
driving for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the four-hour pregame show, studio analyst Steve
Young, who was sharp and laden with timely anecdotes, raised
eyebrows with his bold prediction of, ``40 points from the Rams.''
</P>
<P>
   But the best one-liner of ABC's four-hour telecast belonged to
Rams tight end Ernie Conwell, who said after witnessing the card
tricks by magician David Blaine in one segment, ``Maybe we ought to
suit him up on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   If Conwell's line was best, the segment with the cast of ``The
View'' was the worst. This bid to cater to the women viewers had to
be embarrassing to the participants and condescending to its
intended audience with the shallow continuous references to the
tight pants worn by the players.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a bad execution of a good idea. Luckily for
sports reporters Lesley Visser and Robin Roberts, who joined `View'
regulars Barbara Walters and Co., they had opportunities for
redemption with thoughtful features on the Rams' Marshall Faulk and
Fritz Pollard, pro football's first black quarterback and head
coach in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   But the most stunning performance by a woman Sunday was ESPN
feature reporter Andrea Kremer, showing up for duty on the set of
``Sunday NFL Countdown'' at the Georgia Rail Depot after giving
birth Wednesday to a baby boy.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't ESPN's idea, but the network brass was unable to
talk Kremer out of it and chose not to pull rank.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
