<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-TUCKER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing field level in NFL
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter what you might have heard, this improbable
Super Bowl matchup was not a product of parity.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, the Rams and Titans were a combined 31-6 entering the
game.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot closer to dominance than parity.
</P>
<P>
   This improbable Super Bowl matchup was not an indictment of an
economic system that allows a lot of teams to be 8-8, although the
NFL's system surely does that. It was, instead, an endorsement of
an economic system that allows any team, if well-run and
well-coached and sufficiently lucky, to win big.
</P>
<P>
   This should be the most basic tenet, the overriding operating
philosophy, of any sports league on any level: Establish rules that
give everyone an equal chance to compete and to win.
</P>
<P>
   But in major-league sports in this country, only the NFL _ with
true revenue-sharing and a hard-to-circumvent salary cap _ truly
delivers on that tenet.
</P>
<P>
   A sport that can produce a championship game matching the
nation's Nos. 21 and 30 television markets _ St. Louis and
Nashville, respectively _ is playing on a level field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this Super Bowl matchup underscores something
very important about the strength of the National Football
League,'' NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said. ``We have a system,
and we continue to strive to have a system, that works for all
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where they are located, no matter what size market
they are in, our system gives every team the same chance and gives
the fans serious hope that their team can make the playoffs and
make a run at the Super Bowl championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a Super Bowl is not simply a matter of who had the most
money, who is in the biggest city. . . . It is a matter of who has
an organization that can compete, build a team from top to bottom,
put a lot of outstanding talent together and have that talent work
as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball can't claim that, as you know.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
