<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A SUPER ATTRACTION WITHOUT THE DYNASTIES HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS game result in 5th graf) 
 (ms) 
 By GEORGE VESCEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the nice things about Super Bowl XXXIV was that
neither the St. Louis Rams nor the Tennessee Titans carried the
heavy weight of entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   The players seemed genuinely grateful to be part of the Super
Bowl, knowing that it might only come around once, and none of them
brought an attitude of ``been here, done that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the blessing of parity, of which the National Football
League can never get enough. The concept of parity comes off as a
goofy stereotype until Commissioner Paul Tagliabue starts talking
about how the league shares its network television money to level
the playing field for well-run organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Then along come the Rams and the Titans, two teams that made the
right choices of players and coaches in the short run, which is
really all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   Before they lost Sunday, 23-16, the Titans had never appeared in
a Super Bowl, going back to the Houston Oilers franchise that began
in 1960. The Rams had made their only appearance in a previous life
in Los Angeles back in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   A number of franchises have given off the definite impression
that they belonged in the Super Bowl just about every year _ even
though their identities shifted over the years, from Dallas to San
Francisco, from Buffalo to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the biggest thing was how I always perceived teams who
made it to the Super Bowl,'' said Bruce Matthews of the Titans, in
his first Super Bowl after 17 years. ``I always thought they were
head and shoulders above other teams, or if I was ever going to be
on a Super Bowl team there would be no doubt in my mind that we
were going to make the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Matthews played on a transplanted team with an
excellent 13-3 won-lost record that survived the extra week of the
wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each week our confidence grew, and I don't think until the
clock ran out in Jacksonville that I ever perceived ourselves as a
Super Bowl team,'' Matthews said. ``I think that's a quality in our
team that has helped us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a bunch of hungry guys who haven't really accomplished
anything as far as a team goes in this league. We want to taste
that success. We're sick and tired of hearing, `You can't do this
and you can't do that,' and basically watching other teams in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time two franchises were in the Super Bowl for the
first time was in 1986, when the Chicago Bears and the New England
Patriots met. Leading up to that game, the Bears acted as if they
were good enough to blow away the Patriots, which is exactly what
they did, by a 46-10 score.
</P>
<P>
   This year both teams believed they were good. The Rams were
favored by roughly 7 points, and the Titans smarted a bit about
that, noting that they had already beaten the Rams, 24-21, this
season, and didn't that count for something?
</P>
<P>
   Both teams gave off the old sports cliche of just being happy to
be here.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Proehl, who caught the pass for the Rams' only touchdown
in the conference title game, said: ``I've been to every one since
I've been in the league. I come just because I'm a fan of the game.
It's just fun to come down and see a lot of the guys you play
against.'' Now he was getting paid to attend the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream about it growing up playing football in the streets
with your friends,'' said Frank Wychek, the Tennessee receiver who
tossed the lateral for the game-winning touchdown in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when I'm in my hotel room, I just think about what
is really happening this week. You have to stop and pinch yourself
because these things don't happen to guys like me.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm enjoying every second of it. Just to play in the
game and set foot on the field is enough for me, but to do
something special in a game of this magnitude is just icing on the
cake.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of excitement even came from the two coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fisher of the Titans, who earned a ring with Chicago
although injured in the Bears' Super Bowl season, never lost his
poise in public this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil of the Rams had coached the Philadelphia Eagles in
the 1981 Super Bowl, and then left the business, citing the dreaded
``coach's burnout.'' He returned to coach the Rams three years ago
and has been generally upbeat in this sudden rush to the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil did turn crabby when both teams were advised against
trying to get to the Georgia Dome for a practice last Saturday
because of the icy roads.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the nasty weather that produced an introverted
feeling of waiting for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no golf, no going around in shorts,'' noted Neil
O'Donnell, the Titans' backup quarterback, who played for
Pittsburgh in the 1996 game in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was a focus, a looking forward to the game
itself. If this was to be their Super Bowl experience, they were
going to enjoy it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1245 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-1S     01-30 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS WIN SUPER BOWL WITH A QUICK STRIKE AND A TACKLE ON THE 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Recasts first four grafs.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In one of the most dramatic Super Bowls ever played,
the Tennessee Titans rallied from 16 points down to tie the St.
Louis Rams late in the fourth quarter Sunday night, but it was a
73-yard touchdown pass from quarterback Kurt Warner to Isaac Bruce
that became the stunning game-winning play in a 23-16 Rams' victory
in Super Bowl XXXIV at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the victory was not secured until the Rams' linebacker Mike
Jones stopped Titans wide receiver Kevin Dyson on the 1-yard line
on the final play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce's touchdown, with 1 minute 54 seconds left in the game,
came one play after Tennessee had tied the score at 16-16 on a
43-yard Al Del Greco field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce's spectacular catch and run along the sideline capped the
Rams' enchanting run from last place to Super Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, who won just four games last season, were led by
Warner, a longtime backup whose rebirth as the league's top player
came to symbolize the Rams' rags-to-riches story. Warner's passing
moved St. Louis, which won 16 of 19 games this season, into
Tennessee territory several times, setting up three Jeff Wilkins
first-half field goals. Warner later threw a third-quarter
touchdown pass to Torry Holt.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl victory was the first for the Rams, who lost
Super Bowl XIV when they played in Los Angeles. Their championship
Sunday also made their 63-year-old coach, Dick Vermeil, the oldest
coach to win a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans, a franchise that moved from Houston to Tennessee
three years ago and changed its name from the Oilers, were
appearing in their first Super Bowl game. Tennessee's offense
struggled throughout much of the game but the Titans found their
stride late in the game behind the running of Eddie George, who
scored on a 1-yard touchdown as the third quarter ended.
Tennessee's attempt to convert a two-point conversion failed.
Midway through the fourth quarter, George again scored on a 1-yard
run off right tackle to cut the Rams' lead to 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that both the Jaguars and the Titans were here.
Both teams took advantage of what was a remarkably topsy-turvy but
exciting season in which there were few dominant teams. The Rams
won just four games last season, but this season with a prolific
offense they were able to overwhelm opponents, especially on the
speedy artificial turf of their home stadium. The Titans used the
opposite approach, a bruising ground game led by George and a
quarterback in Steve McNair who runs first and asks questions
later.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee and St. Louis epitomized this strange season,
overcoming several crucial obstacles. For the Rams, it was the loss
to a season-ending injury of their starting quarterback, Trent
Green, who was replaced by Warner; he turned into one of the better
single-season stories in league history. The Titans, after playing
in four home stadiums in four years, finally settled in Nashville.
They beat the Buffalo Bills in the first round of the playoffs on a
lateral pass on a kick return in the the final seconds and last
week traveled to Jacksonville and defeated the favored Jaguars,
beating them for the third time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The week leading up to the game was bizarre. The normally
warm-weather host city turned chilly, with freezing rain and
subzero wind-chill altering practice schedules, shutting down roads
and leading to the cancellation of dozens of flights.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were ready for the game to begin, and it did in
spectacular fashion, with a series of good plays on both sides of
the ball. Warner threw nice touch passes to his wide receivers, and
the Titans' defense, as it has done all season, gave up some key
yards but was stingy inside the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   A Tennessee blitz on third-and-long early in the game hurried
Warner, causing him to throw an incomplete pass. St. Louis lined up
for a 27-yard field-goal try with kicker Wilkins, who has tendon
damage in his left knee that will require surgery, and the holder
Mike Horan, at 39 one of the oldest players in Super Bowl history.
The combination of an old man and a kicker with a bum leg proved
disastrous, as Horan bobbled the snap and was tackled for a loss,
and the Titans escaped.
</P>
<P>
   The fumbled snap was an obvious case of nerves as players were
clearly rattled by the spectacle of the biggest game of the season.
When later in the first quarter the Titans tried a field goal, from
47 yards by Del Greco, it was wide left.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis continued to put pressure on the Tennessee defense.
Wide receiver Bruce caught a 32-yard pass to begin the Rams' second
series, which was followed by Marshall Faulk's 17-yard catch. Again
the Rams stalled, but this time Wilkins connected from 27 yards on
the field- goal try.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, meanwhile, was miserable on offense and managed only
89 yards in the first half. McNair and the passing game never
really got on track, and in the first half he completed only one
pass to a wide receiver. George had some solid runs and several big
catches, but the Rams, sometimes crowding eight or nine men near
the line of scrimmage, were able to limit the damage.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Wilkins missed another field-goal attempt in the
second quarter but later connected from 29 yards and then 28 yards
for a 9-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans were playing marvelous defense, but it seemed only a
matter of time before the Rams broke out of their field-goal habit.
Tennessee defensive backs sometimes looked a half-step slower than
St. Louis wideouts, unable to keep up with their speed on
underneath crossing routes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had 159 yards of offense in the first quarter alone,
the third-most in Super Bowl history, and Warner had thrown for 277
yards passing in the first half, a halftime record second to
Washington's Doug Williams 306 in Super Bowl XXII. Warner also
threw a record 35 passes in the first half, which were more than
Tennessee's total plays, 24. Warner completed 19 passes, six to
Torry Holt for 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was making great reads, precise throws, and was in the
kind of groove few players experience in the Super Bowl. Still,
after five trips inside the Titans' 20-yard line, the Rams had only
three field goals to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to break, it seemed. Something was going to break.
Soon.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
