<HEADER>
A1262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-TURNING-COX     01-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-TURNING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late-game play the turning point
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What could be more fitting than a Kurt Warner
touchdown pass in the closing minutes to win a Super Bowl for the
St. Louis Rams? After a year when Warner was named the NFL's Most
Valuable Player and terrorized defensive backs all over the league,
it was his 73-yard bomb to Isaac Bruce with 1:54 left that held up
as the key play in the Rams' victory against the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievably, though, thanks to Tennessee's amazing comeback, it
was a play almost wiped out in the end by the heroics of Titans
quarterback Steve McNair. But the Rams held on, with linebacker
Mike Jones tackling Titans receiver Kevin Dyson at the 1-yard line
as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' winning drive began at their own 27 after the Titans,
revived by the defense and a resurgent McNair, had just tied the
game at 16. Suddenly, Warner unloaded down the right sideline to
Bruce. With his eye on the ball, Bruce slowed down just a bit to
snare the ball from Titans cornerback Denard Walker, then took off
for the right corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The pass pushed Warner past the 400-yard mark for the night.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, it was beginning to look like the first Super Bowl
without a touchdown. The Rams were generating their usual amount of
offense, but failing to finish off the drives. You had to wonder
whether Dick Vermeil was going to suffer another case of burnout
before his team found the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they made it there in the third quarter, taking a 16-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   On first down from the Rams' 43, Warner spotted Bruce, who was
sitting down in the Tennessee zone between middle linebacker Barron
Wortham and safety Anthony Dorsett for a 31-yard pass to the
Tennessee 26.
</P>
<P>
   After the Titans were stunned emotionally by the neck injury
suffered by safety Blaine Bishop, the Rams, on a third and-9 from
the 9, scored on Warner's pass across the end zone to Torry Holt,
who beat Dainon Sidney, the former Riverdale High School player.
</P>
<P>
   Warner had thrown for 277 yards in the first half without a
touchdown. The touchdown pass, at that point, was Holt's seventh
reception of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, a botched field goal attempt in the first
quarter by the Rams had the potential for prominence. And the way
the Rams were wasting scoring opportunities, losing three points
was a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   The play came just after a third-and-9 pass to Isaac Bruce from
Kurt Warner that appeared to be pass interference on Sidney. But
there was no flag, and Rams kicker Jeff Wilkins came on to try a
34-yard field goal with 9:40 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The snap was perfect, but holder Mike Horan, instead of getting
the ball spotted properly for Wilkins, put the ball down on its
side with the nose pointed toward the goal post. Seeing the
precarious situation, Wilkins rushed past the ball with his leg
cocked. Horan, trying to salvage something from the botched play,
took off to his left and was tackled by the Titans' Donald Mitchell
after a couple of yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had an opportunity to get on the board on the next
series, but also blew it. After Eddie George's 32-yard screen pass
put the Titans on the Rams' 31, Warner's offense bogged down. In
came Al Del Greco, the Tennessee kicker, who missed a 47-yard field
goal with 5:48 left.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of the first half, a big playmaker from the first
Titans-Rams game appeared on the scene to demonstrate a rookie
mistake. Jevon Kearse, the defensive end who pushed Fred Miller to
six false start penalties in that meeting, got too aggressive on a
the Rams; second-and-14 play from the Tennessee 20. With Warner
dashing to his right, trying to turn the corner, Kearse chased him
down. Unfortunately, instead of just pulling down the St. Louis
quarterback by his shoulder pads -- which seemed easily enough
accomplished -- Kearse also grabbed Warner's facemask with his left
hand. The result was a flagrant penalty of 15 yards which gave the
Rams a first down at the Tennessee 10-yard line. On the next play,
Kenny Holmes sacked Warner. On third down, pressured by a blitz,
Warner threw out of the end zone, trying to hit Torry Holt.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on the Rams' fifth field goal try of the half, Wilkins,
with another good placement from Horan, kicked the ball through
from 28 yards to increase the St. Louis lead to 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
