<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-1S     01-30 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS WIN SUPER BOWL ON A QUICK STRIKE AND A TACKLE ON THE 1
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Combines previous; updates and edits throughout.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a fitting end for this St. Louis Rams team of
castoffs. The quarterback, Kurt Warner, at one point was bagging
groceries. The wide receiver, Isaac Bruce, was once labeled as
soft. The coach, Dick Vermeil, once left the game because he was
burned out. Then came a miraculous play that made them all Super
Bowl heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, with just 1 minute 54 seconds left in the game,
connected on a 73-yard deep pass, one that will surely go down as
one of the most spectacular in championship history, and it broke a
16-16 tie and made the Rams 23-16 winners over Tennessee in Super
Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, while out of football, Warner was at one
point asking people if they wanted paper or plastic, but he threw
for a Super Bowl record 414 yards on 24-of-45 passing. Bruce had a
great game and Vermeil won his first title.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Rams' defense held off a furious comeback by Tennessee,
which had advanced to the St. Louis 10-yard line with six seconds
remaining. Quarterback Steve McNair was brilliant. But on the
Titans' final play, a pass from McNair to Kevin Dyson fell a yard
short when Rams linebacker Mike Jones made the tackle that
prevented a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The game received a serious scare when in the third quarter when
safety Blaine Bishop, leading with his head, was carted off the
field after trying to tackle 265-pound tight end Ernie Conwell.
Bishop's head snapped back ferociously, and he lay on the
artificial turf for almost 10 minutes, with both Titans and Rams
players, on the sidelines, holding hands and praying. Bishop
suffered no serious neck damage _ the preliminary diagnosis was a
sprained neck _ but Bishop had been knocked unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop was immobilized as a precaution, his neck strapped down,
and he was taken to the locker room, and later to an area hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Titans Coach Jeff Fisher, sensing his team was becoming unnerved
by the injury, gathered his players around him, and told them that
while everyone's thoughts were with Bishop, there was still a game
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Before the injury the Rams had dominated offensively, moving the
ball up and down the field almost at will, but the offense usually
stalled once the team got inside the 20-yard line of Tennessee.
Warner was fantastic, throwing for almost 300 yards in the first
half alone, yet all the Rams could manage was three field goals and
a 9-0 lead midway through the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Warner, on third and goal at the Tennessee 9,
threaded a perfectly thrown pass to Torry Holt, and the Rams took a
16-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's McNair, only the second black quarterback in
championship history, proved to be one of the more resilient
players this year. He showed it after the Rams' scoring drive, when
on one play the ensuing series, he scampered 23 yards to the St.
Louis two. It was the longest run by a quarterback in Super Bowl
history. Two plays later running back Eddie George scored from
one-yard out. The Titans missed the two-point try, but still had
hope when the score was cut from 16-6.
</P>
<P>
   McNair continued his hot streak. After Tennessee forced the Rams
to kick their first punt, McNair, often criticized for his lack of
passing skills, made several great throws on the following drive,
including a throwback pass to tight end Jackie Harris that went 21
yards to the St. Louis 3-yard line. George, breaking three tackles,
ran the ball in again from the 1, though replays showed his knee
was clearly down before getting into the end zone. The Rams could
have challenged the touchdown using instant replay, but did not.
</P>
<P>
   That touchdown concluded a 13-play, 79-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who was outstanding in the first half, froze up in the
second half, as the Tennessee defense began to dominate, and McNair
did not waste his opportunities. He led the offense on a scoring
drive again, tying the game at 16 when kicker Al Del Greco
connected with a 44-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Bruce's spectacular play, and the unknown Rams went
down in history.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that both the Jaguars and the Titans were here.
Both teams took advantage of what was a remarkably topsy-turvy but
exciting season in which there were few dominant teams. The Rams
won just four games last season, but this season with a prolific
offense they were able to overwhelm opponents, especially on the
speedy artificial turf of their home stadium. The Titans used the
opposite approach, a bruising ground game led by George and a
quarterback in McNair who runs first and asks questions later.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee and St. Louis epitomized this strange season,
overcoming several crucial obstacles. For the Rams, it was the loss
to a season-ending injury of their starting quarterback, Trent
Green, who was replaced by Warner; he turned into one of the better
single-season stories in league history. The Titans, after playing
in four home stadiums in four years, finally settled in Nashville.
They beat the Buffalo Bills in the first round of the playoffs on a
lateral pass on a kick return in the the final seconds and last
week traveled to Jacksonville and defeated the favored Jaguars,
beating them for the third time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The week leading up to the game was bizarre. The normally
warm-weather host city turned chilly, with freezing rain and
subzero windchill altering practice schedules, shutting down roads
and leading to the cancellation of dozens of flights.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were ready for the game to begin, and it did in
spectacular fashion, with a series of good plays on both sides of
the ball. Warner threw nice touch passes to his wide receivers, and
the Titans' defense, as it has done all season, gave up some key
yards but was stingy inside the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   A Tennessee blitz on third-and-long early in the game hurried
Warner, causing him to throw an incomplete pass. St. Louis lined up
for a 27-yard field-goal try with kicker Wilkins, who has tendon
damage in his left knee that will require surgery, and the holder
Mike Horan, at 39 one of the oldest players in Super Bowl history.
The combination of an old man and a kicker with a bum leg proved
disastrous, as Horan bobbled the snap and was tackled for a loss,
and the Titans escaped.
</P>
<P>
   The fumbled snap was an obvious case of nerves as players were
clearly rattled by the spectacle of the biggest game of the season.
When later in the first quarter the Titans tried a field goal, from
47 yards by Del Greco, it was wide left.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis continued to put pressure on the Tennessee defense.
Wide receiver Bruce caught a 32-yard pass to begin the Rams' second
series, which was followed by Marshall Faulk's 17-yard catch. Again
the Rams stalled, but this time Wilkins connected from 27 yards on
the field- goal try.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, meanwhile, was miserable on offense and managed only
89 yards in the first half. McNair and the passing game never
really got on track, and in the first half he completed only one
pass to a wide receiver. George had some solid runs and several big
catches, but the Rams, sometimes crowding eight or nine men near
the line of scrimmage, were able to limit the damage.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Wilkins missed another field-goal attempt in the
second quarter but later connected from 29 yards and then 28 yards
for a 9-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans were playing marvelous defense, but it seemed only a
matter of time before the Rams broke out of their field-goal habit.
Tennessee defensive backs sometimes looked a half-step slower than
St. Louis wideouts, unable to keep up with their speed on
underneath crossing routes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had 159 yards of offense in the first quarter alone,
the third-most in Super Bowl history, and Warner had thrown for 277
yards passing in the first half, a halftime record second to
Washington's Doug Williams 306 in Super Bowl XXII. Warner also
threw a record 35 passes in the first half, which were more than
Tennessee's total plays, 24. Warner completed 19 passes, six to
Torry Holt for 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was making great reads, precise throws, and was in the
kind of groove few players experience in the Super Bowl. Still,
after five trips inside the Titans' 20-yard line, the Rams had only
three field goals to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to break, it seemed. Something was going to break.
Soon.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
