<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-MOORE31-COX     01-30 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-MOORE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emotion's still there, but he's a new Vermeil
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forget about Kurt Warner's arm or Eddie George's legs.
There also was Tina Turner doing her wonderful thing before the
opening kickoff. Oh, and halftime wasn't shabby either. Just Toni
Braxton, every Disney character known to fantasy and a full
symphony orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, what everybody wanted to know Sunday inside the Georgia
Dome was when the breakdown would come and how long it would last.
You know, the first time. Then the second. Then all of the others,
right through the end of Super Bowl, when Rams coach Dick Vermeil
surely would cry himself a river deeper than the nearby
Chattahoochee.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen in the first quarter, when the Rams' Mike Horan
fumbled a hold on a field-goal attempt of 35 yards. Vermeil simply
chewed his gum a little faster. He also stayed composed after Jeff
Wilkins missed a 34-yarder in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Vermeil didn't lose his mind during the entire
first half after the Rams outgained the Titans 294 yards to 89
yards and managed only three field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil just waited and chewed and hoped that the Rams
eventually would help a 63-year-old coach place an exclamation
point on a miracle. They did just that, but only after Vermeil
spent the second half trying to keep his eyes from popping out of
his head.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rams watched their 16-0 lead become a 16-16 tie in the
fourth quarter, Warner found Isaac Bruce for a 73-yard touchdown
pass that caused the ultimate breakdown for Vermeil. He was that
much closer to a world championship. It didn't come official until
Rams linebacker Mike Jones stopped Titans wide receiver Kevin Dyson
from scoring at the 1-yard line on a frantic pass from Steve McNair
with no time left, and then the Chattahoochee had its rival on the
Rams' sideline.
</P>
<P>
   The man cried and cried. And he deserved it.
</P>
<P>
   Long before this one, Vermeil already had perfected the
impossible. Twice, in fact, starting with his Rams burying their
Lambs heritage for the first time in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   They reached the Super Bowl. They really did, but there was
something more incredulous than that for the Rams. Along the way to
a rare burst of glory, Vermeil modified his coaching style by
switching from emotional maniac to emotional maniac with an
asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Rams linebacker Mike Jones approached Vermeil
about having the team work inside their indoor practice facility on
a frigid day in St. Louis. The new Vermeil agreed. After all, the
old Vermeil didn't work during his opening two seasons with the
Rams that produced a total of nine victories. The old Vermeil was
this control freak who believed the head coach was everything, his
assistants were necessary evils and his players were robots that
needed the head coach to tell them when to breath.
</P>
<P>
   The old, old Vermeil was worse than that. Before joining the
Rams three seasons ago after a 14-year break from coaching, he
spent much of his tenure with the Eagles spending the night in his
office during the late 1970s and early 1980s. When he wasn't doing
that, he was driving his assistants and players absolutely nuts
with obsession with trying to control the world.
</P>
<P>
   So this is a new Vermeil, but only to a point. After Jones got
Vermeil's approval to practice inside that day, he went for the
jugular. He tried to get Vermeil to cancel practice.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen, because some things never change. Like
Vermeil, for instance. He's became only a modified version of his
old, old self, and that almost was Super.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
