<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT &LR;      01-30 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: REWRITING THE REAGAN GOSPEL ON TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Republicans always cheer lustily when Gov.
George W. Bush declares that his presidential campaign represents
``the beginning of the end of the Clinton era.'' But if the
volatile GOP contest in New Hampshire reflects anything about eras,
it is the end of the one ushered in by Ronald Reagan, not Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   That much is obvious when you hear and watch Bush and Sen. John
McCain racing frantically across this freezing state in a bid to
become the party's first standard-bearer from the post-World War II
generation. ``In 1992, the baby boomers took over the Democratic
Party,'' Bush said in a conversation on his bus the other day.
``Now it's our party's turn. We're about to find out what our
generation's made of.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is emerging in New Hampshire is more than a
generational shift in Republican leadership. Even more interesting
is the unacknowledged but pronounced move away from tax-cutting as
an all-consuming party ideology. Bush and McCain are revising the
core Reaganite doctrine of tax cuts first, last and always as the
best way to control government and get votes.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, the Arizona senator represents the most radical
departure from past Republican campaigns. When he criticizes Bush's
tax cut as a threat to Social Security and Medicare, he sounds more
like Tip O'Neill than Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, while trying to club the senator with the tax-cut
issue, just as often emphasizes what he calls ``pro-active
government'' in education, health and reaching out to the poor. He
acknowledged in conversation that this line is different from the
one taken by Reagan and even the old ``thousand points of light''
emphasis on voluntarism alone put forward by his father.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the feel of the campaigns, the Bush crowds here are
sedate, curious and respectful, whereas the McCain people are
boisterous, sometimes contentious and perhaps a little scruffier.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain bus is on a Mr. Toad-like wild ride with rollicking
nonstop conversations and swapping of jokes, one-liners and
locker-room razzing with reporters and aides. Bush also loves to
banter about sports or politics, though he keeps reporters more at
bay. But both candidates come across as tightly wound men whose
egos would not adapt easily to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   McCain rejects the idea that his opposition to Reagan-style tax
cutting is left-wing, as Bush has begun to charge. ``The dynamics
of American politics have changed,'' he said on his bus. ``I will
be the first Republican president since Eisenhower with big budget
surpluses. It's conservative to use those surpluses for Social
Security, Medicare and paying down the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   He says polls show that most Republicans agree, and he has made
shoring up the retirement systems long term central to his appeal
for younger voters. But as the conservative Weekly Standard noted
recently, if he wins, Republicans will have to throw out two
decades of campaign tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts championed by Bush are certainly an echo of the
Reagan era. But Bush gives equal emphasis in speeches to his call
for government to mobilize the ``armies of compassion'' to help
children and society's dropouts. True, his ideas are not coherently
explained in his speeches, but in tone they are a far cry from what
one has heard from Republican leaders these past years.
</P>
<P>
   In his freewheeling conversation, Bush insisted that tax cuts
are ``the issue du jour right now _ that's how I'm going to win in
New Hampshire.'' Indeed, McCain's admission in the last New
Hampshire debate that his own tax-cut plan was similar in magnitude
to President Clinton's has given Bush an opening that he has worked
hard to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor also insisted that once the general election
gets under way, he plans to shift gears and make clear that his
approach is a combination of tax incentives and government spending
to help the disadvantaged involving a much more aggressive role for
government than what Republican leaders in Congress may be
comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides deride this ``compassionate conservatism'' as a
sop to the guilty feelings of wealthy Bush donors. But that glosses
over the ideological revisionism inherent in both campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Clinton redefined liberal orthodoxy by calling for
balanced budgets and welfare reform, Bush and McCain are defining a
Republican third way that blends support for focused tax cuts with
a new emphasis on Social Security, health care and other
traditional Democratic issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
