<HEADER>
A1269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-BRADLEY31-C     01-30 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-BRADLEY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We won't forget ending any time soon
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It only took 34 tries, but the NFL managed to stage a
Super Bowl that outdid its hype. Now, this isn't to say that Super
XXXIV was a full-blown classic _ unless you like batted passes and
bad field-goal kicking and defenses that line up offside, it wasn't
_ but the game was infinitely better than its buildup.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl week featured freezing rain and zero name
recognition. The participants flew here having only just arrived in
their respective base cities, which is great for the
tradition-hungry among us. The Rams were in Anaheim as late as
1995, and as late as 1997 the Titans were based in Memphis and
known, curiously, as the Oilers. Now they were playing in the
planet's most-watched spectacle, which had half the planet asking:
Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Figure more than a few million earthlings leaned forward in
their seats at roughly 9:30 p.m. EST Sunday, which is when the
Titans from somewhere tied the Rams from California inside the
game's final three minutes. Know how many Super Bowls have been
tied with two minutes to play? Exactly two. This would have been
the third, except that Isaac Bruce ran through the Titans secondary
and scored before the refs could signal the two-minute warning.
</P>
<P>
   A year from now, not many of us earthlings will recall that the
first 50 minutes of Super XXXIV were fairly tedious, just as nobody
but us Atlantans will remember that the week of the game was
utterly horrid: Freezing temperatures for the Titans' Wednesday
press conference; freezing rain on Saturday, a frigid reception for
the qualifiers. But maybe this is how the NFL should do it every
year: Give us two faceless teams, scratch the extra week between
the conference championships and just let the game happen.
</P>
<P>
   This game happened as strangely as any in Super Bowl annals. The
inflatable Vince Lombardi Trophy deflated during pregame
introductions. The Rams operated as if under orders from on high to
keep the game cosmetically close. The Titans looked to be the first
option team to play for a championship since Nebraska. It was 16-0
halfway through the third quarter, at which point you thought,
``Eh, just another crummy Super Bowl,'' at which point the darndest
thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans powered their way back by virtue of power. Their
first touchdown, with 14 seconds left in the third period, was no
cause for great notice. A two-point conversion failed, leaving them
still 10 points down, and how would this plodding team ever score
twice in the span of a quarter? Why, by plodding still more.
</P>
<P>
   If this wasn't the best-ever Super Bowl, it was for sure the
best-ever last five minutes. Tennessee moved to the tying field
goal not by throwing to its wide receivers but by having one
wideout, Isaac Byrd, recover Jackie Harris' fumble. Tied with 2:12
to go, and suddenly nobody out there in TV land was worrying about
the quality of the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Rams did in one play what they hadn't been able to do
all game -- throw long. Bruce flashed past Denard Walker to gather
in Kurt Warner's pass. Now the Titans were well and truly finished,
right? Not quite. A stunning drive ended one yard short. And a
forgettable week ended with a flurry not of wintry precipitation
but of something bordering on glory.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
