<HEADLINE>
GEORGE DORSEY BRADEN, CONSTITUTION EXPERT, DIES AT 85 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y., Maine, Ill., Texas, Pa., Conn., Ind.)  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Dorsey Braden, a legal consultant on constitutional
issues, died Jan. 3 at his home in Brooklyn. A former resident of
Schenectady, N.Y., and Scarborough, Maine, he was 85.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Indianapolis, he graduated Phi Beta Kappa from
Swarthmore College in 1938 and graduated from Yale Law School in
1941. After serving in the Army in World War II, he taught law at
Yale until 1951.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the General Electric Co. in the late 1950s and worked
on its legal staff in Schenectady and Manhattan for 17 years. He
left to become a consultant on constitutional matters. He advised
state constitutional conventions in New York, Illinois and Texas in
the late '60s and early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a corporation counsel for the City of Schenectady.
He was an assistant attorney general for New York in charge of
legal opinions until he retired in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Braden's wife of 52 years, Josephine Clarke Braden, died in
1997. He is survived by two daughters, Ann B. Johnson of Brooklyn
and Magdalen Braden Blanco White of Philadelphia; two sons,
William, of Austin, Texas, and Daniel, of Manhattan; and two
granddaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
