u a BC-PROVIDENCE-SHOOTING-B     01-30 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDENCE-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL TENSION OVER OFFICER'S SHOOTING GROWS IN R.I. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI AND ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Three days after a black off-duty police officer
was shot and killed by fellow officers who mistook him for an armed
suspect, Providence's grief Sunday was mixed with a mounting
tension over race.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the black community said their phones had been
ringing from early morning until late at night, with callers
wanting to vent their anger over the shooting of 29-year-old Cornel
Young Jr., who was attempting to assist fellow officers when he was
killed. Meanwhile, Mayor Vincent ``Buddy'' Cianci took to the
airwaves to urge citizens not to view Young's shooting as an
example of racism.
</P>
<P>
   But the overwhelming feeling in Providence Sunday was that a
groundswell of anger is being held back _ at least until after
Young is buried on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking everybody in the community to relax,'' said the
Rev. Marlowe V. N. Washington, pastor of Allen AME Church, during a
service in which congregants interlocked their hands and surrounded
Young's father and grandmother in a ring of embrace. ``We're going
to get the answer. God is going to provide the answer for us in
good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Young _ the son of Major Cornel Young Sr., the highest-ranking
black officer in the department's history _ was shot early Friday
morning at a restaurant that is popular among off-duty police
officers. Overhearing a fight in the parking lot, Young told the
restaurant's patrons to get down and went into the parking lot,
where 30-year-old Aldrin Diaz was allegedly waving a gun. Young had
drawn his gun, and several witnesses said they heard him identify
himself as a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   But officers responding to a 911 call _ Carlos Saraiva and
Michael Solitro III, sources close to the case said _ did not
recognize Young as a fellow officer and shot him in the chest,
head, and stomach. Diaz is being held on a charge of felony murder,
on the theory that he initiated the events that resulted in Young's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Providence police would not comment on the race of Saraiva or
Solitro Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz's girlfriend, 27-year-old Christa Calder, was charged
Saturday with possession of an illegal firearm and held at the
Adult Correctional Institution on $10,000 cash bail, according to
department spokesman Major Martin Hames. Calder will be arraigned
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a Washington, D.C., meeting of the US Conference
of Mayors, Cianci urged citizens to view the shooting as a tragedy
for the entire city, rather than an act of racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is this was an adrenaline-charged atmosphere where
a split-second decision was made. This was a case of mistaken
identity,'' Cianci said after meeting Sunday with ministers,
members of Young's family, and Cliff Monteiro, director of the
Providence NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when it's all done, it was a gun _ a weapon was
pointed at two police officers who didn't know a fellow officer was
pointing it. Let's not make this anything more than it is,'' Cianci
said. ``Let's not make it divide our community.''
</P>
<P>
   But within the minority community, some leaders said Cianci's
quick assurances would only infuriate blacks who believe that race
was a factor in the shooting. Balbina Young said that never in her
11 years on the City Council has she felt such a wave of dispair
over race.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in my community are saying that Cornel Young Jr. was
assassinated, that he was murdered,'' said Young, who represents
Ward 11, which is 70 percent black and Latino. ``They believe had
he been a white officer he would not have been killed. It's not
that they feel it, they know it as fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Aponte, who represents Ward 10, said the response to
Cianci's comments about the shooting ``range from being offended to
being in disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a test'' for Cianci, Aponte said. ``This situation is
going to draw lines. It will place people on one side or on the
other, and people are curious to see what side he'll be on.''
</P>
<P>
   With citizens turning to local organzations for guidance on how
to respond to Young's shooting, community leaders made it clear
that the matter is as much of a balancing act for them as it is for
Cianci. Monteiro, head of Providence's NAACP, said although Cianci
made his own judgment about the incident based on information from
the police, the NAACP would not be able to determine whether racism
was an element in the shooting until Attorney General Sheldon
Whitehouse's office weighs in on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Monteiro said the tension probably would not ease any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting phone calls at 10 o'clock at night, at 7 in the
morning,'' he said. ``I'm trying to calm people down and make sure
they don't do anything foolish . . . I would be adding fuel to the
fire if I shared with you the calls I'm getting.''
</P>
<P>
   But even at the Allen AME Church service, where ministers urged
patience, there was no way to separate the anger from the grief.
During Sunday's service, Washington urged parishioners to have
faith that ``the truth will set us free.'' But he also encouraged
them to sign a petition expressing ``sorrow at the murder of Cornel
Young Jr.'' A group called Direct Action for Rights and Equality is
circulating the petition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
