</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-SIDEBAR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rams defense beaten, but not before a good fight
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The St. Louis defensive unit came to Atlanta as a
group of nobodys with somebody ambitions. It left this morning just
as obscure _ and even more thankful for the popular and explosive
offense. And for linebacker Mike Jones.
</P>
<P>
   After a first half in which it solved the powerful duo of
quarterback Steve McNair and running back Eddie George, the Rams'
defense got pounded. Staked to a 16-0 lead with 7:20 left in the
third quarter, Tennessee treated the Rams' defense like patsies,
running over, around and through it to shift the flow of the game
to the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   McNair and George wore down the Rams' defense and scored 16
unanswered points to draw even a few minutes to play. The goat
label was all prepared to be the underpublicized defense.
</P>
<P>
   It was granted a reprieve when quarterback Kurt Warner hit Isaac
Bruce with a 77-yard touchdown for a 23-16 lead on the first play
after Tennessee tied the game. So, it came down to the defense that
was heroic in the first half and dominated in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans started the final drive on the 12-yard line, with one
time-out and 1:05 left in regulation. McNair got things started by
getting a first down on two plays and then earning a first down
plus 15 yards on a facemask penalty at the end of a 12-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' defense was beaten, exhausted. McNair and George were
far more fresh, and Tennessee continued to move the ball. On
third-and-5 from the St. Louis 27, McNair showed his determination
by avoiding a sack by Pro Bowler Kevin Carter, regaining his
footing and hitting Kevin Dyson for a 17-yard gain to the Rams' 10.
</P>
<P>
   Only six seconds remained. After the Titans' last time-out, the
Rams' defense honed in for one last play. A stop would grant the
team the championship and make all their failures of the second
half moot. A touchdown for Tennessee would tie the game _ and
further destroy the defensive unit's dwindling confidence for
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   McNair dropped back and fired to Dyson on a slant pattern. He
caught it at the 5 and headed for the end zone. Jones, an
eight-year linebacker from Missouri, clutched Dyson's legs and did
not let go. Dyson fell at the 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were champions, and the defense was relieved of the
burden of scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
   It ended the season as the best in the NFL against the run, but
was hardly given much credit for the team's sudden success. The
size of the defense was questioned, as well as its strength. Those
shortcomings were hardly evident in the first half, when Tennessee
could not mount much of an attack against a hustling, fresh Rams
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams nullified George in the first half with a swarming,
gang-tackling scheme. He had just 18 yards on seven carries. Just
as significant was the way St. Louis limited McNair to just two
rushes for 12 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear then that the St. Louis defense was gaining
confidence in its ability to defend the Titans. On their last
possession of the half, Tennessee did not move the ball an inch.
</P>
<P>
   That changed after halftime. George and the offensive line got
stronger, wore down the Rams' defense and pushed it on the brink of
being the major factor in another improbable Tennessee postseason
success.'
</P>
<P>
   But on the last play of the game, a guy with a common name _
Mike Jones _ made a play that saved the game and face for the
defense. The unit will remain obscure. But at least it'll be
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
