<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-HUMMER31-CO     01-30 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-HUMMER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rams' victory fulfills feel-good Warner story
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The world's most renowned stock clerk has reached the
very top shelf. Kurt Warner completed his remarkable
up-from-the-produce-aisle story at the Georgia Dome on Sunday,
taking with him the rest of the itinerant Rams and the city that
took them in.
</P>
<P>
   This 34th Super Bowl served the purpose of giving St. Louis its
first NFL title. An almost higher calling of this game was to
provide the happily-ever-after to the Warner tale, one that had
wandered through so many levels of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the point total _ 23-16 Rams over Tennessee _ was
somewhat modest, Warner's numbers weren't. He was the inspiration
behind a fantastic Super Bowl game, with a last-quarter assist from
a veteran Ram sufferer, receiver Isaac Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   Warner threw for a Super Bowl record 414 yards, and he needed
every one of them. On the other side, the Music City Miracles were
just a yard short of taking this one into overtime. Had Tennessee
receiver Kevin Dyson been able to shake St. Louis linebacker Mike
Jones, had Dyson's reach been just a little more as time expired,
we might still be in the Georgia Dome. And no one would complain,
this game having evolved into one you didn't want to see end.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams won because, for as much as the Titans controlled the
ball in the second half, they couldn't keep it away from Warner
forever. He watched on the sidelines as Tennessee rallied from a
16-0 deficit to tie the game. But the tie lasted only as long as it
took Warner to wind up for one more marvelous heave. He threw it
long down the sideline and let Bruce shake Titans cornerback Denard
Walker for a 73-yard connection that won the night.
</P>
<P>
   Warner threw often and everywhere. His first six receptions
found six different sets of hands, including a reluctant tackle,
Fred Miller, who had gathered in a tipped ball.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Warner was done distributing the ball, surely every
Ram receiver had at least one catch. And not just the present-day
batch. So many balls in the air, certainly Elroy Hirsch, Jack Snow,
Harold Jackson, Henry Ellard and Tom Fears all must have
contributed.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis victory was wrapped around a subplot of
frustration. This victory could have been so much more definitive.
It could have marked the Rams offense as one of the most dangerous
to ever take the Super stage, if not for its curious aversion to
the endzone. The practice that the Rams missed Saturday because of
ice must have been the one where they were to install all the red
zone plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams would have been fine all along, if they were paying by
the mile. By the end of the first quarter, their offense had
amassed 159 yards, the third best opening output in the 34 Super
Bowls. And another 125 before the end of the half. Warner's 35
first-half pass attempts was a Super Bowl record, and his 277
passing yards wasn't far from one. And only nine points to show for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Five St. Louis possessions in that first half. Each one enjoyed
a first down inside the Tennessee 18-yard line. But none of them
led to touchdowns. Just the kind of inefficiency that should put a
company out of business.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no mere cold corporation. Tennessee had tried on
the title of ``team of destiny.'' But, of course, St. Louis had the
ultimate answer to that sort of talk _ Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had to win this one, because the quarterback's story
had to run its inevitable course.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
