<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-BISHER31-CO     01-30 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-BISHER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forget drab and boring; this one's for the ages
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scratch one old Super Bowl tradition, one not to be
lamented. Score one for the Warner, for a guy named Jones, and the
St. Louis Rams, new champions of the professional football world.
The Super Bowl had engraved itself on the hearts and minds of
Americans as an antidote for insomnia. It seemed that the
combatants usually left their game on the battlefields of the
playoffs. They performed as if sleepwalking. The games were
thrill-less.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more. The Rams and the Tennessee Titans brought the
thrill back to the Super Bowl at the Georgia Dome. It couldn't get
any closer than this one got. The score was 23-16, but don't
believe it. It was this close:
</P>
<P>
   In the last desperate moments, as the seconds ticked down to
double zero, Kevin Dyson, a crafty wide receiver from Utah, caught
Steve McNair's 36th pass of the night, struggled futilely to reach
the end zone, and in the final scene, while he flailed like a
drowning man, Mike Jones, a ninth-year Ram linebacker, had him in a
death grip. It was a fierce wrestle of two men with the verdict in
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The play had started on the Rams' 10-yard line, last play of the
game. McNair caught Dyson crossing toward the end zone. Dyson and
Jones and ball came together and went down in one huge human
bundle, and as he hit the turf, Dyson desperately reached for the
goal line with the ball in hand, but came up short.
</P>
<P>
   It was over. As suddenly as a crash. For a split second, the
panting thousands held their breath until it was apparent that
Dyson hadn't made it, that the Rams were champions of the National
Football league. Then the smoke-filled dome exploded, Rams in glee,
Titans in groaning misery. One yard from a touchdown, and one more
chance in overtime. Georgia had come to Georgia and Mrs. Frontiere
would go home with a championship trophy, a kind the Rams hadn't
owned since the days of Norm Van Brocklin when the Rams were in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It was a finish like never before seen in a Super Bowl. Drab and
boring are out. Thrill and suspense are in. It was surely the most
exciting one ever seen by these old eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had run roughshod over the Titans between the 20-yard
lines in the first half, but once inside what is known as the ``red
zone,'' they choked down. They squandered yards by the gross and
settled for field goals. The half was played without a touchdown
for the first time since San Francisco beat Cincinnati in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Once they finally got a touchdown on the board, an(alpha) ran
the score to 16-0, they were looking like a lock. Then came the
resurrection of Steve McNair, and if Jeff Fisher made one damning
mistake, it was going for a two-point conversion after the Titans'
first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   As the balloting came out for the outstanding player, the final
crowning chapter in the fairy tale of Kurt Warner was written. The
yardage, the completions, the touchdowns are submitted as evidence
here, but let's say that if there had been a co-MVP, it would be
Isaac Bruce. He topped, reached back, pulled in Warner's
under-thrown bomb, then ran it in for the deciding touchdown, as it
came out. It brought back to life a team that was dying.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
