<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-NOTEBOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAY HIKE AHEAD FOR FISHER  
 THESE TITANS AREN'T NEW YORK'S  
 THE VERMEIL REGIMEN  
 BUSH ROOTS FOR OILERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS game result in 4th graf) 
 (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee's Jeff Fisher is on his way to becoming one of the
highest-paid coaches in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between the Titans owner Bud Adams and the
representative for Fisher began several days ago in an attempt to
reach a new contractual agreement. Fisher has one year remaining on
his deal.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are believed to have been beneficial in that Adams
made it clear how much he values Fisher and that he is willing to
pay top dollar for his services. It is likely that Fisher and Adams
will reach an agreement for a long-term deal in the weeks after
Super Bowl XXXIV, which the Titans lost to the Rams, 23-16.
</P>
<P>
   There are some minor sticking points, however, according to
several league officials. Last year Adams told Fisher that if the
team did not at least get to the playoffs this season, that Fisher
might lose his job.
</P>
<P>
   Adams also then wanted some changes, including the dismissal of
at least one member of Fisher's coaching staff. Fisher stood up to
Adams and the coach kept his job. Adams, the league officials said,
is again balking at paying that coach, and Fisher is again
defending him.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the assistant coaches and Adams is a
tenuous one. Adams is considered by some of them to be extremely
difficult to work for and is notorious for not paying them well.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Adams will likely pry open his wallet for Fisher. It is
believed the two will eventually agree on a multiyear extension
worth at least $2 million a season. Fisher makes around $800,000 a
year now.
</P>
<P>
   If Fisher gets $2 million a year, he would be among the top five
highest-paid coaches in the league, and maybe in the top three if
coaches with the additional title of general manager are not
included. Before retiring from his coaching duties, the Jets' Bill
Parcells made about $2.5 million a year in his dual capacity as
coach and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is valuable to the Tennessee franchise not only because
of his coaching skills, but also because he is cherished by the
players and highly respected by almost everyone in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone would agree that if it was not for Jeff's
coolness under pressure,'' running back Eddie George said, ``we
would have never made it to the Super Bowl.'' _ MIKE FREEMAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THESE TITANS AREN'T NEW YORK'S &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, Jets' fans. These Tennessee Titans are not named for the
once-upon-New York Titans. Those Titans were an original American
Football League team, most of which left an unusual legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the fact that the Titans (nee Oilers) were
the last of the original eight A.F.L. teams finally to get to a
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But while that is strictly true, the fact is that four of those
original eight cities never got to see their team in the Super Bowl
_ by the time the teams made it to the championship, they were
playing in another city. And most had changed their names.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans, of course, originally were the Houston Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets started life as the Titans, before changing their name
after being rescued from bankruptcy court. But at least they stayed
put before capturing Super Bowl III.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers started life in Los Angeles before moving south to
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Chiefs originally were the Dallas Texans.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Patriots first played in Boston before winding
up in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, only the Pittsburgh Steelers, Oakland Raiders, Buffalo
Bills (who moved to the suburbs) and the Jets rewarded their
original fans with a chance to see them in the ultimate game. _
GERALD ESKENAZI &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE VERMEIL REGIMEN
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years ago, Dick Vermeil's Eagles got to a Super Bowl
against the Raiders, and the Eagles were uptight against a team
that used to come late to its own meetings and never heard of
curfew.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermeil of that era dressed all his coaches in warm-up suits
for the flight to New Orleans _ so they could feel athletic and
have a sense of urgency about what they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   And Vermeil also wanted his coaches to jog between assignments
during the week, much like the plebes at West Point have to
double-time-it everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in a jogging suit and actually jogging was the
septuagenarian quarterback guru Sid Gillman. He was one of the most
innovative minds in the history of the passing game, and Vermeil
had brought him in as a coach for Ron Jaworski.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter interviewing Gillman had to jog along with him as he
ran from one place to another before a practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy,'' Gillman said, speaking of Vermeil, ``will kill
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Vermeil was also tough on his players, who were
drilling twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   This week, though, Vermeil _ while hardly lax _ has put his
players through more normal routines. And none of his coaches (at
least publicly) has complained about the hours or the sweat. _
GERALD ESKENAZI
</P>
<P>
   BUSH ROOTS FOR OILERS
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Bill Bradley were in New
Hampshire Sunday campaigning for the Democratic nomination for
president just two days before the primary here. But their hearts,
and perhaps their minds, were in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV paired teams hailing from the candidates' home
states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is from Carthage, Tenn., and Bradley was born and raised in
Crystal City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign had a Super Bowl party Sunday evening in
Manchester, billing it as an opportunity for Bradley to cheer for
``his hometown St. Louis Rams.'' But hometown team may be a
stretch; the Rams moved to St. Louis from Los Angeles five years
ago, after nearly 50 years in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Missouri,'' Bradley said Sunday morning on the ABC
program ``This Week.'' ``I grew up 35 miles south of St. Louis and
so I'm pulling for the Rams.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his staff watched the game with other Tennessee Titans
fans at a restaurant in Nashua. Gore's team is also new to his
state _ moving to Tennessee from Houston for the 1997 season. Marla
Romash, a spokewoman for Gore, said that he is a big fan of the
team, and cheered strongly for Tennessee. He has attended at least
one Titan game this season, Romash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has been fighting hard for the voters of
New Hampshire, and he'll be using some of that energy to cheer on
the Tennessee Titans,'' Romash said. ``And then he'll go back to
fighting for New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who is also campaigning in New Hampshire,
attended a Super Bowl party in Portsmouth. When asked who he
thought would win the game, Bush said, ``the Houston Oilers.'' The
Oilers moved to Tennessee and became the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, another candidate combining the game and
politicking with a party in Amherst, said that he was ``uninformed,
but partial to St. Louis.'' -- JOHN FILES &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
