<HEADER>
A1396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-1STLD-W     01-30 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE THE GAME, ABC'S PERFORMANCE FINISHES STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
 (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the breathless fourth quarter of Sunday's Super Bowl, ABC's
Boomer Esiason came alive. Until then, the game had few
scintillating plays, little to challenge Esiason. And he hadn't
stepped up, falling into the habit of describing the obvious to us,
telling us what we clearly saw in the replays.
</P>
<P>
   On a first-half run by the Tennessee quarterback Steve McNair,
Esiason, the second-year analyst, said: ``They're bringing the
blitz, right up the middle. Nobody's panicking, the offensive line
is doing its job. Watch Steve McNair. Poise, poise, poise. He looks
downfield, then decides to take off. Watch him run. He breaks a
tackle there, another tackle there and takes a defensive lineman
on.'' Well, that's exactly what we had just seen.
</P>
<P>
   Or, on a replay of the St. Louis offensive lineman Orlando Pace,
Esiason said, ``Pace pushing down a defender. Then, he goes after
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, we had just seen that.
</P>
<P>
   But when the fourth quarter made Sunday night's game one of the
most memorable Super Bowls, Esiason's insights became crisper. He
described line play better, forecast plays and strategies with more
savvy, noted who was committing penalties before they were called
and stopped describing the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   When Tennessee's Jackie Harris caught a crucial pass to take the
Titans to the Rams' 2-yard line, Esiason said excitedly, ``What a
great call by Les Steckel. Number ninety-eight Grant Wistrom sees
it. He reads it. He senses exactly what's happening. Watch him
stop! Oh! Ho! What a great throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he exhorted the Titans' center, Kevin Long, as if he were
shouting at him from a sandlot sideline: ``C'mon Long, let's go.
Kevin Long is just kind of jogging in the park. Let's go! We've got
to get in the end zone!''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before, with the Rams on offense, and the game tied at
16, Esiason made a fortuitous remark. ``Now, the MVP, Kurt Warner,
comes into a situation that every kid dreams about. When you were a
kid, you dreamed of broadcasting the Super Bowl. I was thinking of
how to win the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   On cue, Warner threw the game-winning 73-yard touchdown to Isaac
Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   Al Michaels' call was a dandy one. With the camera cutting from
the Rams' owner to the field, he said, ``Georgia Frontiere. Heart
pounding. Warner to throw. Throwing deep downfield. Adjusting for
it is Isaac Bruce. And Isaac Bruce threads his way for a touchdown.
Seventy-three yards.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michaels' most memorable call _ a stark, staccato narration
_ came on McNair's desperation run-and-throw with seconds left in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels: ``Three receivers set to the right. McNair. Stepping
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason: ``Oh, oh, got him. Got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels: ``Rolling. Needs help. Stays on his feet somehow.
Throws. Eleven-yard line. It's caught! First down. They saved their
timeout. They have it here. They stop the clock. Kevin Dyson made
the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   With Michaels, there is always something extra. He's
three-quarters play-by-play announcer, one-quarter analyst. Upon
seeing Frontiere _ whom the ABC cameras frequently found in better
light than it could espy the Titans owner Bud Adams in _ he said,
``There's Georgia Frontiere. She took the name of her seventh
husband after inheriting the team from her sixth husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The production of the game usually matched the level of ABC's
best work on ``Monday Night Football.'' But it overused sideline
and booth shots of assistant coaches, which seldom escalated
tension; for that one shot of a frustrated Mike Martz, the Rams'
offensive coordinator, we saw too many lingering, inconsequential
shots of Pete Giunta, the Rams' defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The two irresistible sideline shots were of St. Louis Coach Dick
Vermeil's wife, Carol, and Brenda Warner, Kurt's wife. ABC rightly
played up Warner's tale of supermarket stockboy to Super Bowl
quarterback _ and he delivered.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ABC's four-hour pre-game show delivered. Not
always, and not as emotionally as its top producer promised. The
high points include:
</P>
<P>
   --The surprisingly loopy special edition of ``The View,'' the
Barbara Walters-hosted daytime show. During six minutes of harmless
fun, the Walters crew debated the meaning of football:``It is all
about the butt,'' Meredith Viera said. Added Joy Behar: ``It's
about a bunch of guys jumping around in tights.'' (When the game
ended, the victorious Rams proved that.)
</P>
<P>
   --The tale of Dan and Claire Marino's adoption of an abandoned
Chinese girl, was a beautiful story, told sensitively by Jimmy
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   --The profile of Fritz Pollard, a black player-coach in the
National Football League in the 1920s, illuminated the life of a
pioneer. But it omitted details of his post-football life in
finance, journalism and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   --Andrea Kremer's report on concussions typified her stellar
work. The animation of what happens to the brain during a
concussion was jarring, as was the former Giant Harry Carson's
admission about memory loss caused by 15 concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent were a sense of icy weather outside the
Georgia Dome, a feature on the carpetbagging pasts of Tennessee and
St. Louis, and the daring to profile unsung and lesser-known
players on the teams.
</P>
<P>
   As studio host and analyst, Chris Berman and Steve Young made a
comfortable team. The overly busy format (we didn't need the magic
tricks or the interview with Phil Collins) prevented them from
being seen too much, but Young showed an active intelligence and a
sense of humor that elevated him above most active athletes turned
into instant analysts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1398 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-ANALYSIS31-     01-30 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-ANALYSIS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Highs and Lows: Warner-to-Bruce is play of the day
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What went right for the Rams
</P>
<P>
   The Kurt Warner-to-Isaac Bruce 73-yard pass for the winning
touchdown with 1:54 to play. Tennessee had completed a 16-point
comeback to tie the game on an Al Del Greco field goal on the
previous play.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams totaled 294 offensive yards in the first half, while
grounding Air McNair and the Titans, holding them to 89. The Rams'
offensive line made Jevon Kearse a non-factor in the early stages.
</P>
<P>
   Warner completed his Cinderella story by winning the Super Bowl
MVP award after passing for 414 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong for the Rams
</P>
<P>
   The Rams allowed the game to turn in the second half, largely by
an inability to stop Eddie George. After limiting him to 18 yards
on seven carries in the first half, George had 77 yards on 21
carries in the second, including both Tennessee touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams marched inside the Titans' 20 on all five of their
first-half possessions but led only 9-0 at halftime. What could
have been a 35-0 shellacking at best was still very much a game. It
stayed that way until the final play.
</P>
<P>
   Twice St. Louis field-goal attempts failed, once on a botched
hold by Mike Horan, the second on a Jeff Wilkins miss from 34 yards
that sailed right.
</P>
<P>
   On the botched attempt, the snap appeared to be a good one, but
Horan bobbled it and didn't get the ball down in time for Wilkins
to make contact. Wilkins ran past it as Horan picked the ball up
and was tackled easily by Donald Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Warner failed to complete a pass on 10 attempts inside the 20.
Otherwise in the first half he was 19-for-25 for 270 yards. He had
problems throughout the game with batted passes from the Tennessee
defensive line, which swatted away four overall.
</P>
<P>
   What went right for the Titans
</P>
<P>
   Outside of his 52-yard pass play on busted coverage, the Rams
shut Marshall Faulk down. He was held to 12 yards on five rushing
attempts in the first half and 17 yards on 10 carries for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans' offense materialized just in time to make a game of
it after being shut out in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong for the Titans
</P>
<P>
   The knock against the Titans' offense was its lack of big-play
ability, its overreliance on short passes and dumps to the running
backs and tight ends. Maybe it's only fitting the game ended on one
final play from the Rams' 10, when Steve McNair threw to wide
receiver Kevin Dyson, who'd run a route that had him catch the ball
underneath the defense and shy of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Warner had more passing yards that McNair _ 414 yards to 214 _
and it was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Al Del Greco had a couple of 47-yard field goal tries fail, the
first in the first half when he missed it wide left and the second
on a breakdown on the right side of the line allowed Todd Lyght to
burst through unblocked and smother the kick on the Titans' first
possession of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Best pass play
</P>
<P>
   Easy. Warner to Bruce for the game and the championship. Bruce
ran a deep pattern along the right sideline with cornerback Denard
Walker in hot pursuit. Warner, with Jevon Kearse applying a blow to
his chest, appeared to just unload hoping Bruce could come up with
something big. Let's just say he answered. The ball was underthrown
but Bruce waited on it, cutting behind Walker and once he caught it
he made a move to avoid one tackle from and then took off for the
end zone. Safety Perry Phenix made one last diving try at stopping
Bruce and failed.
</P>
<P>
   Best run play
</P>
<P>
   Eddie George's 1-yard touchdown run in the fourth quarter, his
second touchdown run of the second half, which cut into the Rams
lead 16-13. George had bounced outside after drawing some contact
from Kevin Carter and then took to grinding his way into the end
zone. He had to get past 6-3, 300-pound defensive tackle Jeff
Zgonina first, which he did with a powerful legwork and some help
from the officials. Television replays showed George had bounced
his left knee into the turf before he crossed the goal line, but in
live action the way his legs were moving it would have been
difficult to see.
</P>
<P>
   Best tackle
</P>
<P>
   Rams linebacker Mike Jones came up with not only the best tackle
of the game but maybe the best of the season and best of his life.
With a Super Bowl championship on the line, the 8-year veteran
wrapped up receiver Kevin Dyson a yard shy of the end zone on the
final play to secure the Rams' victory.
</P>
<P>
   Worst play
</P>
<P>
   Faulk completely baffled the Titans defense late in the first
quarter when he took off wide to the right out of the backfield to
catch a swing pass from Warner completely unhindered. He turned it
into a 52-yard gain before Denard Walker caught up to him and
shoved him out of bounds at Titans 17. Otherwise, it would have
been a 10-0 lead on a touchdown, but still it set the tone for the
kind of things the Rams would be able to do to Tennessee's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Scariest moment
</P>
<P>
   When Titans hard-hitting safety and emotional leader Blaine
Bishop crashed into Rams tight end Ernie Conwell head first and had
not only the impact from Conwell's but from fellow defender Anthony
Dorsett .
</P>
<P>
   Best Hit
</P>
<P>
   Titans' defensive end Kenny Holmes gave Warner a Super Bowl
memory with a blow to his back on a sack that had Warner letting
out a grunt which the field microphones caught for the millions of
TV viewers. That sack, which was among the most vicious of the
game, came at a pretty opportune time with the Rams sitting at
second-and-goal on the 10 at the end of the first half. They had to
settle for a field goal two plays later.
</P>
<P>
   Worst Hit
</P>
<P>
   Kearse had finally shed some blockers and was on his way to
wreaking some havoc _ aka chasing down Warner _ but when he caught
him he brought him down with his facemask. So instead of a sack,
Kearse was hit with a 15-yard facemask penalty, which gave the Rams
a first down on the Titans' 10.
</P>
<P>
   Oops
</P>
<P>
   Referee Bob McElwee appeared to be making up new rules when he
mistakenly called a delay of game penalty against the defense with
the Titans driving inside St. Louis territory in the first quarter.
He changed his call moments later to the chagrin of the Titans,
whose drive was all but thwarted from a first and long situation
they couldn't convert. The drive ended in a failed field goal try.
</P>
<P>
   Deja Vu
</P>
<P>
   Warner had to wonder what was going on when, for the second week
in a row, his first pass attempt on St. Louis' first play from
scrimmage was batted by a defensive lineman. Last week it was the
Bucs Steve White who batted the ball and intercepted it, setting up
a Bucs field goal in the NFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Titans defensive tackle Josh Evans batted the ball at
the line, but offensive guard Fred Miller caught the batted ball
for a 1-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
