<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HOUSTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS BEAT LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ All the pomp and circumstance fitting the occasion was
there Sunday. The music blared, the dancing girls danced and the
lights shone brightly. But as a Super Bowl warm-up act, the Los
Angeles Lakers proved less compelling than an hour of Boomer
Esiason analysis and a bowl of warm guacamole.
</P>
<P>
   They watched a rookie carve them up like seven-layer dip. They
took shots that had the accuracy of a shanked punt. And they made
the woeful Houston Rockets look like Titans in front of a home
crowd still enthralled with its former Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   So coach Phil Jackson didn't hide his disgust after an 89-83
loss at Compaq Center that may have been the Lakers' worst of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an embarrassing performance today of our basketball
club,''he said. ``I was very disappointed in our effort.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of embarrassment to go around as the
Lakers lost for the fifth time in eight games, lost on national
television and lost to a sub-.500 team for the first time in two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Sabotaged by their own shooting ineptitude _ 36 percent, the
Lakers' fourth worst effort this season _ they hardly put up a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant was 6 for 22, Shaquille O'Neal 12 for 27 and Glen
Rice 1 for 7 (with just one shot in the second half). Ron Harper
was 3 for 7 and Derek Fisher missed all six of his attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant could only shake his head and smile, but was admittedly
frustrated by his personal worst shooting performance of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially when you get pretty good looks at the basket. We
just weren't making them,'' he said. ``People say sometimes that
happens, you have nights like those, but I want to figure out
why.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers opened with a 16-point first quarter, matching their
slowest start of the season, and closed with a 17-point fourth,
only briefly taking a seven-point lead in between.
</P>
<P>
   Then they lost to a Rockets team no longer built around Dream
Teamers named Pippen, Barkley and Olajuwon, but around a flashy
rookie named Francis and a lot of guys named Role Player.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Francis led a continuous whirlwind of speedy young Rockets
and was held to a mere 17 points by his own foul trouble. While he
was out, second-year guards Cuttino Mobley (15 points) and Bryce
Drew (10 points) took turns gliding unfettered to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   How could the the Lakers defense allow easy penetration, time
and again? ``That's exactly what I asked them,'' Jackson said. ``We
just never really had control of Drew, whatever his name is, the
kid that was out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-to-identify guard almost single-handedly erased the
Lakers' last significant lead, a 54-47 advantage in the third. Drew
hit a runner,a layup and a floater over O'Neal's outstretched arm
to fuel a 10-2 run, and the Lakers never regained the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``That killed us,'' Rice said of the Rockets' layup line, and
the Lakers' recent trend of allowing such displays. ``We can't
afford to let guys to keep penetrating and breaking us down and
getting easy shots and dropping it off to guys that are popping
jumpers. That's definitely something we've got to improve on.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, the Lakers couldn't even rely on their best
weapon. O'Neal finished with a game-high 27 points but missed 15
shots and had two big ones blocked by Kelvin Cato.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just timed it real well. He's known for his
shot-blocking,'' O'Neal said. ``We just missed a lot of shots. ...
I missed a couple of chippies there. We've just got to play through
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
