<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR--NY     01-30 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MCNAIR NEARLY TURNS OUT THE RAMS' LIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time Lucille McNair can remember her son
Steve crying and laying his head on her shoulder was nine years ago
when McNair was a high school senior in Mount Olive, Miss. A
teacher had accused McNair of turning out the lights in her
classroom. McNair said he had not.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher insisted he had. After a testy debate, she
threatened to slap him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really got Steve upset,'' Lucille McNair said. ``And he
was still upset about it when he told me the story. He said:
`You've whipped us, but even you never tried to slap us. I could
have taken a paddling even though I didn't do anything wrong, but
it was going to be a fight if she had slapped me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She sent Steve to the principal's office and I received a
disciplinary note at home. It was the only one Steve ever got in
his 12 years of schooling. It hurt him. And that was the last time
he ever cried and laid his head on my shoulders. It was the last
time I ever saw him so emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, Steve is like me,'' his mother explained Sunday
morning before watching McNair work in Super Bowl XXXIV. ``He does
not show his emotions very easily. He is not frigid. He never
complains. Steve in college and as a pro has always taken matters
into his own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe after this oh-so-close miss, this gripping finish that
must have broken his heart, who could blame McNair if, one more
time, he privately sought his mother, cried and laid his head on
her shoulder?
</P>
<P>
   This time, against the St. Louis Rams in the biggest game of his
life, McNair helped to turn Super Bowl XXXIV into a circus-like
affair. St. Louis scored the first 16 points as McNair struggled.
Then McNair sparkled and led Tennessee to 16 consecutive points.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two minutes, the Rams scored on a dramatic bomb.
Rams ahead, 23-16.
</P>
<P>
   But back came McNair, driving the Titans to the 1-yard line
before the clock struck zero. In an emotional aftermath, Coach Jeff
Fisher consoled McNair on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   McNair so close. McNair with flair.
</P>
<P>
   He is used to the spectacular. It was the norm for him at Alcorn
State, shunning bigger schools that wanted him to play defensive
back. He paved ground at Alcorn State to become one of college
football's most productive passers. With the Titans, he has grown
from being a backup his first two years and then becoming a starter
in the last three.
</P>
<P>
   Late in Super Bowl XXXIV, McNair took matters into his own
hands. He scrambled for crucial yards, passed for pivotal gains and
nearly squeezed life from the Rams. He completed 22 of 36 passes
for 214 yards and ran 8 times for 64 yards, a Super Bowl rushing
record for a quarterback. His point _ that he is as fine a
quarterback as can be found, a passer, a runner, a winner. That he
has a hunger to always be a winner and a champion.
</P>
<P>
   His road to stardom has been littered with others' doubts. There
has always been the novelty of being one of the few black
quarterbacks. Some pro scouts doubted whether he could mentally
master an offense. There was the notion that he was a runner first
and a passer second. Some experts said he played against college
competition that was too soft.
</P>
<P>
   This Super Bowl was a chance for McNair to have the last word.
</P>
<P>
   The absolute and final one.
</P>
<P>
   But after starting at his 12-yard line with 1 minute 48 seconds
to play and with only one timeout, McNair could drive the Titans
only 87 yards. His 9-yard pass to Kevin Dyson finished one-yard
short of a touchdown as the clock struck zero. Linebacker Mike
Jones made sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a one-on-one play and they made the play,'' McNair
said. ``I thought we were going to get it in. That is the
excitement you have. He ran a couple of yards with it and you
expect the score. But we came up short. And that's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has gone from the bottom to the top,'' Lucille McNair
said. ``And he knows how to work for what he wants and how to earn
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucille McNair, 50, raised her four sons _ Fred (31), Tim (29),
Jason (28), Steve (26) and Michael (12) _ in that manner. Growing
up in Mount Olive, McNair learned about farming, house chores and
responsibility. About respect, especially for his mother, whom he
calls Lucy Mae.
</P>
<P>
   She worked long hours and long years to rear her sons. She had
help from family and friends in the neighborhood. ``Back then you
helped raise all the kids around; if any of my sons misbehaved, the
neighbors could whip them and I didn't have to know about it,''
Lucille McNair said. ``Maybe a day or two later they would tell me,
but my kids wouldn't. They knew that they would be getting another
whipping from me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple, disciplined life, she said, in their modest
three-bedroom, one-bathroom, $14,000 home built in 1971. She had
been reared in a simple, disciplined way, too, and remembers
picking cotton as a child.
</P>
<P>
   So, once McNair signed his first pro contract in 1995, he bought
the land in Collins, Miss., near Mount Olive, where his mother once
picked cotton. He bought that land and much more around it, a total
of 643 acres. On half of it are pine trees. On the rest are 110
cattle, 7 horses, 7 ponds stocked with catfish and bass and an area
where hay is grown and sold. He and his wife and children live in
the ranch house, and on the land he built another house, one for
his mother, a six-bedroom, seven-and-a-half-bathroom home complete
with a movie theater and one of her favorite rooms, a trophy room
displaying all of her sons' athletic achievements.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that McNair did not just buy land anywhere for his
mother, for his family, but land also stocked with family history.
His plan then and now is to rewrite history.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, some of his teachers would post his football
articles on the bulletin board, but McNair would never read them in
front of his peers and teachers. To many, he seemed uninterested.
But one teacher recalls coming back to a room after school to pick
up forgotten supplies and seeing young McNair inside, scanning the
board, reading the news.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McNair is slyly perceptive of all around him, aware of
this Super Bowl chance that slipped past him, of his place in
history as only the second black quarterback to start in a Super
Bowl. His intent was not to win a Super Bowl _ he was certain he
could win several. But the clock struck zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to Steve to show people what he can
accomplish,'' Lucille McNair said. ``The black quarterback thing,
the way people think of him as a quarterback; he is going to
convince people they have to rethink their position. I drove here
from Mount Olive on Thursday, and I've only seen Steve three brief
times. On Saturday, I hugged him and told him to pray before the
game and keep God first and do your best and you'll come out a
winner regardless of the score. And he held my hands and said,
`Thank you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is married with three sons now. During college, he was a
young man. Now he considers himself a man, a husband, a father, a
leader. He wants to be a role model. He's settled. Sometimes when
he comes back to Mississippi, to the ranch, I can't find him. I
call around and then I remember exactly where to find him; he's at
the old house in Mount Olive. We've kept it. There are too many
memories there to just get rid of it. He'll just go in and sit and
talk with his brothers. I go there a lot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One day McNair might return to the Super Bowl and finish the
job. Maybe he will win the game's most valuable player trophy. And
if he does, his mother will put it in a perfect place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just for a while, I'd like to put it in my trophy room,'' she
said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   For Lucy Mae, Steve McNair would gladly turn on the light. And
let it shine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
