u s BC-FBN-TITANS-GEORGE-NYT     01-30 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-GEORGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE'S SECOND HALF COMEBACK FALLS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An astonishing collapse of the Titans' offense almost
was reversed in the second half of Super Bowl XXXIV Sunday as Eddie
George began to pound the Rams inside and outside.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort fell short, with the Titans stopped 1 yard away
from a touchdown as time ran out in the Rams' 23-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half George carried the ball 21 times, he scored
two touchdowns, he amassed 77 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't begin to tell you how I feel,'' said the running
back, who had gained more than 2,500 all-purpose yards during the
season. ``I'm going to take the best of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced repeatedly with second-and-long situations in the opening
half, failing on four of five attempts on third downs, the Rams
were stacked against George.
</P>
<P>
   He carried only seven times the first half, had only 18 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how Eddie George played this year,'' said coach Jeff
Fisher later. ``He was carrying the load and after a while he was
going to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Titans knew the Rams were going to stack the
defense to halt George. Other teams had tried and were stymied when
quarterback Steve McNair successfully passed.
</P>
<P>
   But McNair's passes were dropped often until late in the game.
Also, McNair was looking for quick, short completions _ 14 of his
22 connections went to players who weren't wide receivers. There
wasn't much yardage there, and the Rams were glad to give it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, George started to pick up yardage, winding up with 95
yards on 28 carries. He added 35 on two receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Agnew's handling of Titans' center Kevin Long was pivotal to
the Rams' defensive incursions and ability to halt George.
</P>
<P>
   Agnew, the defensive left tackle, often acts as a nose tackle.
Against the center, whose job is to zone-block so George can pick a
hole, Agnew gave him little time to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed in the second half, though. Down by 16-0, the
Titans, said Fisher, ``started to get first downs. And we made up
our mind we were going to pound them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those first-half carries of George _ Fisher claimed it
was simply a question of possession time. The Rams had 5 minutes 10
seconds more time of possession. But by the end of the game the
Titans enjoyed an advantage of almost 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to deal with what they were giving us,'' explained
George about the first half. ``When they take away the run, we
pass. But it wasn't working. We had to put ourselves in position
the second half. We did a great job with that in the second half,
getting some yardage on first down.''
</P>
<P>
   George, a 6 foot 3 inch, 240-pound runner, put the Titans on the
scoreboard with a 1-yard run in the third quarter after McNair had
dashed 23 yards to breathe some life into the offense.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, George scored again to narrow the margin
to 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   And while he was polite as he stood in a booth in the post-game
interview area, the longer he spoke the sadder he became.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to forget this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Fisher, who told McNair to remember how close they had come,
the work on next season ``starts tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   For George, it seemed to have started Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
