<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- OLDMASTERS-MARKET-3 --
``Alexander and Campaspe with Apelles, the Painter'' by Giovanni
Batista Tiepolo (1696-1770). This painting and many other master
works are for sale in New York. Sotheby's and Christie's in
Manhattan are taking advantage of a significant increase in
Americans buying old masters and the intricate web of import taxes
crippling dealers living in European Union countries. (Christie's
Images/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- OLDMASTERS-MARKET-2 --
People glance several paintings at Sotheby's Auction house that
will be auctioned off at a later date. Here they examine Giovanni
Battista Tiepolo (1696-1770), ``Putto with a Sheaf of Wheat.''
Sotheby's and Christie's auction houses in Manhattan are taking
advantage of a significant increase in Americans buying old masters
and the intricate web of import taxes crippling dealers living in
European Union countries. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- OLDMASTERS-MARKET-1 -- From
left, Ian Kennedy, Rachel Mauro, Simon Dickinson and David Ker of
Dickinson Roundell in the Manhattan branch of the London Gallery.
Until recently London was the center of the old master universe,
but now several London dealers are increasing their presence in New
York. They are opening Manhattan spaces in order to capitalize on
its flourishing market. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BALTIMORE -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- SCI-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE
-- At Kernan Hospital in Baltimore, Dr. Lixing Lao used acupuncture
to treat a patient, Ruth Young. Alternative care is becoming much
more popular. Just five years ago, many academics would not have
gone near such studies, for fear they would become laughingstocks.
And while alternative therapies remain hugely controversial in the
stodgy world of science, large multimillion-dollar clinical trials
are getting under way this year at some of the nation's most
prestigious university hospitals. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Jan. 30, 20000 -- PRIESTS-II-KAN -- The Rev.
William Hart McNichols who enetered the St. Stanislaus Seminary in
Florissant, a 150-year-old Jesuit institution tucked away in the
rolling countryside northwest of St. Louis in the fall of 1968.
McNichols is now a renowned iconographer and spent years working in
a New York City AIDS hospice. McNichols thinks there is hope for
gays, for priests with AIDS and for the Catholic Church's struggle
to deal with the issue. (Rich Sugg/The Kansas City Star)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ATLANTA -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- FBN-SUPER-BOWL-6 -- The
Tennessee Titans Steve McNair, 9, feels the pressure from the St.
Louis Rams defensive line just before halftime of Super Bowl XXXIV
at the Georgia Dome in Atlanta, Sunday. (Michelle V. Agins/The New
York Times)
</P>
