<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- DILLER-MEDIA-MARKETPLACE --
For more than two decades, Barry Diller, 58, has been among the
most respected, and feared, figures in the entertainment industry.
Today, Diller's career has come to a crossroads and he is no longer
the whiz kid who took control of the Paramount film studio 26 years
ago, or the can't-miss programmer who in the late 1980s built the
Fox network into a challenger to television's traditional Big
Three. The company he now controls, USA Networks, ranks far behind
top old-media players like Disney in clout, size and profitability.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- WRITERS-ON-WRITING -- Hilma
Wolitzer found ``a staunch fellowship of writers'' in a workshop.
(Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CANNONSBURG, Pa. -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- TV-CAPTIONS-MEDIA --
Marla M. Lahr, above, who was trained originally as a court
stenographer, now does ``real time captioning'' for live programs
like CNN Headline News. Captioning on TV, example below, appears
frequently in places like bars and offices, where sounds would be
inaudible or distracting. (Gary Tramontina/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PHILADELPHIA -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- CHINA-SCHOLAR-FLOATER --
Song Yongyi, an American-based Chinese scholar, freed after months
of detention in China, with his wife, Helen Yeo, at Philadelphia's
international airport, Saturday. Yongyi returned to the U.S. and
confirmed that he had been ``mentally tortured'' by Chinese
security agents who demanded that he confess to espionage and
implicate others. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HAMPSHIRE HILLS, N.H. -- Jan. 30. 2000 -- BUSH -- Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas was joined Saturday by his father, former
President George Bush, during an appearance in Hampshire Hills.
Three days before the nation's first primary in New Hampshire and
with some polls showing Bush closing on Arizona Sen. John McCain,
the Texan looked and acted like a winner as he and his extended
family took the stage before almost 2,000 chanting, foot-stomping,
placard-waving supporters. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
