<P>
   (NYT29) LAKEWOOD, N.J. -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- TEMP-WORKERS --
Bernardo Perez, on the job in a parking lot, works for PRC Temps in
Lakewood, N.J. Once a month, a dozen temporary workers from PRC
meet to try to ignite a campaign to win benefits like health
insurance, sick pay and paid holidays for the nation's 3 million
temporary workers. The New Jersey temps are planning to make a
major push this March, with temps in New York, California,
Massachusetts and elsewhere, to promote their code. (Laura
Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 30, 2000 -- KERREY-POLITICS -- Sen.
Bob Kerrey, 56, D-Neb., is returning to private sector life, but he
says he has not ruled out a return to electoral politics at some
point. Still, it is tempting to see Kerrey's impassioned
campaigning in New Hampshire as one more chapter in a long-running
feud between Bob Kerrey and Bill Clinton, who, by the way, were
bitter rivals for the 1992 Democratic presidential nomination. ``I
see in Bill Bradley the most uncorruptible politician I've ever
met, and I like him.'' (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
