<SLUG> BC-SUPER-BOWL-BISHOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLISION, AND TIME STANDS STILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The noise of more than 72,000 fans was muffled, even
stilled, for almost 10 minutes during Super Bowl XXXIV on Sunday.
In a scary, familiar scene, a player was on the ground with a neck
injury.
</P>
<P>
   But Blaine Bishop appears to be recovering _ in fact, said
Tennessee Coach Jeff Fisher, Bishop wanted to go back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, a 5-foot-9-inch, 203-pound strong safety, charged
head-first into the back of Rams tight end Ernie Conwell in the
third period. Bishop's head snapped back after he hit the 265-pound
ball carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher went over as doctors from both teams ministered to him.
Players stood about 10 yards away. Fisher then spoke to the Titans,
who were on the other side of the field. Meanwhile, the Rams
huddled in an impromptu prayer meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Later, though, Fisher said: ``There's nothing final about his
condition, but we're going to take him back. The X-rays are
negative. He was moving his arms and legs and wanted to play again.
But he still had some tingling in his fingers, and when we go home
we're going to take him for a CAT scan.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he had told his players what was happening while
Bishop was on the turf because it looked serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have a player down for any length of time, you
want to tell the team how he's doing,'' Fisher said. ``I could tell
that it wasn't a critical situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bishop's head and body were strapped onto a stretcher and
he was lifted onto what appeared to be an elongated golf cart that
had flashing lights.
</P>
<P>
   As it headed for the exit, the crowd began to roar and Bishop
got a huge ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The roaring did not stop after he was gone from view, though.
Play had continued, and the noise went from cheers of relief and
respect to cheering for the game.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
