<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENCHING DOESN'T SIT WELL WITH COLD RICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Glen Rice took seven shots from the field Sunday and
made just one. But he wouldn't call that a bad game, per se.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad shooting half for me,'' he said. ``I can't go out
on a limb and say (it was a bad shooting) night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers in fact lost an afternoon game to the
Houston Rockets, but Rice wasn't making a day-night distinction.
His point was that his poor shooting effort was only the product of
one half. In the other half, he barely shot at all.
</P>
<P>
   After going 1 for 6 in the first half, Rice took just one shot
the rest of the game, and clearly wasn't pleased. Not enough
touches in the second half?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's putting it plain and simple,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooters got to get an opportunity to get it going,'' Rice
said, ``and as for myself, the opportunities weren't there in the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice missed a 19-foot jumper to start the third quarter, and
never took another shot. Three free throws accounted for all of his
second-half scoring, and he finished with seven points _ his lowest
total in the last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Then coach Phil Jackson went to a three-guard lineup to counter
the Rockets' quickness, and Rice simmered on the bench, for more
than six minutes spanning the end of the third and start of the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always tough for me to sit. I'm not an assistant coach,''
he said. ``Anytime you sit that long, it's going to take you a
minute or two to get warmed up. But that happens. I try and do the
best to go out there and be ready when called upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Showdown: As the coach for the Western Conference All-Star team,
the Lakers' Phil Jackson was guaranteed to go against an old rival,
as the coaching race in the East came down to Miami's Pat Riley and
New York's Jeff Van Gundy. Neither have friendly relations with
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his thoughts on facing either one, Jackson took a long
pause, then he took a pass on stirring the pot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel sorry for the person that has to travel that
distance,''he said. ``Riley's great at those games. He's probably
coached more of them than any other coach in the NBA. Van Gundy
probably deserves a shot at it because he's sat on the perimeter of
this now for a while, and he got to the Finals last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy clinched the spot later in the day, when the Knicks
beat the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
