<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-NYT &LR;      01-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER FINDS PERFECT ENDING TO STORYBOOK SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Kurt Warner came on the Georgia Dome field for
the last time Sunday, he wondered what happened to the game he
thought his St. Louis Rams had under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it was the Super Bowl, and we had been up 16 points,''
Warner said. ``And now it's tied. And their fans are going nuts. Of
course, I thought about some things. I wouldn't call them doubts,
but you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner's last complete pass had been in the third quarter. The
Rams had gained 2 yards in the fourth quarter. And the Tennessee
Titans, who had been chasing the St. Louis Rams for a half, had
finally caught them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's moments like those when you draw back on your success
through the whole year,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   What the Rams specialized in this season was attacking and
throwing the ball down the field. And though the Titans had just
tied the game, Warner went for it all on the next play, the Rams'
first snap after the kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Warner found wide receiver Isaac Bruce along the right sideline,
using a technique that has been around football for decades but is
very much in vogue again. Warner threw toward the back shoulder of
Bruce, who stopped and caught the pass as cornerback Denard Walker
_ unable to stop his momentum _ drifted past him.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce cut back and out-raced a handful of defenders to the end
zone, scoring the stirring, game-winning touchdown in the Rams
23-16 victory in Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Titans came within a yard of being an extra point
away from tying the game, a NFL season that has seemed like a
five-month-long victory tour for the Rams concluded with a very
Rams-like championship game.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of it all was Warner, who was named the game's
Most Valuable Player after completing 24 of 45 passes for 414
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who also threw a third-quarter touchdown pass, set a
Super Bowl record for passing yards. The old record was set by Joe
Montana in 1989 with 357 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true,'' said Warner. ``It's everything you
try to accomplish when you start playing football as a kid. I
couldn't be happier.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner said the Bruce touchdown was actually a play the team had
called earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get the ball in the right place then even though
Isaac had him beat,'' Warner said. ``I knew he could beat him
again. I have a lot of confidence in him. I think our confidence
had a lot to do with the way things ended. We were in the huddle
saying, `We got two minutes. That's plenty of time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Several Tennessee players said they expected the Rams to go deep
in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been doing it that way all season,'' said Walker. ``I
actually got in good position. I figured he might come at me. I
just got my legs tangled up and I lost the ball for a few seconds.
That's all it takes in the league now.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Titans coach Jeff Fisher: ``I was very worried about Warner
in that situation. He's beat a lot of people like that. Kurt had a
marvelous game. He took a pounding. We hit him and hit him. But he
stood in there and ultimately made that big play like he has all
year. That's how they got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Warner was sacked just once, he was frequently under
pressure from Tennessee's active front defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That young man has a lot of fortitude,'' said Rams coach Dick
Vermeil. ``He's a great example of persistence. He is what we'd all
like to be. This guy is a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner started the game strong, leading the Rams to three field
goals when he had 277 passing yards in the first half. The Rams
also missed one first-half field goal and botched another when
holder Mike Horan dropped the snap from center.
</P>
<P>
   Warner had to carry the Rams because the Titans were doing such
a good job stopping St. Louis running back Marshall Faulk, who had
just 17 rushing yards in the game on 10 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third quarter, Warner hit Torry Holt for a 9-yard
touchdown pass to extend the Rams lead to 16-0. It was a crossing
route, a pattern that Warner throws especially well and went to
repeatedly in the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, things looked pretty good for a while,'' Warner said.
``When we were up 16-0, I was hoping we'd get one more touchdown
and then maybe that would be enough to close it out from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they were fighting back. In some ways, I'm glad they did.
Because we had to reach back. And that touchdown was a perfect
ending for our season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
