<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS GET LITTLE RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The lowly New York Islanders might seem the
perfect team to play after the Kings' heartbreaking loss Saturday
night in Toronto. But after seven consecutive losses, the Islanders
have swept the first two games of their three-game California swing
that continues tonight against the Los Angeles Kings at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never count out a team like that,'' Kings coach Andy
Murray said. ``Their guys are playing hard, looking to keep jobs
for next year. There is plenty of motivation in their dressing
room.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Kings, who gave up three third-period goals
to the Leafs, including the game-winner with 18.9 seconds left?
</P>
<P>
   They arrived back in Los Angeles at 3:30 a.m. Sunday and
participated in a light workout in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing we can do is let the (Toronto) game
go and move on with the season,'' defenseman Garry Galley said.
``You can't let something like that fester. We have to come out
(tonight) like we beat the Maple Leafs and want more.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight marks the only time the Kings and Islanders meet this
season. It also is the first time the clubs have played since last
summer's major trade that sent Ziggy Palffy, Bryan Smolinski,
goaltender Marcel Cousineau and a fourth-round draft choice (Daniel
Johansson) to the Kings in exchange for Olli Jokinen, Josh Green
and Martin Biron.
</P>
<P>
   A strange statistic that seems to be going around the league
this season is losing the first game at home after a trip of three
games or more.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Cup champion Dallas was 0-5 before beating the Kings 3-1
last Wednesday. The Kings are 0-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a trend this year, but it's hard to explain,''
Murray said. ``I don't anticipate us being flat. I never do. We
know what happened on the trip. Against Dallas we didn't take
advantage of scoring chances. Against Toronto we let in late goals.
We talked about those things today. But our effort is still
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-line winger Donald Audette, who hoped to return for the
Toronto game after missing a month with a sprained left ankle, will
miss tonight's action but hopes to be back Thursday against
Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000130.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-2N     01-30 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-BOWL-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CASTOFFS TO CHAMPIONS: RAMS STOP TITANS ONE YARD SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs for complete writethru.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a fitting end for this St. Louis Rams team of
castoffs. The quarterback, Kurt Warner, at one point was bagging
groceries at a small store in Cedar Falls, Iowa. The wide receiver,
Isaac Bruce, was once labeled as soft, his injured hamstrings
making the news more than his touchdown catches. The coach, Dick
Vermeil, succumbed to burnout, leaving the profession for almost
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a miraculous play, made on the biggest stage in the
world, and suddenly the three men were not the punchline to a joke.
Instead, they were Super Bowl heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, with just several minutes left in the game, connected on
a 73-yard deep pass to Bruce for the game-winning touchdown, a play
that will surely go down in championship lore. It broke a 16-16 tie
and made the Rams winners over Tennessee in Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis then held on, by the skin of its teeth, as Tennessee
made a thrilling last-second drive, only seeing a pass from
quarterback Steve McNair to wide receiver Kevin Dyson fall about a
yard short of being an extra point away from sending the game into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the most exciting Super Bowls ever, culminating a
year in which no-name players like Warner turned from pumpkins to
Pro Bowlers and non-traditional teams like the Titans and Rams went
from an embarrassment to championship contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, while out of professional football, Warner
was busy asking people if they wanted paper or plastic, but Sunday
night he threw for a record 414 yards, breaking Joe Montana's mark
of 357 in Super Bowl XXIV against Cincinnati in 1989. Warner, who
was compared to Montana by Vermeil last week, was voted the game's
most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it is sort of a storybook ending,'' Warner said.
``When you think about where I was and where I am now, it seems
pretty incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of players in this game who were great is long. Bruce
had 162 yards on six catches, while Rams receiver Torry Holt set a
rookie record with 109 reception yards. McNair, only the second
black quarterback to ever play in a Super Bowl, was at times
breathtaking, going 22 of 36 for 214 passing yards. He set a record
for rushing yards by a quarterback with 64. Tennessee running back
Eddie George, a bruiser who dominated the second half, finished
with 95 yards on 28 carries.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Vermeil, who at 63 years old becomes the
oldest coach to win a Super Bowl. At one point, Vermeil was hated
by Rams players for his brutal practices, but after consulting with
them and changing his ways from a stern disciplinarian to a more
laid-back approach, he earned their respect and trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I feel so good and so proud of this football team
and organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the spectacular plays and outstanding personal stories
came a scary moment when in the third quarter safety Blaine Bishop,
was carted off the field after attempting to tackle 265-pound tight
end Ernie Conwell. Bishop led with his head on the play, and it
snapped back ferociously, and he lay on the turf for almost 10
minutes, with both Titans and Rams players, on the sidelines,
holding hands and praying. Bishop suffered no serious neck
damage-the preliminary diagnosis was a sprained neck _ but Bishop
had been knocked unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop was immobilized as a precaution, his neck strapped down,
and he was taken to the locker room, and later to an area hospital
for further examinations, while a crowd of 72,625 at the Georgia
Dome sat in stunned silence. About an hour after the game, Bishop
rejoined his team.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Fisher, sensing his team was becoming unnerved by the
injury, gathered his players around him, and told them that while
everyone's thoughts were with Bishop, there was still a game to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in this stadium and around the country was
concerned,'' said Fisher. ``I wanted to let my team know that he
was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The cold reality of professional football is that game goes on
despite what can be grotesque injuries. The Titans, in wake of
Bishop's injury, were left without both of their starting safeties.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before the injury the Rams had dominated offensively, moving the
ball up and down the field almost at will, but the offense usually
stalled once the team got inside the 20-yard line of Tennessee. All
the Rams could manage were three field goals and a 9-0 lead midway
through the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Warner, on third and goal at the Tennessee
10-yard line, threaded a perfectly thrown pass to Torry Holt, and
the Rams took a 16-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   McNair proved to be one of the more resilient players this
season. He showed it after the Rams' scoring drive when during
Tennessee's drive he scampered 23 yards to the St. Louis two. It
was the longest run by a quarterback in Super Bowl history. Two
plays later George scored from one-yard out. The Titans missed the
two-point conversion, but still had hope when the score was cut to
16-6.
</P>
<P>
   McNair continued his hot streak. After Tennessee forced the Rams
to kick their first punt, McNair, often criticized for his lack of
passing skills, made several great throws on the following drive,
including a throwback pass to tight end Jackie Harris that went 21
yards to the St. Louis three. George, breaking three tackles, ran
the ball in again from the one, though replays showed his knee was
clearly down before getting into the end zone. The Rams could have
challenged the touchdown using instant replay, but did not.
</P>
<P>
   That score concluded a 13-play, 79-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who was outstanding in the first half, froze up in the
second half, as the Tennessee defense began to dominate, and McNair
did not waste his opportunities. He led the offense on a scoring
drive again, tying the game at 16 when kicker Al Del Greco
connected with a 44-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The play to Bruce had been called by offensive coordinator Mike
Martz earlier in the game, on the opposite sideline, but it was
unsuccessful. After the Titans scored, there were just 2 minutes
and 12 seconds left. Most teams would have been conservative,
attempting to eat up the clock, and maneuver into field goal range.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams are extremely aggressive offensively, and Martz
blurted into Vermeil's headset, ``Let's put the ball in the hands
of Isaac Bruce.''
</P>
<P>
   Good idea. Quick strike. Long ball. Touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the safety overrun me, and I ducked under him, and after
that it was a race to the end zone,'' said Bruce. ``I wasn't going
to lose that race.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair wasn't done, though. He took the helm and led the Titans
from their 12-yard line, all the way to the St. Louis 10 with six
seconds left. Along the way, he made several key runs that kept the
drive alive, including one where he spun free of two defensive
lineman like a magician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had him right in my grasp,'' said the Rams' Kevin Carter,
``and he slipped away.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, on what would be the final play of the game, McNair again
rolled out, and under pressure, threw a strike to Dyson at about
the five-yard line. But in what is surely the most important tackle
of his life, linebacker Mike Jones wrapped up Dyson. The wide
receiver stretched as far as he could, but his reach ended about a
yard short. The clock wound down to zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a touchdown,'' said McNair. ``But you have
great athletes on both sides of the ball and they made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Vermeil: ``When I saw the ball in the air, I was
terrified.''
</P>
<P>
   The terror lasted only for a second. It was replaced by joy, and
probably a small feeling of vindication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-30-00 2346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
