r s BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN     01-30 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS COULD USE SOME HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA got the split it needed this weekend to stay
on pace for an NCAA Tournament bid. Now, the Bruins need a little
help from their foes.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between a seventh seed and an eighth seed, for
instance, might be their power rating, and that's determined by
record, schedule strength and opponent performance.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's time for the Bruins to root for North
Carolina, Gonzaga, South Florida, DePaul, Purdue and even
Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night, I look at the ticker (on Headline News or ESPN2)
as the scores flash up,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``(The
power rating is based) not just on our game, but on all the other
games (opponents) play. You don't dramatically overreact (to
scores), but you are aware.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins (12-6, 3-4) are on the bubble on Selection Sunday,
if they're 17-13 and mired in fifth place, then their power rating
could determine whether they get a bid.
</P>
<P>
   That said, here's a look at how UCLA's foes have fared.
</P>
<P>
   __North Carolina, which recently lost four straight, is 13-8
after defeating Maryland and Georgia Tech this week.
</P>
<P>
   __The Bruins aren't getting much help from DePaul. The Blue
Demons are 13-7 after defeating Florida and losing to
Alabama-Birmingham this week.
</P>
<P>
   __South Florida is struggling. The Bulls lost to Cincinnati and
are 12-8 with no impressive victories.
</P>
<P>
   __Lavin's former boss, Purdue coach Gene Keady, is doing his
part. The Boilermakers are 13-7 overall and 4-3 in the rugged Big
Ten.
</P>
<P>
   __Gonzaga staggered through a brutal December schedule, but the
Bulldogs are rolling this month. They hammered Portland on Saturday
to improve to 16-5.
</P>
<P>
   __Pepperdine is 16-5 and tied with Gonzaga for first place in
the WCC.
</P>
<P>
   __The Bruins should root for the top teams in the Pacific-10, as
well. If they finish fifth, they'll benefit from each victory by
teams above them.
</P>
<P>
   Even USC.
</P>
<P>
   Up and down: UCLA guard Ray Young scored a career-high 22 points
Thursday at Oregon State. He was 0 of 8 and scoreless in Saturday's
73-58 loss at Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Words to remember: What were Oregon coach Ernie Kent's
second-half instructions?
</P>
<P>
   ``(He) wanted us to put a dagger in their hearts,'' forward
Bryan Bracey told The Oregonian. ``He wanted us to not just win,but
to hurt them. Make them know they were blown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice adjustment: Trailing by 10 points late in the first half,
the Ducks changed their defense on UCLA forward Jerome Moiso and
snuffed the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started double-teaming him, and that forced him to make
decisions,'' Ducks forward A.D. Smith said. ``We got a couple
steals, and that let us get our fast break going.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso scored eight points on 3-of-8 shooting in the first half.
In the second, he took two shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
