<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAFLAG-PROTEST31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marchers outside Super Bowl protest Georgia flag
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Standing beneath flags honoring America, the Super
Bowl and Georgia, about 100 people marched outside the Georgia Dome
on Sunday to protest the state's lingering symbol of the
Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson, the Rev. Joseph Lowery, state
Rep. Tyrone Brooks (D-Atlanta) and the Coalition to Change the
Georgia Flag, the marchers sang civil rights songs.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's flag ``stands for white supremacy and slavery,'' said
Lowery, former president of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference. ``A state flag ought to be a uniting force, not a
dividing force.''
</P>
<P>
   The marchers urged members of the General Assembly to take
action. Lowery said Georgia political leaders had been noncommittal
about starting talks to remove the Confederate battle emblem from
the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not now, when?'' Lowery asked the crowd. ``We're committed
to utilize every nonviolent means available to see that the flag is
changed, including a boycott.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Jan. 1, South Carolina has been the target of a tourism
boycott called by the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People. The NAACP vows to keep up the economic pressure
until the Confederate battle flag is removed from the Statehouse
dome there.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowery and Brooks said they hoped a boycott would be a last
resort. Brooks said civil rights leaders have been meeting with
Georgia business leaders to discuss what could be done to change
the flag.
</P>
<P>
   One marcher, Atlanta educator John Michael, said Georgians have
tolerated the flag long enough. ``This is a despicable symbol of
not only racism but a refusal for politicians to make the law
work,'' he said. ``They know it was put on as a symbol of defiance
that should have been acted on long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Georgia legislators placed the Confederate battle
emblem on the state flag as an act of protest against school
desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Most onlookers acknowledged the marchers with well wishes and
support. One man, however, taunted the marchers, saying he was a
son of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
