<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS OF LARRY BIG BLOW TO NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Andre Larry was the Cal State Northridge men's
basketball player who probably benefited most last season when Rico
Harris walked away from the team.
</P>
<P>
   Now Larry is gone. Through a phone call to coach Bobby Braswell
last week, he asked to leave the program.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a basketball decision.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell said: ``I can't get into specifics, and the only thing
I can tell you is it is of a personal nature, and (Larry) asked us
to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Harris, who quit because he wasn't getting along with his
teammates and the coaches, Larry was one of the most popular
Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre is still our boy,'' junior guard Carl Holmes said.
``He's not an outcast. Andre knows we're not going to turn our back
on him. You'll see him behind the bench next (home) game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is pray for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry, a 6-foot-9 senior, surged last year when Harris quit. He
averaged 17.2 points in Northridge's last five games _ almost
double his season average (9.6).
</P>
<P>
   Larry was CSUN's second-leading scorer (13.9) when he quit, and
he had a combined 37 points in his last two games, including 21
against Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he liked to shoot 3-pointers, Larry's absence means
the Matadors are going to become a guard-oriented team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're losing a big 6-9 guy who is your second-leading scorer
and he's grabbing a lot of rebounds for you every game,'' Braswell
said. ``We told Marco (McCain) and Carl, Denny Ogden and Lionel
Benjamin, those four guys have to come up with between 15 and 18
rebounds a game if they can. Some of these guys are now going to
have an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   One Matador who is challenging himself is junior center Brian
Heinle, the team's leading scorer at 16 per game. Heinle, who is
6-9 but only 225 pounds, says he needs to become more forceful
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be up to me to step up and pick up the slack,''
Heinle said. ``It's a big loss for us. (Larry) is a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry, 22, is majoring in Pan-African studies at Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing with Andre for three years,'' Heinle said.
``It's going to be tough. It was a surprise to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Positive sign: An ambitious fund-raising project undertaken by
CSUN's development office _ called ``Northridge Rising'' _ may
ultimately benefit Northridge's football program, according to
coach Jeff Kearin.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, who signed a four-year contract in December to become
CSUN's fourth football coach in the last six years, said he's been
told the success of Northridge Rising which has already raised $5
million could lead to efforts to raise money for an on-campus
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Antiquated North Campus Stadium is scheduled for demolition in
the summer of 2001 to make way for the second phase of a
bio-technology office park.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Interim president Louane Kennedy) has said the next priority
for her ... will be the stadium,'' Kearin said. ``She has given the
green light to go ahead and start raising money to build a stadium.
From that office, that's the biggest commitment I've ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be wishful thinking on Kearin's part, however. Athletic
director Dick Dull, who reports directly to Kennedy, said he hasn't
heard Northridge Rising mentioned in the same breath as athletic
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe (Northridge Rising) is designed toward
benefiting athletics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, no one asked, but ``CSUN Rising'' has a better ring
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Adding talent: The football team is close to getting a top
transfer in Ramsey Venner, who was a promising defensive lineman at
Fresno State last season before he quit the team.
</P>
<P>
   Venner, a 6-foot-6 freshman who also was a walk-on to the
Bulldogs' basketball team, was at Northridge's home game against
Montana on Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the airwaves: The sudden appearance of CSUN men's and
women's road basketball games on campus-based KCSN-FM is going to
cost the athletic department $15,000 for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Finney, CSUN's assistant athletic director in charge of
sports information, said the decision to broadcasts the games was
made at the top, by Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president stepped up and approved it,'' Finney said. ``She
OK'd the expenditure.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge's football road games were carried by KCSN last
season, but the basketball programs haven't been on radio for at
least four years because of the athletic department's shrinking
budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
