<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-30 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-LEAD31-COX     01-30 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-LEAD31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pass-happy Rams stifle Titans' last gasp
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All week, the city was criticized for its chilly
weather. But when the smoke cleared at the Georgia Dome on Sunday,
Atlanta had played host to the most exciting Super Bowl in NFL
history.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams won the game 23-16, when Titans receiver Kevin Dyson
was pulled down at the 1-yard line as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by a touchdown with less than two minutes remaining,
the Titans started the game's final drive at their 12. But
much-maligned quarterback Steve McNair led a meticulous two-minute
drive, getting his team to the Rams' 27 with 22 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-5, McNair was flushed from the pocket and nearly
tackled by defensive ends Jay Williams and Kevin Carter for an
apparent 11-yard loss. But McNair broke their tackles and planted
his left hand on the artificial turf to maintain his balance before
firing a 17-yard completion to Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans took their final timeout with six seconds left to set
up the final play. Dyson, lined up wide on the right side, went in
motion toward the middle of the field, then broke back.
</P>
<P>
   When McNair took the snap, Dyson ran a slant toward the middle
of the field. He caught McNair's pass near the 5, but couldn't
break linebacker Mike Jones' tackle.
</P>
<P>
   The play stunned much of the crowd of 72,625, who hopefully saw
the play through a cloud of smoke left behind by pregame and
halftime fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, the former Arena League star who was stocking groceries
in Iowa only five years ago, broke a Super Bowl record with 414
passing yards and was named the game's MVP. Warner completed 24 of
45 attempts with two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner was largely shut down in the second half. After the
Titans tied the score at 16 with 2:12 remaining, the Rams' big-play
offense finally struck.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the Rams' final drive, Warner threw a
73-yard touchdown to receiver Isaac Bruce for a 23-16 lead with
1:54 left.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce, working against cornerback Denard Walker down the right
sideline, came back for an underthrown pass and broke Walker's
tackle before bursting into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called the play earlier,'' Warner said. ``Isaac came back
and said he could beat (Walker). Isaac's our go-to guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce had six catches for 162 yards, the third-highest total in
the game's history. Rams receiver Torry Holt, a rookie from N.C.
State, had seven receptions for 109 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it seemed the game was heading into overtime for the
first time in history. After trailing 16-0, the Titans tied the
score on Al Del Greco's 43-yard field goal with 2:12 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had trimmed St. Louis' lead to three points with 7:21
left. In a drive that took more than seven minutes, McNair threw a
cross-field screen pass to tight end Jackie Harris, who gained 21
yards to the Rams' 3.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, running back Eddie George ran around left
tackle and pushed defensive tackle Jeff Zgonina across the goal
line. Al Del Greco's extra point cut the Rams' lead to 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 16-0, the Titans got back into the game. After McNair
broke loose for a 23-yard run to the Rams' 2, Eddie George scored
on a 1-yard run. The Titans tried a two-point conversion, but
McNair's pass was incomplete, leaving the Rams a 16-6 lead with 14
seconds left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, who scored the third-highest point total in league
history in 1999, became the first team in Super Bowl history to
fail to score on its first five trips inside an opponent's 20-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   But they finally broke through on their first drive of the
second half. Facing third-and-goal at the Titans' 9, Warner, who
missed his first 12 pass attempts in the red zone, fired a 9-yard
touchdown pass to Holt. Jeff Wilkins' point-after gave the Rams a
16-0 lead with 7:20 remaining in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams moved inside the 20-yard line five times in the first
half, but came away with nine points.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, who has been bothered by patella tendinitis in his
left, nonkicking knee for more than two months, kicked three field
goals, missed one and had another thwarted by a muffed snap.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams missed field goals on their opening drives. The Rams
finally took a 3-0 lead on Wilkins' 27-yarder with three minutes
left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, who was nearly replaced with 43-year-old Nick Lowery
twice in the postseason, missed a 34-yarder wide right on the third
play of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins later kicked field goals of 29 and 28 yards, giving the
Rams a 9-0 lead at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
